/* Country / territory descriptions (5-sentence, general & timeless — no number-grid figures) for the Atlas globe
   click popup. Regenerated from the accurate source summaries, adversarially fact-checked. Keyed by lowercased name.
   Load before app.js. Safe to re-generate. */
window.COUNTRY_INFO = {
  "accra": "Accra is the capital and largest city of Ghana, located on the country's southern coast along the Gulf of Guinea, an arm of the Atlantic Ocean. The name sometimes refers to the older, larger territory of the Accra Metropolitan District as it existed before its reorganization in 2008. That earlier district has since been divided into several local government districts. These include a number of independent municipal districts and a reduced Accra Metropolitan District. The Accra Metropolitan District is the only district within the capital area to hold formal city status.",
  "afghanistan": "Afghanistan is a landlocked country located at the crossroads of Central and South Asia. It is bordered by Pakistan to the east and south, Iran to the west, Turkmenistan to the northwest, Uzbekistan to the north, Tajikistan to the northeast, and China to the northeast and east. The country is predominantly mountainous, with plains in the north and the southwest that are separated by the Hindu Kush mountain range. Kabul is its capital and largest city. Its position at the crossroads of Central and South Asia has long made it a meeting point of the two regions.",
  "akrotiri": "Akrotiri is a Greek place name meaning \"cape\" or \"promontory.\" Because of this general meaning, the name is shared by many different seaside locations. It is derived from the Greek word for a headland jutting into the sea. As a common toponym, it appears across Greek-speaking coastal regions. The name accordingly refers to several distinct capes and settlements rather than a single place.",
  "albania": "Albania is a country in Southeast Europe, situated in the Balkans along the Adriatic and Ionian Seas within the Mediterranean. It shares land borders with Montenegro to the northwest, Kosovo to the northeast, North Macedonia to the east, and Greece to the south. Its terrain is highly varied, ranging from rugged, snow-capped ranges such as the Albanian Alps and the Korab, Skanderbeg, Pindus, and Ceraunian Mountains to fertile lowland plains along the coasts. The country encompasses a wide range of climatic, geological, and hydrological conditions across its compact territory. Tirana is the capital and largest city, followed by Durrës, Vlorë, and Shkodër.",
  "algeria": "Algeria is a country in the Maghreb region of North Africa and is the largest country on the African continent by land area. It is bordered to the northeast by Tunisia, to the east by Libya, to the southeast by Niger, to the southwest by Mali, Mauritania, and Western Sahara, to the west by Morocco, and to the north by the Mediterranean Sea. It is also the tenth-largest country in the world. Algiers is its capital and largest city. It ranks among the most populous countries in Africa.",
  "american samoa": "American Samoa is a self-governing, unincorporated territory of the United States located in the south Pacific Ocean, within the Polynesia subregion of Oceania. It lies southeast of the independent nation of Samoa, east of the International Date Line, and near neighbors including Wallis and Futuna, the Cook Islands, Tonga, and Tokelau. It is the southernmost territory of the United States, situated far to the southwest of the U.S. state of Hawaii. It is one of only two U.S. territories located south of the Equator, along with the uninhabited Jarvis Island. Its distinctive position places it among the most remote parts of the United States.",
  "andorra": "Andorra is a landlocked country on the Iberian Peninsula, set high in the eastern Pyrenees of southwestern Europe and bordered by France to the north and Spain to the south. It is traditionally believed to have been created by Charlemagne and was later ruled by the count of Urgell before being transferred to the Diocese of Urgell in 988. The country was formed as a polity by a charter in 1278, remaining a lordship within the Principality of Catalonia until 1715. It is governed as a principality headed by two co-princes: the Bishop of Urgell in Spain and the president of France. Its capital and largest city is Andorra la Vella.",
  "angola": "Angola is a country on the western coast of Southern Africa and one of the largest nations on the continent. A Portuguese-speaking state, it shares that colonial linguistic heritage with several other Lusophone countries. It is bordered by Namibia to the south, the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the north, Zambia to the east, and the Atlantic Ocean to the west. Angola includes an exclave province, Cabinda, which borders the Republic of the Congo and the Democratic Republic of the Congo. Its capital and most populous city is Luanda.",
  "anguilla": "Anguilla is a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, situated in the North Atlantic Ocean. It is one of the most northerly of the Leeward Islands in the Lesser Antilles, lying east of Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands and directly north of Saint Martin. The territory consists of the main island of Anguilla, a long and narrow low-lying island, together with a number of much smaller uninhabited islands and cays. Its capital is The Valley. As a British Overseas Territory, it remains under British sovereignty while managing its own local affairs.",
  "antarctica": "Antarctica is Earth's southernmost and least-populated continent. Situated almost entirely south of the Antarctic Circle and surrounded by the Southern Ocean, it contains the geographic South Pole. Most of its surface is covered by the vast Antarctic ice sheet, which reaches great average thickness. On average, it is the coldest, driest, and windiest of the continents and has the highest average elevation. As the least-populated continent, it has no permanent inhabitants.",
  "antigua and barb.": "Antigua and Barbuda is an archipelagic country in the Caribbean composed of Antigua, Barbuda, and dozens of other small islands. It is one of the smallest countries in the Caribbean by land area. The terrain is mostly flat, with the highest points found in the Shekerley Mountains on Antigua and the Highlands on Barbuda. The islands have a tropical savanna climate, with pockets of tropical monsoon in Antigua's southwest. Its most populated city is St. John's, followed by All Saints and Bolans.",
  "antigua and barbuda": "Antigua and Barbuda is an archipelagic country in the Caribbean composed of Antigua, Barbuda, and dozens of other small islands. It is one of the smallest countries in the Caribbean by land area. The terrain is mostly flat, with the highest points found in the Shekerley Mountains on Antigua and the Highlands on Barbuda. The islands have a tropical savanna climate, with pockets of tropical monsoon in Antigua's southwest. Its most populated city is St. John's, followed by All Saints and Bolans.",
  "arabia": "The Arabian Peninsula, or simply Arabia, is a peninsula in West Asia that forms most of the land on the Arabian tectonic plate. It is the world's largest peninsula, roughly comparable in size to India. Nine countries lie wholly or partly on the peninsula, including Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, and Yemen. The southern portions of Iraq and Jordan also extend onto it. It accounts for the majority of the land situated on the Arabian plate.",
  "argentina": "Argentina is a country in the Southern Cone of South America and the second-largest country on the continent after Brazil. It shares the bulk of the Southern Cone with Chile to the west and is also bordered by Bolivia and Paraguay to the north, Brazil to the northeast, Uruguay and the South Atlantic Ocean to the east, and the Drake Passage to the south. It is a federal state subdivided into twenty-three provinces and one autonomous city, Buenos Aires, which serves as the federal capital and largest city. The provinces and the capital have their own constitutions while existing within a shared federal system. It is the second-largest country in South America and the eighth-largest in the world.",
  "armenia": "Armenia is a landlocked country in the Armenian highlands of West Asia, forming part of the wider Caucasus region. It is bordered by Turkey to the west, Georgia to the north, Azerbaijan to the east, and Iran and the Azerbaijani exclave of Nakhchivan to the south. Yerevan serves as its capital, largest city, and financial center. The Armenian highlands were historically home to peoples such as the Hayasa-Azzi, Shupria, and Nairi. By at least 600 BC an archaic form of Proto-Armenian, an Indo-European language, had diffused into the region.",
  "aruba": "Aruba is a constituent island country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, lying in the southern Caribbean Sea. It sits a short distance north of the Venezuelan peninsula of Paraguaná and northwest of Curaçao. In 1986 it became a constituent country within the Kingdom and acquired its present official name. The island stretches from its northwestern to its southeastern end and narrows to a modest width at its broadest point. Geologically it belongs to South America, resting on the South American continental shelf.",
  "asante": "The Asante (also spelled Ashanti) Empire was an Akan state in the forest region of what is now south-central Ghana, together with adjoining parts of present-day Côte d'Ivoire and Togo. Founded around the turn of the eighteenth century under Osei Tutu and his adviser Okomfo Anokye, it united a confederation of Akan chiefdoms centered on the capital, Kumasi. Its ruler bore the title Asantehene, and the sacred Golden Stool (Sika Dwa) served as the spiritual embodiment of the nation and the symbol of the king's authority. The empire grew into one of West Africa's most powerful states, sustained by gold, trade, and a sophisticated administration, and it fought a long series of wars against the British from the early nineteenth century onward. Following its defeat in these conflicts, Asante was annexed by Britain in the early twentieth century and absorbed into the Gold Coast, though the Asante monarchy and its traditions endured.",
  "ashmore and cartier is.": "The Territory of Ashmore and Cartier Islands is an uninhabited external territory of Australia made up of four low-lying islands across two separate reefs. It lies in the Timor Sea on the edge of the Sahul Shelf, off the northwest coast of Australia and south of the Indonesian island of Rote. The islands were reached by Indonesian fishermen in the early 1700s, who visited regularly to harvest sea cucumbers. Cartier Reef and Ashmore Reef were charted by Europeans around 1800 and 1811 respectively. In the late nineteenth century they were mined for guano by American whalers.",
  "australia": "Australia is a country comprising the mainland of the Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, and numerous smaller islands. It ranks among the largest countries in the world and is the flattest and driest inhabited continent. As a megadiverse land, its vast expanse encompasses a wide variety of landscapes and climates, from deserts in the interior to tropical rainforests along the coast. The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia tens of thousands of years ago, during the Last Glacial Period. Their arrival marks the beginning of a deep Indigenous presence across the continent.",
  "austria": "Austria is a landlocked country in Central Europe, lying in the Eastern Alps. It is organized as a federation of nine states, of which the capital Vienna is the most populous city and also a state in its own right. Austria is bordered by Germany, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, Slovenia, Italy, Switzerland, and Liechtenstein. The area of today's Austria has been inhabited since at least the Paleolithic period. Its position in the Eastern Alps gives much of the country a mountainous character.",
  "austria hungary": "Austria-Hungary, also known as the Austro-Hungarian Empire, was a multi-national constitutional dual monarchy in Central Europe that existed between 1867 and 1918. It joined two sovereign states under a single ruler titled both Emperor of Austria and Apostolic King of Hungary. The union represented the last phase in the constitutional evolution of the Habsburg monarchy. It was formed by the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867, in the aftermath of the Austro-Prussian War. The arrangement followed earlier Hungarian struggles for independence, including Rákóczi's War of Independence and the Hungarian Revolution of 1848–1849, waged in opposition to Habsburg rule.",
  "azerbaijan": "Azerbaijan is a transcontinental landlocked country at the boundary of Western Asia and Eastern Europe, forming part of the South Caucasus region. It is bounded by the Caspian Sea to the east, Russia's republic of Dagestan to the north, Georgia to the northwest, Turkey and Armenia to the west, and Iran to the south, with the exclave of Nakhchivan set apart from the main territory. Baku is its capital and largest city. In antiquity the territory was ruled first by Caucasian Albania. It later came under the control of various Persian empires.",
  "bahamas": "The Bahamas is an archipelagic country in the Caribbean, situated within the Lucayan Archipelago in the Atlantic Ocean. It comprises hundreds of islands and thousands of cays lying north of Cuba, northwest of Hispaniola and the Turks and Caicos Islands, and southeast of Florida. Its capital and largest city is Nassau on the island of New Providence. The nation's territory spreads across a vast expanse of ocean space dotted with low-lying islands. For many centuries the islands were inhabited by the Arawak and Lucayans, a branch of the Arawakan-speaking Taíno.",
  "bahrain": "Bahrain is an island country in West Asia, situated near the western shore of the Persian Gulf. It consists of a small archipelago of natural and artificial islands centered on Bahrain Island, which makes up the great majority of its landmass. The country lies between Qatar and the northeastern coast of Saudi Arabia, to which it is connected by the King Fahd Causeway. Its population includes both Bahraini nationals and a large community of expatriates. Compact in size, it is among the smallest nations in Asia.",
  "baikonur": "Baikonur is a city in Kazakhstan on the northern bank of the Syr Darya river. It is leased and administered by the Russian Federation under a long-term arrangement. The town was built to serve the nearby Baikonur Cosmodrome, providing administrative offices and housing for its employees. During the Soviet period it was known as Leninsk and was sometimes referred to as Zvezdograd, meaning 'Star City'. It was officially renamed Baikonur by Russian president Boris Yeltsin on December 20, 1995.",
  "bajo nuevo bank": "Bajo Nuevo Bank, also known as the Petrel Islands, is an uninhabited reef with a few grass-covered islets in the western Caribbean Sea. Its nearest neighboring land feature is Serranilla Bank, lying some distance to the west. The reef is the subject of a sovereignty dispute involving Colombia, Jamaica, and the United States. In 2012 the International Court of Justice addressed Nicaraguan claims to the area. It ruled that Colombia held sovereignty over both Bajo Nuevo and Serranilla Banks.",
  "bangladesh": "Bangladesh is a country in South Asia, ranking among the most populous and most densely populated nations in the world. It shares land borders with India to the north, west, and east, and with Myanmar to the southeast. To its south lies a coastline along the Bay of Bengal, while the narrow Siliguri Corridor separates it from Bhutan and Nepal, and the Indian state of Sikkim divides it from China to the north. Dhaka, its capital and largest city, is the nation's political, financial, and cultural centre. Its location on the Bay of Bengal gives it a coastline along the country's southern edge.",
  "barbados": "Barbados is an island nation in the Caribbean, lying in the Atlantic Ocean. It forms part of the Lesser Antilles of the West Indies and is the southernmost and easternmost island of the Caribbean region. It sits on the boundary of the South American and Caribbean tectonic plates. Its capital and largest city is Bridgetown. The island was inhabited by the Kalinago people from the 13th century, and by other Indigenous peoples before them, who knew it as Ichirouganaim.",
  "barotse": "Barotseland, called Bulozi or Barotseland by its people, is the homeland of the Lozi, a Bantu-speaking ethnic group also known as the Balozi. The Lozi are native to the region straddling parts of present-day Zambia and Zimbabwe. They are not a single tribe but a confederation encompassing many groups, among them the Bamakoma, Kwanda, Lukolwe, Bafwe, Batotela, Bayeyi, Mbowe, Bambukushu, Muenyi, Mwanga and Basubia. Intermarriage among these tribes has long reinforced their shared cultural identity. The name thus denotes both a people and the territory they regard as their own.",
  "basutoland": "Basutoland was a British Crown colony in Southern Africa occupying the territory of present-day Lesotho. Its people, the Basotho, and their land came under British control in 1868 and were ruled by the Cape Colony from 1871, an arrangement that proved unpopular and ineffective at governing the territory. As a result it was placed under the direct authority of the British Crown, administered through a High Commissioner and a series of Resident Commissioners presiding over an Executive Council. Bordered by the Cape, Natal and Orange River colonies and later entirely surrounded by South Africa, it remained a distinct enclave. It was divided into the districts of Berea, Leribe, Maseru, Mohale's Hoek, Mafeteng, Qacha's Nek and Quthing.",
  "belarus": "Belarus, officially the Republic of Belarus, is a landlocked country in Eastern Europe. It is bordered by Russia to the east and northeast, Ukraine to the south, Poland to the west, and Lithuania and Latvia to the northwest. The country has a hemiboreal climate. It is administratively divided into six regions. Minsk is the capital and largest city, administered separately as a city with special status.",
  "belgium": "Belgium, officially the Kingdom of Belgium, is a country in Northwestern Europe within the coastal lowland region known as the Low Countries. It is bordered by the Netherlands to the north, Germany to the east, Luxembourg to the southeast, France to the south, and the North Sea to the west. The capital and largest metropolitan region is Brussels, while other major cities include Antwerp, Ghent, Charleroi, Liège, Bruges, Namur, and Leuven. Belgium is a parliamentary constitutional monarchy with a complex federal system structured along regional and linguistic lines. It is one of Europe's most densely populated states.",
  "belize": "Belize is a country on the northeastern coast of Central America. It is bordered by Mexico to the north, the Caribbean Sea to the east, and Guatemala to the west and south, and shares a maritime boundary with Honduras to the southeast. Part of the Caribbean region, it is a member of the Caribbean Community and the Commonwealth Caribbean, the historical British West Indies. The Maya civilization spread into the area between about 1500 BC and 300 AD and flourished there until around 1200. This heritage, alongside later British colonial influence, shapes Belize's distinctive cultural character.",
  "benin": "Benin, officially the Republic of Benin and formerly known as Dahomey, is a country in West Africa. It is bordered by Togo to the west, Nigeria to the east, Burkina Faso to the northwest, and Niger to the northeast. Much of its population lives along the southern coastline of the Bight of Benin, part of the Gulf of Guinea on the northernmost tropical edge of the Atlantic Ocean. The official capital is Porto-Novo, while the seat of government lies in Cotonou, the most populous city and economic center. Together these give the country both an administrative and an economic focal point along its southern coast.",
  "bermuda": "Bermuda is a British Overseas Territory in the North Atlantic Ocean. The nearest land is the US state of North Carolina, roughly 1,035 kilometres to the west-northwest. It is an archipelago of some 181 islands, the most significant of which are linked by bridges so that they appear to form a single landmass. The territory has a tropical climate marked by warm winters and hot summers. Its position in the open North Atlantic leaves it far removed from any other land.",
  "bhutan": "Bhutan, officially the Kingdom of Bhutan, is a landlocked country in South Asia located in the Eastern Himalayas. It borders China to the north and northwest and India to the south and southeast. It is a constitutional monarchy in which a King serves as head of state and a prime minister as head of government. The Je Khenpo is the head of the state religion, Vajrayana Buddhism, which is central to Bhutanese culture. The Himalayan mountains in the north rise sharply from the country's lush subtropical plains in the south.",
  "bir tawil": "Bir Tawil, whose name means 'tall water well,' is an area of land along the border between Egypt and Sudan that is claimed by neither country. Together with the neighbouring Halaib Triangle it is sometimes called the Bir Tawil Triangle, despite its quadrilateral shape, the two regions meeting at a quadripoint. Its unclaimed status arises from a discrepancy between the straight political boundary set between Egypt and Sudan in 1899 and the irregular administrative boundary set in 1902. Egypt asserts the political boundary while Sudan asserts the administrative one, so that the Halaib Triangle is claimed by both and Bir Tawil by neither. This makes it one of the few land areas on Earth actively renounced by all bordering states.",
  "bolivia": "Bolivia, officially the Plurinational State of Bolivia, is a landlocked country in central South America. Its geography is dominated by an Andean region to the west, including the high-altitude Altiplano plateau, snow-capped peaks and temperate valleys, and by tropical lowlands to the east and north. This range produces a wide diversity of climates and biomes, from the vast Amazonian plain and the Gran Chaco to part of the Pantanal, the world's largest tropical wetland, along its eastern border. Bolivia is bordered by Brazil to the north and east, Paraguay to the southeast, Argentina to the south, Chile to the southwest, and Peru to the west. Its landlocked position and varied terrain have strongly shaped its history and identity.",
  "bosnia and herz.": "Bosnia and Herzegovina, often called Bosnia-Herzegovina or simply Bosnia, is a country in Southeast Europe on the Balkan Peninsula. It borders Serbia to the east, Montenegro to the southeast, and Croatia to the north and southwest, with a short coast on the Adriatic Sea in the south. Bosnia, the larger northern region, has a moderate continental climate with hot summers and cold, snowy winters. Its geography is largely mountainous, especially in the central and eastern parts dominated by the Dinaric Alps. Herzegovina, the smaller southern region, has a Mediterranean climate and is likewise mostly mountainous.",
  "bosnia-herzegovina": "Bosnia and Herzegovina, often called Bosnia-Herzegovina or simply Bosnia, is a country in Southeast Europe on the Balkan Peninsula. It borders Serbia to the east, Montenegro to the southeast, and Croatia to the north and southwest, with a short coast on the Adriatic Sea in the south. Bosnia, the larger northern region, has a moderate continental climate with hot summers and cold, snowy winters. Its geography is largely mountainous, especially in the central and eastern parts dominated by the Dinaric Alps. Herzegovina, the smaller southern region, has a Mediterranean climate and is likewise mostly mountainous.",
  "botswana": "Botswana, officially the Republic of Botswana, is a landlocked country in Southern Africa. It is topographically flat, with roughly seventy percent of its territory forming part of the Kalahari Desert. It is bordered by South Africa to the south and southeast, Namibia to the west and north, Zambia to the north, and Zimbabwe to the northeast. Sparsely populated relative to its size, it is de facto the nation-state of the Batswana people, who make up the large majority of the population. The Kalanga people form the single largest ethnic minority.",
  "br. indian ocean ter.": "The British Indian Ocean Territory is a British Overseas Territory situated in the Indian Ocean. It comprises the seven atolls of the Chagos Archipelago, made up of more than a thousand individual islands, many of them very small. The largest and most southerly island is Diego Garcia, the site of a joint military facility of the United Kingdom and the United States. Official administration is conducted remotely from London, though the local capital is often regarded as being on Diego Garcia. Mauritius contests British control, arguing that the government separated the Chagos Archipelago from Mauritius to create the territory as a new colony.",
  "brazil": "Brazil, officially the Federative Republic of Brazil, is the largest country in South America and one of the largest in the world by both area and population. It is a federation composed of twenty-six states and a Federal District, which hosts the capital, Brasília. Its most populous city is São Paulo, followed by Rio de Janeiro. Brazil has more Portuguese speakers than any other country and is the only nation in the Americas where Portuguese is an official language. This Portuguese heritage, rooted in the colonial era, sets Brazil apart culturally and linguistically from its Spanish-speaking neighbours.",
  "british guiana": "British Guiana was a British colony on the northern coast of South America. Since 1966 the territory has existed as the independent nation of Guyana. Among the first known Europeans to encounter the wider Guiana region were the English explorer Sir Walter Raleigh and his crew, and Raleigh later published a book titled The Discovery of Guiana, though it dealt mainly with the Guayana region of present-day Venezuela. The Dutch were the first Europeans to settle in the area, beginning in the early seventeenth century. Control later passed to Britain, giving the colony its name and its lasting English-speaking and Caribbean character.",
  "british raj": "The British Raj was the period of rule by the British Crown over the Indian subcontinent, lasting from 1858 to 1947. It is also known as Crown rule or direct rule in India, and the region was commonly called India in contemporary usage. It included areas directly administered by the United Kingdom, collectively called British India, and areas ruled by indigenous rulers under British paramountcy, known as the princely states. The region was sometimes informally called the Indian Empire, though this was never an official title. As India, it was a founding member of the League of Nations and of the United Nations in 1945.",
  "british virgin is.": "The British Virgin Islands, officially the Virgin Islands, are a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, lying east of Puerto Rico and the US Virgin Islands and north-west of Anguilla. They are geographically part of the Virgin Islands archipelago, within the Leeward Islands of the Lesser Antilles and the broader West Indies. The territory consists of the main islands of Tortola, Virgin Gorda, Anegada and Jost Van Dyke, along with more than fifty smaller islands and cays, of which about sixteen are inhabited. The capital, Road Town, sits on Tortola, the largest island. Its Caribbean setting and status as a British possession shape its enduring identity.",
  "brunei": "Brunei, officially Brunei Darussalam, is a country in Southeast Asia on the northern coast of the island of Borneo. Apart from its coastline on the South China Sea, it is completely surrounded by the Malaysian state of Sarawak, whose Limbang district splits Brunei's territory into two parts. It is the only sovereign state located entirely on Borneo, the rest of the island being divided between Malaysia and Indonesia. Its capital and largest city is Bandar Seri Begawan. Malay is the official language, and Sunni Islam is the state religion, though other faiths are nominally tolerated.",
  "buganda": "Buganda is a Bantu kingdom within Uganda and the homeland of the Baganda people. It is the largest of the traditional kingdoms in present-day East Africa, encompassing Uganda's Central Region, including the national capital Kampala. The Baganda form the largest ethnic group in Uganda and a significant share of its population. The kingdom traces its unification to the thirteenth century under its first king, Kato Kintu, founder of the Kintu dynasty. Buganda grew into one of the largest and most powerful states in East Africa during the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries.",
  "bulgaria": "Bulgaria, officially the Republic of Bulgaria, is a country in Southeast Europe on the eastern part of the Balkan Peninsula. It lies directly south of the Danube river and west of the Black Sea. Bulgaria is bordered by Greece and Turkey to the south, Serbia and North Macedonia to the west, and Romania across the Danube to the north. Sofia is the nation's capital and largest city, with other major cities including Plovdiv, Varna, and Burgas. Its position on the Balkans has made it a historic crossroads between Europe and the Near East.",
  "bunyoro": "Bunyoro, also called Bunyoro-Kitara, is a traditional Bantu kingdom in Western Uganda. It was one of the most powerful kingdoms in Central and East Africa from the sixteenth to the nineteenth century. The kingdom is ruled by a monarch bearing the title Omukama of Bunyoro-Kitara. Its rulers have long held both political and cultural authority over the Banyoro people. The kingdom's historical strength and enduring dynastic tradition remain central to its identity.",
  "burkina faso": "Burkina Faso is a landlocked country in West Africa. It is bordered by Mali to the northwest, Niger to the northeast, Benin to the southeast, Togo and Ghana to the south, and Ivory Coast to the southwest. It shares its longest frontiers with these neighbours across the interior of the region. After gaining independence, it was known as the Republic of Upper Volta from 1958 to 1984 before adopting its present name. The change of name reflected a break from the colonial-era designation toward a national identity.",
  "burundi": "Burundi, officially the Republic of Burundi, is a landlocked country in East Africa. It lies in the Great Rift Valley at the junction between the African Great Lakes region and Southeast Africa. It is bordered by Rwanda to the north, Tanzania to the east and southeast, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the west, with Lake Tanganyika running along its southwestern edge. Gitega is the political capital, while Bujumbura is the economic capital and largest city. The Twa, Hutu, and Tutsi peoples have lived in the territory for at least five hundred years.",
  "cabo verde": "Cabo Verde, also known in English as Cape Verde and officially the Republic of Cabo Verde, is an archipelagic country in the central Atlantic Ocean off the coast of West Africa. It consists of ten volcanic islands lying several hundred kilometres west of Cap-Vert, the westernmost point of continental Africa, after which the islands are named. The country forms part of the Macaronesia ecoregion, along with the Azores, the Canary Islands, Madeira and the Savage Isles. Its Portuguese colonial heritage is reflected in its official language and its Cape Verdean Creole. The islands' Atlantic location has long made them a crossroads of oceanic trade and migration.",
  "calabar": "Calabar is the capital city of Cross River State in southeastern Nigeria. It was originally named Akwa Akpa in the Efik language, as the Efik people have historically dominated the area. The city sits adjacent to the Calabar and Great Kwa rivers and the creeks of the Cross River inland delta. Calabar has been described as a tourism capital of Nigeria, gaining a reputation as one of the country's cleanest and most environmentally friendly cities. Its riverine setting and Efik heritage give it a distinctive place among Nigerian cities.",
  "cambodia": "Cambodia, officially the Kingdom of Cambodia, is a country in mainland Southeast Asia. It is bordered by Thailand to the northwest, Laos to the north, and Vietnam to the east, with a coastline along the Gulf of Thailand to the southwest. Its landscape is dominated by a low-lying plain and the confluence of the Mekong river and the Tonlé Sap, Southeast Asia's largest lake. The country has a tropical climate. Its population is predominantly ethnically Khmer, whose culture and language define the nation's heritage.",
  "cameroon": "Cameroon, officially the Republic of Cameroon, is a country in Central Africa. It shares borders with Nigeria to the west and north, Chad to the northeast, the Central African Republic to the east, and Equatorial Guinea, Gabon, and the Republic of the Congo to the south. Its coastline lies on the Bight of Biafra, part of the Gulf of Guinea and the Atlantic Ocean. Because of its position at the crossroads between West Africa and Central Africa, it is often described as belonging to both regions. Cameroon is notably diverse, with hundreds of native languages spoken alongside its national languages, English and French.",
  "canada": "Canada is a country in North America whose ten provinces and three territories stretch from the Atlantic Ocean to the Pacific Ocean and northward into the Arctic Ocean. It is the second-largest country in the world by total area and has the longest coastline of any nation. Its boundary with the United States is the longest international land border on Earth. The country is characterized by a wide range of both meteorological and geological regions. Population densities vary greatly, with most people living in urban areas and vast stretches remaining sparsely inhabited.",
  "cape colony": "The Cape Colony, also known as the Cape of Good Hope, was a British colony in present-day South Africa named after the Cape of Good Hope. It began as a Dutch colony established in 1652 by the Dutch East India Company, which governed it from 1652 to 1795. The British took control in 1795, and after a period of Batavian rule from 1803 to 1806, held it again from 1806 until 1910. In 1910 it united with three other colonies to form the Union of South Africa and thereafter became the Cape Province. The Cape Province continued to exist even after 1961, when South Africa became a republic.",
  "cayman is.": "The Cayman Islands are a self-governing British Overseas Territory in the western Caribbean. The territory comprises the three islands of Grand Cayman, Cayman Brac, and Little Cayman, which lie south of Cuba and north-east of Honduras, between Jamaica and Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula. The capital city is George Town, on Grand Cayman, which is the most populous of the three islands. The Cayman Islands are considered to be part of the geographic Western Caribbean zone as well as the Greater Antilles. It is the most populated of all the British Overseas Territories.",
  "central african rep.": "The Central African Republic is a landlocked country located in Central Africa. It is bordered by Chad to the north, Sudan to the northeast, South Sudan to the east, the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the south, the Republic of the Congo to the southwest, and Cameroon to the west. Its population consists of about 80 ethnic groups. It was formerly a French colony known as Ubangi-Shari, and French remains its official language. Sango, a Ngbandi-based creole language, serves as the national and co-official language.",
  "ceylon": "Ceylon is the former name of Sri Lanka, an island country in South Asia. It is located in the Indian Ocean, southwest of the Bay of Bengal, and is separated from India by the Gulf of Mannar and the Palk Strait. It shares a maritime border with the Maldives to the southwest and India to the northwest, and lies across the Bay of Bengal from Bangladesh and Myanmar to the northeast. Its capital is Sri Jayawardenepura Kotte, while Colombo is its largest city and the political, financial, and cultural centre. It is separated from the Andaman and Nicobar Islands of India, which lie to its east.",
  "chad": "Chad, officially the Republic of Chad, is a country in Central Africa. It is bordered by Libya to the north, Sudan to the east, the Central African Republic to the south, Cameroon and Nigeria to the southwest, and Niger to the west. Its capital and largest city is N'Djamena, and it borders Nigeria at Lake Chad. It is the fifth-largest country in Africa and the twentieth largest nation by area. Chad's official languages are French and Arabic, with French serving as the lingua franca and the language of government and education.",
  "chile": "Chile, officially the Republic of Chile, is a country in western South America. It is the southernmost country in the world and the closest to Antarctica, extending along a narrow strip of land between the Andes Mountains and the Pacific Ocean. It shares borders with Peru to the north, Bolivia to the northeast, and Argentina to the east, with the Drake Passage lying to the south. Chile also administers several Pacific islands, including the Juan Fernández archipelago, Isla Salas y Gómez, the Desventuradas Islands, and Easter Island. It further claims a wedge of Antarctica as the Chilean Antarctic Territory.",
  "china": "China, officially the People's Republic of China, is a country in East Asia and one of the most populous nations in the world. It is divided into province-level divisions, including special administrative regions, with Beijing as its capital and Shanghai as its most populous urban area. Its geography features the vast Central Plain, deserts, subtropical and temperate forests, and towering mountain ranges such as the Himalayas. Major rivers including the Yangtze and the Yellow River flow across its landscape and have long shaped its settlement and agriculture. It ranks among the largest countries by land area and possesses a wide diversity of climates and terrains.",
  "clipperton i.": "Clipperton Island, also known as Clipperton Atoll, is an uninhabited coral atoll in the eastern Pacific Ocean. It is the only French territory in the North Pacific, lying far from the French mainland and from French Polynesia, and closest to the Mexican port of Acapulco. The island was documented by French merchant-explorers in 1711 and formally claimed as part of the French protectorate of Tahiti in 1858. American guano miners nonetheless began working the island in the early 1890s, contesting its control. A remote ring of coral enclosing a lagoon, it remains without permanent inhabitants.",
  "colombia": "Colombia, officially the Republic of Colombia, is a country in South America, with insular regions in North America. Its mainland is bordered by the Caribbean Sea to the north, Venezuela to the east, Brazil to the southeast, Peru and Ecuador to the south and southwest, the Pacific Ocean to the west, and Panama to the northwest. The country is divided into departments, with the Capital District of Bogota as its largest city and its principal financial and cultural hub. Other major urban centres include Medellin, Cali, Barranquilla, Cartagena, and Bucaramanga. Further urban areas include Pereira, Santa Marta, Cucuta, Ibague, Villavicencio, and Manizales.",
  "comoros": "The Comoros, officially the Union of the Comoros, is an archipelagic country made up of three islands off the coast of Southeast Africa. It lies at the northern end of the Mozambique Channel in the Indian Ocean, with Moroni as its capital and largest city. Islam is the predominant religion of the population and the official state religion. The country proclaimed its independence from France in 1975. It has three official languages: Comorian, French, and Arabic.",
  "congo": "The Republic of the Congo, commonly called Congo-Brazzaville after its capital, is a country on the western coast of Central Africa, lying to the west of the lower Congo River. It borders Gabon, Cameroon, the Central African Republic, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, the Angolan exclave of Cabinda, and the Atlantic Ocean. The region was long home to Bantu-speaking peoples and precolonial states such as the Kingdom of Loango and the Tio (Teke) Kingdom before France colonized it in the late nineteenth century and administered it as the Middle Congo within French Equatorial Africa. It became independent from France in August 1960, and its politics have since been shaped by periods of Marxist-Leninist single-party rule, civil conflict, and the long dominance of President Denis Sassou Nguesso. Its economy is heavily dependent on petroleum, and it should not be confused with the larger neighboring Democratic Republic of the Congo across the river.",
  "cook is.": "The Cook Islands are an island country and associated state of New Zealand in Polynesia, part of Oceania, in the South Pacific Ocean. The country consists of fifteen islands scattered across a large expanse of ocean. The capital is Avarua, located on the island of Rarotonga. The Cook Islands are self-governing while in free association with New Zealand. Their exclusive economic zone covers a vast area of the surrounding ocean.",
  "coral sea is.": "The Coral Sea Islands Territory is an external territory of Australia lying in the Coral Sea, north-east of Queensland. It encompasses a large area of ocean scattered with small islands and reefs, though their combined land area is very small. Apart from a small staff of Bureau of Meteorology employees at a weather station on Willis Island, the territory is uninhabited. The islands and reefs were charted in the early 1800s, and some were briefly mined for guano between the 1870s and 1880s. A weather monitoring station was established on Willis Island in 1921 and remains its main human presence.",
  "costa rica": "Costa Rica, officially the Republic of Costa Rica, is a country in Central America. It borders Nicaragua to the north, the Caribbean Sea to the northeast, Panama to the southeast, and the Pacific Ocean to the southwest, and shares a maritime border with Ecuador to the south of Cocos Island. Its capital and largest city is San José, which anchors a surrounding metropolitan area. Humans have been present in the region since between roughly 7,000 and 10,000 BC. Various indigenous peoples inhabited the territory before it was colonized by Spain in the 16th century.",
  "cotonou": "Cotonou is the largest city and seat of government of Benin. It lies in the southeast of the country, between the Atlantic Ocean and Lake Nokoué. It serves as the administrative heart of the republic, home to most government buildings, government departments, and foreign embassies. The official capital, where the national legislature sits, is the smaller city of Porto-Novo. The urban area continues to expand, notably toward the west.",
  "croatia": "Croatia, officially the Republic of Croatia, is a country in Central and Southeast Europe, on the coast of the Adriatic Sea. It borders Slovenia to the northwest, Hungary to the northeast, Serbia to the east, Bosnia and Herzegovina and Montenegro to the southeast, and shares a maritime border with Italy to the west. The Croatian archipelago contains over 1,000 islands and islets, the largest such territory on the Adriatic. Its capital, largest city, and main cultural and economic centre is Zagreb. Other major urban centres include Split, Rijeka, and Osijek.",
  "cuba": "Cuba, officially the Republic of Cuba, is an island country in the Caribbean. It comprises the main island of Cuba along with thousands of smaller islands, islets, and cays. Situated at the convergence of the Caribbean Sea, the Gulf of Mexico, and the Atlantic Ocean, it lies east of the Yucatán Peninsula, south of Florida and the Bahamas, west of Hispaniola, and north of Jamaica and the Cayman Islands. Havana is the capital and largest city. Cuba is among the most populous countries in the Caribbean.",
  "curaçao": "Curaçao, officially the Country of Curaçao, is a constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands. It is an island country in the southern Caribbean Sea, in the Dutch Caribbean region, lying north of Venezuela and southeast of Aruba. Curaçao includes the main island of the same name and the much smaller, uninhabited island of Klein Curaçao. Its capital is Willemstad. Its name Klein Curaçao translates as \"Little Curaçao\".",
  "cyprus": "Cyprus, officially the Republic of Cyprus, is an island country in the eastern Mediterranean Sea, off the coast of the Levant mainland in West Asia. It is among the largest and most populous islands in the Mediterranean, and it is divided along the United Nations Buffer Zone between the internationally recognised Republic of Cyprus and the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus, which is recognised only by Turkey. The south of the island also hosts the British sovereign military bases of Akrotiri and Dhekelia. The capital and largest city is Nicosia. Cyprus was first settled by hunter-gatherers around 13,000 years ago, with farming communities emerging by the 9th millennium BC.",
  "czechia": "The Czech Republic, also known as Czechia and historically as Bohemia, is a landlocked country in Central Europe. It is bordered by Austria to the south, Germany to the west, Poland to the northeast, and Slovakia to the southeast. The country has a hilly landscape and a mostly temperate continental and oceanic climate. Its capital and largest city is Prague, while other major cities and urban areas include Brno, Ostrava, Plzeň, and Liberec. The Duchy of Bohemia was founded in the late 9th century under Great Moravia.",
  "côte d'ivoire": "Ivory Coast, also known as Côte d'Ivoire and officially the Republic of Côte d'Ivoire, is a country on the southern coast of West Africa. Its political capital, Yamoussoukro, lies in the centre of the country, while Abidjan is its largest city and economic centre. It borders Guinea and Mali to the northwest, Liberia to the west, Burkina Faso to the northeast, Ghana to the east, and the Atlantic Ocean's Gulf of Guinea to the south. It is one of the most populous countries in West Africa. Its official language is French, and indigenous languages are also widely used, including Bété, Baoulé, Dyula, Dan, Anyin, and Cebaara Senufo.",
  "dahomey": "The Kingdom of Dahomey was a West African kingdom located within the present-day Republic of Benin that existed from approximately 1600 until 1904. It developed on the Abomey Plateau among the Fon people in the early 17th century and became a regional power in the 18th century. It expanded south to conquer key coastal cities such as Whydah, gaining unhindered access to the Atlantic slave trade. Ending its tributary status to the Oyo Empire, Dahomey became a key regional state for much of the middle 19th century. European visitors extensively documented the kingdom, making it one of the most familiar African states known to Europeans.",
  "dem. rep. congo": "The Democratic Republic of the Congo, also known as DR Congo, Congo-Kinshasa, or simply the Congo, and formerly named Zaire, is a country in Central Africa. By land area, it is the second-largest country in Africa and among the largest in the world. It is one of the most populous countries in Africa and the most populous Francophone country in the world. French is the official and most widely spoken language. There are over 200 indigenous languages, of which Lingala is among the most widely spoken.",
  "denmark": "Denmark is a Nordic country in Northern Europe. It is the metropole and most populous constituent of the Kingdom of Denmark, a unitary state that also includes the autonomous territories of the Faroe Islands and Greenland in the North Atlantic. Metropolitan Denmark consists of the northern Jutland peninsula and an archipelago of hundreds of islands. It is the southernmost of the Scandinavian countries, lying southwest of Sweden, south of Norway, and north of Germany, with which it shares a short border. Denmark proper is situated between the North Sea to the west and the Baltic Sea to the east.",
  "dhekelia": "Dhekelia, formally Dhekelia Cantonment, is a British military base on the island of Cyprus, administered as part of the Sovereign Base Areas of Akrotiri and Dhekelia, a British Overseas Territory. It is the larger of the two British military bases on the island and is home to Alexander Barracks. It forms part of British Forces Cyprus. The cantonment contains the village of Dasaki Achnas and a portion of the village of Pergamos. It also encloses several Cypriot enclaves, including Xylotymbo, Ormidhia, and the Dhekelia Power Station.",
  "djibouti": "Djibouti, officially the Republic of Djibouti, is a country in the Horn of Africa. It is bordered by Somalia to the south, Ethiopia to the southwest, Eritrea to the north, and the Red Sea and the Gulf of Aden to the east. In antiquity, the territory, together with neighbouring lands, was part of the Land of Punt, while nearby Zeila was later the seat of the medieval Adal and Ifat Sultanates. In the late 19th century, the colony of French Somaliland was established after local Somali and Afar sultans signed treaties with the French. Its railroad to Dire Dawa and later Addis Ababa allowed it to quickly supersede Zeila as the port for southern Ethiopia and the Ogaden.",
  "dominica": "Dominica, officially the Commonwealth of Dominica, is an island country in the Caribbean. It is part of the Windward Islands chain in the Lesser Antilles archipelago in the Caribbean Sea. The capital, Roseau, is located on the western side of the island. Its closest neighbours are two overseas departments of France: Guadeloupe to the northwest and Martinique to the south-southeast. The island is notably mountainous, with its highest point at Morne Diablotins.",
  "dominican rep.": "The Dominican Republic is a country occupying the eastern portion of the Caribbean island of Hispaniola in the Greater Antilles. It shares a maritime border with Puerto Rico to the east and a land border with Haiti to the west, taking up the eastern five-eighths of Hispaniola. Along with Saint Martin, Hispaniola is one of only two islands in the Caribbean shared by two sovereign states. It is one of the larger and more populous nations of the Antilles, second in area only to Cuba. Its capital and principal metropolitan center is Santo Domingo.",
  "dominican republic": "The Dominican Republic is a country occupying the eastern portion of the Caribbean island of Hispaniola in the Greater Antilles. It shares a maritime border with Puerto Rico to the east and a land border with Haiti to the west, taking up the eastern five-eighths of Hispaniola. Along with Saint Martin, Hispaniola is one of only two islands in the Caribbean shared by two sovereign states. It is one of the larger and more populous nations of the Antilles, second in area only to Cuba. Its capital and principal metropolitan center is Santo Domingo.",
  "dutch guiana": "Dutch Guiana, more formally the colony of Surinam, was a Dutch plantation colony on the northeastern coast of South America and the predecessor of the modern country of Suriname. It came under Dutch control in 1667, when the Netherlands took the settlement from England during the Second Anglo-Dutch War and retained it in the settlement that also transferred New Amsterdam to the English. Its colonial economy was built on plantations producing crops such as sugar, coffee, cotton, and cacao, worked for nearly two centuries by enslaved Africans until slavery was abolished in 1863. After emancipation the colony recruited large numbers of indentured labourers from British India and the Dutch East Indies, giving the territory a markedly diverse population. Dutch Guiana remained a colony of the Netherlands until 1954, when it became a constituent country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands, and it achieved full independence as Suriname in 1975.",
  "ecuador": "Ecuador, officially the Republic of Ecuador, is a country in northwestern South America, bordered by Colombia to the north, Peru to the east and south, and the Pacific Ocean to the west. Its territory also includes the Galápagos Islands, lying in the Pacific well to the west of the mainland. The capital is Quito, while the largest city is Guayaquil. The land was home to several indigenous peoples who were gradually incorporated into the Inca Empire during the 15th century before Spanish colonization in the 16th century. It achieved independence in 1820 as part of Gran Colombia, emerging as a sovereign state in 1830.",
  "egypt": "Egypt, officially the Arab Republic of Egypt, is a country spanning the northeast corner of Africa and, via the Sinai Peninsula, the southwest corner of Asia. It is bordered by the Mediterranean Sea to the north, Palestine and Israel to the northeast, the Red Sea to the east, Sudan and the Sahara to the south, and Libya to the west, with the Gulf of Aqaba separating it from Jordan and Saudi Arabia. Cairo is the capital, largest city, and leading cultural center, while Alexandria is the second-largest city and an important hub of industry and tourism. It is one of the most populous countries of both the Arab world and the African continent. It also ranks among the most populous countries in the world as a whole.",
  "el salvador": "El Salvador, officially the Republic of El Salvador, is a country in Central America. It is bordered to the northeast by Honduras, to the northwest by Guatemala, and to the south by the Pacific Ocean. Its capital and largest city is San Salvador. Among the Mesoamerican nations that historically controlled the region were the Maya. The Cuzcatlecs were also among the peoples who held sway over the area.",
  "eq. guinea": "Equatorial Guinea, officially the Republic of Equatorial Guinea, is a country on the west coast of Central Africa and the only Spanish-speaking country in Africa. Formerly the colony of Spanish Guinea, its post-independence name refers to its location both near the Equator and within the African region of Guinea. Its territory includes a mainland section as well as islands, among them Bioko in the Gulf of Guinea. Most of its people belong to the Fang, the country's dominant ethnic group. The Bubi people, indigenous to Bioko, form the second-largest group.",
  "eritrea": "Eritrea, officially the State of Eritrea, is a country in the Horn of Africa region of East Africa. Its capital and largest city is Asmara. It is bordered by Ethiopia to the south, Sudan to the west, and Djibouti to the southeast. The northeastern and eastern parts of the country have an extensive coastline along the Red Sea. Its territory also includes the Dahlak Archipelago and several of the Hanish Islands.",
  "estonia": "Estonia, officially the Republic of Estonia, is a country in the Baltic region of Northern Europe. It is bordered to the north by the Gulf of Finland across from Finland, to the west by the Baltic Sea across from Sweden, to the south by Latvia, and to the east by Russia. Its territory consists of the mainland together with the larger islands of Saaremaa and Hiiumaa and more than two thousand smaller islands and islets on the eastern coast of the Baltic Sea. The capital, Tallinn, along with the city of Tartu, are the country's two largest urban areas. The Estonian language, of the Finnic family, is the official language and the first language of most of its people.",
  "eswatini": "Eswatini, formally the Kingdom of Eswatini and historically called KaNgwane, is a landlocked country in Southern Africa also known by its former name Swaziland. It is bordered by South Africa on all sides except the east, where it shares a border with Mozambique. It is one of the smallest countries in Africa, measuring no more than a couple hundred kilometers in either direction. Despite its size, its climate and topography are diverse, ranging from a cool and mountainous highveld to a hot and dry lowveld. The executive capital and largest city is Mbabane, while Lobamba serves as the legislative and second capital.",
  "ethiopia": "Ethiopia, officially the Federal Democratic Republic of Ethiopia, is a landlocked country in the Horn of Africa region of East Africa. It shares borders with Eritrea to the north, Djibouti to the northeast, Somalia to the east, Kenya to the south, and South Sudan to the west. Sudan lies to its northwest. It is one of the most populous countries in the world and among the most populous in Africa. The national capital and largest city, Addis Ababa, lies just west of the East African Rift, which splits the country between the African and Somali tectonic plates.",
  "faeroe is.": "The Faroe Islands, also known as the Faroes, are an archipelago in the North Atlantic Ocean and an autonomous territory of the Kingdom of Denmark. They lie between Iceland, Norway, and the Hebrides and Shetland isles of Scotland. The official language is Faroese, which is partially mutually intelligible with Icelandic. The terrain is rugged, dominated by fjords and cliffs with sparse vegetation and few trees. Owing to their proximity to the Arctic Circle they experience long summer twilight and short winter days, yet a subpolar oceanic climate and the Gulf Stream keep temperatures mild year-round.",
  "falkland is.": "The Falkland Islands, known in Spanish as the Islas Malvinas and commonly called the Falklands, are an archipelago in the South Atlantic Ocean on the Patagonian Shelf. The principal islands lie a few hundred kilometers east of South America's southern Patagonian coast, at a latitude of about 52 degrees south. The archipelago comprises East Falkland, West Falkland, and hundreds of smaller islands. As a British Overseas Territory, the Falklands have internal self-governance while the United Kingdom takes responsibility for their defence and foreign affairs. The capital and largest settlement is Stanley, on East Falkland.",
  "fiji": "Fiji, officially the Republic of Fiji, is an archipelagic country in Melanesia, part of Oceania in the South Pacific Ocean. It lies to the north-northeast of New Zealand across a broad stretch of open ocean. Fiji consists of an archipelago of more than three hundred islands, of which about a hundred are permanently inhabited, together with more than five hundred islets. The most outlying island group is Ono-i-Lau. The great majority of the population lives on the two major islands, Viti Levu and Vanua Levu.",
  "finland": "Finland, officially the Republic of Finland, is a Nordic country in Northern Europe. It borders Sweden to the northwest, Norway to the north, and Russia to the east, with the Gulf of Bothnia to the west and the Gulf of Finland to the south, opposite Estonia. Its capital and largest city is Helsinki. Finnish and Swedish are its official languages, with Finnish spoken by the great majority of the population. Swedish is the mother tongue of a smaller share of its inhabitants.",
  "fr. polynesia": "French Polynesia is an overseas collectivity of France and its sole overseas country, located in the South Pacific Ocean. It comprises well over a hundred geographically dispersed islands and atolls stretching across more than two thousand kilometres of ocean. The territory is associated with the European Union as an overseas country and territory. The largest share of its population lives in the Society Islands, with the remainder spread across the rest of the archipelago. It is classified by the United Nations as a non-self-governing territory.",
  "fr. s. antarctic lands": "The French Southern and Antarctic Lands, abbreviated TAAF, form an overseas territory of France scattered across the far southern reaches of the globe. The territory includes Adélie Land, the French claim on the continent of Antarctica. It also encompasses the Crozet Islands and the Kerguelen Islands, groups of volcanic islands in the southern Indian Ocean south of Madagascar and southeast of Africa. Saint Paul and Amsterdam Islands, lying to the north of the Kerguelen group, are likewise part of the territory. Together these scattered island groups and the Antarctic claim make up the whole of the territory.",
  "france": "France, officially the French Republic, is a country primarily located in Western Europe, alongside overseas regions and territories on several continents. Its overseas holdings include French Guiana in South America, Saint Pierre and Miquelon in the North Atlantic, the French West Indies, and numerous islands in Oceania and the Indian Ocean. Metropolitan France shares borders with Belgium and Luxembourg to the north, Germany to the northeast, Switzerland to the east, Italy and Monaco to the southeast, and Andorra and Spain to the south, with a maritime border with the United Kingdom to the northwest. Its metropolitan territory extends from the Rhine to the Atlantic Ocean and from the Mediterranean Sea to the English Channel and the North Sea. Its overseas presence spans South America, the North Atlantic, the West Indies, Oceania, and the Indian Ocean.",
  "french guiana": "French Guiana, also known by its French name Guyane, is an overseas department and region of France on the northern coast of South America. It is bordered by Suriname to the west and Brazil to the east and south, and lies within the Guianas and the West Indies. It is the second-largest region of France and the largest outermost region within the European Union, roughly one-seventh the size of European France. It has a very low population density. Its territory covers a large land area on the northern South American coast.",
  "french indochina": "French Indochina, officially the Indochinese Union and later the Indochinese Federation, was a grouping of French dependent territories in Southeast Asia established in 1887 and dissolved in 1954. It began as a federation of French colonies and later became a confederation of French associated states. Its constituent parts included Cambodia, Laos, the leased territory of Guangzhouwan, Cochinchina, and the Vietnamese regions of Tonkin and Annam. It served as the framework for French colonial rule across the region for several decades. In 1949, Vietnam was reunited and regained Cochinchina.",
  "futa jalon": "Fouta Djallon is a highland region in West Africa, located in the center of Guinea. It roughly corresponds with the area known as Middle Guinea. The region lies in the interior of Guinea, in West Africa. Its name is also rendered in Fula and Arabic forms. It is one of the recognized geographic regions of Guinea.",
  "futa toro": "Futa Toro, often called simply the Futa, is a semidesert region along the middle run of the Senegal River, located in present-day Senegal. It is historically significant as the center of several Fulani states and as a source of jihad armies and of migrants to Fouta Djallon. The name combines Futa, a general term the Fulbe applied to the areas they inhabited, with Toro, the region's own identity, likely derived from the ancient kingdom of Takrur. Most of its people speak Pulaar, a dialect of the Fula language spoken across West Africa from Senegal to Cameroon. They identify themselves through this language as the Haalpulaar'en, meaning those who speak Pulaar.",
  "gabon": "Gabon, officially the Gabonese Republic, is a country on the Atlantic coast of Central Africa, lying on the equator. It is bordered by Equatorial Guinea to the northwest, Cameroon to the north, the Republic of the Congo to the east and south, and the Gulf of Guinea to the west. Its landscape includes coastal plains, interior mountains such as the Cristal Mountains and the Chaillu Massif, and savanna in the east. Libreville is the country's capital and largest city. Its original inhabitants were the Bambenga.",
  "gambia": "The Gambia, officially the Republic of The Gambia, is a country in West Africa and the smallest country in continental Africa. It is bounded by Senegal on all sides except for its western coast, which faces the Atlantic Ocean. Its territory follows both banks of the lower Gambia River, which flows through the center of the country and empties into the Atlantic, giving the nation its distinctive elongated shape. Its capital is the island city of Banjul, formerly called Bathurst during the colonial era. Banjul is the most extensive metropolitan area in the country.",
  "georgia": "Georgia most commonly refers to a country in the South Caucasus region. The name may also refer to a state in the southeastern United States. As a place name it is shared by these two otherwise distinct entities. The South Caucasus country is one of its principal meanings. The United States state is the other most common meaning of the name.",
  "germany": "Germany, officially the Federal Republic of Germany, is a country in Western and Central Europe. It lies between the Baltic Sea and the North Sea to the north and reaches the Alps to the south. It borders Denmark to the north; Poland and the Czech Republic to the east; Austria and Switzerland to the south; and France, Luxembourg, Belgium, and the Netherlands to the west. It is organized as a federation of sixteen constituent states and is among the most populous countries in Europe. Its capital and largest city is Berlin, while Frankfurt is a major financial centre and the Ruhr is its largest urban area.",
  "ghana": "Ghana, officially the Republic of Ghana, is a country in West Africa. It lies along the Gulf of Guinea and the Atlantic Ocean to the south and shares borders with Ivory Coast to the west, Burkina Faso to the north, and Togo to the east. Its territory spans varied ecologies, ranging from coastal savannas to tropical rainforests. It is among the more populous countries of West Africa and the wider continent. Its capital and most populous city is Accra.",
  "gibraltar": "Gibraltar is a British Overseas Territory and city at the southern tip of the Iberian Peninsula, on the Bay of Gibraltar near where the Mediterranean Sea meets the Atlantic Ocean through the Strait of Gibraltar. It is bordered to the north by Spain, in the area known as the Campo de Gibraltar. Its landscape is dominated by the Rock of Gibraltar, at the foot of which lies a densely populated town area. Its inhabitants are primarily Gibraltarians. It was founded as a permanent watchtower by the Almohads in 1160.",
  "greece": "Greece, officially the Hellenic Republic, occupies the southern tip of the Balkan peninsula in Southeast Europe. Made up of a mainland and thousands of islands, it has the longest coastline on the Mediterranean, with the Ionian Sea to the west and the Aegean Sea to the east. It is bordered by Albania to the northwest and by North Macedonia and Bulgaria to the north, while Turkey lies to the east across both land and the Aegean. The capital, Athens, is the largest city, followed by Thessaloniki and Patras. The country is organized into nine regions, and its thousands of islands make up much of its territory.",
  "greenland": "Greenland is an autonomous territory of the Kingdom of Denmark. It is the largest of the kingdom's three constituent parts by land area, the others being Denmark proper and the Faroe Islands. Its people are citizens of Denmark and thus of the European Union, although Greenland itself is not part of the EU. It is the world's largest island, lying between the Arctic and Atlantic oceans, east of the Canadian Arctic Archipelago. It shares a short border with Canada on Hans Island in the far north.",
  "grenada": "Grenada is an archipelagic country of the West Indies in the eastern Caribbean Sea. It is the southernmost of the Windward Islands, lying directly south of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines. It also sits to the north of Trinidad and the South American mainland. The country consists of the main island of Grenada together with the smaller islands of Carriacou and Petite Martinique, plus several islets to the north that form part of the Grenadines. Its capital is St George's, situated on the main island.",
  "griqualand west": "Griqualand West is a region of central South Africa that now forms part of the Northern Cape Province. It was inhabited by the Griqua, a semi-nomadic, Afrikaans-speaking people of mixed-race origin who established several states beyond the expanding frontier of the Cape Colony. The area was also an ancestral home to the Tswana and Khoisan peoples. In 1873 it was proclaimed a British colony, with its capital at Kimberley, and in 1880 it was annexed by the Cape Colony. When the Union of South Africa was formed in 1910, Griqualand West became part of the Cape Province while retaining its own regional sports teams.",
  "guadeloupe": "Guadeloupe is an overseas department and region of the French Republic located in the Caribbean. It is made up of several inhabited islands, chiefly Basse-Terre, Grande-Terre, Marie-Galante, La Désirade, and the Îles des Saintes, along with numerous smaller islets. It lies south of Antigua and Barbuda and Montserrat and north of Dominica. The capital, Basse-Terre, sits on the southwestern coast of Basse-Terre Island, while the main centre of business is Pointe-à-Pitre on Grande-Terre Island. The most populous city is Les Abymes, also on Grande-Terre Island.",
  "guam": "Guam is an island that is an organized, unincorporated territory of the United States in the Micronesia subregion of the western Pacific Ocean. Its capital is Hagåtña, while its most populous village is Dededo. It is the westernmost point and territory of the United States as measured from the country's geographic center. In Oceania, Guam is the largest and southernmost of the Mariana Islands and the largest island in Micronesia. The geographic center from which it is measured is marked by point Udall.",
  "guatemala": "Guatemala, officially the Republic of Guatemala, is a country in northern Central America. It is bordered by Mexico to the north and west, Belize to the northeast, Honduras to the east, and El Salvador to the southeast, with the Pacific Ocean to the south and the Gulf of Honduras to the northeast. The territory of modern Guatemala hosted the core of the Maya civilization, which extended across Mesoamerica. In the 16th century most of this land was conquered by the Spanish and claimed as part of the viceroyalty of New Spain. Guatemala attained independence from Spain and Mexico in 1821.",
  "guernsey": "Guernsey is the second-largest of the Channel Islands, lying to the west of the Cotentin Peninsula in Normandy. It is the largest island in the Bailiwick of Guernsey, which also includes the inhabited islands of Alderney, Herm, Jethou, Lihou, and Sark, along with many smaller islets and rocks. Guernsey formed part of the Duchy of Normandy until 1204, when the Channel Islands remained loyal to the English crown after splitting from mainland Normandy. In 1290 the Channel Islands were divided administratively, and Guernsey became part of the Bailiwick of Guernsey. Most of the bailiwick's population lives on the island of Guernsey itself.",
  "guinea": "Guinea, officially the Republic of Guinea, is a coastal country in West Africa. It borders the Atlantic Ocean to the west, Guinea-Bissau to the northwest, Senegal to the north, Mali to the northeast, Ivory Coast to the southeast, and Sierra Leone and Liberia to the south. It is sometimes called Guinea-Conakry, after its capital Conakry, to distinguish it from other territories in the region such as Guinea-Bissau and Equatorial Guinea. Formerly known as French Guinea, it achieved independence in 1958. The name distinguishes it from the wider eponymous region that shares the name Guinea.",
  "guinea-bissau": "Guinea-Bissau, officially the Republic of Guinea-Bissau, is a country in West Africa. It borders Senegal to the north and Guinea to the southeast. The region was once part of the kingdom of Kaabu and of the Mali Empire, and parts of Kaabu persisted into the 18th century. From the 16th century some areas came under the influence of the Portuguese Empire, and in the 19th century the territory was colonised as Portuguese Guinea. It takes its modern name from the former colony of Portuguese Guinea.",
  "guyana": "Guyana, officially the Co-operative Republic of Guyana, is a country on the northern coast of South America. It is bordered by the Atlantic Ocean to the north, Suriname to the east, Brazil to the south and southwest, and Venezuela to the west. It forms part of the region known as The Guianas. The capital and largest city is Georgetown, on the Atlantic coast. It is among the smallest and least densely populated of the sovereign states of mainland South America.",
  "haiti": "Haiti, officially the Republic of Haiti, is a country in the Caribbean on the island of Hispaniola, east of Cuba and Jamaica and south of The Bahamas. It occupies the western side of the island, which it shares with the Dominican Republic. Haiti is among the larger countries of the Caribbean by area and one of its most populous. The capital and largest city is Port-au-Prince. The island was originally inhabited by the Indigenous Taíno people before European colonization.",
  "heard i. and mcdonald is.": "The Territory of Heard Island and McDonald Islands is an Australian external territory in the southern Indian Ocean. Discovered in the mid-19th century, it is a group of sub-Antarctic volcanic islands lying on the Kerguelen Plateau. It sits far to the southwest of the Australian mainland and north of Antarctica. The territory contains Australia's only active volcanoes and its highest point outside the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mawson Peak. Uninhabited and difficult to reach, it has been described as one of the most remote places on Earth.",
  "honduras": "Honduras, officially the Republic of Honduras, is a country in Central America. It is bordered by Guatemala to the west, El Salvador to the southwest, and Nicaragua to the southeast, with the Pacific Ocean to the south at the Gulf of Fonseca and the Caribbean Sea to the north at the Gulf of Honduras. Its capital and largest city is Tegucigalpa. Before Spanish colonization in the sixteenth century, Honduras was home to several important Mesoamerican cultures, most notably the Maya. The Spanish introduced Catholicism and the now-predominant Spanish language, along with customs that blended with indigenous culture.",
  "hong kong": "Hong Kong is a special administrative region of China, situated on the country's southern coast just south of Shenzhen. It consists of Hong Kong Island, the Kowloon Peninsula, and the New Territories, and ranks among the most densely populated territories in the world. It was established as a colony of the British Empire after the Qing dynasty ceded Hong Kong Island following its defeat in the First Opium War. The colony expanded to Kowloon in 1860 and was further extended when the United Kingdom obtained a 99-year lease of the New Territories in 1898. This colonial legacy shaped its distinct status, blending Chinese and British influences within a single densely built maritime hub.",
  "hungary": "Hungary is a landlocked country in Central Europe, spanning much of the Carpathian Basin. It is bordered by Slovakia to the north, Ukraine to the northeast, Romania to the east and southeast, Serbia to the south, Croatia and Slovenia to the southwest, and Austria to the west. The land lies within the Danube River's drainage basin and is dominated by great lowland plains. Its population consists mostly of ethnic Hungarians, or Magyars, alongside a significant Romani minority. Hungarian is the official language and is among the few in Europe that lie outside the Indo-European family.",
  "ibadan": "Ibadan is the capital and most populous city of Oyo State in Nigeria, and bears a Yoruba name. It ranks among the largest cities in Nigeria and is the country's largest city by land area. At the time of Nigeria's independence in 1960, it was the largest and most populous city in the country, and among the most populous in Africa. It has since been ranked one of the fastest-growing cities in sub-Saharan Africa. It remains a major urban center of the country.",
  "iceland": "Iceland is a Nordic island country between the Arctic Ocean and the North Atlantic Ocean, lying on the Mid-Atlantic Ridge between Europe and North America. It is culturally and politically linked with Europe and is the region's westernmost and most sparsely populated country. Its capital and largest city is Reykjavík, home to a large share of the country's residents. The official language is Icelandic. Situated on a rift between tectonic plates, the island is highly geologically active, with geysers and frequent volcanic eruptions.",
  "imerina": "The Kingdom of Imerina, also known as the Kingdom of Merina or the Kingdom of Madagascar, was a pre-colonial state off the coast of Southeast Africa that came to dominate most of what is now Madagascar. It spread outward from Imerina, the Central Highlands region primarily inhabited by the Merina ethnic group, with a spiritual capital at Ambohimanga and a political capital to the west at Antananarivo, still the seat of government today. Its rulers descended from a long line of hereditary Merina royalty tracing back to Andriamanelo, traditionally credited with founding Imerina. By the 18th century the kingdom had extended its authority across much of the island. Its monarchs reigned over greater Madagascar through the 19th century until the state's dissolution.",
  "imperial japan": "The Empire of Japan, also known as Imperial Japan, was the period of Japanese history that began with the Meiji Restoration in 1868 and ended with the ratification of the postwar Constitution of Japan in 1947. At its height it encompassed the Japanese archipelago along with the Kuril Islands, Karafuto, Korea, and Taiwan. Dependent territories such as the South Seas Mandate and leased concessions like the Kwantung Leased Territory were governed as outlying possessions rather than internal parts of the empire. The era was marked by territorial expansion across East Asia and the Pacific. It came to a close with the establishment of a new constitutional order.",
  "india": "India, officially the Republic of India, is a country in South Asia and one of the largest nations in the world by area. Bounded by the Indian Ocean to the south, the Arabian Sea to the southwest, and the Bay of Bengal to the southeast, it shares land borders with Pakistan to the west; China, Nepal, and Bhutan to the north; and Bangladesh and Myanmar to the east. In the Indian Ocean it lies near Sri Lanka and the Maldives, while its Andaman and Nicobar Islands share maritime borders with Myanmar, Thailand, and Indonesia. Since gaining independence in 1947, it has been the world's most populous democracy. It is also the most populous country in the world.",
  "indonesia": "Indonesia, officially the Republic of Indonesia, is a country in Southeast Asia and Oceania, spanning the seas between the Indian and Pacific oceans. Comprising over 17,000 islands, including Sumatra, Java, Sulawesi, and parts of Borneo and New Guinea, it is the world's largest archipelagic state. It contains significant areas of wilderness that support one of the world's highest levels of biodiversity. It shares land borders with Papua New Guinea, Timor-Leste, and Malaysia, as well as maritime borders with several other countries, including Australia, Singapore, and the Philippines. This sprawling island geography underpins its rich ecological diversity.",
  "iran": "Iran, officially the Islamic Republic of Iran and historically known as Persia, is a country in West Asia. It borders Iraq to the west; Turkey, Azerbaijan, and Armenia to the northwest; the Caspian Sea to the north; Turkmenistan to the northeast; Afghanistan to the east; Pakistan to the southeast; and the Gulf of Oman and the Persian Gulf to the south. The country is divided into five regions comprising thirty-one provinces. Tehran is the nation's capital and largest city and serves as its primary economic center. It ranks among the larger countries in the world in both geographic size and population.",
  "iraq": "Iraq, officially the Republic of Iraq, is a country in West Asia within the Middle East. It is bordered by Saudi Arabia to the south, Turkey to the north, Iran to the east, the Persian Gulf and Kuwait to the southeast, Jordan to the southwest, and Syria to the west. Baghdad is the capital and largest city in the country. Beginning in the 6th millennium BC, the fertile plains between the Tigris and Euphrates rivers, known as Mesopotamia, fostered the rise of early cities, civilizations, and empires. These included Sumer, Akkad, Babylonia, and Assyria.",
  "ireland": "Ireland is an island in the North Atlantic Ocean, in Northwestern Europe. Geopolitically it is divided between the Republic of Ireland, a sovereign state covering five-sixths of the island, and Northern Ireland, which is part of the United Kingdom and covers the remaining sixth. It is separated from Great Britain to its east by the North Channel, the Irish Sea, and St George's Channel. Ireland is the second-largest island of the British Isles, the third-largest in Europe, and among the largest in the world. Its history and identity are shaped by this partition and its close, complex relationship with neighboring Britain.",
  "isle of man": "The Isle of Man, known in Manx as Mannin, is a self-governing British Crown Dependency in the Irish Sea, lying between Great Britain and Ireland. As head of state, the British monarch holds the title Lord of Mann and is represented on the island by a Lieutenant Governor. The government of the United Kingdom is responsible for the island's military defence and represents it abroad, though the Isle of Man retains a separate international identity. Humans have lived on the island since prehistoric times, well before 6500 BC. Gaelic cultural influence and settlement arrived by the 5th century AD, and the Manx language emerged as a branch of the Goidelic languages.",
  "israel": "Israel, officially the State of Israel, is a country in the Southern Levant region of West Asia. It is bordered by Lebanon to the north, Syria to the northeast, Jordan to the east, and Egypt to the southwest. Its western coast lies on the Mediterranean Sea, its southern tip reaches the Red Sea, and to the east lies Earth's lowest point near the Dead Sea. Jerusalem is the government seat and proclaimed capital, while Tel Aviv is the largest urban area and economic center. The Land of Israel, also called Palestine or the Holy Land, was home to the ancient Canaanites and later the kingdoms of Israel and Judah and Hasmonean Judea.",
  "italy": "Italy, officially the Italian Republic, is a country in Southern and Western Europe. It consists of a peninsula that extends into the Mediterranean Sea, with the Alps along its northern land border, as well as numerous islands, notably Sicily and Sardinia. It shares land borders with France to the west; Switzerland and Austria to the north; Slovenia to the east; and the two enclaves of Vatican City and San Marino. Its capital and largest city is Rome, while other major cities include Milan, Naples, Turin, Palermo, Bologna, Florence, Genoa, Bari, and Venice. It is one of the larger countries in Europe by area and among the most populous member states of the European Union.",
  "ivory coast": "Ivory Coast, also known as Côte d'Ivoire and officially the Republic of Côte d'Ivoire, is a country on the southern coast of West Africa. Its political capital, Yamoussoukro, lies in the centre of the country, while Abidjan is its largest city and economic centre. It borders Guinea and Mali to the northwest, Liberia to the west, Burkina Faso to the northeast, and Ghana to the east, with the Atlantic Ocean's Gulf of Guinea forming its southern coast. It is one of the most populous countries in West Africa. French is its official language, while numerous indigenous languages, including Bété, Baoulé, Dyula, Dan, Anyin, and Cebaara Senufo, remain widely used.",
  "jamaica": "Jamaica is an island country in the Caribbean and the third-largest island in the Greater Antilles, after Cuba and the island of Hispaniola. It lies south of Cuba, west of Hispaniola, and southeast of the Cayman Islands. Kingston is the country's capital and largest city. Jamaica is one of the more populous Anglophone countries in the Americas and a leading population centre within the Caribbean. Hispaniola, its neighbour to the west, contains both Haiti and the Dominican Republic.",
  "japan": "Japan is an island country in East Asia, located in the Pacific Ocean off the northeast coast of the Asian mainland. It is bordered to the west by the Sea of Japan and extends from the Sea of Okhotsk in the north to the East China Sea in the south. The Japanese archipelago consists of four major islands alongside thousands of smaller ones, and the country is divided into 47 administrative prefectures and eight traditional regions. Most of its terrain is mountainous and heavily forested, concentrating agriculture and its highly urbanized population along the eastern coastal plains. It is one of the world's most populous countries.",
  "jersey": "Jersey, officially the Bailiwick of Jersey, is an autonomous and self-governing British Crown Dependency in northwestern Europe, lying off the Cotentin Peninsula of north-west France. The main island, Jersey, is the largest of the Channel Islands, and the bailiwick also includes several surrounding uninhabited islands and rocks. Although not a sovereign state, it has its own legal, fiscal, and governmental systems, on which basis it is regarded as a small nation or island country. Jèrriais, a Norman language, is part of its traditional cultural heritage. It is a Crown Dependency and thus lies outside the United Kingdom while being closely associated with the British Crown.",
  "jordan": "Jordan, officially the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan, is a country in the Southern Levant region of West Asia. It is bordered by Syria to the north, Iraq to the east, Saudi Arabia to the south, and both Israel and Palestine's West Bank to the west. The Jordan River, flowing into the Dead Sea, runs along its western border within the Jordan Rift Valley. In the southwest a small coastline along the Red Sea is separated by the Gulf of Aqaba from Egypt. Amman is the country's capital and largest city, as well as the most populous city in the Levant.",
  "kanem-bornu": "The Kanem–Bornu Empire was an empire based around Lake Chad that once ruled areas now part of Nigeria, Niger, Cameroon, Libya, Algeria, Sudan, and Chad. Sustained by the prosperous trans-Saharan trade, it was one of the oldest and longest-lived empires in world history and especially in African history. Its early history is poorly known, but it is believed to have been founded around the year 700, though later and earlier dates have been proposed. The Duguwa dynasty ruled from the capital Njimi in the Kanem region, in modern-day Chad. Its rulers used the title mai.",
  "kazakhstan": "Kazakhstan, officially the Republic of Kazakhstan, is a landlocked country situated primarily in Central Asia, with a portion of its territory extending into Eastern Europe. It borders Russia to the north and west, China to the east, Kyrgyzstan to the southeast, Uzbekistan to the south, and Turkmenistan to the southwest, and it has a coastline along the Caspian Sea. The capital is Astana, while the largest city and principal cultural and economic centre is Almaty, which served as the capital until 1997. It is the world's largest landlocked country and one of the largest countries overall by land area. Hilly plateaus and plains account for much of its vast territory, with lowlands forming another portion and mountainous regions along its southern and eastern frontiers.",
  "kenya": "Kenya, officially the Republic of Kenya, is a country located in East Africa. It is among the most populous countries on the African continent. Its capital and largest city is Nairobi, while the second-largest and oldest city is the port of Mombasa, located on Mombasa Island. Other major cities include Kisumu, Nakuru, and Eldoret. It ranks among the most populous nations in Africa and the wider world.",
  "kingdom of brazil": "The Kingdom of Brazil, in Portuguese Reino do Brasil, was a constituent kingdom of the United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves. As a constituent kingdom, it formed one of the component parts of that larger united kingdom. Its name in Portuguese was rendered Reino do Brasil. It was thus not an independent state but a member kingdom within the United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves. In this way Brazil held the formal standing of a kingdom within that union.",
  "kingdom of hawaii": "The Hawaiian Kingdom, also known as the Kingdom of Hawaiʻi, was an archipelagic country that eventually encompassed all of the inhabited Hawaiian Islands. It was established when Kamehameha I, then Aliʻi nui of Hawaii, conquered Oʻahu, Maui, Molokaʻi, and Lānaʻi and unified them under one government. The islands were fully unified when Kauaʻi and Niʻihau voluntarily joined the kingdom. Two major dynastic families ruled it, the House of Kamehameha and the House of Kalākaua. The kingdom gained diplomatic recognition from European powers and the United States.",
  "kiribati": "Kiribati, officially the Republic of Kiribati, is an archipelagic country spanning the Micronesia and Polynesia sub-regions of Oceania in the central Pacific Ocean. It comprises 32 atolls and other islands together with one remote raised coral island, Banaba. Its small land area is dispersed across an enormous expanse of ocean, giving it one of the largest maritime domains in the world. The spread of its islands, from Banaba in the west to Kiritimati in the east, straddles the equator and the 180th meridian. Because of this reach, the International Date Line bends around Kiribati and swings far to the east.",
  "kong": "The Kong Empire, also called the Wattara or Ouattara Empire, was a Dyula Muslim trading and military state founded in the early eighteenth century by Seku Watara and centered on the city of Kong in what is now northeastern Côte d'Ivoire. Established by Mandé merchants whose commercial network reached back to the Mali Empire, it grew into a largely decentralized power built on merchant houses and the protection of long-distance trade routes. At its height in the eighteenth century it extended across parts of present-day Côte d'Ivoire, Burkina Faso, Mali, and Ghana, becoming a major state south of the Niger River. Kong also flourished as a prominent center of Islamic scholarship and Quranic learning in the region. The empire was shattered in 1897–1898 when the forces of Samori Ture sacked and burned the city of Kong, after which the area fell under French colonial control.",
  "korea": "Korea is a peninsular region in East Asia consisting of the Korean Peninsula, Jeju Island, and smaller islands. Since the end of the Second World War in 1945, it has been politically divided at or near the 38th parallel between North Korea and South Korea. Both states proclaimed independence in 1948, and the two fought the Korean War from 1950 to 1953. The region is bordered by China to the north and Russia to the northeast, across the Amnok and Duman rivers, and is separated from Japan to the southeast by the Korea Strait. Known human habitation of the peninsula dates back tens of thousands of years.",
  "kosovo": "Kosovo, officially the Republic of Kosovo, is a landlocked country in Southeast Europe with partial diplomatic recognition. It is bordered by Albania to the southwest, Montenegro to the west, Serbia to the north and east, and North Macedonia to the southeast. The vast majority of its population are ethnic Albanians. Kosovo has a varied terrain of high plains, rolling hills, and mountains, some rising to considerable altitude. Its climate is mainly continental with some Mediterranean and Alpine influences.",
  "kuba": "The Kuba Kingdom was a Central African state in the south-central Congo basin, in the region bounded by the Sankuru, Lulua, and Kasai rivers in what is now the Democratic Republic of the Congo. Founded in the early seventeenth century under the reformer-king Shyaam a-Mbul a Ngoong, it united a cluster of Bushoong-speaking chiefdoms and neighbouring peoples into a single confederation. Its monarch bore the title nyim and was drawn from the ruling Bushoong clan, governing through an elaborate structure of councils, titled offices, and courts that checked royal authority. The kingdom became especially renowned for its arts, including intricate raffia textiles, geometric masks, decorated boxes, and carved ndop portrait figures of its kings. Relatively sheltered by its inland position, it flourished for more than two centuries before European colonization ended its independence in the late nineteenth century, though the Kuba monarchy survives as a traditional institution.",
  "kuwait": "Kuwait, officially the State of Kuwait, is a small country in West Asia situated at the head of the Persian Gulf on the northeastern edge of the Arabian Peninsula. It borders Iraq to the north and Saudi Arabia to the south, and lies close to mainland Iran across a short stretch of Iraqi coastline. The country has a coastline of roughly 500 kilometres along the Gulf. It is effectively a city-state, with most of its inhabitants concentrated in the urban agglomeration of Kuwait City, the capital and largest city. Its population includes both Kuwaiti citizens and a large body of foreign nationals drawn from many countries.",
  "kyrgyzstan": "Kyrgyzstan, officially the Kyrgyz Republic and formerly known as Kirghizia, is a landlocked country in the eastern part of Central Asia. It lies within the Tian Shan and Pamir mountain ranges and is bordered by Kazakhstan to the north, Uzbekistan to the west, Tajikistan to the south, and China to the east and southeast. Its capital and largest city is Bishkek, which sits on the northern border with Kazakhstan. Ethnic Kyrgyz form the majority of the population, alongside significant Uzbek and Russian minorities. The country's history spans a succession of cultures and empires.",
  "lagos": "Lagos, also called Lagos City and known in Yoruba as Èkó, is a large metropolitan port city in southwestern Nigeria. It ranks as the country's largest city and one of the most populous urban areas on the African continent, and among the fastest-growing megacities in the world. Lagos served as Nigeria's national capital until the government's 1991 decision to relocate the capital to Abuja in the centre of the country. It remains a major African financial centre and plays a leading role in the national economy. The city functions as the economic hub both of Lagos State and of Nigeria as a whole.",
  "laos": "Laos, officially the Lao People's Democratic Republic, is a country in mainland Southeast Asia and the region's only landlocked state. It is bordered by Myanmar and China to the northwest, Vietnam to the east, Cambodia to the southeast, and Thailand to the west and southwest. Its capital and most populous city is Vientiane. The country holds three UNESCO World Heritage Sites: the town of Luang Prabang, the temple complex of Vat Phou, and the Plain of Jars. The Boten–Vientiane railway, the Laotian section of the Laos–China Railway, connects Vientiane to Kunming.",
  "latvia": "Latvia, officially the Republic of Latvia, is a country in the Baltic region of northern Europe. It is one of the three Baltic states, together with Estonia to the north and Lithuania to the south. Latvia borders Russia to the east and Belarus to the southeast. It also shares a maritime border with Sweden to the west. The country has a temperate seasonal climate.",
  "lebanon": "Lebanon, officially the Lebanese Republic, is a country in the Levant region of West Asia. Set at the crossroads of the Mediterranean Basin and the Arabian Peninsula, it is bordered by Syria to the north and east, Israel to the south, and the Mediterranean Sea to the west, with Cyprus lying a short distance off its coast. Beirut is the country's capital and largest city. Human habitation in Lebanon dates back to around 5000 BC. Its position on the eastern Mediterranean has long placed it at a meeting point of the Mediterranean world and the Arabian Peninsula.",
  "lesotho": "Lesotho, officially the Kingdom of Lesotho, is a landlocked country in Southern Africa entirely surrounded by South Africa. It is the largest of the world's three sovereign enclaves, states completely encircled by a single other country. The kingdom lies within the Maloti Mountains and contains the highest peak in southern Africa. Its capital and largest city is Maseru. Its elevated terrain gives it a distinctive highland character within the region.",
  "liberia": "Liberia, officially the Republic of Liberia, is a country on the West African coast. It is bordered by Sierra Leone to the northwest, Guinea to the north, Ivory Coast to the east, and the Atlantic Ocean to the south and southwest. The official language is English, though over twenty indigenous languages are spoken, reflecting the country's ethnic and cultural diversity. Its capital and largest city is Monrovia. The country's position along the Atlantic seaboard has shaped its role in West Africa.",
  "libya": "Libya, officially the State of Libya, is a country in the Maghreb region of North Africa. It borders the Mediterranean Sea to the north, Egypt to the east, Sudan to the southeast, Chad to the south, Niger to the southwest, Algeria to the west, and Tunisia to the northwest. It is among the largest countries in Africa and the Arab world by area. The country maintains a territorial claim to an area of southeastern Algeria, south of the Libyan town of Ghat. Its capital and largest city is Tripoli, located in the northwest along the Mediterranean coast.",
  "liechtenstein": "Liechtenstein, officially the Principality of Liechtenstein, is a doubly landlocked microstate in the Central European Alps. It lies between Austria to the east and northeast and Switzerland to the north, west, and south. Formed in 1719, it became fully independent upon the dissolution of the German Confederation in 1866. The state is a monarchy headed by the reigning prince of Liechtenstein. Its Alpine setting and small size have shaped its identity as one of Europe's smallest sovereign states.",
  "lithuania": "Lithuania, officially the Republic of Lithuania, is a country in the Baltic region of Europe. It is one of the three Baltic states and lies on the eastern shore of the Baltic Sea, bordered by Latvia to the north, Belarus to the east and south, Poland to the south, and the Russian exclave of Kaliningrad Oblast to the southwest, with a maritime border with Sweden to the west. Its capital and largest city is Vilnius, while other major cities include Kaunas, Klaipėda, Šiauliai, and Panevėžys. Lithuanians are the titular nation and belong to the Baltic ethnolinguistic group. They speak Lithuanian, the country's national language.",
  "lozi": "The Lozi kingdom, also known as Barotseland or Bulozi, was a Central African state of the Lozi people (formerly called the Luyana) centered on the Barotse Floodplain of the upper Zambezi River in what is now western Zambia. Founded around the seventeenth century by settlers whose ruling dynasty traced its origins to the Lunda region, it was headed by a king titled the Litunga and grew into a substantial power through conquest, tribute, and control of the fertile flood-plain lands. Its society was shaped by the annual flooding of the Zambezi, most famously expressed in the Kuomboka ceremony, in which the Litunga and his people move from the inundated plain to higher ground. In the 1840s the kingdom was overrun by the Kololo, a Sotho-speaking group from the south, until a Lozi rebellion restored the indigenous monarchy in 1864. Under Litunga Lewanika in the late nineteenth century it entered treaties with the British South Africa Company, coming under British protection within what became Northern Rhodesia while the Lozi monarchy retained considerable internal authority.",
  "luba": "The Luba Empire was a Central African state that arose in the savanna and marshy grasslands around the Upemba Depression, in the region of the present-day southern Democratic Republic of the Congo. Its Bantu-speaking people were ruled by a sacred king who bore the title Mulopwe, and tradition traced the royal line to the hunter-hero Kalala Ilunga, who was said to have overthrown the earlier ruler Kongolo Mwamba. Growing out of communities skilled in ironworking, fishing, and farming, the kingdom drew its power from control of trade in salt, copper, and iron and from a tribute system that redistributed resources among a class of nobles. At its height in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries it extended its influence across a wide region through vassal tributary chiefdoms and shaped political models later adopted by neighbouring peoples. The empire declined amid nineteenth-century disruption from the East African slave and ivory trade and a succession dispute, and its lands were ultimately absorbed into the Congo Free State.",
  "lunda": "The Lunda Empire was a Central African state that flourished from the 17th to the 19th centuries in the savanna region spanning present-day Democratic Republic of the Congo, Angola, and Zambia. Its paramount ruler bore the title Mwata Yamvo and headed a hierarchical system of subordinate chiefs, a political model whose institutions spread to influence neighboring peoples. The empire grew wealthy through long-distance trade, exchanging ivory and captives for cloth, guns, and other goods with both Portuguese traders on the Atlantic coast and merchants linked to the Indian Ocean. At its height it controlled an extensive territory and stood among the larger of the Bantu-speaking states of central Africa. In the later 19th century it fragmented under internal strain and external pressure, including Chokwe incursions, before its lands were partitioned among the Congo Free State, Portuguese Angola, and British-administered territory.",
  "luxembourg": "Luxembourg, officially the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg, is a landlocked country in Western Europe. It is bordered by Belgium to the west and north, Germany to the east, and France to the south and west. Its capital and most populous city, Luxembourg City, is one of the four institutional seats of the European Union and hosts several EU institutions, notably the Court of Justice of the European Union, the highest judicial authority in the EU. As part of the Low Countries, Luxembourg has close historic, political, and cultural ties to Belgium and the Netherlands. Its status as a grand duchy and its central location give it a distinctive place among European states.",
  "macao": "Macau, also spelled Macao, is a special administrative region of China. It comprises the Macau Peninsula together with the islands of Taipa and Coloane and the reclaimed Cotai zone between them, along with several smaller islets. It borders Zhuhai to the north and west and lies west of Hong Kong, separated by the Pearl River estuary. Formerly a Portuguese colony, the territory was first leased to Portugal by the Ming dynasty as a trading post in 1557, giving it a long Luso-Chinese heritage. Densely populated, Macau blends Portuguese and Chinese influences in its culture and administration.",
  "madagascar": "Madagascar, officially the Republic of Madagascar, is an island country in the Indian Ocean lying off the southeastern coast of Africa. It comprises the island of Madagascar, one of the world's largest, together with numerous smaller peripheral islands. Its capital and largest city is Antananarivo. Following the breakup of the supercontinent Gondwana, Madagascar split from Africa during the Early Jurassic period and later separated from the Indian subcontinent, leaving it long isolated. This isolation allowed its native plants and animals to evolve in relative seclusion, giving the island exceptional biological distinctiveness.",
  "malawi": "Malawi, officially the Republic of Malawi, is a landlocked country in Southeast Africa. It is bordered by Zambia to the west, Tanzania to the north and northeast, and Mozambique to the east, south, and southwest. Lilongwe is its capital and largest city. The region now known as Malawi was settled around the 10th century by early inhabitants including the Akafula, also known as the Abathwa. Its history and geography have long shaped life across this part of the African interior.",
  "malaya": "Malaya, also called British Malaya, is the historical term for the Malay Peninsula and the network of British colonies and protectorates established there, in what is today Peninsular Malaysia and Singapore. Rather than a single unified state, it consisted of the Straits Settlements, a British crown colony that included Penang, Malacca, and Singapore, alongside a set of Malay sultanates that came under British protection while retaining their own hereditary rulers. From 1896 four of these states, Perak, Selangor, Negeri Sembilan, and Pahang, were grouped as the Federated Malay States under a British Resident-General, while others, such as Johor, Kedah, Kelantan, Terengganu, and Perlis, later formed the more autonomous Unfederated Malay States. British control brought large-scale tin mining and rubber plantation economies, drawing substantial Chinese and Indian immigrant labor that reshaped the peninsula's population. After the Second World War these territories were reorganized into the Malayan Union and then the Federation of Malaya, which gained independence in 1957 and became the core of modern Malaysia.",
  "malaysia": "Malaysia is a country in Southeast Asia and a federal constitutional monarchy. It consists of thirteen states and three federal territories, separated by the South China Sea into two regions: Peninsular Malaysia on the mainland and East Malaysia on the island of Borneo. Peninsular Malaysia shares land and maritime borders with Thailand, along with maritime borders with Singapore, Vietnam, and Indonesia, while East Malaysia shares land borders with Brunei and Indonesia. Kuala Lumpur is the national capital, largest city, and seat of the legislature, while Putrajaya serves as the federal administrative capital housing the executive and judicial branches. Straddling both mainland and maritime Southeast Asia, Malaysia spans two distinct regions.",
  "maldives": "The Maldives, officially the Republic of Maldives and historically known as the Maldive Islands, is an archipelagic country in South Asia. It lies in the Indian Ocean near the southeastern boundary of the Arabian Sea, southwest of India and Sri Lanka. Its chain of 26 atolls stretches across the equator from Ihavandhippolhu Atoll in the north to Addu Atoll in the south. Although its land is minimal, it is scattered across a vast expanse of sea, making it one of the world's most spatially dispersed sovereign states. Built from atolls, the Maldives is renowned for its dispersed island geography.",
  "mali": "Mali, officially the Republic of Mali, is a landlocked country in West Africa and one of the largest states on the continent. It is bordered by Algeria to the north, Niger to the east, Mauritania to the northwest, Burkina Faso and Ivory Coast to the south, and Guinea and Senegal to the west. Its capital and largest city is Bamako. It ranks among the largest countries both in Africa and in the world by area. A significant share of its population is young, with a large proportion estimated to be under the age of fifteen.",
  "malta": "Malta, officially the Republic of Malta, is an island country of Southern Europe located in the Mediterranean Sea between Sicily and North Africa. It consists of an archipelago lying south of Italy, east of Tunisia, and north of Libya. The two official languages are Maltese and English, with Maltese recognised as the national language. The country's capital is Valletta, among the smallest capital cities in the European Union. Densely populated for its size, Malta ranks among the world's smallest and most crowded countries.",
  "qing dynasty": "The Qing dynasty was the last imperial dynasty of China, which ruled from the mid-seventeenth century until the early twentieth century. It was founded by the Manchus, a people descended from the Jurchens of the northeast whose rulers came from the Aisin-Gioro house, who overthrew the Ming and established a foreign conquest dynasty over China. Under emperors such as Kangxi, Yongzheng, and Qianlong the empire reached its height, expanding to incorporate Manchuria, Mongolia, Tibet, and Xinjiang and becoming one of the largest and most populous states in the world. The Qing governed a vast multiethnic realm through a dual system that preserved Manchu identity and privileges while adopting Chinese administrative and Confucian institutions. Weakened in the nineteenth century by internal rebellions and foreign pressure, the dynasty collapsed in the Xinhai Revolution, ending more than two millennia of imperial rule in China.",
  "marshall is.": "The Marshall Islands, officially the Republic of the Marshall Islands, is an archipelagic country in Oceania. The sovereign state lies west of the International Date Line and north of the equator in the Micronesia region of the Northwestern Pacific Ocean. Its territory consists of coral atolls and small islands divided across two chains, Ratak in the east and Ralik in the west. The overwhelming majority of its territory is lagoon waters, giving it one of the largest proportions of water to land of any sovereign state. It shares maritime boundaries with Wake Island, Kiribati, Nauru, and the Federated States of Micronesia.",
  "mauritania": "Mauritania, officially the Islamic Republic of Mauritania, is a country in the Maghreb region of West Africa. It is bordered by the Atlantic Ocean to the west, Western Sahara to the north and northwest, Algeria to the northeast, Mali to the east and southeast, and Senegal to the southwest. Much of its territory lies within the Sahara desert, and most of its population lives in the more temperate south. Its capital and largest city, Nouakchott, sits on the Atlantic coast. The country's name derives from Mauretania, the Latin name for a region in the ancient Maghreb.",
  "mauritius": "Mauritius, officially the Republic of Mauritius, is an island country in the Indian Ocean located off the southeastern coast of Africa, east of Madagascar. It includes the main island of Mauritius as well as Rodrigues, Agaléga, and St. Brandon. Together with Rodrigues and nearby Réunion, it forms part of the Mascarene Islands. The main island, where the population is concentrated, hosts the capital and largest city, Port Louis. The nation also holds a vast exclusive economic zone across the surrounding ocean, reflecting its dispersed island character.",
  "mbailundu": "Bailundo, known before 1975 as Vila Teixeira da Silva, is a municipality and town in the province of Huambo, Angola. It lies in the central highlands of the country and gives its name to the non-sovereign Kingdom of Bailundo, a traditional monarchy seated there. During the 1990s the town served as the location of the headquarters of the UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi. The kingship of Bailundo has continued as a customary institution into the present era, passing between traditional rulers. The area sits in a mountainous region near the city of Huambo and its airport.",
  "mexico": "Mexico, officially the United Mexican States, is a country in North America and the northernmost country in Latin America. It borders the United States to the north and Guatemala and Belize to the southeast, with maritime frontiers on the Pacific Ocean to the west, the Caribbean Sea to the southeast, and the Gulf of Mexico to the east. It ranks among the larger countries of the world by land area and is home to the largest population of native Spanish speakers. Mexico City is the capital and largest city, ranking among the most populous metropolitan areas in the world. It is one of the most populous countries in the world and one of the northernmost states of Latin America.",
  "micronesia": "Micronesia is a subregion of Oceania made up of roughly two thousand small islands scattered across the Northwestern Pacific Ocean. It shares a close cultural history with Maritime Southeast Asia to the west, Polynesia to the east, and Melanesia to the south, as well as with the wider community of Austronesian peoples. The region has a tropical marine climate and forms part of the Oceanian biogeographic realm. Its islands include four main archipelagos, the Caroline Islands, the Gilbert Islands, the Mariana Islands, and the Marshall Islands, along with many islands belonging to no archipelago. Political control across Micronesia varies from island to island and is distributed among several sovereign nations.",
  "moldova": "Moldova, officially the Republic of Moldova, is a landlocked country in Eastern Europe. It is bordered by Romania to the west and Ukraine to the north, east, and south, with the unrecognised breakaway region of Transnistria lying across the Dniester river along its eastern edge. It is a unitary parliamentary democratic republic whose capital and largest city, Chișinău, serves as its main cultural and commercial centre. Most of its territory belonged to the Principality of Moldavia from the 14th century until 1812. In that year the region was ceded to the Russian Empire by the Ottoman Empire, to which Moldavia had been a vassal, and became known as Bessarabia.",
  "monaco": "Monaco, officially the Principality of Monaco, is a sovereign city-state and microstate in Western Europe. Situated on the French Riviera, it forms a semi-enclave bordered by France to the north, east, and west, with the Mediterranean Sea to the south and the Italian region of Liguria a short distance to the east. It is among the smallest sovereign states in the world, ranking behind only Vatican City, and it is also the most densely populated. Monaco has the shortest national coastline of any non-landlocked country. Only a minority of its residents hold Monégasque nationality.",
  "mongolia": "Mongolia is a landlocked country in East Asia, bordered by Russia to the north and China to the south. It ranks among the largest countries in the world by area and is the second largest landlocked state after Kazakhstan, as well as the largest landlocked country that does not border an inland sea. It is one of the world's most sparsely populated sovereign states. Much of the country lies on the Mongolian Plateau, and its natural environment is defined by grassy steppe, mountains to the north and west, and the Gobi Desert to the south. Its only neighbours are Russia and China, giving it borders solely with those two states.",
  "montenegro": "Montenegro is a country in Southeast Europe, on the Balkan Peninsula. It is bordered by Serbia to the northeast, Bosnia and Herzegovina to the northwest, Kosovo to the east, Albania to the southeast, and Croatia to the west, and it has a coastline along the Adriatic Sea to the southwest. Its capital and largest city is Podgorica, while Cetinje serves as the Old Royal Capital and a cultural centre. Before the arrival of the Slavic peoples in the Balkans in the 6th and 7th centuries CE, the area now known as Montenegro was inhabited principally by peoples known as Illyrians. The country is divided administratively into a number of municipalities.",
  "montserrat": "Montserrat is a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean. It forms part of the Leeward Islands, the northern portion of the Lesser Antilles chain of the West Indies. The island is a small landmass with a modest length, width, and coastline. It is nicknamed the Emerald Isle of the Caribbean, both for its resemblance to coastal Ireland and for the Irish ancestry of many of its inhabitants. Montserrat is the only non-fully-sovereign full member of the Caribbean Community and the Organisation of Eastern Caribbean States.",
  "morocco": "Morocco, officially the Kingdom of Morocco, is a country in the Maghreb region of North Africa. It has coastlines on the Mediterranean Sea to the north and the Atlantic Ocean to the west, and it borders Algeria to the east and the disputed territory of Western Sahara to the south, much of which it has occupied since 1975. Along its northern coast lie the Spanish exclaves of Ceuta, Melilla, and Peñón de Vélez de la Gomera, which Morocco claims together with several small Spanish-controlled islands. Its capital is Rabat, while its largest city is Casablanca. It also claims to share a border with Mauritania through the disputed territory of Western Sahara.",
  "mossi states": "The Mossi, also spelled Mosi, are a Gur ethnic group native to what is now Burkina Faso, concentrated primarily in the Volta River basin. They are the largest ethnic group in the country, forming a majority of its population. The remainder of Burkina Faso's people belong to more than sixty other ethnic groups, chiefly the Gurunsi, Gurma, Senufo, Lobi, Bobo, Bissa, and Fulani. The Mossi speak the Mòoré language. Their homeland lies chiefly in the Volta River basin of modern Burkina Faso.",
  "mozambique": "Mozambique, officially the Republic of Mozambique, is a country in Southeast Africa bordered by the Indian Ocean to the east, Tanzania to the north, Malawi and Zambia to the northwest, Zimbabwe to the west, and Eswatini and South Africa to the south and southwest. It is separated from the Comoros, Mayotte, and Madagascar by the Mozambique Channel to the east. Its capital and largest city is Maputo. Between the 7th and 11th centuries a series of Swahili port towns developed along the coast, contributing to a distinct Swahili culture and dialect. In the late medieval period these towns were frequented by traders from Somalia, Ethiopia, Egypt, Arabia, Persia, and India.",
  "myanmar": "Myanmar, officially the Republic of the Union of Myanmar and also known as Burma, is a country in the northwest of Southeast Asia. It is the largest country by area in Mainland Southeast Asia and is bordered by India and Bangladesh to the northwest, China to the northeast, Laos and Thailand to the east and southeast, and the Andaman Sea and the Bay of Bengal to the south and southwest. Its capital is Naypyidaw, while its largest city is Yangon, formerly known as Rangoon. Early civilisations in the region included the Tibeto-Burman-speaking Pyu city-states in Upper Myanmar and the Mon kingdoms in Lower Myanmar. Burma was the country's official English name until 1989.",
  "n. cyprus": "Northern Cyprus, officially the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus, is a de facto state comprising the northern third of the island of Cyprus. It is recognised only by Turkey, while the international community regards it as territory of the Republic of Cyprus under Turkish military occupation. Its terrain extends from Cape Apostolos Andreas at the tip of the Karpass Peninsula in the northeast to Morphou Bay in the northwest, with Cape Kormakitis as its westernmost point and the Kokkina exclave lying west of the mainland. A United Nations buffer zone separates the two sides of the island and runs through Nicosia, the island's largest city. Nicosia serves as the capital of both the northern and southern administrations.",
  "n. mariana is.": "The Northern Mariana Islands, officially the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands, is an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States. It consists of the fourteen northern islands of the Mariana Archipelago in the northwestern Pacific Ocean, with the southernmost island, Guam, forming a separate U.S. territory. During the colonial period the islands were variously under the control of the Spanish, German, and Japanese empires. After World War II they were administered by the United States as part of the United Nations trust territories, having been listed by the United Nations as a non-self-governing territory until 1990. The islands formally joined the United States as a territory in 1986, with their population gaining United States citizenship.",
  "namibia": "Namibia, officially the Republic of Namibia, is a country in Southern Africa fronting the Atlantic Ocean along its western coast. It borders Angola and Zambia to the north, Botswana to the east, and South Africa to the south, and comes within a short distance of Zimbabwe along the Zambezi river in the northeast, near a quadripoint at Kazungula. Windhoek is its capital and largest city. Namibia is the driest country in sub-Saharan Africa. It has been inhabited since prehistoric times by the Khoi, San, Damara, and Nama peoples, with Bantu peoples arriving around the 14th century as part of the Bantu expansion.",
  "natal": "Natal was a British colony on the southeastern coast of Africa, in the region that is now the KwaZulu-Natal province of South Africa. It was proclaimed a British colony in 1843 after Britain annexed the short-lived Boer republic of Natalia, and its capital was established at Pietermaritzburg. Initially administered as an appendage of the Cape Colony, Natal became a separate crown colony in 1856 and was granted responsible self-government in 1893. Its economy centred on coastal sugar plantations worked from 1860 by large numbers of Indian indentured labourers, giving the colony a distinctive multi-ethnic population alongside its African majority and settler minority. Bordering the Zulu Kingdom, Natal was shaped by conflict with the Zulu and by the Second Boer War, and in 1910 it ceased to exist as a colony when it became a founding province of the Union of South Africa.",
  "nauru": "Nauru, officially the Republic of Nauru and formerly known as Pleasant Island, is an island country and microstate in the South Pacific Ocean. It lies within the Micronesia subregion of Oceania, with its nearest neighbour being Banaba, part of Kiribati, to the east. One of the smallest countries in the world, Nauru is also the smallest member state of the Commonwealth of Nations by both area and population. It is likewise among the least populous countries in the world, ranking near the very bottom by population. Nauru is a member of the United Nations, the Commonwealth of Nations, and the Organisation of African, Caribbean and Pacific States.",
  "ndebele": "The Ndebele kingdom, also known as Matabeleland or Mthwakazi, was a Southern African state founded in the early nineteenth century by Mzilikazi of the Khumalo clan, a leader of Nguni origin who broke from the Zulu ruler Shaka during the upheavals of the Mfecane. After migrating northward across the Transvaal and eventually the Limpopo River, his followers—the Ndebele or Matabele—settled in the southwestern part of present-day Zimbabwe, with their principal centre at Bulawayo. The kingdom was organized as a highly militarized society built around age-based regiments modelled on the Zulu system, and it incorporated conquered Sotho-Tswana and Shona peoples into a centralized, multi-ethnic state. Under Mzilikazi and his successor Lobengula, it dominated the surrounding region and exacted tribute from neighbouring communities. The kingdom fell to the British South Africa Company in the First Matabele War of 1893, after which its territory was absorbed into the colony of Southern Rhodesia.",
  "nepal": "Nepal, officially the Federal Democratic Republic of Nepal, is a landlocked country in South Asia. It is mainly situated in the Himalayas but also includes parts of the Indo-Gangetic Plain, bordering the Tibet Autonomous Region of China to the north and India to the south, east, and west. It is narrowly separated from Bangladesh by the Siliguri Corridor and from Bhutan by the Indian state of Sikkim. Nepal has a diverse geography ranging from fertile plains and subalpine forested hills to eight of the world's ten highest mountains, including Mount Everest, the highest point above mean sea level on Earth. Kathmandu is the nation's capital and its largest city.",
  "netherlands": "The Netherlands, informally known as Holland, is a country in Northwestern Europe with overseas territories in the Caribbean. It is the largest of the four constituent countries of the Kingdom of the Netherlands and consists of twelve provinces along with three overseas special municipalities. The European portion has land borders with Germany to the east and Belgium to the south, and a coastline along the North Sea to the north and west. It shares maritime borders with the United Kingdom, Germany, and Belgium in the North Sea. These maritime boundaries are set within that same body of water shared with its neighbours.",
  "netherlands antilles": "The Netherlands Antilles, also known as the Dutch Antilles, was a constituent Caribbean country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands. It comprised the islands of Saba, Sint Eustatius, and Sint Maarten in the Lesser Antilles, together with Aruba, Bonaire, and Curaçao in the Leeward Antilles. The country came into being in 1954 as the autonomous successor of the Dutch colony of Curaçao and Dependencies. It was gradually reshaped as Aruba, Sint Maarten, and Curaçao gained the status of constituent countries within the Kingdom. It was dissolved in 2010, with Saba, Sint Eustatius, and Bonaire becoming special municipalities of the Netherlands as the Caribbean Netherlands.",
  "netherlands indies": "The Dutch East Indies, also known as the Netherlands East Indies, was a Dutch colony whose territory largely corresponds to the modern state of Indonesia. It was formed from the nationalised trading posts of the Dutch East India Company, which came under the administration of the Dutch government in 1800. Through the Anglo-Dutch Treaty of 1824, the Dutch ceded the governorate of Dutch Malacca to Britain, an area later incorporated into modern Malaysia. During the 19th century the Dutch fought many wars against indigenous rulers and peoples across the archipelago. Indonesia declared independence in 1945, and after the Indonesian War of Independence the Netherlands recognized it in 1949.",
  "new caledonia": "New Caledonia is a French territory consisting of a group of islands in the southwest Pacific Ocean, lying southwest of Vanuatu and east of Australia. Located far from Metropolitan France, it forms a sui generis collectivity of the French Republic with a unique legal status enshrined in a dedicated chapter of the French Constitution. Part of the Melanesia subregion, the archipelago includes the main island of Grande Terre, the Loyalty Islands, the Chesterfield Islands, the Belep archipelago, the Isle of Pines, and various remote islets. The Chesterfield Islands lie within the Coral Sea. Grande Terre is affectionately nicknamed le Caillou by locals, a name often extended to New Caledonia as a whole.",
  "new zealand": "New Zealand is an island country in the southwestern Pacific Ocean, consisting of two main landmasses—the North Island (Te Ika-a-Māui) and the South Island (Te Waipounamu)—along with over 600 smaller islands. It lies east of Australia across the Tasman Sea and south of New Caledonia, Fiji, and Tonga. Its varied topography and sharp mountain peaks, including the Southern Alps (Kā Tiritiri o te Moana), owe much to tectonic uplift and volcanic eruptions. Wellington is the country's capital, while Auckland is its most populous city. It is the sixth-largest island country by area.",
  "nguni": "The Nguni are a cluster of closely related Bantu ethnic groups native to Southern Africa, forming one of the region's largest ethnolinguistic communities. They are traditionally divided into a northern branch, which includes the Zulu and the Swazi, and a southern branch, which includes the Xhosa along with related societies such as the Thembu and Mpondo, while the Ndebele are also counted among them. Their closely related tongues, the Nguni languages, are distinguished among Bantu languages by click consonants absorbed through contact and intermarriage with earlier Khoisan-speaking inhabitants. The ancestors of the Nguni settled the eastern regions of Southern Africa during the later Iron Age, developing societies based on cattle-keeping and cultivation. Today Nguni peoples are concentrated in South Africa, Eswatini, and Zimbabwe, where their languages and traditions remain a major part of the region's cultural identity.",
  "ngwato": "The Bamangwato, also known as the BaNgwato or Ngwato, are one of the eight principal Tswana chieftaincies of Botswana. The community is centred in the Central District, historically forming in the Serowe, Palapye, and Mahalapye area. Its main town and capital, established after 1902, is Serowe. The Bamangwato are led by a paramount chief who holds a hereditary position. That chief occupies one of the seats in the Ntlo ya Dikgosi, the national House of Chiefs.",
  "nicaragua": "Nicaragua, officially the Republic of Nicaragua, is the geographically largest country in Central America. It is bordered by Honduras to the north, the Caribbean Sea to the east, Costa Rica to the south, and the Pacific Ocean to the west, and also shares maritime borders with El Salvador and Colombia. It is among the more populous countries of Central America. Managua is the country's largest city and national capital, and ranks among the largest cities in Central America. It is the third-most populous country in Central America, after Guatemala and Honduras.",
  "niger": "Niger, officially the Republic of the Niger, is a landlocked country in West Africa. It is bordered by Libya to the northeast, Chad to the east, Nigeria to the south, Benin and Burkina Faso to the southwest, Mali to the west, and Algeria to the northwest. It is the largest landlocked country in West Africa, with the majority of its land area lying within the Sahara. Its predominantly Muslim population is concentrated mostly in clusters in the south and west of the country. It is also the second-largest landlocked nation in Africa, behind Chad.",
  "nigeria": "Nigeria, officially the Federal Republic of Nigeria, is a country in West Africa lying between the Sahel to the north and the Gulf of Guinea on the Atlantic Ocean to the south. It borders Niger to the north, Chad to the northeast, Cameroon to the east, and Benin to the west. The most populous country in Africa, it ranks among the most populous nations in the world. Nigeria is a federal republic composed of thirty-six states together with the Federal Capital Territory. Its capital is Abuja, located within that territory.",
  "niue": "Niue is a self-governing island country in free association with New Zealand, situated in the South Pacific Ocean. It forms part of Polynesia and is predominantly inhabited by Polynesians. One of the world's largest coral islands, it is nicknamed \"The Rock,\" derived from the traditional name \"Rock of Polynesia.\" Niue lies within a triangle formed by Tonga, Samoa, and the Cook Islands. It sits to the northeast of both New Zealand and Tonga.",
  "norfolk island": "Norfolk Island is an external territory of Australia located in the Pacific Ocean between New Zealand and New Caledonia, lying to the east of the Australian mainland. Together with the neighbouring Phillip Island and Nepean Island, the three collectively form the Territory of Norfolk Island. Its capital is Kingston. East Polynesians were the first to settle the island, but they had already departed before European arrival. Great Britain settled it as part of its 1788 colonisation of Australia.",
  "north korea": "North Korea, officially the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, is a country in East Asia occupying the northern half of the Korean Peninsula. It borders China and Russia to the north along the Yalu and Tumen rivers, and South Korea to the south at the Korean Demilitarized Zone. Its western border is formed by the Yellow Sea, while the Sea of Japan lies to the east. Pyongyang is the capital and largest city. The Korean Peninsula was first inhabited as early as the Lower Paleolithic period.",
  "north macedonia": "North Macedonia, officially the Republic of North Macedonia, is a landlocked country in Southeast Europe. It shares borders with Greece to the south, Albania to the west, Bulgaria to the east, Kosovo to the northwest, and Serbia to the north. The country constitutes roughly the northern third of the larger geographical region of Macedonia. Skopje is its capital and largest city, home to a substantial share of the national population. The majority of its residents are ethnic Macedonians, a South Slavic people.",
  "norway": "Norway, officially the Kingdom of Norway, is a Nordic country comprising the western and northernmost parts of the Scandinavian Peninsula in Northern Europe, along with the remote Arctic island of Jan Mayen and the archipelago of Svalbard. Bouvet Island, located in the Subantarctic, is a dependency rather than part of the Kingdom, and Norway also claims the Antarctic territories of Peter I Island and Queen Maud Land. Its capital and largest city is Oslo. The country shares a long eastern border with Sweden. It is bordered by Finland and Russia to the northeast.",
  "oman": "Oman, officially the Sultanate of Oman, is a country in the southeastern Arabian Peninsula in West Asia. It shares land borders with Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, and Yemen. Its coastline faces the Arabian Sea to the southeast and the Gulf of Oman to the northeast. The exclaves of Madha and Musandam are surrounded on their land borders by the United Arab Emirates, while Musandam's coast is defined by the Strait of Hormuz and the Gulf of Oman. Oman occupies a strategic position at the eastern edge of the Arabian Peninsula.",
  "opobo": "Opobo is a community and former city-state in Rivers State, in the South South region of Nigeria. It is divided into fourteen sections, known as \"polo.\" These sections are made up of sixty-seven war canoe houses. The fourteen sections are Adibie, Biriye, Diepiri, Dapu, Dappa Ye Amakiri, Epelle, and Fubarakworo. The remaining sections are Iroanya, Jaja, Kalaomuso, Ukonu, Kiepirima, Owujie, and Tolofari.",
  "orange free state": "The Orange Free State was a landlocked independent Boer republic in Southern Africa during the second half of the nineteenth century. It ceased to exist after being defeated and surrendering to the British Empire at the end of the Second Boer War in 1902. Extending between the Orange and Vaal rivers, its borders were determined by the United Kingdom in 1848, when the region was proclaimed as the Orange River Sovereignty, with a British Resident based in Bloemfontein. Bloemfontein and the southern parts of the territory had previously been settled by Griqua and by Trekboere from the Cape Colony. It is one of the three historical precursors to the present-day Free State province.",
  "ottoman empire": "The Ottoman Empire, historically also known as the Turkish Empire, was a state that spanned much of Southeast Europe, West Asia, and North Africa from the fourteenth century to the early twentieth century, centred in modern-day Turkey. It also controlled parts of southeastern Central Europe between the early sixteenth and early eighteenth centuries. The empire emerged from a principality founded in northwestern Anatolia around 1299 by the Turkoman tribal leader Osman I, whose successors conquered much of Anatolia and expanded into the Balkans by the mid-fourteenth century. The Ottomans ended the Byzantine Empire with the conquest of Constantinople in 1453 by Mehmed II. Further conquests by Selim I led the Sultans to adopt the title of caliph.",
  "ovimbundu": "The Ovimbundu, also known as the Southern Mbundu, are a Bantu ethnic group living on the Bié Plateau of central Angola and in the coastal strip west of these highlands. They are the largest ethnic group in Angola. The Ovimbundu overwhelmingly follow Christianity, mainly the Igreja Evangélica Congregacional de Angola, founded by American missionaries, and the Catholic Church. However, some still retain beliefs and practices drawn from African traditional religions. Their homeland forms a central highland region of the country.",
  "oyo": "The Oyo Empire was a Yoruba state centered in the northern savanna of Yorubaland, in what is now southwestern Nigeria. According to tradition it was founded by Oranmiyan, a prince linked to the sacred dynasty of Ile-Ife, and it rose to become the most powerful Yoruba polity. Its capital, Oyo-Ile (Old Oyo), was the seat of the Alaafin, the supreme ruler, whose authority was checked by a council of chiefs known as the Oyo Mesi led by the Bashorun. Exploiting open grasslands to build a formidable cavalry, Oyo dominated much of the region at its height in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, extending influence over neighbouring peoples and the kingdom of Dahomey. Weakened by internal disputes, the revolt of Ilorin, and the pressures of civil war, the empire collapsed in the early nineteenth century, giving way to successor states such as Ibadan.",
  "pakistan": "Pakistan, officially the Islamic Republic of Pakistan, is a country in South Asia. It is among the most populous countries in the world and has one of the largest Muslim populations of any nation. Islamabad is the capital, while Karachi is the largest city and financial centre. Bounded by the Arabian Sea to the south, the Gulf of Oman to the southwest, and the Sir Creek to the southeast, it shares land borders with India to the east, Afghanistan to the west, Iran to the southwest, and China to the northeast. It ranks among the larger countries in the world by area.",
  "palau": "Palau, officially the Republic of Palau, is an island country in the Micronesia subregion of Oceania in the western Pacific Ocean. It consists of roughly 340 islands and forms the western part of the Caroline Islands, while the eastern and central parts make up the Federated States of Micronesia. It ranks among the smallest countries in the world. The most populous island is Koror, home to the country's largest city of the same name. The capital, Ngerulmud, is located on the largest island of Babeldaob, in Melekeok State.",
  "palestine": "Palestine, officially the State of Palestine, is a country in the Southern Levant region of West Asia. It encompasses the West Bank, including East Jerusalem, and the Gaza Strip, both of which are occupied by Israel. These territories are collectively known as the Palestinian territories, or the occupied Palestinian territory. The West Bank also borders Jordan to the east, while the Gaza Strip borders Egypt to the southwest. Together the West Bank and the Gaza Strip make up the territory of the State of Palestine.",
  "panama": "Panama, officially the Republic of Panama, lies at the southern end of Central America in North America, bordering South America. It is bounded by Costa Rica to the west, Colombia to the southeast, the Caribbean Sea to the north, and the Pacific Ocean to the south. Its capital and largest city is Panama City, whose metropolitan area is home to a large share of the country's inhabitants. Before the arrival of Spanish colonists in the 16th century, the region was inhabited by a number of different Indigenous peoples. Panama broke away from Spain in 1821 and joined the Republic of Gran Colombia, a union of Nueva Granada, Ecuador, and Venezuela.",
  "papua new guinea": "Papua New Guinea, officially the Independent State of Papua New Guinea, is an island country in Oceania that comprises the eastern half of the island of New Guinea together with offshore islands in Melanesia, a region of the southwestern Pacific Ocean north of Australia. It has a land border with Indonesia to the west and maritime borders with Australia to the south and the Solomon Islands to the east. Its capital is Port Moresby, and the country includes a large mainland along with hundreds of islands. The eastern half of New Guinea was divided in 1884 between German New Guinea in the north and British New Guinea in the south. The latter was ceded to Australia in 1902 and reorganised as the Territory of Papua.",
  "paraguay": "Paraguay, officially the Republic of Paraguay, is a landlocked country in the central region of South America. It borders Bolivia to the northwest and north, Brazil to the northeast and east, and Argentina to the southeast, south, and west. Despite being landlocked, it has access to the Atlantic Ocean via the Paraná–Paraguay Waterway. The country is governed as a unitary presidential republic composed of a capital district and seventeen departments. Its capital and largest city is Asunción.",
  "persia": "Persia, known in the modern era as Iran and officially the Islamic Republic of Iran, is a country in West Asia. It borders Iraq to the west, Turkey, Azerbaijan, and Armenia to the northwest, the Caspian Sea to the north, Turkmenistan to the northeast, Afghanistan to the east, Pakistan to the southeast, and the Gulf of Oman and the Persian Gulf to the south. It ranks among the largest countries in the world by geographic size and is divided administratively into provinces. Tehran is the nation's capital and largest city and serves as its primary economic centre. The country was historically known as Persia.",
  "peru": "Peru, officially the Republic of Peru, is a country in western South America. It is bordered to the north by Ecuador and Colombia, to the east by Brazil, to the southeast by Bolivia, to the south by Chile, and to the south and west by the Pacific Ocean. Peru is a megadiverse country, with habitats ranging from the arid plains of the Pacific coastal region in the west, to the peaks of the Andes mountains extending from the north to the southeast, to the tropical Amazon basin rainforest in the east drained by the Amazon River. Its capital and largest city is Lima. It is among the largest countries in South America.",
  "philippines": "The Philippines, officially the Republic of the Philippines, is an archipelagic country in Southeast Asia located in the western Pacific Ocean. It consists of thousands of islands, broadly categorized into three main geographical divisions from north to south: Luzon, Visayas, and Mindanao. The country is bounded by the South China Sea to the west, the Philippine Sea to the east, and the Celebes Sea to the south. It shares maritime borders with Taiwan to the north, Japan to the northeast, Palau to the east and southeast, Indonesia to the south, Malaysia to the southwest, Vietnam to the west, and China to the northwest. It is one of the most populous countries in the world.",
  "pitcairn is.": "The Pitcairn Islands, officially Pitcairn, Henderson, Ducie and Oeno Islands, are a group of four volcanic islands in the southern Pacific Ocean. They form the sole British Overseas Territory in the Pacific Ocean. The four islands are scattered across several hundred kilometres of ocean, and Henderson Island accounts for the great majority of the land area, though only Pitcairn Island is inhabited. The nearest inhabited islands are Mangareva, part of French Polynesia, to the west, and Easter Island to the east. The islands are remote and sparsely populated, with a very small resident community.",
  "poland": "Poland, officially the Republic of Poland, is a country in Central Europe. It extends from the Baltic Sea in the north to the Sudetes and Carpathian Mountains in the south, and borders Lithuania and Russia to the northeast, Belarus and Ukraine to the east, Slovakia and the Czech Republic to the south, and Germany to the west. The territory has a varied landscape, diverse ecosystems, and a temperate climate. Poland is composed of sixteen voivodeships and is one of the more populous member states of the European Union. Its capital and largest city is Warsaw, while other major cities include Kraków, Wrocław, Łódź, Poznań, and Gdańsk.",
  "portugal": "Portugal, officially the Portuguese Republic, is a country in Southwestern Europe. It is a unitary republic comprising mainland Portugal on the southwestern Iberian Peninsula, bordered by Spain to the north and east, together with the Atlantic archipelagos of Madeira and the Azores. Lisbon is its capital and largest city. Portugal's internal waters and territorial sea account for a large share of its territory, and its exclusive economic zone is one of Europe's largest, while its terrain contains a diverse range of landscapes and regional climates. The western Iberian Peninsula has been inhabited since prehistory, with the earliest signs of settlement dating to the sixth millennium BC.",
  "portuguese east africa": "Portuguese Mozambique, also known as Portuguese East Africa, was the name by which Mozambique was designated during the period in which it was a Portuguese overseas territory. It originally constituted a string of Portuguese possessions along the south-east African coast, and later became a unified province, which now forms the Republic of Mozambique. Portuguese trading settlements, and later territories, were formed along the coast and into the Zambezi basin from 1498, when Vasco da Gama first reached the Mozambican coast. Lourenço Marques explored the area that is now Maputo Bay in 1544. The territory remained under Portuguese control until Mozambique achieved independence.",
  "portuguese guinea": "Portuguese Guinea was a Portuguese overseas territory in West Africa. It was known as the Overseas Province of Guinea from 1951 until 1972, and then as the State of Guinea from 1972 until 1974. Portugal held the territory from 1588 until 1974. It gained independence in September 1974 as the country of Guinea-Bissau. The territory lay in West Africa and formed part of Portugal's colonial holdings in the region.",
  "puerto rico": "Puerto Rico, officially the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico, is a self-governing Caribbean archipelago and island organized as an unincorporated territory of the United States under the designation of commonwealth. Located southeast of Florida, it lies between the Dominican Republic in the Greater Antilles and the U.S. Virgin Islands in the Lesser Antilles. It consists of the main island and numerous smaller islands, including Vieques, Culebra, and Mona. It is divided into municipalities, of which the most populous is the capital, San Juan. Spanish and English are the official languages of the government, though Spanish predominates.",
  "qatar": "Qatar, officially the State of Qatar, is a country in West Asia. It occupies the Qatar Peninsula on the northeastern coast of the Arabian Peninsula in the Middle East, sharing its sole land border with Saudi Arabia to the south, with the rest of its territory surrounded by the Persian Gulf. The Gulf of Bahrain, an inlet of the Persian Gulf, separates Qatar from nearby Bahrain. The capital is Doha, home to the great majority of the country's inhabitants. Most of the land area is made up of flat, low-lying desert.",
  "rapa nui": "Rapa Nui, also known as Easter Island, is an island and special territory of Chile in the southeastern Pacific Ocean. It lies at the southeasternmost point of the Polynesian Triangle in Oceania. The island is renowned for its monumental stone statues, called moai, which were carved by the early Rapa Nui people. Much of the island is protected within Rapa Nui National Park, and UNESCO named it a World Heritage Site. It is the only territory in Polynesia where Spanish is an official language, and experts still differ on when its Polynesian inhabitants first arrived.",
  "rattanakosin kingdom": "The Rattanakosin Kingdom, also known as the Kingdom of Siam after 1855, was the Siamese kingdom occupying the territory of modern-day Thailand. It was founded in 1782 with the establishment of Rattanakosin, or Bangkok, which replaced Thonburi as the capital of Siam. The kingdom governed through the mandala system. This arrangement allowed high local autonomy while the central kingdom effectively ruled over its wider area of suzerainty. The era spanned from the founding of the new capital until the Siamese revolution of 1932.",
  "romania": "Romania is a country in Southeast and Central Europe, lying on the lower course of the Danube and the northwestern shore of the Black Sea. It sits north of the Balkan Peninsula and borders Ukraine, Hungary, Serbia, Bulgaria, and Moldova. It is one of the larger countries of Europe by area and a member state of the European Union. The capital, largest city, and economic centre is Bucharest. It meets the Black Sea along its southeastern edge.",
  "russia": "Russia, or the Russian Federation, is a country spanning Eastern Europe and North Asia. It is the largest country in the world by area, extending across eleven time zones and sharing land borders with fourteen countries. It is the most populous country in Europe and a highly urbanised society. Moscow is the capital and largest city, ranking as Europe's most populous metropolitan area, while Saint Petersburg is the second-largest city and a major cultural centre. Its territory reaches across two continents.",
  "russian empire": "The Russian Empire was the final period of the Russian monarchy, spanning most of northern Eurasia from its establishment in 1721 until the proclamation of the Russian Republic in 1917. At its height in the late 19th century it was one of the largest empires in history, covering roughly one-sixth of the world's landmass. It also colonized Alaska before selling the territory in 1867. The empire conducted a single census, in 1897, which revealed a population of great ethnic, linguistic, religious, and socioeconomic diversity. It ranked among the largest empires ever, behind only the British and Mongol empires.",
  "rwanda": "Rwanda, officially the Republic of Rwanda, is a landlocked country in East Africa. Known as the \"Land of a Thousand Hills\" for its high elevation and rolling terrain, its geography is dominated by mountains in the west and savanna in the southeast. Its most notable lakes lie mainly in the western and northern regions, and several volcanoes of the Virunga chain rise in the northwest. The climate is a tropical highland one, with two rainy seasons and two dry seasons each year. Its capital and largest city is Kigali, located at the centre of the country and set at high altitude.",
  "s. geo. and the is.": "South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands is a British Overseas Territory in the southern Atlantic Ocean. It is a remote and inhospitable collection of islands, consisting of South Georgia and a chain of smaller islands known as the South Sandwich Islands. South Georgia is by far the largest island in the territory. The South Sandwich Islands lie several hundred kilometres to its southeast. Together they make up a small and isolated total land area.",
  "s. sudan": "South Sudan, officially the Republic of South Sudan, is a landlocked country in East Africa. It is bordered by Sudan to the north, Ethiopia to the east, Kenya, Uganda, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the south, and the Central African Republic to the west. Its diverse landscape includes vast plains and plateaus, dry and tropical savannahs, inland floodplains, and forested mountains. The Nile River system is the defining physical feature of the country, running south to north across its center. Much of that centre is dominated by a large swamp known as the Sudd.",
  "saint barthelemy": "Saint Barthélemy, officially the Territorial Collectivity of Saint Barthélemy, is an overseas collectivity of France in the Caribbean. The island lies southeast of Saint Martin and north of the independent country of Saint Kitts and Nevis. It is situated northeast of the Dutch islands of Saba and Sint Eustatius. For many years the island was a French commune forming part of Guadeloupe, an overseas region and department of France. In 2003 its inhabitants voted in favour of secession from Guadeloupe to form a separate overseas collectivity of France.",
  "saint helena": "Saint Helena is a volcanic tropical island located in the South Atlantic Ocean, west of Africa. Its nearest countries geographically are Angola and Namibia. The island lies far out in the ocean, thousands of kilometres from the coast of Brazil to its west. It forms one of the three constituent parts of Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha, a British overseas territory. The island is small and rugged, reflecting its volcanic origins.",
  "saint kitts and nevis": "Saint Kitts and Nevis, officially the Federation of Saint Christopher and Nevis, is an island country in the Caribbean. It consists of the two islands of Saint Kitts and Nevis, in the Leeward Islands chain of the Lesser Antilles. It is among the smallest sovereign states in the Western Hemisphere and is the world's smallest sovereign federation. The country is a Commonwealth realm, recognising the British monarch as head of state. The capital is Basseterre, on the larger island of Saint Kitts, which also serves as the main port for passenger and cargo entry.",
  "saint lucia": "Saint Lucia is an island country in the eastern and southern Caribbean. Part of the Windward Islands of the Lesser Antilles, it lies north of Saint Vincent, northwest of Barbados, and south of Martinique. The nation's capital and largest city is Castries. The first proven inhabitants of the island are believed to have been the Arawaks. They are thought to have settled there in the early centuries AD.",
  "saint martin": "Saint Martin is an island in the Leeward Islands of the Lesser Antilles, in the northeastern Caribbean Sea east of Puerto Rico. It has been divided between France and the Netherlands since the Treaty of Concordia of 1648, making it one of the smallest inhabited land masses in the world shared by two sovereign powers. The larger northern portion is French, while the smaller southern portion, known as Sint Maarten, is Dutch, and the boundary between them has long remained open and freely crossable. The island's terrain is marked by low volcanic hills, salt ponds, and lagoons, and its economy historically rested on salt harvesting and small-scale agriculture before shifting toward tourism. Long shaped by European colonial rivalry and a Creole-speaking population of mixed African and European descent, Saint Martin retains a dual cultural and administrative character rooted in its French and Dutch heritage.",
  "samoa": "Samoa, officially the Independent State of Samoa, is an island country in Polynesia, part of Oceania in the South Pacific Ocean. It consists of two main islands, Savai'i and Upolu, two smaller inhabited islands, and several uninhabited islets. The country lies west of American Samoa, northeast of Tonga and Fiji, and within the broader Polynesian region of the Pacific. The capital and largest city is Apia, located on the island of Upolu. Its outlying islets include the Aleipata group off Upolu's eastern end.",
  "san marino": "San Marino, officially the Republic of San Marino, is a landlocked microstate in Southern Europe completely surrounded by Italy. It lies on the northeastern slopes of the Apennine Mountains and is one of two microstates within the Italian Peninsula, the other being Vatican City. Its capital, the City of San Marino, sits atop Monte Titano, while its largest settlement is Dogana in the municipality of Serravalle. San Marino claims to have been founded in AD 301, and it presents itself as the oldest extant sovereign state. It also claims the distinction of being the world's oldest constitutional republic.",
  "saudi arabia": "Saudi Arabia, officially the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, is a country in West Asia occupying the bulk of the Arabian Peninsula at the centre of the Middle East. It is the largest country in the Middle East and one of the largest in Asia, bordered by the Red Sea to the west and by Jordan, Iraq, and Kuwait to the north. To the east lie the Persian Gulf, Bahrain, Qatar, and the United Arab Emirates, with Oman to the southeast and Yemen to the south. The Gulf of Aqaba in the northwest separates it from Egypt and Israel, and it is the only country with a coastline along both the Red Sea and the Arabian Gulf. Most of its terrain consists of arid desert, lowland, steppe, and mountains.",
  "scarborough reef": "Scarborough Shoal, also known as Bajo de Masinloc, Huangyan Island, and Panatag Shoal, is a coral atoll and reef with an inner lagoon and several rocks that stand above high tide. It lies between Macclesfield Bank to the west and the island of Luzon to the east. Luzon, roughly 220 kilometres away, is the nearest landmass to the shoal. The atoll is a disputed territory, claimed simultaneously by the People's Republic of China, the Republic of China, and the Republic of the Philippines. Its status as a claimed feature has kept it contested among those three governments.",
  "senegal": "Senegal, officially the Republic of Senegal, is the westernmost country of mainland West Africa, situated along the Atlantic Ocean coast. It borders Mauritania to the north, Mali to the east, Guinea to the southeast, and Guinea-Bissau to the southwest. Senegal nearly surrounds the Gambia, a country occupying a narrow strip of land along the Gambia River that separates the southern region of Casamance from the rest of the country. It also shares a maritime border with Cape Verde in the Atlantic. The capital and largest city of Senegal is Dakar.",
  "serbia": "Serbia, officially the Republic of Serbia, is a landlocked country in Southeast and Central Europe located in the Balkans. It is bordered by Hungary to the north, Romania to the northeast, Bulgaria to the southeast, and North Macedonia to the south. To the west it adjoins Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Montenegro, and it also claims a border with Albania through the disputed territory of Kosovo. Belgrade, the country's capital, is also its largest city. Serbia lies within the Balkans at the meeting of Southeast and Central Europe.",
  "serranilla bank": "Serranilla Bank is a partially submerged reef with small uninhabited islets in the western Caribbean Sea. It lies northeast of the Punta Gorda River in Nicaragua and southwest of Jamaica. Its closest neighbouring land feature is Bajo Nuevo Bank, situated to the east. Serranilla Bank was first depicted on Spanish maps in 1510. It is administered by Colombia as part of the department of San Andrés and Providencia.",
  "seychelles": "Seychelles, officially the Republic of Seychelles, is an archipelagic country consisting of 115 islands in the Indian Ocean. Its capital and largest city, Victoria, lies east of mainland Africa. Nearby island countries and territories include the Maldives, Comoros, Madagascar, Mauritius, and the French overseas departments of Mayotte and Réunion to the south, along with the Chagos Archipelago to the east. It is among the smallest and least populous of Africa's sovereign states. The Seychelles archipelago was uninhabited prior to sustained external contact.",
  "shona": "Shona most commonly refers to the Shona people, a Southern African ethnic group, and to the Shona language, a Bantu language they speak. The term is also applied to the wider Shona group of languages defined in the early twentieth century. It is historically associated with the Kingdom of Zimbabwe, a Shona state that flourished from the thirteenth to the fifteenth centuries. The name additionally attaches to various other things, including a given name and geographical features such as the Shona hotspot in the Atlantic Ocean. As a label, Shona thus spans a people, their languages, and their historical polities in Southern Africa.",
  "siachen glacier": "The Siachen Glacier is a glacier in the eastern Karakoram range of the Himalayas, lying just northeast of the point where the Line of Control between India and Pakistan ends in northeastern Kashmir. It is the longest glacier in the Karakoram and the second-longest in the world's non-polar regions. The glacier descends from its head at Indira Col on the India–China border down to its terminus at a much lower altitude. Its remote, high-altitude terrain includes numerous major mountain passes. The entire glacier has been under the administration of India as part of the union territory of Ladakh since 1984.",
  "sierra leone": "Sierra Leone, officially the Republic of Sierra Leone, is a country on the west coast of West Africa. It is bordered to the southeast by Liberia and to the north by Guinea. The country has a tropical climate, with environments ranging from savannahs to rainforests. Its landscapes span a range of natural settings across this territory. Sierra Leone thus combines a West African coastal position with varied tropical environments.",
  "singapore": "Singapore, officially the Republic of Singapore, is an island country in Southeast Asia. Its territory comprises a main island, dozens of smaller satellite islands and islets, and one outlying islet. Lying just north of the equator off the southern tip of the Malay Peninsula, it borders the Strait of Malacca to the west, the Singapore Strait and Indonesia's Riau Islands to the south, the South China Sea to the east, and the Straits of Johor and the Malaysian state of Johor to the north. In its early history, Singapore was a maritime emporium known as Temasek. It later became a major constituent of several successive maritime empires.",
  "sint maarten": "Sint Maarten is a constituent country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands located in the Caribbean region of North America. It occupies the southern portion of the divided island of Saint Martin, while the northern portion constitutes the French overseas collectivity of Saint Martin. Its capital is Philipsburg. Together with the other Dutch islands in the Caribbean, Sint Maarten is often referred to as part of the Dutch Caribbean. The island's split between Dutch and French administration is a longstanding feature of its identity.",
  "slovakia": "Slovakia, officially the Slovak Republic, is a landlocked country in Central Europe. It is bordered by Poland to the north, Ukraine to the east, Hungary to the south, Austria to the west, and the Czech Republic to the northwest. Its territory is mostly mountainous. The capital and largest city is Bratislava, while the second largest city is Košice. The Slavs arrived in the territory of present-day Slovakia in the fifth and sixth centuries.",
  "slovenia": "Slovenia, officially the Republic of Slovenia, is a country in Central Europe. It borders Italy to the west, Austria to the north, Hungary to the northeast, and Croatia to the south and southeast, while its southwestern boundary features a short coastline on the Adriatic Sea. The country is mostly mountainous and forested, with terrain shaped by the Julian Alps and other ranges. Slovene is the official language. Slovenia has a predominantly temperate continental climate, apart from the Slovene Littoral and the Julian Alps.",
  "sokoto caliphate": "The Sokoto Caliphate, also known as the Sultanate of Sokoto, was a Sunni Muslim caliphate in West Africa. It was founded by Usman dan Fodio in 1804 during the Fulani jihads, after his victory over the Hausa Kingdoms in the Fulani War. At its height its territory extended across lands now part of present-day Cameroon, Burkina Faso, Niger, and Nigeria. It became the most populous empire in West Africa. The caliphate was dissolved after 1903, when British, French, and German forces conquered the region and partitioned it among their colonial holdings.",
  "solomon is.": "Solomon Islands, also known simply as the Solomons, is an archipelagic country in Melanesia, in the southwestern Pacific to the north-east of Australia. It comprises six major islands and over a thousand smaller ones scattered across the ocean. It lies near Bougainville to the west, New Caledonia and Vanuatu to the south-east, Fiji and Tuvalu to the east, and the Federated States of Micronesia and Nauru to the north. Its capital and largest city, Honiara, sits on Guadalcanal, the largest island. The country is part of the wider Oceania region and shares deep cultural and geographic ties with its Melanesian neighbours.",
  "somalia": "Somalia, officially the Federal Republic of Somalia, is the easternmost country in continental Africa. Stretching across the Horn of Africa, it borders Ethiopia to the west, Djibouti to the northwest, and Kenya to the southwest, with the Gulf of Aden to the north and the Indian Ocean to the east. It has the longest coastline on Africa's mainland. Its capital and largest city is Mogadishu. Somalia is among Africa's most ethnically homogeneous countries, with ethnic Somalis forming the great majority of its residents.",
  "somaliland": "Somaliland, officially the Republic of Somaliland, is a partially recognised state in the Horn of Africa. It lies on the southern coast of the Gulf of Aden and is bordered by Djibouti to the northwest, Ethiopia to the south and west, and Somalia to the east. Its capital and largest city is Hargeisa. Various Somali Muslim kingdoms were established in the area during the early Islamic period, including the Zeila-based Adal Sultanate in the 14th and 15th centuries. The territory has a distinct political history and claims the status of an independent republic.",
  "south africa": "South Africa, officially the Republic of South Africa, is the southernmost country in Africa. Its nine provinces are bounded to the south by a long coastline stretching along the South Atlantic and Indian Oceans, and to the north by Namibia, Botswana, and Zimbabwe, with Mozambique and Eswatini to the east and northeast; it entirely encloses Lesotho. It is unusual in having three capitals: Pretoria as the administrative capital, Cape Town as the legislative capital and seat of Parliament, and Bloemfontein as the judicial capital. Cape Town lies at the country's southwestern tip and is home to the national Parliament. South Africa is one of the most populous and economically significant countries on the continent.",
  "south korea": "South Korea, officially the Republic of Korea, is a country in East Asia occupying the southern half of the Korean Peninsula. It borders North Korea along the Korean Demilitarized Zone, with the Yellow Sea to the west and the Sea of Japan to the east. It claims to be the sole legitimate government of the entire peninsula and its adjacent islands. Its capital, Seoul, anchors a vast metropolitan area that holds a large share of the national population, with Busan, Daegu, and Incheon among other major cities. The Korean Peninsula has been inhabited since the Lower Paleolithic period and has a long, continuous cultural history.",
  "southern patagonian ice field": "The Southern Patagonian Ice Field, known in Spanish as Campo de Hielo Patagónico Sur, lies along the Southern Patagonian Andes on the border between Chile and Argentina. It is the world's second-largest contiguous extrapolar ice field. It is the larger of two surviving remnants of the Patagonian Ice Sheet, which once covered much of southern Chile during the last glacial period. That glaciation is known locally as the Llanquihue glaciation. The ice field remains a major feature of the high southern Andes.",
  "spain": "Spain, officially the Kingdom of Spain, is a country in Southern and Western Europe with additional territories in North Africa. It occupies most of the Iberian Peninsula and is the largest country in Southern Europe. Its territory also includes the Canary Islands in the eastern Atlantic, the Balearic Islands in the western Mediterranean, and the autonomous cities of Ceuta and Melilla in mainland Africa. Peninsular Spain borders France, Andorra, and the Bay of Biscay to the north; the Mediterranean Sea, Gibraltar, and Morocco to the east and south; and Portugal and the Atlantic Ocean to the west. It contains the southernmost point of continental Europe.",
  "spanish guinea": "Spanish Guinea, known in Spanish as Guinea Española, was a set of insular and continental territories controlled by Spain in the Gulf of Guinea and on the Bight of Bonny, in Central Africa. Spain held the territories from 1778 onward. They lay along the coast and islands of the equatorial African region. The colony brought together separate mainland and island possessions under a single administration. It gained independence in 1968 as Equatorial Guinea.",
  "spratly is.": "The Spratly Islands are a disputed archipelago in the South China Sea. Composed of islands, islets, cays, and more than a hundred reefs, sometimes grouped in submerged old atolls, they lie off the coasts of the Philippines, Malaysia, and southern Vietnam. The archipelago holds only a very small amount of naturally occurring land spread across a wide expanse of the sea. It was named after the 19th-century British whaling captain Richard Spratly, who sighted Spratly Island in 1843. The islands are a long-running focus of maritime dispute.",
  "sri lanka": "Sri Lanka, officially the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka and formerly known as Ceylon, is an island country in South Asia. It lies in the Indian Ocean, southwest of the Bay of Bengal, and is separated from India by the Gulf of Mannar and the Palk Strait. It shares a maritime border with the Maldives to the southwest and India to the northwest, lying across the Bay of Bengal from Bangladesh and Myanmar to the northeast. Its capital is Sri Jayawardenepura Kotte, while Colombo is its largest city and its political, financial, and cultural centre. The island lies along Indian Ocean sea routes separating it from its neighbours.",
  "st-barthélemy": "Saint Barthélemy, officially the Territorial Collectivity of Saint Barthélemy and also known as St. Barts or St. Barth, is an overseas collectivity of France in the Caribbean. The island lies about 30 kilometres southeast of Saint Martin, northeast of the Dutch islands of Saba and Sint Eustatius, and north of Saint Kitts and Nevis. For many years it was a French commune forming part of Guadeloupe, an overseas region and department of France. In 2003 the island voted in favour of secession from Guadeloupe to form a separate overseas collectivity of France. It has long been associated with French Caribbean administration.",
  "st-martin": "Saint-Martin is the French territory occupying the northern portion of the Caribbean island of Saint Martin, which it shares with the Dutch territory of Sint Maarten to the south under a division dating to a 1648 partition. Its principal town and administrative centre is Marigot, and it lies in the northern Lesser Antilles, separated from Anguilla by the Anguilla Channel. For most of the twentieth century the French side was administered as a commune within the overseas department of Guadeloupe, making it fully part of France and, later, of the European Union. Following a local vote to separate from Guadeloupe, it became a distinct French overseas collectivity in 2007, governed by its own elected Territorial Council. As part of France it confers French and EU citizenship, and its economy rests heavily on tourism.",
  "st. kitts and nevis": "Saint Kitts and Nevis, officially the Federation of Saint Christopher and Nevis, is an island country in the Caribbean consisting of the two islands of Saint Kitts and Nevis. It lies in the Leeward Islands chain of the Lesser Antilles. It is the smallest sovereign state in the Western Hemisphere in both area and population, as well as the world's smallest sovereign federation. The country is a Commonwealth realm, with the British monarch as head of state. Its capital, Basseterre, lies on the larger island of Saint Kitts and serves as the main port for passenger and cargo traffic.",
  "st. pierre and miquelon": "Saint Pierre and Miquelon is a self-governing territorial overseas collectivity of France in the northwestern Atlantic Ocean. It lies off the coast of the Canadian island of Newfoundland and forms an archipelago of eight islands. Its residents are French citizens who elect their own deputy to the National Assembly and take part in senatorial and presidential elections. The territory is an overseas country and territory of the European Union, though not an integral part of it. It is officially known as the Territorial Collectivity of Saint Pierre and Miquelon.",
  "st. vin. and gren.": "Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, sometimes known simply as Saint Vincent, is an archipelagic country in the eastern Caribbean. It lies in the southeast Windward Islands of the Lesser Antilles, at the southern end of the boundary between the Caribbean Sea and the Atlantic Ocean. Saint Lucia lies to its north, Barbados to the east, and Grenada to the south. Most of its territory consists of the main island of Saint Vincent, which includes the capital and largest city, Kingstown. To the south stretch the northern islands of the Grenadines, a chain of smaller islands shared with Grenada.",
  "sudan": "Sudan, officially the Republic of the Sudan, is a country in Northeast Africa and one of the largest states on the continent by area. It borders the Central African Republic, Chad, Libya, Egypt, the Red Sea, Eritrea, Ethiopia, and South Sudan. Its capital and most populous city is Khartoum. The region has been inhabited since deep prehistory, with early cultures such as the Khormusan among its ancient inhabitants. It ranks as Africa's third-largest country by area.",
  "sultanate of utetera": "The Sultanate of Utetera, also referred to as Tippu Tip's state, was a short-lived Arab sultanate established in eastern Africa in the nineteenth century. It was ruled by the Swahili slave trader Tippu Tip, born Hamad al Murjebi, and later by his son Sefu. Its capital was the town of Kasongo, located in what is now Maniema Province in the Democratic Republic of the Congo. At its height the state's controlled territory extended as far as eastern Kasai in one direction and the Aruwimi Basin in the other. It existed only briefly during the late nineteenth century.",
  "suriname": "Suriname, officially the Republic of Suriname, is a country in northern South America that is also considered part of the Caribbean and the West Indies. Situated slightly north of the equator, the vast majority of its territory is covered by rainforest, giving it one of the highest proportions of forest cover in the world. It is bordered by the Atlantic Ocean to the north, French Guiana to the east, Brazil to the south, and Guyana to the west. It is the smallest country in South America by both population and land area. Its capital and largest city is Paramaribo, which is home to roughly half of the population.",
  "swaziland": "Eswatini, formally the Kingdom of Eswatini and historically known as Swaziland, is a landlocked country in Southern Africa. It is bordered by South Africa on all sides except the east, where it shares a border with Mozambique. It is one of the smallest countries in Africa, measuring only a short distance from north to south and from east to west. Despite its small size, its climate and topography are diverse, ranging from a cool, mountainous highveld to a hot, dry lowveld. The executive capital and largest city is Mbabane, while Lobamba serves as the legislative and second capital.",
  "sweden": "Sweden, formally the Kingdom of Sweden, is a Nordic country located on the Scandinavian Peninsula in Northern Europe. It borders Norway to the west and north and Finland to the east, and shares a maritime border with Denmark to the south. It is the largest and most populous of the Nordic countries and one of the larger states in Europe. Its capital and largest city is Stockholm. The great majority of Swedes live in urban areas, concentrated mostly in the southern and central portions of the country.",
  "sweden–norway": "Sweden and Norway, officially the United Kingdoms of Sweden and Norway, was a personal union of the two separate kingdoms under a common monarch and a common foreign policy. It lasted from 1814 until its peaceful dissolution in 1905. The two states retained separate constitutions, laws, legislatures, administrations, state churches, armed forces, and currencies. The kings mostly resided in Stockholm, where foreign diplomatic representations were located. The Norwegian government was presided over by viceroys until that office was left vacant and then abolished in 1873.",
  "switzerland": "Switzerland, officially the Swiss Confederation, is a landlocked country located at the intersection of Central, Western, and Southern Europe. It is bordered by Germany to the north, France to the west, Austria and Liechtenstein to the east, and Italy to the south. The country is divided geographically among the Swiss Alps, the Swiss Plateau, and the Jura Mountains, with the Alps covering most of its territory. Most of the population is concentrated on the plateau, which hosts many of the largest cities and economic centres, including Zurich, Geneva, Basel, Bern, Lausanne, and Lucerne. Switzerland is a federal republic composed of twenty-six cantons, with Bern serving as the federal city and seat of the national government.",
  "syria": "Syria, officially the Syrian Arab Republic, is a country in West Asia located in the Eastern Mediterranean and the Levant. It borders the Mediterranean Sea to the west, Turkey to the north and northwest, Iraq to the east and southeast, Jordan to the south, and Israel and Lebanon to the southwest. It is a republic and is divided administratively into fourteen governorates. Damascus is its capital and largest city. It lies within the Eastern Mediterranean region of the Levant.",
  "são tomé and principe": "São Tomé and Príncipe, officially the Democratic Republic of São Tomé and Príncipe, is an island country in the Gulf of Guinea, off the western equatorial coast of Central Africa. It consists of two archipelagos around the two main islands of São Tomé and Príncipe, which lie a short distance apart and off the northwestern coast of Gabon. It is among the smallest and least populous sovereign states in Africa. The islands were uninhabited until Portuguese explorers, including João de Santarém and Pedro Escobar, reached them in 1470. Those explorers were the first to discover the islands.",
  "taiwan": "Taiwan, officially the Republic of China, is a country in East Asia. The main island, also known as Formosa, lies between the East and South China Seas in the northwestern Pacific Ocean, with mainland China to the northwest, Japan to the northeast, and the Philippines to the south. Mountain ranges dominate the eastern two-thirds of the island, while plains in the western third hold most of its highly urbanized population. The territories under its control also include numerous smaller outlying islands. The largest metropolitan area is formed by the capital Taipei together with New Taipei City and Keelung.",
  "tajikistan": "Tajikistan, officially the Republic of Tajikistan, is a landlocked country in Central Asia. Dushanbe is its capital and most populous city. It borders Afghanistan to the south, Uzbekistan to the west, Kyrgyzstan to the north, and China to the east, and is narrowly separated from Pakistan by Afghanistan's Wakhan Corridor. Its mountainous territory was home in antiquity to cultures of the Neolithic and the Bronze Age, including the Oxus civilisation in the west. Those early cultures make the region one of long-settled human habitation.",
  "tanzania": "Tanzania, officially the United Republic of Tanzania, is a country in East Africa within the African Great Lakes region. It is bordered by Uganda, Kenya, the Indian Ocean, Mozambique, Malawi, Zambia, Rwanda, Burundi, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo. It is the most populous African country located entirely south of the equator. Many important hominid fossils have been found within its borders, making it significant to the study of human origins. Its geography ranges from the Indian Ocean coast to the great lakes and highlands of the interior.",
  "teke": "The Teke Kingdom, also known as the Kingdom of Tio or the Anziku Kingdom, was a Central African state of the Teke (Tio or Bateke) people on the grassland plateaus north of the lower Congo River, spanning parts of present-day Congo-Brazzaville, Gabon, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo. Traditionally dated to around the fourteenth century, it was one of the older states of the region and for a time rivalled the Kingdom of Kongo to its south. It was headed by a king known as the Makoko, whose authority was bound up with control of the powerful nature spirit Nkwe Mbali and who ruled through a hierarchy of tributary lords. Its centres on the Mbé plateau and at Pool Malebo on the Congo River commanded important trade routes, exchanging local goods and later ivory and captives for European wares such as cloth, muskets, and gunpowder. In 1880 its ruler signed a treaty with the French explorer Pierre Savorgnan de Brazza that placed the kingdom under French protection and opened the region to colonization, though the Teke monarchy endures as a traditional institution.",
  "thailand": "Thailand, officially the Kingdom of Thailand and formerly known as Siam until 1939, is a country in Mainland Southeast Asia. It shares land borders with Myanmar to the west and northwest, Laos to the east and northeast, Cambodia to the southeast, and Malaysia to the south. Its coasts front the Gulf of Thailand and the Andaman Sea, giving it maritime boundaries with neighbours including Vietnam, Indonesia, and India. The capital and largest city is Bangkok, the country's dominant political, economic, and cultural center. It occupies a central position in Mainland Southeast Asia, bordered by several neighbouring states on land and by two seas along its coasts.",
  "timor-leste": "Timor-Leste, also known as East Timor and officially the Democratic Republic of Timor-Leste, is a country in Southeast Asia. It comprises the eastern half of the island of Timor, the coastal exclave of Oecusse in the island's northwest, and the islands of Atauro and Jaco. It shares a land border with Indonesia to the west, while Australia lies to the south across the Timor Sea. Dili, on the north coast of Timor, is its capital and largest city. Timor was settled over time by various Papuan and Austronesian peoples, producing a diverse mix of cultures and languages linked to both Southeast Asia and Melanesia.",
  "togo": "Togo, officially the Togolese Republic, is a country in West Africa. It is bordered by Ghana to the west, Benin to the east, and Burkina Faso to the north. The country extends northward from the Gulf of Guinea, where its capital and largest city, Lomé, is located, up to the Burkina Faso border. It is a small, tropical nation with a coastline on the Gulf of Guinea in the south. Togo is often counted among the least developed countries in the world.",
  "tonga": "Tonga, officially the Kingdom of Tonga, is an island country in Polynesia, within the wider region of Oceania. The country consists of 171 islands, of which 45 are inhabited, scattered across a broad expanse of the southern Pacific Ocean. Its islands stretch roughly 800 kilometres from north to south. Most of the population lives on the main island of Tongatapu, the site of the capital. The islands are spread widely across the southern Pacific, with the great majority of people concentrated on that one main island.",
  "transvaal": "Transvaal is a historical geographic term for the land north of, or beyond, the Vaal River in South Africa. A number of states and administrative divisions have carried the name over time. The South African Republic, a Boer republic also known in English as the Transvaal, existed from 1856 until 1902. It was succeeded by the Transvaal Colony under British rule from 1902 to 1910. From 1910 to 1994 the Transvaal was a province, first of the Union of South Africa and later of the Republic of South Africa.",
  "trinidad and tobago": "Trinidad and Tobago, officially the Republic of Trinidad and Tobago, is the southernmost archipelagic country in the Caribbean. It comprises the main islands of Trinidad and Tobago along with several smaller islets, forming the southern end of the Caribbean's eastern island chain. The capital is Port of Spain, while its largest and most populous municipality is Chaguanas. The country lies just off the northeastern coast of Venezuela, close to the South American mainland and northwest of Guyana. Grenada lies to its north and Barbados to its northeast across the surrounding waters.",
  "trucial oman": "The Trucial States, also known as the Trucial Coast, the Trucial Sheikhdoms, or Trucial Oman, were a group of tribal confederations in southeastern Arabia south of the Persian Gulf. Their leaders signed a series of protective treaties with the British Empire between 1820 and 1892, giving the region its name. The states remained an informal British protectorate until the treaties were revoked on 1 December 1971. The following day, six of the sheikhdoms—Dubai, Abu Dhabi, Sharjah, Ajman, Umm Al Quwain, and Fujairah—joined to form the United Arab Emirates. The seventh, Ras Al Khaimah, joined the union on 10 February 1972.",
  "tunisia": "Tunisia, officially the Republic of Tunisia, is a country in the Maghreb region of North Africa. It is bordered by Algeria to the west and southwest, Libya to the southeast, and the Mediterranean Sea to the north and east. Across the sea it shares maritime borders with Italy and Malta to the north and east. The country is home to major historical sites, including the archaeological remains of ancient Carthage and the Great Mosque of Kairouan. It is widely known for its ancient architecture, its souks, and its blue Mediterranean coastline.",
  "turkey": "Turkey, officially the Republic of Türkiye, is a country located mainly in Anatolia in West Asia, with a smaller part called East Thrace in Southeast Europe. It borders the Black Sea to the north; Georgia, Armenia, Azerbaijan, and Iran to the east; Iraq, Syria, and the Mediterranean Sea to the south; and the Aegean Sea, Greece, and Bulgaria to the west. Its population is predominantly ethnic Turks, with Kurds forming the largest ethnic minority. Officially a secular state, Turkey has a Muslim-majority population. Ankara serves as its capital and second-largest city.",
  "turkmenistan": "Turkmenistan is a landlocked country in Central Asia, bordered by Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan to the north, Afghanistan to the southeast, Iran to the south and southwest, and the Caspian Sea to the west. It is one of six independent Turkic states and lies among the most sparsely populated nations of the Asian continent. Ashgabat is its capital and largest city. It has the lowest population of the Central Asian republics, being one of the most sparsely settled countries on the continent. Turkmenistan has long served as a thoroughfare for numerous empires and cultures crossing Central Asia.",
  "turks and caicos is.": "The Turks and Caicos Islands are a British Overseas Territory consisting of the larger Caicos Islands and the smaller Turks Islands. These two groups of tropical islands lie within the Lucayan Archipelago of the Atlantic Ocean and the northern West Indies. The territory is known primarily for tourism and as an offshore financial centre. The islands sit southeast of Mayaguana in the Bahamas island chain and north of the island of Hispaniola. They are among the more prominent of the British overseas territories in the Caribbean region.",
  "tuvalu": "Tuvalu is an archipelagic country in the Polynesian sub-region of Oceania in the Pacific Ocean, lying roughly midway between Hawaii and Australia. It sits east-northeast of the Santa Cruz Islands, northeast of Vanuatu, southeast of Nauru, south of Kiribati, and north of Fiji. The country is composed of three reef islands and six atolls, spread between about 5° and 10° south latitude and 176° and 180° longitude. Its islands lie just west of the International Date Line. Tuvalu is one of the world's smallest and least populous nations, known for its low-lying coral islands.",
  "u.s. virgin is.": "The United States Virgin Islands, officially the Virgin Islands of the United States, are a Caribbean unincorporated territory of the United States. The islands are geographically part of the Virgin Islands archipelago and are located in the Leeward Islands of the Lesser Antilles. They consist of the main islands of Saint Croix, Saint John, and Saint Thomas, along with dozens of surrounding minor islands and cays. The territory has a tropical climate and a landscape shaped by its position in the eastern Caribbean. It remains under United States sovereignty as one of several American territories in the region.",
  "uganda": "Uganda, officially the Republic of Uganda, is a landlocked country in East Africa. It is bordered by Kenya to the east, South Sudan to the north, the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the west, Rwanda to the south-west, and Tanzania to the south. Its southern part includes a substantial portion of Lake Victoria, which it shares with Kenya and Tanzania. Uganda lies within the African Great Lakes region and the Nile basin, and it has a varied equatorial climate. Its capital and largest city is Kampala.",
  "ukraine": "Ukraine is a country in Eastern Europe and is the second-largest country in Europe after Russia. It borders Russia to the east and northeast, Belarus to the north, Poland and Slovakia to the west, and Hungary, Romania and Moldova to the southwest. To the south and southeast it faces the Black Sea and the Sea of Azov. Kyiv is its capital and largest city, followed by Kharkiv, Odesa and Dnipro. The official language of the country is Ukrainian.",
  "united arab emirates": "The United Arab Emirates, also known simply as the Emirates, is a country in West Asia, situated at the eastern end of the Arabian Peninsula. It is a federal semi-constitutional monarchy made up of seven emirates. Abu Dhabi serves as its national capital. The UAE borders Oman to the east and northeast and Saudi Arabia to the southwest. It shares maritime borders with Qatar and Iran in the Persian Gulf and with Oman in the Gulf of Oman.",
  "united kingdom": "The United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland, commonly known as the United Kingdom or Britain, is a country in northwestern Europe, off the coast of the continental mainland. It comprises England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland. The UK includes the island of Great Britain, the north-eastern part of the island of Ireland, and most of the smaller islands within the British Isles. It shares a land border with the Republic of Ireland and is surrounded by the Atlantic Ocean, the North Sea, the English Channel, the Celtic Sea and the Irish Sea. It also maintains sovereignty over the Crown Dependencies and the British Overseas Territories.",
  "united kingdom of great britain and ireland": "The United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland was established by the Acts of Union in 1801, which united the Kingdom of Great Britain and the Kingdom of Ireland into one unitary and sovereign state. It continued in this form until it evolved into the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland, after the Irish Free State gained a degree of independence in 1922. Rapid industrialisation that had begun in the decades prior to the state's formation continued up to the mid-19th century. The Great Irish Famine, exacerbated by government inaction, led to demographic collapse in much of Ireland and increased calls for Irish land reform. During this era of the Industrial Revolution and the growth of trade and finance, Britain largely dominated the world economy.",
  "united states of america": "The United States of America, also known as the United States or America, is a country primarily located in North America. It is a federal republic consisting of 50 states and a federal capital district, Washington, D.C. The 48 contiguous states border Canada to the north and Mexico to the south, with the semi-exclave of Alaska in the northwest and the archipelago of Hawaii in the Pacific Ocean. The United States also asserts sovereignty over five major island territories and various uninhabited islands in Oceania and the Caribbean. It is a megadiverse country with one of the world's largest land areas.",
  "united states virgin islands": "The United States Virgin Islands, officially the Virgin Islands of the United States, are a Caribbean unincorporated territory of the United States. They are geographically part of the Virgin Islands archipelago. The islands are located in the Leeward Islands of the Lesser Antilles. They have a tropical climate. The territory consists of the main islands of Saint Croix, Saint John and Saint Thomas, along with 50 other surrounding minor islands and cays.",
  "uruguay": "Uruguay, officially the Oriental Republic of Uruguay, is a country in South America. It shares borders with Argentina to its west and southwest and Brazil to its north and northeast. It also borders the Río de la Plata to the south and the Atlantic Ocean to the southeast. It is part of the Southern Cone region of South America. Its capital and largest city is Montevideo.",
  "usnb guantanamo bay": "Guantanamo Bay Naval Base, officially known as Naval Station Guantanamo Bay and commonly called GTMO or Gitmo, is a United States military base on the shore of Guantánamo Bay at the southeastern end of Cuba. It occupies land and water leased from Cuba and has functioned under de facto U.S. control since 1903, when it began as a coaling station and naval base. It is the oldest overseas American naval base. Under the lease arrangement, the United States pays the Cuban government an annual sum for use of the bay. The terms of the lease were revised in 1934 to be tied to the value of gold.",
  "uzbekistan": "Uzbekistan, officially the Republic of Uzbekistan, is a doubly landlocked country located in Central Asia. It is bordered by Kazakhstan to the north, Kyrgyzstan to the northeast, Tajikistan to the southeast, Afghanistan to the south, and Turkmenistan to the southwest. It is one of only two doubly landlocked countries in the world, the other being Liechtenstein. It is the most populous of the Central Asian republics. Uzbekistan is a member of the Organization of Turkic States.",
  "vanuatu": "Vanuatu, officially the Republic of Vanuatu, is an archipelagic country in Melanesia located in the South Pacific Ocean. The archipelago is of volcanic origin and lies east of northern Australia, northeast of New Caledonia, east of New Guinea, southeast of the Solomon Islands, and west of Fiji. It was first inhabited by Melanesian people. The first Europeans to visit the islands were a Spanish expedition led by the Portuguese navigator Fernandes de Queirós. They arrived on the largest island, Espíritu Santo, in 1606.",
  "vatican": "Vatican City is an independent city-state located entirely within the Italian capital of Rome, serving as the spiritual and administrative center of the Catholic Church. It came into being as a sovereign state through the Lateran Treaty of 1929, which resolved the long-standing dispute between the Holy See and Italy over the former Papal States. It is the world's smallest fully independent country by both area and population, encompassing landmarks such as St. Peter's Basilica, the Apostolic Palace, and the Vatican Museums. Governed as an absolute elective monarchy, it is headed by the pope, who serves as head of state by virtue of his role as Bishop of Rome and leader of the worldwide Catholic Church. It maintains its own institutions, including a postal service, media outlets, and the Swiss Guard, and enjoys a status distinct from the surrounding Italian state.",
  "venezuela": "Venezuela, officially the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela, is a country on the northern coast of South America. It consists of a continental landmass and various islands and islets in the Caribbean Sea. Its capital and largest urban agglomeration is Caracas. The continental territory is bordered on the north by the Caribbean Sea and the Atlantic Ocean, on the west by Colombia, on the south by Brazil, to the north-east by Trinidad and Tobago, and on the east by Guyana. Venezuela consists of 23 states, the Capital District, and federal dependencies covering its offshore islands.",
  "vietnam": "Vietnam, officially the Socialist Republic of Viet Nam, is a country at the eastern edge of Mainland Southeast Asia. It is one of two communist states in Southeast Asia and is bordered by China to the north and Laos and Cambodia to the west. It lies along the Gulf of Thailand to the southwest and the South China Sea to the east, where it has shared and disputed maritime borders with other countries. Its capital is Hanoi, while its largest city is Ho Chi Minh City. Vietnam was inhabited by the Paleolithic age, with states established in the first millennium BC on the Red River Delta in modern-day northern Vietnam.",
  "w. sahara": "Western Sahara is a territory in north-western Africa, designated by the United Nations as a non-self-governing territory. It consists mainly of desert flatlands and is one of the most sparsely populated territories in the world. It is often described as Africa's last colony, being the last African territory yet to achieve full independence. Spain colonized the region as the Spanish Sahara, holding it until 1975, when it withdrew during the Spanish transition to democracy. Its final political status has remained unresolved since that withdrawal.",
  "wallis and futuna is.": "Wallis and Futuna, officially the Territory of the Wallis and Futuna Islands, is a French island collectivity in the South Pacific. It lies between Tuvalu to the northwest, Fiji to the southwest, Tonga to the southeast, Samoa to the east, and Tokelau to the northeast. Its capital and largest settlement is Mata Utu. As a French overseas country and territory, it is associated with the European Union rather than being a full member. The territory comprises two main island groups, Wallis and the Futuna Islands, and is among the smallest of France's overseas holdings.",
  "wallis and futuna islands": "Wallis and Futuna, officially the Territory of the Wallis and Futuna Islands, is a French island collectivity in the South Pacific. It lies between Tuvalu to the northwest, Fiji to the southwest, Tonga to the southeast, Samoa to the east, and Tokelau to the northeast. Its capital and largest settlement is Mata Utu. As a French overseas country and territory, it is associated with the European Union rather than being a full member. The territory comprises two main island groups, Wallis and the Futuna Islands, and is among the smallest of France's overseas holdings.",
  "yaka": "The Yaka were a Central African kingdom and people of the Kwango region, in the forest and savanna between the Kwango and Wamba rivers in what is now southwestern Democratic Republic of the Congo, near the Angolan border. The kingdom arose from a westward Lunda migration that established authority over the area, blending with the resident Kongo-related populations so that the Yaka came to speak a Kongo language while retaining Lunda political traditions. It was headed by a paramount chief known as the kiambvu, beneath whom a body of titled nobles and local earth-chiefs governed clusters of villages. The Yaka were a matrilineal, farming and hunting society, and their kingdom was regarded as one of the more centralized and organized states of the region. During the colonial era the Yaka became known for their sustained resistance to European penetration, and they remain celebrated for their sculpture, masks, and other arts.",
  "yeke": "The Yeke Kingdom, also called the Garanganze kingdom, was a nineteenth-century state in the Katanga region of what is now the southeastern Democratic Republic of the Congo. It was founded and ruled by Msiri, a Nyamwezi trader from the Tabora area of present-day Tanzania, and lasted from around 1856 until 1891 under his sole reign. The kingdom grew powerful by exploiting Katanga's copper and ivory, which Msiri traded for firearms and gunpowder, and by controlling a major east-west trans-continental trade route as well as forging alliances through marriage. At its height it dominated a large territory in south-central Africa, extracting wealth from copper, ivory, and the slave trade. The kingdom ended in 1891 when Msiri was killed during the Stairs Expedition, and its lands were absorbed into King Leopold II's Congo Free State.",
  "yemen": "Yemen, officially the Republic of Yemen, is a country in West Asia occupying the southern part of the Arabian Peninsula. It borders Saudi Arabia to the north and Oman to the northeast, with coastlines along the Arabian Sea, the Gulf of Aden, and the Red Sea, and includes the Socotra Archipelago. Across the Horn of Africa it shares maritime borders with Djibouti, Eritrea, Somaliland, and Somalia. Sanaa is its constitutional capital and largest city. Yemen is one of the larger states of the Arabian Peninsula and has a long coastline commanding strategic access between the Red Sea and the Indian Ocean.",
  "zambia": "Zambia, officially the Republic of Zambia, is a landlocked country in Southern Africa. It borders the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the north, Tanzania to the northeast, Malawi to the east, Mozambique to the southeast, Zimbabwe and Botswana to the south, Namibia to the southwest, and Angola to the west. Its capital and largest city is Lusaka, in the south-central part of the country, and its population is concentrated mainly around Lusaka and the Copperbelt Province in the north, the nation's core economic hubs. The region was originally inhabited by Khoisan peoples before being reshaped by the Bantu expansion. These migrations laid the foundation for the peoples who live in the country today.",
  "zimbabwe": "Zimbabwe, officially the Republic of Zimbabwe, is a landlocked country in Southeast Africa lying between the Zambezi and Limpopo Rivers. It borders South Africa to the south, Botswana to the southwest, Zambia to the north, and Mozambique to the east. Its capital and largest city is Harare, with Bulawayo the second largest. The Shona and Northern Ndebele are the country's largest ethnic groups, and it recognizes numerous official languages, of which English, Shona, and Ndebele are the most widely used. Zimbabwe is a member of the United Nations, the African Union, the Southern African Development Community, and the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa.",
  "zululand": "Zululand is a name for the historical homeland of the Zulu people in what is now south-eastern South Africa. It is most closely associated with the Zulu Kingdom, the powerful nineteenth-century state that arose in the region. Under later South African policy the name was applied to KwaZulu, a Bantustan established for Zulu people in the twentieth century. Today the region falls within the province of KwaZulu-Natal, and the name survives in the Zululand District Municipality. It is also used ecclesiastically, as in the Anglican Diocese of Zululand.",
  "åland": "Åland is an autonomous and demilitarised region of Finland, situated in an archipelago at the entrance to the Gulf of Bothnia in the Baltic Sea. It received its autonomy in 1920 and is the smallest of Finland's regions by both area and population. Its sole official language is Swedish, and its capital is Mariehamn. The region comprises Fasta Åland, the main island where the great majority of the population lives, together with thousands of surrounding skerries and smaller islands, only a few dozen of which are inhabited. Fasta Åland is separated from the Roslagen coast of Sweden to the west by a stretch of open water.",
  "british empire": "The British Empire was a global network of colonies, protectorates, dominions, mandates, and other territories ruled or administered by the United Kingdom, originating with English overseas trading posts and settlements from the late 16th and early 17th centuries and enduring until the era of decolonisation in the mid-to-late 20th century. At its height in the early 20th century it was the largest empire in history, spanning every inhabited continent and including major possessions in North America, the Caribbean, Africa, South and Southeast Asia, Australasia, and numerous islands across the Atlantic, Indian, and Pacific oceans. Its holdings were governed through varied arrangements, from crown colonies under Crown-appointed governors and protectorates administered through local rulers to self-governing dominions such as Canada, Australia, New Zealand, and South Africa that gained increasing autonomy, formalised by the Statute of Westminster in 1931. The empire's expansion was driven by maritime commerce, naval power, and the pursuit of resources and markets, and it played a central role in global trade, migration, and the spread of the English language, legal traditions, and institutions. Following the Second World War most territories became independent, with many joining the Commonwealth of Nations, and the empire's legacy remains significant and widely debated in the histories of its former colonies and of Britain itself.",
  "french colonial empire": "The French colonial empire was the collection of overseas territories, protectorates, and mandates ruled or administered by France, conventionally divided into a first empire that flourished from the 16th to the 18th centuries and a second empire that expanded through the 19th and early 20th centuries. The first empire centered on North America, the Caribbean, and trading posts in India and West Africa, much of which was lost or ceded by the early 19th century, while the second empire, beginning with the conquest of Algiers in 1830, came to span large parts of Africa, Indochina and other regions of Southeast Asia, and scattered island possessions across the Pacific, Indian, and Atlantic oceans. At its height it ranked among the largest empires in the world, second only to the British Empire, and its holdings were governed through a patchwork of directly ruled colonies, protectorates that retained local rulers, and later League of Nations mandates, all ultimately subordinate to authorities in Paris. Colonial administration blended assimilationist ideals with unequal legal systems, and most colonial subjects were governed as such rather than granted full French citizenship. Following the Second World War the empire was progressively dismantled through decolonization, culminating in the independence of most territories by the 1960s, though France retains several overseas departments and territories, and the empire left enduring legacies in language, law, and the cultural sphere often described as the Francophone world.",
  "german colonial empire": "The German colonial empire was the collection of overseas territories governed by Germany from the mid-1880s until the aftermath of the First World War, established largely under Chancellor Otto von Bismarck as the German Empire joined the late-nineteenth-century scramble for colonies. Its possessions lay chiefly in Africa, including German East Africa, German South West Africa, Kamerun, and Togoland, alongside holdings in the Pacific such as parts of New Guinea, Samoa, and various island groups, and a leased concession at Kiautschou in China. Administration was at first often delegated to chartered trading companies granted state protection, but responsibility increasingly shifted to direct imperial rule overseen by a colonial office answerable to the government in Berlin. German rule was marked by economic exploitation and military campaigns against local populations, including the war against the Herero and Nama peoples in South West Africa, which is widely regarded as a genocide. Following Germany's defeat in the First World War, the empire was dissolved by the Treaty of Versailles in 1919, with its territories redistributed among the victorious powers as League of Nations mandates.",
  "italian colonial empire": "The Italian colonial empire was the overseas territories controlled by Italy from the late nineteenth century until the mid-twentieth century, concentrated mainly in northern and eastern Africa. Its principal possessions were Eritrea, Italian Somaliland, and Libya, joined after the conquest of Ethiopia in the 1930s to form Italian East Africa, while smaller holdings included the Dodecanese Islands in the Aegean and a concession in the Chinese city of Tianjin. The empire was administered through appointed governors and colonial officials answerable to the government in Rome, and its expansion was driven by aspirations to national prestige, strategic access to the Mediterranean and Red Sea, and settlement schemes for Italian emigrants. It reached its greatest extent in the late 1930s but collapsed during the Second World War, when Allied forces occupied its African territories, and Italy formally renounced its colonies in the 1947 peace treaty. Its legacy includes lasting cultural and infrastructural traces in the former colonies, contested historical memory in Italy, and the shaping of the modern states of Libya, Eritrea, Somalia, and Ethiopia.",
  "dutch colonial empire": "The Dutch colonial empire was the network of overseas territories, colonies, and trading posts controlled by the Netherlands from the late 16th century until the late 20th century. At its greatest extent it stretched across the globe, with holdings in the East Indies and other parts of Asia, southern and western Africa, the Caribbean, and northeastern South America, together with trading stations in North America, India, Ceylon, and East Asia. Much of the empire was administered not directly by the state but by chartered trading companies, above all the Dutch East India Company and the Dutch West India Company, which were granted quasi-governmental powers to wage war, sign treaties, and govern territory in pursuit of commerce in spices, sugar, and other goods. After these companies were dissolved around the turn of the 19th century, their possessions passed to the Kingdom of the Netherlands, which ruled the remaining colonies as a state until the independence of Indonesia in 1949 and Suriname in 1975. Its legacy endures in language, place names, legal and administrative institutions, and lasting cultural ties, while several Caribbean islands remain constituent countries within the modern Kingdom of the Netherlands.",
  "portuguese empire": "The Portuguese Empire was one of the earliest and longest-lasting of the European seaborne colonial empires, conventionally dated from the capture of Ceuta in 1415 to the handover of Macau in 1999. Built on maritime exploration and trade, it was a globally dispersed network of coastal territories, fortified ports, and trading posts spanning South America, Africa, the Indian subcontinent, Southeast and East Asia, and Oceania, with Brazil as its largest and most populous colony until Brazilian independence in 1822. Authority was exercised on behalf of the Portuguese crown through appointed governors and viceroys, royal officials, and military garrisons, with ultimate legal and administrative control centered in Lisbon. Its economy rested heavily on the spice and Asian trade, plantation agriculture, and the transatlantic slave trade, and after the loss of Brazil the empire became predominantly African, centered on Angola, Mozambique, and Guinea. The empire's legacy includes the global spread of the Portuguese language, Catholicism, and cultural influence, as well as the enduring political and social consequences of colonization and the slave trade across several continents.",
  "spanish empire": "The Spanish Empire was one of the largest empires in history, extending from the late fifteenth century following the transatlantic voyages of Christopher Columbus until the twentieth century, and at its height it was often described as the empire on which the sun never set. Its territories spanned much of the Americas, the Philippines and other Pacific islands, coastal enclaves and possessions in Africa, and lands within Europe including areas of Italy and the Low Countries. The empire was ruled by the Crown of Castile and administered through institutions such as the Council of the Indies and a network of viceroyalties, notably New Spain and Peru, each governed by a viceroy acting as the monarch's direct representative. Reaching its zenith under the Habsburg dynasty during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, it drew great wealth from silver mining and transoceanic trade while spreading the Spanish language, Catholicism, and Iberian institutions across its domains. It declined gradually amid warfare and financial strain, losing most of its American colonies in the early nineteenth century and its remaining major overseas holdings by the end of that century, leaving a lasting legacy in the languages, religions, and cultures of many nations today.",
  "belgian colonial empire": "The Belgian colonial empire comprised the overseas territories governed by Belgium and its monarch, overwhelmingly concentrated in Central Africa and dominated by the vast Congo basin, alongside the smaller neighboring territory of Ruanda-Urundi and a few minor holdings and concessions elsewhere. Its principal possession originated as the Congo Free State, held from the 1880s as the personal domain of King Leopold II, whose regime of forced labor and violent resource extraction provoked international outcry and led the Belgian state to annex the territory as the Belgian Congo in 1908. Ruanda-Urundi, seized from German East Africa during the First World War, was administered by Belgium as a League of Nations mandate and later a United Nations trust territory, governed in close connection with the Congo. Colonial administration rested largely on a partnership of the state, Catholic missions, and private companies, which together controlled government, education, and the extraction of minerals, rubber, and other commodities. The empire was dismantled around 1960 to 1962 as the Congo, Rwanda, and Burundi became independent, and its legacy remains marked by the enduring social and political consequences of Belgian rule and the enormous human toll of the early Congo regime.",
  "danish realm": "The Danish Realm is the collective term for the Kingdom of Denmark together with its North Atlantic dependencies, historically comprising metropolitan Denmark in northern Europe alongside Iceland, Greenland, and the Faroe Islands. Denmark proper occupies the Jutland peninsula and an archipelago between the North and Baltic Seas, while its dependencies stretch far across the North Atlantic and into the Arctic, making Greenland the world's largest island and giving the realm an enormous but sparsely populated overseas reach. The realm has been governed as a unitary constitutional monarchy under the Danish crown, with the outlying territories long administered as dependencies before gradually acquiring autonomy, Iceland gaining home rule in 1904 and full sovereignty under a personal union in 1918 before becoming an independent republic in 1944. The Faroe Islands and Greenland remained within the kingdom and were granted home rule in the 20th century and expanded self-government thereafter, an arrangement known as Rigsfællesskabet, the Unity of the Realm, under which Copenhagen retains foreign affairs and defence. As a historical entity the Danish Realm reflects the maritime and colonial expansion of a small European kingdom into the North Atlantic and Arctic, and its legacy survives in the lasting constitutional ties between Denmark, Greenland, and the Faroe Islands.",
  "warlord-era china": "Warlord-era China refers to the period of the Republic of China, roughly from the death of President Yuan Shikai in 1916 until reunification in 1928, when effective authority over the country was fragmented among rival regional military commanders. Although a central Beiyang government based in Beijing continued to represent China internationally and was recognized by foreign powers as the legitimate state, in practice it controlled little beyond the capital and functioned largely as the instrument of whichever military clique held Beijing at a given time. Real power rested with competing factions such as the Anhui, Zhili, and Fengtian cliques in the north and the Yunnan, Guangxi, and Sichuan cliques in the south, each holding sway over provinces or clusters of provinces through their own armies and shifting alliances. The era was marked by frequent civil wars, a persistent north-south division, weak central institutions, and continued foreign influence over Chinese territory and finances. It ended with the Kuomintang's Northern Expedition, which defeated or absorbed the major warlords and formally reunified China under a Nationalist government at Nanjing in 1928, though regional military power endured well beyond that date.",
  "ussr": "The Soviet Union, officially the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics (USSR), was a state in Eastern Europe and northern Asia that existed from 1922 until its dissolution in 1991, emerging from the Russian Empire in the wake of the Russian Revolution and civil war. Stretching from the Baltic Sea and the borders of Central and Eastern Europe eastward across Siberia to the Pacific Ocean, it was the largest country in the world by land area and spanned numerous time zones and climatic zones. It was organized as a nominally federal union of national republics, growing to encompass fifteen constituent republics, of which the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic was the largest and most dominant. In practice it functioned as a highly centralized one-party state governed by the Communist Party under the ideology of Marxism-Leninism, with a command economy in which industry and agriculture were placed under state control. As one of the two superpowers of the Cold War, it exercised broad influence over allied socialist states and left a lasting legacy on twentieth-century geopolitics, its collapse giving rise to fifteen independent successor states.",
  "empire of japan": "The Empire of Japan was the Japanese state that existed from the Meiji Restoration in 1868 until the promulgation of a new constitution in 1947, spanning the reigns of the Meiji, Taishō, and Shōwa emperors. Centered on the Japanese archipelago in East Asia, it expanded through war and annexation to include Taiwan, Korea, southern Sakhalin, the Kuril Islands, and Pacific island territories, and during the Second World War it briefly occupied large portions of the Asia-Pacific region. Under the Meiji Constitution of 1889 it was governed as a semi-constitutional monarchy in which the emperor was the sovereign head of state and supreme commander of the armed forces, alongside a bicameral Imperial Diet, an appointed cabinet, and influential elder statesmen. From the 1920s and 1930s the military assumed a dominant role in politics, driving an era of aggressive expansionism and colonial rule across the region. The empire ended with Japan's defeat and surrender in 1945 and the subsequent Allied occupation, after which the 1947 constitution reduced the emperor to a ceremonial figure and reconstituted the country as a parliamentary democracy.",
  "union of south africa": "The Union of South Africa was a state occupying the southern tip of the African continent, established in 1910 through the unification of the former Cape, Natal, Transvaal, and Orange River colonies. It began as a self-governing Dominion of the British Empire and later a Commonwealth realm, with the British monarch as head of state represented locally by a Governor-General, while executive power rested with a prime minister and cabinet answerable to an elected parliament. Its territory encompassed the same broad region as present-day South Africa, and it administered the neighbouring mandate of South West Africa, while the surrounding British high commission territories remained separate. Political power was reserved almost entirely for the white minority, with the Black African majority as well as Coloured and Indian communities largely excluded from the franchise, laying the groundwork for the segregationist policies that culminated in apartheid. The Union endured until 1961, when a referendum among white voters led to its replacement by the Republic of South Africa and its departure from the Commonwealth.",
  "british canada": "The Constitutional Act of 1791 partitioned the Province of Quebec into Lower Canada and Upper Canada, giving each an appointed governor or lieutenant-governor, an appointed legislative and executive council, and an elected legislative assembly. Lower Canada retained French civil law, seigneurial tenure, and the privileges of the Roman Catholic Church, while Upper Canada was organized under English common law to accommodate the Loyalists who had fled the American Revolution. Effective executive power rested with the British-appointed governor general at Quebec, and the elected assemblies had limited authority over the colonial administration. Persistent friction between the assemblies and the appointed councils fed constitutional grievances that culminated in the Rebellions of 1837–1838 in both provinces. Lord Durham's ensuing report led to the Act of Union of 1840, which merged the two into the single Province of Canada in 1841, ending this constitutional arrangement.",
  "bambara empire": "The Bambara Empire of Ségou emerged as a centralized state around 1712 when Mamari (Biton) Coulibaly transformed the communal ton age-group associations into a standing military monarchy on the upper Niger. Power rested on the faama (ruler) commanding the tonjon, a warrior caste drawn largely from enslaved and captive soldiers, giving the state an unusually militarized and predatory character sustained by raiding and the slave trade. After Biton's death in 1755 the Coulibaly dynasty collapsed into instability until Ngolo Diarra seized the throne in 1766, founding the Ngolosi (Diarra) dynasty and restoring firm control over Djenné and Timbuktu. His son Mansong (Monzon) Diarra ruled from 1790 to 1808, marking the empire's zenith through relentless campaigns against Kaarta, Massina, the Dogon, and the Mossi. The empire declined after Mansong's death, suffered defeat by Fula jihadists at Noukouma in 1818, and was finally conquered in 1861 by El Hadj Umar Tall's Toucouleur forces.",
  "awadh": "Awadh was founded in 1722 when the Persian-born Shia adventurer Saadat Ali Khan I, styled Burhan-ul-Mulk, was appointed subahdar and turned the office into a hereditary principality under nominal Mughal suzerainty. His successors Safdar Jung and Shuja-ud-Daula expanded the state and secured the Mughal office of wazir, until defeat by the East India Company at Buxar in 1764 forced Awadh into an increasingly subordinate alliance. Asaf-ud-Daula moved the capital from Faizabad to Lucknow in 1775, presiding over a celebrated court culture even as British subsidies and territorial demands mounted. In 1798 the Company deposed Wazir Ali Khan and installed Saadat Ali Khan II, who by the 1801 Treaty of Lucknow ceded roughly half the state's territory to the British in exchange for military protection. The much-reduced state endured as a British-dependent kingdom after its rulers assumed the royal title in 1819, until the Company annexed it in 1856 on the pretext of misgovernment.",
  "batavian republic": "The Batavian Republic was proclaimed on 19 January 1795 when French revolutionary armies and Dutch Patriot exiles toppled the stadtholderate of William V, who fled to England, ending the old Republic of the Seven United Netherlands. Established as a French sister republic, it abolished the federal structure of the provinces and, under the unitary constitution of 1798, created a centralized state modelled on the French Directory, with executive power held by a five-member Uitvoerend Bewind. Its politics were turbulent, marked by successive coups d'état between radical unitarist and moderate federalist factions and by financial ruin from war indemnities and the loss of overseas trade. A revised constitution in October 1801 recast it as the Batavian Commonwealth under a twelve-member Staatsbewind, and in 1805 Napoleon imposed rule by a single grand pensionary, Rutger Jan Schimmelpenninck. The republic was dissolved on 5 June 1806 when Napoleon replaced it with the Kingdom of Holland under his brother Louis Bonaparte.",
  "bahawalpur": "Bahawalpur was founded in 1748 by Nawab Bahawal Khan I, whose Daudpotra family, claiming Abbasid descent, had migrated from Shikarpur in Sindh and carved out a principality along the Sutlej. The Abbasi nawabs ruled continuously, holding their territory as tributaries of the Durrani Empire until that empire's collapse allowed Muhammad Bahawal Khan II to assert effective independence in the early nineteenth century. The dynasty consolidated power through a network of desert forts, most notably Derawar, which sheltered the ruling house during an Afghan-backed assault on the capital in 1785. In 1833 Bahawalpur entered a subsidiary alliance with the British East India Company, becoming a princely state that supported the British in the First Anglo-Afghan War and the 1848 campaign against Multan. It survived under the Abbasi nawabs until 1947, when it acceded to Pakistan as the first princely state to do so, and was finally merged into West Pakistan in 1955.",
  "anhalt principalities": "The Anhalt lands were held by the House of Ascania, whose Henry I was made a Prince of the Holy Roman Empire in 1218, making Anhalt one of the oldest continuously ruled German princely territories. After Joachim Ernest briefly reunited the lands, his sons partitioned Anhalt in 1603 into the branch principalities of Dessau, Bernburg, Köthen, Zerbst, and Plötzkau, each a sovereign Imperial Estate under its own Ascanian prince. The lines repeatedly extinguished and re-merged, most notably when Anhalt-Zerbst died out in 1793 and was divided among Dessau, Bernburg, and Köthen. In 1806 Napoleon elevated the three surviving principalities to duchies, and they were dissolved as separate states only when the Köthen line failed in 1847/1853 and the Bernburg line in 1863, at which point all Anhalt was reunited under Dessau as the single Duchy of Anhalt. Throughout their history the principalities remained small, closely intermarried Ascanian states, punching above their weight through Enlightenment reform, Protestant patronage, and a tradition of famous soldiers.",
  "bornu empire": "The Bornu Empire was the west-of-Lake-Chad successor to the earlier Kanem state, established around 1380 when Mai Umar I and the Sayfawa dynasty relocated their imperial center to Bornu after being driven from Kanem by the Bilala. Ruled by the mais of the long-lived Sayfawa line, it reached its zenith under Mai Idris Alooma in the late sixteenth and early seventeenth centuries, whose military and administrative reforms, firearms, and consolidation of Islam made Bornu a dominant regional power. From the mid-seventeenth century onward the empire entered a slow decline, weakened by dynastic troubles, drought, defeats such as the 1781 Mandara reverse, and the erosion of its trans-Saharan trade dominance. In the early nineteenth century Fulani forces of Usman dan Fodio's jihad overran the empire and sacked Ngazargamu in 1808, after which the scholar-warrior Muhammad al-Kanemi rose to become the true power in the state while the Sayfawa mais became figureheads. The Sayfawa dynasty finally ended in 1846 when the last mai was killed, and the al-Kanemi shehus supplanted them as rulers of Bornu.",
  "british ceylon": "British forces took the Dutch-held maritime provinces of Ceylon in a campaign of 1795–96, receiving the surrender of Colombo on 15 February 1796. The captured coastal belt was at first governed from Madras by the East India Company, whose fiscal exactions provoked a serious revolt in 1797. From 1798 the territory passed to a dual arrangement in which Frederick North served as the first British governor while the Company retained control of commercial affairs, and in 1802 the Treaty of Amiens confirmed British possession and made Ceylon a distinct crown colony. British rule was long confined to the maritime lowlands, as the highland Kingdom of Kandy preserved its independence until its annexation in 1815 unified the whole island under the Crown. British Ceylon endured as a colony until the island gained independence as the Dominion of Ceylon in 1948.",
  "british west indies": "The British West Indies grew from seventeenth-century settlement and conquest, as England seized islands such as Barbados, the Leewards, and Jamaica (taken from Spain in 1655) and built them into wealthy sugar-and-slave plantation colonies. Each island was administered as a distinct Crown colony or proprietary colony, typically with its own governor, appointed council, and elected assembly of white planters, rather than as a single federated territory. Their fortunes were shaped by the transatlantic slave trade and by repeated Anglo-French and Anglo-Spanish wars, which passed islands like Grenada, Dominica, and St. Vincent back and forth before Britain secured them by the treaties of 1763 and 1783. The abolition of the British slave trade in 1807 and the emancipation of the enslaved in 1833–1838 undercut the plantation economy and reshaped colonial society. The colonies persisted under varied administrative unions into the twentieth century, briefly forming the West Indies Federation in 1958 before it dissolved and the territories moved toward independence in the 1960s.",
  "cisalpine republic": "The Cisalpine Republic was proclaimed by Napoleon Bonaparte on 29 June 1797, formed by merging the Transpadane and Cispadane republics he had established in northern Italy, and it was governed under a French-modelled constitution with a five-member Directory and legislative councils. It served as a French sister-republic, its politics dominated by Paris even as local figures such as Giovanni Galeazzo Serbelloni and Francesco Melzi d'Eril held office. After the French defeat at Cassano in April 1799 the republic was overrun and occupied by Austrian and Russian forces under an imperial commission. As French forces reoccupied Lombardy in the Marengo campaign, Napoleon restored the republic on 4 June 1800, reorganising its government first under an extraordinary commission and Consulta and then a narrow Committee of Government. In January 1802 an Extraordinary Consulta meeting at Lyon renamed the state the Italian Republic with Napoleon as its president, ending the Cisalpine Republic.",
  "denmark–norway": "Denmark–Norway was a multinational, absolutist dual monarchy ruled by the House of Oldenburg, formed as a personal union of the two kingdoms after the collapse of the Kalmar Union in the 1520s and consolidated as an integrated hereditary state from 1537. Political and economic power was centralized in Copenhagen, where the crown governed Denmark, Norway, the duchies of Schleswig and Holstein, the North Atlantic dependencies of Iceland, Greenland and the Faroe Islands, and overseas trading colonies in the Caribbean, West Africa and India. The monarchy became an absolute one under Frederick III in 1660–1661, a system codified in the Kongelov, and it repeatedly contested Sweden for supremacy in the Baltic across the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries. From 1784 Crown Prince Frederick governed as regent for his mentally incapacitated father Christian VII, presiding over a period of enlightened reform including the abolition of adscription serfdom for Danish peasants. The union was dissolved after the Napoleonic Wars, when a defeated Frederick VI ceded Norway to the Swedish crown by the Treaty of Kiel in January 1814, though Denmark retained Norway's former Atlantic dependencies.",
  "bundelkhand": "Bundelkhand took its name from the Bundela Rajputs, who rose to prominence in the 16th century when Rudra Pratap Singh established Orchha as the parent Bundela kingdom, from which Datia and Panna later split off. The Bundelas repeatedly resisted Mughal authority, most famously under Chhatrasal of Panna, who after 1729 invited Peshwa Baji Rao I to aid him against Muhammad Khan Bangash and rewarded the Marathas with lands and diamond mines, opening the region to Maratha power. Through the 18th century the Bundela states fragmented into numerous small chieftaincies while the Marathas exacted tribute and eventually placed the tract under a subahdar, Ali Bahadur, grandson of Baji Rao I, who consolidated much of it as Nawab of Banda. The region thus became a mosaic of Bundela Rajput principalities and Maratha-administered districts, chronically divided and heavily burdened by tribute demands. Maratha control unravelled after the Treaty of Bassein (1802) and the Anglo-Maratha wars, and following the Third Anglo-Maratha War of 1818 the British absorbed the whole tract, reorganising it as the Bundelkhand Agency.",
  "barotseland": "The Lozi kingdom, known to its people as Bulozi and later as Barotseland, was founded in the seventeenth century by the Aluyi (Luyana) after a migration associated with the Lunda world, with Mboo Mwanasilundu Muyunda remembered as the first Litunga (king). It developed into a highly centralized, aristocratic monarchy in which the Litunga ruled through a bureaucracy of appointed councillors, headed by the Ngambela (chief minister), and a national council or kuta, with a distinctive dual-capital system dividing power between a senior northern seat and a junior southern one at Nalolo. Under successive rulers such as Ngalama, Ngombala and Yeta the kingdom expanded across the floodplain, subordinating and integrating neighbouring peoples, and it reached its classical form under the tenth Litunga, Mulambwa Santulu, celebrated as a great lawgiver who codified property, marriage and military custom and opposed the slave trade. Mulambwa's death around 1830 triggered a civil war between his sons Silumelume and Mubukwanu, which fatally weakened the state and left it vulnerable to invasion. Within a few years the Kololo under Sebitwane conquered Barotseland and ruled it until 1864, when a Lozi rebellion restored the indigenous dynasty, whose later kings culminated in Lewanika and eventual absorption into the British sphere.",
  "cyrenaica": "Cyrenaica formed the eastern portion of the Ottoman Regency of Tripoli, which from 1711 was governed as a hereditary de facto monarchy by the Karamanli dynasty while still paying nominal tribute to the Ottoman sultan. Real authority over the region was exercised from Tripoli rather than locally, and the Bedouin tribes of the interior retained wide autonomy under only light central control. Under Yusuf Karamanli, who ruled the regency from 1795, the dynasty tightened its grip, and by 1807 he had forced the tribes of Cyrenaica and the Fezzan to submit to his authority. In 1835 the Ottoman government of Sultan Mahmud II exploited local disorder to depose the Karamanlis and reassert direct imperial rule, ending the dynasty's control of the region. Later in the nineteenth century Cyrenaica became a separate Ottoman administrative unit centered on Benghazi and the seat of the influential Sanusi religious order.",
  "carnatic": "The Nawabate of the Carnatic emerged as a Mughal governorship of the Deccan, becoming a distinct hereditary Muslim principality under Saadatullah Khan I from about 1710 while nominally subordinate to the Nizam of Hyderabad. It rose to prominence under Muhammad Ali Khan Wallajah, who reigned from 1749 to 1795 and made the Nawabate a close ally of the British East India Company, drawing on Company troops to prevail over French-backed rivals in the Carnatic Wars. Wallajah's growing debts to the Company and its private creditors progressively mortgaged the state's revenues and eroded its independence, leaving successive Nawabs financially and militarily dependent on the British. His son Umdat ul-Umara, who succeeded in 1795, resisted Company demands and was accused of secret dealings with Tipu Sultan, giving the British a pretext to seize control after Tipu's defeat in 1799. Following Umdat ul-Umara's death in 1801, his nephew Azim-ud-Daula signed the Carnatic Treaty ceding civil and revenue administration to the Company, reducing the Nawabs to titular pensioners until the line was abolished under the Doctrine of Lapse in 1855.",
  "duchy of brunswick-wolfenbüttel": "The principality emerged in 1269 from a partition of the lands of the House of Welf and was ruled continuously by cadet branches of that dynasty. Its seat lay at Wolfenbüttel from 1432 until 1753, when Duke Charles I moved the court back to the larger city of Brunswick. As a princely state of the Holy Roman Empire within the Lower Saxon Circle, it retained sovereignty while its rulers cultivated ties to Prussia and to Hanover. Charles William Ferdinand, duke from 1780, was a celebrated Prussian field marshal whose defeat and mortal wounding at Jena-Auerstedt in 1806 exposed the small state to French power. Napoleon abolished it in 1807, folding its territory into the Kingdom of Westphalia until it was restored in 1815 as the Duchy of Brunswick.",
  "duchy of holstein": "The Duchy of Holstein was created on 14 February 1474 when Emperor Frederick III elevated Christian I of Denmark's County of Holstein-Rendsburg to ducal rank, and it was ruled throughout its existence by the Danish House of Oldenburg jointly with the neighbouring Duchy of Schleswig. Uniquely, it lay within the Holy Roman Empire while its dukes were also Kings of Denmark, making it a bridge between the German and Danish worlds. From 1544 the duchy was repeatedly partitioned between the royal (Glückstadt) line and the rival Holstein-Gottorp line, a fragmentation that fuelled conflict with Denmark for nearly two centuries. This division ended in 1773 when the Gottorp claimant, Grand Duke Paul of Russia, ceded his Holstein lands to the Danish crown in exchange for the County of Oldenburg, reuniting Holstein under sole Danish royal authority. After the Holy Roman Empire dissolved in 1806 the duchy briefly became sovereign, then joined the German Confederation in 1815, and it was ultimately severed from Denmark and absorbed into Prussia following the wars of 1864 and 1866.",
  "duchy of massa and carrara": "The Duchy of Massa and Principality of Carrara was a small Italian state formed in 1473 when the lord of Massa acquired the lordship of Carrara, uniting the two towns under one rule. It was governed first by the Malaspina family and, after 1520, by the Cybo-Malaspina dynasty, which elevated the domain to a duchy and principality and enriched it through the region's marble quarries. The line passed to Maria Teresa Cybo-Malaspina and then, in 1790, to her daughter Maria Beatrice d'Este, the last hereditary sovereign, whose marriage tied the state to the House of Austria-Este. French Revolutionary armies deprived the dynasty of the territory in 1796, folding it into the Cispadane and then the Cisalpine Republic and ending its independence. Restored to Maria Beatrice at the Congress of Vienna in 1815, the duchy was inherited on her death in 1829 by her son Francis IV, who absorbed it into the Este states of Modena, and it later joined the Kingdom of Italy.",
  "duchy of mecklenburg-strelitz": "The Duchy of Mecklenburg-Strelitz was created by the 1701 Treaty of Hamburg, which resolved a succession dispute by permanently partitioning the old Duchy of Mecklenburg between the senior Schwerin line and the junior Strelitz line under Adolphus Frederick II. Ruled throughout by the Strelitz branch of the House of Mecklenburg, it remained a small state of the Holy Roman Empire whose sovereigns held a shared vote with Mecklenburg-Schwerin in the Imperial Diet. Its capital moved to the newly built residence town of Neustrelitz after the old seat of Strelitz was destroyed by fire in 1712. Under Duke Charles II, whose sister Charlotte was queen consort of George III of the United Kingdom, the duchy pursued cautious neutrality during the Napoleonic upheavals before joining the French-sponsored Confederation of the Rhine in 1808. At the Congress of Vienna its ruler was elevated to grand duke in 1815, transforming the state into the Grand Duchy of Mecklenburg-Strelitz.",
  "duchy of mecklenburg-schwerin": "The Duchy of Mecklenburg-Schwerin was created in 1701 by the Treaty of Hamburg, which partitioned the older Duchy of Mecklenburg between the Schwerin and Strelitz lines of the ruling Nikloting (Obotrite-descended) dynasty. It was governed as a constitutional estate-based monarchy in which the dukes shared power uneasily with an entrenched Estates assembly of nobility and towns, a relationship formalized in the 1755 Landesgrundgesetzlicher Erbvergleich. Duke Friedrich Franz I, who succeeded his uncle Friedrich II in 1785, ruled a small but internationally recognized German principality within the Holy Roman Empire. During the Napoleonic era the duchy was occupied by French troops and coerced into joining the Confederation of the Rhine in 1808 before defecting to the anti-French coalition in 1813. In recognition of this stance, Friedrich Franz I was raised to Grand Duke at the Congress of Vienna in 1815, ending the duchy's existence as a duchy and beginning the Grand Duchy of Mecklenburg-Schwerin.",
  "duchy of württemberg": "The Duchy of Württemberg was created on 21 July 1495 when Emperor Maximilian I raised the County of Württemberg to ducal rank, with Eberhard I \"the Bearded\" as its first duke. Its early history was turbulent under Duke Ulrich, whose heavy debts, misrule, and expulsion led to a Habsburg occupation from 1520 to 1534 before he was restored and introduced the Protestant Reformation. Governed thereafter as a Lutheran state within the Holy Roman Empire, the duchy developed a strong constitutional tradition in which the territorial estates checked the ruler's power, anchored by the Treaty of Tübingen of 1514. Its strategic position exposed it to repeated French invasions during the wars of the 17th and 18th centuries, and rulers such as Duke Charles Eugene pursued absolutist and lavish courtly ambitions that strained relations with the estates. The ducal iteration ended in 1803, when Duke Frederick was elevated to Elector under the imperial reorganization, a prelude to the Kingdom of Württemberg proclaimed in 1806.",
  "duchy of parma": "The Duchy of Parma and Piacenza was created in 1545 by Pope Paul III for his illegitimate son Pier Luigi Farnese, and the Farnese dynasty ruled it until its male line died out in 1731. After a brief Habsburg interlude, the 1748 Peace of Aix-la-Chapelle installed the Spanish Bourbon Infante Philip, founding the House of Bourbon-Parma and adding Guastalla to the duchy's title. Philip's son Ferdinand I succeeded on his father's death in 1765 and presided over a devout, conservative court through the upheavals of the revolutionary era. French armies under Bonaparte overran the duchy from 1796, and by the Treaty of Aranjuez in 1801 it was ceded to France, with Ferdinand's son Louis compensated with the newly created Kingdom of Etruria. Ferdinand refused to abandon Parma and clung to nominal rule until his death in 1802, whereupon France assumed direct administration, ending this Bourbon iteration of the state.",
  "dutch east indies": "The Dutch East Indies originated when the bankrupt Dutch East India Company was dissolved on 31 December 1799 and its Asian territories, debts, and administration were nationalized by the Batavian Republic. The colonial High Government of Governor-General and Council of the Indies, inherited from the Company, continued to rule from Batavia under state rather than corporate authority. The colony passed briefly under Franco-Dutch and then British administration during the Napoleonic Wars before being restored to the Netherlands in 1816, after which Dutch power was steadily expanded across the archipelago through the nineteenth century. Its character shifted from a mercantile trading network into a directly governed territorial state, marked by systems such as the Cultivation System and by prolonged campaigns of conquest against local polities. The colony endured until the Japanese invasion of 1942 and the subsequent Indonesian struggle for independence, formally ending with the transfer of sovereignty in 1949.",
  "duchy of oldenburg": "The Duchy of Oldenburg arose in the 1770s when the counties of Oldenburg and Delmenhorst, ceded by the Danish crown to the junior Holstein-Gottorp line under the 1773 Treaty of Tsarskoye Selo, were elevated to a duchy within the Holy Roman Empire. Its first duke was Frederick August I, an aged prince-bishop of Lübeck, who was succeeded in 1785 by his son William, whose mental incapacity meant the state was governed throughout its ducal period by the regent Peter Frederick Louis. The regency oversaw a cautious, well-administered Enlightenment-era principality and gained the secularized Prince-Bishopric of Lübeck around Eutin in 1803. In 1810 Napoleon annexed the duchy to the French Empire, and its seizure became a notable grievance feeding the diplomatic rupture between France and Russia. Restored after Napoleon's fall, it was elevated by the Congress of Vienna to the Grand Duchy of Oldenburg, the form in which it continued into the 19th century.",
  "durrani empire": "The Durrani Empire was founded in 1747 when Ahmad Shah Durrani of the Sadozai clan of the Abdali (Durrani) Pashtuns was elected ruler by a tribal council following the assassination of Nader Shah, forging a confederal, tribally-based monarchy. Ahmad Shah expanded the realm through repeated campaigns, decisively defeating the Marathas at the Third Battle of Panipat in 1761 and building one of the largest Muslim empires of its era. After his death in 1772 the throne passed to his son Timur Shah, who quelled revolts and moved the primary capital from Kandahar to Kabul, keeping Peshawar as the winter seat. Following Timur Shah's death in 1793 his sons fought for the succession, and the empire slid into chronic civil war among rival Sadozai princes and their Barakzai backers, hastening the loss of Indian and Persian territories. Weakened by these dynastic feuds, the state disintegrated by the 1820s as the Barakzai dynasty displaced the Sadozai rulers, paving the way for the later Emirate of Afghanistan.",
  "electorate of bavaria": "The Wittelsbach Duchy of Bavaria was raised to an electorate on 25 February 1623 when Emperor Ferdinand II transferred the electoral dignity from the banned Frederick V of the Palatinate to Duke Maximilian I as a reward for his Catholic loyalty in the Thirty Years' War. Maximilian secured the electoral vote permanently at the Peace of Westphalia in 1648, and the Bavarian Wittelsbachs governed as one of the leading Catholic powers of the Empire for the next century and a half. When the Bavarian line died out with Maximilian III Joseph in 1777, the succession passed to Charles Theodore of the Palatinate, reuniting Bavaria and the Electoral Palatinate under a single ruler after centuries of division. On Charles Theodore's death in 1799 the inheritance devolved on Maximilian IV Joseph of the Palatinate-Zweibrücken branch, whose minister Maximilian von Montgelas launched a sweeping program of enlightened, centralizing reform. The electorate was dissolved in 1806 when Maximilian assumed the title King of Bavaria and joined the Napoleonic Confederation of the Rhine, ending Bavaria's membership in the Holy Roman Empire.",
  "emirate of diriyah": "The Emirate of Diriyah, known as the First Saudi State, was founded in 1744 when Muhammad bin Saud, emir of the Najdi town of Diriyah, allied with the religious reformer Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab to spread a puritanical revivalist doctrine under the political leadership of the House of Saud. Muhammad bin Saud's successor Abdulaziz bin Muhammad, who ruled from 1765 to 1803, dramatically expanded the state across Najd and eastern Arabia and was assassinated in the mosque at Diriyah in 1803. Under Saud bin Abdulaziz, who reigned from 1803 to 1814, the state reached its zenith, seizing the holy cities of Mecca and Medina and directly challenging Ottoman authority over the Hejaz. This defiance provoked the Ottoman sultan to task Muhammad Ali of Egypt with crushing the emirate, and his son Ibrahim Pasha campaigned into the Arabian interior against the final ruler Abdullah bin Saud. After a months-long siege, Diriyah fell in 1818 and was razed, Abdullah was executed in Constantinople, and the First Saudi State came to an end.",
  "electorate of hanover": "The Electorate was created in 1692 when Emperor Leopold I elevated Duke Ernest Augustus of the House of Brunswick-Lüneburg to the rank of prince-elector as a reward for support in the Nine Years' War, a promotion formally ratified by the Imperial Diet in 1708. In 1714 the succession of Elector George Louis to the British throne bound the electorate into a personal union with Great Britain and Ireland that would last until 1837, so that its ruler was simultaneously a German prince and the British sovereign. Because successive electors after George II resided in Britain, Hanover was governed on their behalf by a Privy Council in the city of Hanover coordinating with a German Chancery in London. Though styled Elector of Brunswick-Lüneburg, the rulers were commonly known as Electors of Hanover after their principal residence, and the state remained a mid-sized Protestant power within the Holy Roman Empire. The electorate was extinguished in 1806 upon the dissolution of the Empire, its lands passing through French and Westphalian control before being restored and raised to the Kingdom of Hanover in 1814.",
  "emirate of sindh": "The Emirate of Sindh was founded in 1783 when the Baloch Talpur clan, led by Mir Fateh Ali Khan, overthrew the ruling Kalhora dynasty at the Battle of Halani and Fateh Ali proclaimed himself Rais of Sindh. Fateh Ali governed jointly with his three brothers in an arrangement known as the Chauyari, or \"rule of four,\" and the dynasty split into semi-autonomous branches centred on Hyderabad, Khairpur, and Mirpur Khas. The Talpurs adopted Shia Islam, held nominal suzerainty under the Durrani Afghans and the Khanate of Kalat, and paid tribute that lapsed as Kabul's power waned. Under the Talpur amirs Sindh remained a decentralised, tribal confederation of Baloch chiefs rather than a centralised state, and it repelled an invasion by the deposed Afghan king Shah Shuja in 1832. The emirate was conquered by the British East India Company under Sir Charles Napier, whose victory at the Battle of Miani on 17 February 1843 ended Talpur rule over most of Sindh, though the Khairpur branch survived as a princely state.",
  "funj sultanate": "The Funj Sultanate was founded in 1504 by Amara Dunqas, whose people rose to power in the Nile valley after the collapse of the Christian Nubian kingdom of Alwa, and it soon adopted Islam while retaining African sacral-kingship traditions. Ruled from Sennar by the Funj dynasty in alliance with the Abdallab and a council of elders, it reached its territorial and commercial zenith in the 17th and early 18th centuries under sultans such as Badi II, who conquered Fazughli and its goldfields, and Badi III. Royal authority eroded through the 18th century as merchants and Islamic scholars gained influence and the unpopular centralizing sultan Badi IV was deposed in 1760–1762 by the Hamaj regent Muhammad Abu Likayik. This coup established the Hamaj Regency, under which the actual rulers governed while the Funj sultans were reduced to nominal figureheads, and outlying provinces such as Kordofan and Dongola were lost. The sultanate finally collapsed when Badi VII submitted to the invading Turco-Egyptian army of Ismail Pasha in 1821, ending more than three centuries of Funj rule.",
  "free city of bremen": "Bremen won broad municipal autonomy through Emperor Frederick Barbarossa's Gelnhausen Privilege of 1186 and became a leading member of the Hanseatic League, joining formally in 1358 and thriving on Weser and North Sea trade. Full imperial immediacy was confirmed by Emperor Ferdinand III's Linz Diploma of 1646, establishing it as a Free Imperial City answerable only to the Emperor, a status it defended against Swedish and Hanoverian encroachment over the following decades. It was governed as an aristocratic merchant republic in which a self-perpetuating Senate led by several Bürgermeister held executive power alongside an assembly of the citizenry. Hanover, having acquired the neighbouring Duchy of Bremen-Verden, formally acknowledged the city's free status in 1720, ending a long rivalry over its independence. The city retained this republican constitution until Napoleon's France annexed it in 1811, after which its independence was restored in 1813 and confirmed at the Congress of Vienna in 1815.",
  "free city of hamburg": "Hamburg's career as a free town began with a charter attributed to Emperor Frederick I in 1189, and it grew into a leading member of the Hanseatic League that dominated Baltic and North Sea trade. It was ruled not by a prince but as a republic, governed by a Senate or Rat of co-opted patrician merchant families alongside a citizens' assembly, an oligarchic arrangement fixed by the constitutional recess of 1712. For centuries its imperial immediacy was contested by the kings of Denmark, whose theoretical claims were finally renounced in the 1768 Treaty of Gottorp, leading to Hamburg's recognition as an immediate imperial city around 1770. When the Holy Roman Empire was dissolved in 1806 the city continued as a sovereign state styled the Free and Hanseatic City of Hamburg, but it was soon occupied and then annexed by Napoleonic France, becoming capital of the Bouches-de-l'Elbe department from 1810 to 1814. Restored after Napoleon's fall, it joined the German Confederation in 1815 as a fully sovereign member, preserving its merchant-republican identity into the modern era.",
  "ethiopian empire": "The Ethiopian Empire was founded in 1270 when Yekuno Amlak overthrew the Zagwe dynasty and established the Solomonic dynasty, whose rulers claimed descent from the biblical King Solomon and the Queen of Sheba to legitimize their reign. Under emperors such as Amda Seyon I and Zara Yaqob the medieval realm expanded and consolidated Christian rule across the highlands, before the devastating war with Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi and the subsequent Oromo migrations reshaped the state in the sixteenth century. In the seventeenth century Emperor Fasilides fixed the capital at Gondar, inaugurating a cultural and architectural flowering that lasted until royal authority disintegrated. From 1769 the empire entered the Zemene Mesafint, an era of princes in which the crowned emperor became a ceremonial figurehead while rival regional lords such as the Yejju rases of Begemder governed and warred in his name. Central power was finally restored by Emperor Tewodros II in 1855, and the Solomonic empire endured until the 1974 revolution deposed Haile Selassie and abolished the monarchy.",
  "free city of lübeck": "Emperor Frederick II granted Lübeck the status of a Free Imperial City in 1226, making it an autonomous republic answerable only to the Emperor. Rising to lead the Hanseatic League, it became the \"Queen of the Hanse\" and dominated Baltic commerce as the trading network's foremost member, its Lübeck law adopted by scores of Baltic towns. Power lay with a merchant patriciate that governed through a self-perpetuating Senate presided over by Bürgermeister, a constitution that endured with little change into the nineteenth century. After the Hanseatic League's effective dissolution in 1669 the city's wider influence waned, yet it retained its independence and self-government as a small sovereign city-republic. It survived the mediatization of 1803 and the empire's collapse in 1806 before Napoleon annexed it to France in 1811, after which it was restored in 1813 and confirmed as a sovereign state by the Congress of Vienna in 1815.",
  "grand duchy of tuscany": "The Habsburg-Lorraine Grand Duchy of Tuscany was created in 1737 when Francis Stephen of Lorraine succeeded the last Medici grand duke, transferring the state from the extinct Medici line to the House of Lorraine. Its most celebrated ruler, Grand Duke Leopold (Pietro Leopoldo, r. 1765–1790), made Tuscany a byword for Enlightened absolutism, overhauling taxation and abolishing capital punishment in 1786 before leaving to become Holy Roman Emperor. His son Ferdinand III succeeded in 1790 and continued a cautiously reformist, largely peaceful course, declaring Tuscan neutrality in the Revolutionary Wars in 1795. That neutrality collapsed when French armies invaded in 1799, expelling Ferdinand and provoking the royalist \"Viva Maria\" uprising centred on Arezzo. The Habsburg-Lorraine grand duchy was extinguished by the Treaty of Aranjuez in 1801, which handed Tuscany to the Bourbon-Parma as the Kingdom of Etruria, though the dynasty would be restored to a revived grand duchy in 1814.",
  "electorate of saxony": "The Electorate of Saxony took its enduring form in 1547 when, after the Schmalkaldic War, the Albertine duke Maurice supplanted the Ernestine line and was invested with the Saxon electoral dignity, shifting the seat of power to Dresden. As one of the leading princes of the Holy Roman Empire and a prime mover of the Reformation, the electorate ranked among the foremost German states, second in weight only to Habsburg Austria. Its rulers of the House of Wettin culminated in Augustus the Strong and his son, who held the Polish crown in personal union through much of the eighteenth century, entangling Saxony in the wars of the age. The dynasty's conversion to Catholicism in 1697 to secure that throne left a Catholic sovereign governing an overwhelmingly Lutheran land, a defining tension of the state. The electorate was devastated by the Seven Years' War, pursued cautious neutrality thereafter, and finally ended in December 1806 when Napoleon elevated its last elector to King Frederick Augustus I of Saxony.",
  "great lakes kingdoms": "The interlacustrine region was home to several independent Bantu monarchies whose ruling dynasties traced their legitimacy to the earlier Empire of Kitara, from which Bunyoro-Kitara emerged as the senior power under the Babiito dynasty founded by Rukidi-Mpuga in the late sixteenth century. Buganda, ruled by its Kabaka, expanded steadily at Bunyoro's expense from the seventeenth century onward, seizing counties such as Bulemeezi and Kyaggwe and building a centralized state administered through appointed chiefs headed by the Katikkiro, eventually eclipsing Bunyoro as the region's dominant kingdom. To the south, the Nyiginya dynasty consolidated the Kingdom of Rwanda under its Mwami, while the Ganwa aristocracy governed the Kingdom of Burundi and the Bahinda dynasty ruled the cattle-keeping kingdom of Nkore. These states shared broadly similar institutions of sacred kingship, clientage, and cattle-based hierarchy, yet remained politically separate and frequently warred, raided, and negotiated with one another. Their independence endured until the late nineteenth century, when British and German colonial expansion absorbed them into the Uganda Protectorate and German East Africa.",
  "habsburg monarchy": "The Habsburg Monarchy took shape in 1526 when Ferdinand I united the Austrian hereditary lands with the crowns of Bohemia and Hungary, creating a composite state held together only by shared dynastic rule rather than a single constitution. For centuries its rulers also monopolized the elective title of Holy Roman Emperor, so the monarchy blended dynastic hereditary lands with leadership of the wider German realm. Under Maria Theresa and Joseph II in the eighteenth century the dynasty pursued centralizing and enlightened reforms that strengthened the bureaucracy and army while provoking resistance in Hungary and the Austrian Netherlands. The dynastic line continued through the House of Habsburg-Lorraine after 1740, and the monarchy became a leading opponent of Revolutionary France in the 1790s. This iteration ended in 1804 when Francis II proclaimed the hereditary Austrian Empire, formally consolidating the separate realms into a single imperial state.",
  "helvetic republic": "The Helvetic Republic was proclaimed \"One and Indivisible\" on 12 April 1798 after French troops invaded and dissolved the Old Swiss Confederacy, replacing cantonal sovereignty with a centralized unitary state modeled on the French constitution of 1795 and largely drafted by the Basel magistrate Peter Ochs. Executive power rested with a five-member Directory over a bicameral legislature, but the regime was a French client dependent on Paris for its survival and never commanded broad Swiss loyalty. Its brief life was consumed by factional strife between centralists and federalists, producing more than six constitutions and a cascade of coups d'état, including the deposition of Peter Ochs in 1799 and the ousting of Frédéric-César de La Harpe on 7 January 1800. Armed uprisings in the Catholic cantons, mounting debt, and the 1802 Stecklikrieg civil war exposed the state's chronic instability and its inability to govern without French bayonets. Napoleon Bonaparte ended the experiment with the Act of Mediation of 19 February 1803, restoring a confederal structure with substantial cantonal autonomy.",
  "hyderabad state": "Hyderabad State arose in 1724 when Asaf Jah I (Nizam-ul-Mulk), a Mughal viceroy of the Deccan, asserted de facto independence and founded the Asaf Jahi dynasty. His successors, most notably Nizam Ali Khan (Asaf Jah II), consolidated the state amid the rivalries of the Marathas, Mysore, and rival European powers, permanently establishing the seat of government at Hyderabad city. Pressed between these powers, the Nizam allied with the British East India Company, becoming in 1798 the first Indian ruler to accept a subsidiary alliance, which surrendered his foreign policy and defence to the Company in exchange for protection. Thereafter Hyderabad endured as the largest and most senior of the princely states within the British paramountcy, ruled by successive Nizams under a British Resident. The dynasty ended in 1948 when the independent Indian state annexed Hyderabad through the military action known as Operation Polo.",
  "hohenzollern principalities": "The two Swabian Hohenzollern principalities descend from the County of Hohenzollern, which was partitioned in 1576 among the sons of Count Karl I into the lines of Hechingen, Sigmaringen, and the soon-extinct Haigerloch. Both surviving lines, which remained Roman Catholic and formed the senior branch of the dynasty that would later rule Prussia and Germany, were elevated from counts to Imperial Princes in 1623. As immediate fiefs of the Holy Roman Empire they governed small, largely independent territories from their seats at Hechingen and Sigmaringen, sharing dynastic origins but ruling as distinct sovereign states. After the Empire's dissolution they joined the Confederation of the Rhine in 1806 and then the German Confederation in 1815, retaining their sovereignty into the 19th century. Following the Revolutions of 1848 both princes abdicated, and in 1849–1850 the territories were ceded to the Kingdom of Prussia, which combined them into the Province of Hohenzollern.",
  "hausa kingdoms": "By tradition the Hausa states traced their origin to the Bayajidda legend, in which a wandering hero married the queen of Daura and fathered the founders of the seven \"true\" states known as the Hausa Bakwai—Daura, Kano, Katsina, Zazzau, Gobir, Rano, and Biram. They never formed a single kingdom but functioned as a loose set of rival city-states, each ruled by its own sarki and lacking any central authority or shared overlord. From the fourteenth century onward Islam spread among their courts through Wangara and other merchants, and reformers such as Muhammad Rumfa of Kano and Muhammad al-Korau of Katsina strengthened Islamic institutions while older ritual practices persisted alongside them. Their history was one of shifting hegemonies and constant warfare, with Kano and Katsina dominating trade in earlier centuries and militarized Gobir rising to prominence in the eighteenth. The states' era of independence ended when Usman dan Fodio launched his jihad in 1804, defeating their rulers and incorporating them one by one as emirates of the Sokoto Caliphate by around 1808.",
  "asante empire": "The Asante Empire was forged around 1701 when Osei Tutu I, aided by the priest Okomfo Anokye, united the Akan states of the Kumasi region and, according to tradition, bound them together under the sacred Golden Stool after defeating the rival Denkyira at the Battle of Feyiase. Osei Tutu built a centralised confederacy with Kumasi as its capital, and his successor Opoku Ware I greatly extended its reach across the forest zone in the early eighteenth century. The empire developed a sophisticated bureaucracy, standing army, and roads radiating from Kumasi, and it grew wealthy on gold and on the Atlantic trade in enslaved captives exchanged with European traders on the coast. Ruled by a line of Asantehenes from the Oyoko clan, it dominated much of what is now Ghana and repeatedly clashed with coastal Fante states and later with Britain. After a long series of Anglo-Asante wars through the nineteenth century, the empire was defeated and formally annexed by Britain in 1901, ending its sovereign existence.",
  "first french republic": "The First French Republic was proclaimed on 22 September 1792 after the monarchy was abolished, and it executed King Louis XVI in January 1793. Its early years passed through the radical Jacobin Convention and the Reign of Terror under the Committee of Public Safety, followed by the Thermidorian Reaction and the more conservative but unstable Directory from 1795. On 9–10 November 1799 General Napoleon Bonaparte overthrew the Directory in the coup of 18 Brumaire, establishing the Consulate under the Constitution of the Year VIII with himself as First Consul wielding effective sole power. During the Consulate he centralized the state, promulgated the Napoleonic Civil Code, signed the Concordat of 1801 with the Papacy, and had himself made Consul for Life in 1802. The Republic endured in name until Napoleon was proclaimed Emperor of the French on 18 May 1804, transforming it into the First French Empire.",
  "kingdom of mysore": "The Wodeyar dynasty had ruled Mysore since around 1399, but real power was seized in 1761 by the general Hyder Ali, whose son Tipu Sultan turned the kingdom into a formidable rival of the British East India Company. After Tipu was killed at the fall of Seringapatam in the Fourth Anglo-Mysore War of 1799, the victorious British partitioned the state and restored the Wodeyar line, crowning the five-year-old Krishnaraja Wodeyar III as maharaja under a subsidiary alliance. This restored kingdom was administered for its first decade by the capable Dewan Purnaiah as regent, with a British Resident overseeing external affairs, making Mysore a princely state within British paramountcy. Krishnaraja Wodeyar III took personal charge in 1810 but was later stripped of governing power in 1831 for alleged misrule, after which the British administered the state directly until it was restored to his adopted successor in 1881. The Wodeyars ruled as maharajas until the state acceded to independent India in 1947, ending the dynasty's long reign as a sovereign house.",
  "principality of waldeck": "The Principality of Waldeck and Pyrmont was created on 6 January 1712 when Emperor Charles VI elevated the ancient County of Waldeck, ruled by the House of Waldeck, to princely rank under Friedrich Anton Ulrich. Its princes governed a modest immediate territory from their baroque residence at Arolsen, punctuating a chronic shortage of revenue by hiring out soldiers as mercenaries, most famously the Waldeck regiments sent to serve Britain in the American Revolutionary War. Perpetually indebted, the dynasty briefly split off the small exclave of Pyrmont to a cadet line in 1805 before the two were formally reunited in 1812. The principality survived the Napoleonic upheavals as a member of the Confederation of the Rhine and afterward the German Confederation, though its finances forced it in 1867 to sign an accession treaty placing its administration under Prussia while keeping nominal sovereignty. It endured as one of the German Empire's smallest states until the last prince, Friedrich, abdicated in November 1918, after which it became a free state and was finally absorbed into Prussia in 1929.",
  "tây sơn dynasty": "The Tây Sơn dynasty arose from a peasant rebellion led by three brothers from Tây Sơn village in Bình Định, with the eldest, Nguyễn Nhạc, proclaiming himself emperor in 1778 after toppling the Nguyễn lords and challenging the Trịnh lords and the Lê emperors. Its most capable figure, Nguyễn Huệ, took the throne as Emperor Quang Trung in 1788 and crushed a Qing Chinese invasion at the Battle of Ngọc Hồi-Đống Đa in early 1789, reunifying much of Vietnam under Tây Sơn authority. Quang Trung's sudden death in 1792 left the throne to his young son Nguyễn Quang Toản, who reigned as Emperor Cảnh Thịnh while real power fell to regents whose purges and infighting badly weakened the regime. This internal decay allowed the surviving Nguyễn claimant, Nguyễn Ánh, to rebuild his forces in the south and gradually reconquer Tây Sơn territory. The dynasty was destroyed in 1802 when Nguyễn Ánh captured and executed Cảnh Thịnh, founding the Nguyễn dynasty and ending Tây Sơn rule after roughly a quarter-century.",
  "viceroyalty of new spain": "The Viceroyalty of New Spain was the first of Spain's American viceroyalties, established by royal decree in 1535 with Antonio de Mendoza as its inaugural viceroy and Mexico City, built atop the conquered Aztec capital of Tenochtitlan, as its seat of government. Ruled by a viceroy who served as the king's direct representative and was advised by the Audiencia, it grew into the administrative heart of Spain's empire in North America, the Caribbean, Central America, and across the Pacific to the Philippines. Its wealth rested on silver mining in centers such as Zacatecas and Guanajuato, whose bullion financed the Spanish crown and flowed to Asia via the Manila galleon trade. The Bourbon Reforms of the eighteenth century reorganized its governance into intendancies, tightened royal control, and reshaped its economy and defenses. The viceroyalty was ultimately dissolved in 1821 when the Mexican War of Independence ended Spanish rule and gave rise to an independent Mexico.",
  "kingdom of naples and sicily": "Bourbon rule over the southern Italian mainland and Sicily began in 1735 when Charles of Bourbon, a son of Philip V of Spain, conquered both territories and was installed as king, founding a cadet dynasty that governed them as an absolute monarchy. When Charles inherited the Spanish throne in 1759, he left his southern realms to his young son Ferdinand, who reigned as Ferdinand IV of Naples and Ferdinand III of Sicily over two crowns kept legally distinct despite their shared sovereign. Opposition to Revolutionary France led Ferdinand to invade Rome in 1798, but a French counterthrust drove him from Naples to Palermo and enabled the proclamation of the short-lived Parthenopean Republic in January 1799. That republic collapsed within months under Cardinal Ruffo's Sanfedist counter-revolution backed by British sea power, and the Bourbon throne was restored amid harsh reprisals against the republicans. After further Napoleonic upheavals, Ferdinand ultimately merged his two kingdoms into the single Kingdom of the Two Sicilies in 1816, ending their separate existence.",
  "sultanate of muscat and oman": "The Al Bu Said dynasty rose to power in Oman under Ahmad bin Said, elected Imam in 1744 after expelling the Persians, and his descendants gradually shifted the seat of power from the interior toward the coastal port of Muscat. Sultan bin Ahmad seized control at Muscat in 1792 following the death of his nephew Hamad bin Said, arranging a power-sharing settlement at Barka that split temporal authority on the coast from the Ibadi Imamate held by his brother Said at Rustaq. His reign focused on securing Oman's ports, navy, and Indian Ocean commerce, building a maritime domain distinct from the landward Imamate and extending Omani influence to Zanzibar and the East African coast as well as the enclave of Gwadar on the Makran coast. He deepened ties with the British East India Company through treaties in 1798 and 1800 aimed against French and Dutch commercial rivalry, while facing pressure from expanding Wahhabi forces to the north. Sultan bin Ahmad died in 1804 on an expedition toward Basra, leaving his young sons Salim and Said as heirs under a regent, after which Said bin Sultan eventually consolidated power and presided over the dynasty's imperial high point.",
  "oyo empire": "Founded by legend by Oranyan, the last prince of Ile-Ife, the Oyo Empire grew from a Yoruba kingdom into West Africa's dominant power, ruled by a sacred monarch titled the Alaafin. Royal authority was constitutionally checked by the Oyo Mesi, a council of seven notables led by the Bashorun, and by the Ogboni society, giving Oyo an unusually balanced political structure. From the late sixteenth century its cavalry armies subjugated hundreds of tributary states, extending Oyo's reach over neighbouring Yoruba lands and the kingdom of Dahomey. Internal crisis set in when the powerful Bashorun Gaha dominated the throne until Alaafin Abiodun executed him in 1774, after which Abiodun favoured Atlantic commerce over the army and left the empire militarily weakened. Successive revolts, the secession of Ilorin under the war-chief Afonja, and Fulani incursions unravelled the empire, culminating in the abandonment of Oyo-Ile around 1835.",
  "kaarta": "Kaarta was a Bambara kingdom ruled by the Massassi (Coulibaly) clan, first founded around 1650 near Sounsan and re-established in 1754 by Sey Bamana Coulibaly after a Segou-led invasion had destroyed the earlier state and killed its ruler Foulakoro. Under Faama Sira Bo, who reigned from 1761 to 1781, it re-emerged as a major regional power, fixed a permanent capital at Diangounté, and subjugated neighboring polities such as Diarra and Khasso. Political authority was tightly held by the Massassi lineage, giving Kaarta unusually smooth successions compared with its great rival Segou, though the two Bambara states waged repeated wars for dominance of the western Sudan. Sira Bo's successor Desse Koro was defeated by Mansong Diarra of Segou, and the kingdom's power later revived under Bodian Moriba, who reigned from 1818 to 1832 and made peace with Segou. Kaarta was destroyed as an independent force in 1854 when El Hadj Umar Tall's Tijaniyya jihad seized Nioro and executed the last faama, Mamady Kandian, ending the Massassi dynasty.",
  "kingdom of cambodia": "The Post-Angkor Kingdom of Cambodia emerged after the abandonment of Angkor in the fifteenth century, ruled by a Khmer monarchy that shifted its capitals to Longvek and, from 1618 under Chey Chetha II, to Oudong. From the seventeenth century onward the kingdom was reduced to a contested buffer, its throne repeatedly disputed by rival princes who sought backing from the more powerful Siam and Vietnam. Ang Eng was installed as king with Siamese support and crowned at Bangkok, ceding Battambang and Siem Reap to Siam, and after his death in 1796 a regency governed until his son Ang Chan II was crowned in 1806. Ang Chan II leaned toward Vietnam to secure his throne against Siamese-backed brothers, triggering the invasions and rebellions of 1811–1813 that shifted Cambodia from Siamese into Vietnamese dominance. The kingdom endured decades of foreign intervention and near-annexation before Ang Duong and his successor Norodom turned to France, culminating in the French protectorate established in 1863.",
  "sultanate of aussa": "The Sultanate of Aussa was founded in 1734 when Data Kadafo, head of the Mudaito clan of the Afar, seized power and established the Mudaito dynasty, succeeding the earlier Imamate of Aussa. It emerged as the leading Afar monarchy, and other Afar chiefs nominally acknowledged the primacy of its sultan. Its rulers governed a Muslim polity in which the sovereign consolidated authority through control of trade routes, agriculture along the Awash, and a martial defense of the capital against outside raiders. Through the nineteenth century the sultanate preserved its independence from the Khedivate of Egypt and remained autonomous within the expanding Ethiopian Empire. It endured until the Italian invasion of 1936, when it was absorbed into Italian East Africa during the Second Italo-Ethiopian War.",
  "kingdom of great britain": "The Kingdom of Great Britain was created on 1 May 1707 when the Treaty of Union merged the Kingdom of England and the Kingdom of Scotland into a single state governed by one Parliament at Westminster. It was ruled successively by the last Stuart monarch Anne and then the Hanoverian kings George I, George II, and George III, with real executive power resting increasingly on ministers commanding a Commons majority. Its politics were shaped by Whig ascendancy, recurring wars with France and Spain, the suppression of the Jacobite risings of 1715 and 1745, and the loss of the thirteen American colonies confirmed in 1783. Under George III and William Pitt the Younger it consolidated a powerful fiscal-military state, an expanding overseas empire, and a parliamentary system dominated by a landed and mercantile elite. The kingdom ceased to exist as a separate entity when the Acts of Union 1800 joined it with the Kingdom of Ireland to form the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland on 1 January 1801.",
  "maratha confederacy": "Founded when Shivaji Bhonsle was crowned Chhatrapati in 1674, the Maratha polity grew from a Deccan resistance state into the dominant power of eighteenth-century India. After Aurangzeb's death effective authority passed from the Chhatrapati at Satara to the hereditary Peshwas of the Bhat family, under whom Baji Rao I and Madhavrao I carried Maratha arms across northern and central India. The catastrophic defeat at the Third Battle of Panipat in 1761 checked expansion, and over the following decades the leading houses of Scindia, Holkar, Bhonsle, and Gaekwad hardened into semi-autonomous princes bound loosely to the Peshwa in a confederacy rather than a centralized empire. The death of the veteran minister Nana Fadnavis in 1800 removed the last figure able to hold the chiefs together, leaving them to pursue rival ambitions and drift toward open conflict. Defeated by Holkar and driven to seek British protection through the Treaty of Bassein in 1802, the confederacy was dismantled through the Second and Third Anglo-Maratha Wars, ending with its annexation by the East India Company in 1818.",
  "kingdom of bhutan": "Bhutan was unified in 1616 by the exiled Tibetan lama Ngawang Namgyal, the Zhabdrung, who repelled repeated Tibetan invasions and welded rival valleys and monastic factions into a single state. He established a dual system of government, the Chösi, dividing authority between a spiritual head embodied in the Zhabdrung line and a temporal ruler, the Druk Desi or Deb Raja, with the Je Khenpo leading the monastic order. After the Zhabdrung's death was concealed for decades and successor incarnations proved weak, real power drained away into recurring civil wars and the rivalry of regional governors, the penlops of Paro and Trongsa chief among them. The Druk Desi, nominally elected for a three-year term, was in practice the strongest contending governor, and central authority over the penlops steadily eroded through the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. This fractious dual order endured until 1907, when the penlop of Trongsa, Ugyen Wangchuck, abolished it and founded the hereditary Wangchuck monarchy.",
  "kanara": "The Canara district was created by the British East India Company in 1799, carved from the coastal territory seized when Tipu Sultan of Mysore was defeated and killed at the fall of Seringapatam on 4 May 1799. This tract had been absorbed into Mysore by Hyder Ali in the 1760s and held by Tipu after him, having earlier been governed by the Keladi Nayakas under the shadow of the fallen Vijayanagara Empire. The Company organised the annexed coast as a single collectorate within the Madras Presidency and appointed Captain Thomas Munro as its first Collector, tasking him with establishing revenue administration and British authority. Munro's tenure laid groundwork for the ryotwari land-revenue system of direct settlement between the state and individual cultivators that later spread across the Madras Presidency. The unified district endured until 1859, when it was bifurcated into North and South Canara, with North Canara subsequently transferred to the Bombay Presidency.",
  "kong empire": "The Kong Empire was founded around 1710 by Seku Watara, a Dyula merchant-warrior claiming descent from the Malinké Keita lineage, who united rival Dyula war-leaders and overthrew Lasiri Gbambele to seize the trading city of Kong. Under Seku and his brother Famagan the state expanded rapidly through the savanna, seizing towns and trade routes as far as Bobo-Dioulasso and campaigning westward toward Segou. Governed by Muslim Dyula merchants and the Watara \"war houses,\" it functioned less as a centralized kingdom than as an instrumental state built to protect commerce in gold and kola nuts while becoming a renowned center of Islamic scholarship. After Seku's death around 1745 no successor could master the whole Watara clan, and the empire fragmented into a constellation of semi-independent chiefdoms bound by nominal loyalty to Kong. Weakened by internal rivalries and later pressure from the Kenedougou kingdom, it fell to Samory Touré, whose forces sacked and burned Kong in 1897–1898, ending the empire.",
  "oromo states": "The Oromo states were not a single polity but a cluster of communities and emerging kingdoms in the southern Ethiopian highlands, where the Oromo had settled during their great sixteenth-century migrations and long governed themselves through the egalitarian, generation-based Gadaa system. From the later eighteenth century, competition over land, cattle, and the reviving long-distance caravan trade produced ambitious war leaders who converted the office of moti from a temporary Gadaa war chief into a hereditary monarchy, borrowing the concept of sacral kingship in part from the neighbouring kingdom of Kaffa. The earliest of these Gibe kingdoms was Limmu-Ennarea, consolidated around 1800-1802 by Bofo, known as Abba Gomol, followed over the next generation by Gumma under Oncho Jilcha, Gomma, Jimma under the Abba Jifar dynasty, and Gera under Tullu Gunji. These states grew wealthy as entrepôts on the routes carrying gold, coffee, ivory, and enslaved people toward the Red Sea and Gojjam, and Islam spread among their ruling classes and merchants. Their independence ended in the late nineteenth century when Emperor Menelik II's expanding Ethiopian Empire conquered and annexed them, with Limmu-Ennarea absorbed by 1891 and Jimma retaining tributary autonomy until 1932.",
  "sikh confederacy": "The Sikh Confederacy was formally established on 29 March 1748 when the Sarbat Khalsa passed a gurmata reorganizing the scattered Sikh militias into a structured alliance of twelve sovereign misls, each led by its own sardar. It was governed collectively rather than by a single monarch: the biannual Sarbat Khalsa assembly at Amritsar reached binding decisions by gurmata, and the combined armies formed the Dal Khalsa, led successively by Nawab Kapur Singh, Jassa Singh Ahluwalia, and later jathedars. Through the later eighteenth century the misls expelled Mughal and Afghan authority from most of the Punjab, though the individual chiefs frequently warred among themselves for territory and revenue. Beginning in the 1790s Ranjit Singh of the Sukerchakia Misl used marriage alliances, diplomacy, and conquest to subdue his rivals, capturing Lahore in July 1799. This consolidation dissolved the confederal structure, which gave way to Ranjit Singh's centralized Sikh Empire proclaimed in 1801, while the Phulkian states to the southeast kept a separate existence and later became British-allied princely states.",
  "kingdom of imerina": "The Kingdom of Imerina was founded around 1540 by Andriamanelo, who began subjugating the earlier Vazimba communities of the central highlands and established a dynasty that ruled from a succession of fortified hill towns. Under later kings such as Ralambo and Andrianjaka the realm consolidated, adopted the name Imerina, and made Antananarivo a royal seat, but a partition by Andriamasinavalona in the late 17th century plunged the kingdom into roughly seventy-seven years of civil war among rival principalities. Andrianampoinimerina, who seized power around 1787 by deposing his uncle Andrianjafy, reunified the fragmented kingdom by 1795 and became its most celebrated ruler, codifying laws, organizing markets and irrigation, and building a conscript army with the ambition of uniting the whole island. His son Radama I opened the kingdom to British alliance, Christian missionaries, and modernization, extending Merina dominance over much of Madagascar, while the long reign of Ranavalona I later resisted European influence. The kingdom endured as the dominant Malagasy state until France conquered the island and abolished the monarchy in 1897, exiling the last sovereign, Ranavalona III.",
  "margraviate of baden": "The House of Baden, a branch descended from the Swabian Zähringen dynasty, had held the margravial title since the twelfth century, but the territory was long divided, splitting in 1535 into the Catholic Baden-Baden and the Protestant Baden-Durlach lines. This reunified iteration was created in 1771 when Charles Frederick of Baden-Durlach, who had ruled since 1738, inherited Baden-Baden upon the extinction of its ruling line and consolidated the fragmented lands under a single Protestant ruler. Charles Frederick governed as an enlightened reformer, abolishing serfdom in his lands and cultivating close ties with leading thinkers of the age. Through shrewd diplomacy backed by France and by Alexander I of Russia, he positioned the small state to profit from the upheavals of the Revolutionary and Napoleonic era. The Margraviate's existence ended in 1803 when the Imperial Diet's mediatisation settlement elevated Charles Frederick to Prince-Elector, transforming the state into the Electorate of Baden, which in turn became the Grand Duchy of Baden in 1806.",
  "central asian khanates": "These successor states arose from the fragmentation of Timurid and Shaybanid Central Asia, as new Uzbek tribal dynasties seized the settled oasis khanates during the eighteenth century: the non-Chingissid Manghits formalized the Emirate of Bukhara under Shah Murad in 1785, the Qungrats consolidated power in Khiva, and the Ming dynasty built the Khanate of Kokand from the Fergana Valley after breaking away from Bukhara around 1709. Alongside these settled emirates, the nomadic Kazakhs were divided into three hordes—the Great, Middle, and Junior jüz—whose khans had sworn largely symbolic allegiance to the Russian crown from 1731 while remaining effectively self-governing. Rulers such as Kokand's Alim Khan expanded aggressively, seizing Tashkent and Khujand, while Bukhara, Khiva, and Kokand waged chronic wars against one another over oases, caravan routes, and control of the Amu Darya and Syr Darya basins. The states were governed as Islamic monarchies in which emirs and khans ruled through tribal aristocracies, the ulama, and Sharia courts, and their economies rested on caravan trade, agriculture, and a notorious slave market. Encircled by expanding Russian and, in the Caucasus, Persian and Russian power, these polities were progressively conquered or reduced to protectorates across the nineteenth century, with Kokand annexed outright in 1876 and Bukhara and Khiva surviving as Russian vassals until 1920.",
  "swabian circle": "The Swabian Circle was created in 1500 under Emperor Maximilian I as one of the administrative circles into which the Holy Roman Empire was divided, with the full set of ten circles fixed by 1512. It never had a single ruler but was jointly directed by two co-directors, the Prince-Bishop of Constance and the Duke of Württemberg, whose delegates convened the circle diet to coordinate imperial taxation, defense, coinage regulation, and the keeping of the peace. Comprising dozens of small ecclesiastical states, free imperial cities, counties, and lordships, it was among the most fragmented yet best-organized of the circles, maintaining an effective collective government and even fielding its own army from 1694. It repeatedly mobilized troops and levied contributions during the wars against France, and its cohesion made it a notable example of small-state cooperation within the Empire. The circle was shattered by the secularization and mediatization of the Reichsdeputationshauptschluss in 1803, dissolved with the Holy Roman Empire in 1806, and formally abolished in 1808.",
  "kingdom of prussia": "The Kingdom of Prussia was proclaimed in 1701 when the Hohenzollern Elector of Brandenburg, Frederick III, crowned himself King Frederick I, elevating the scattered Brandenburg-Prussian lands into a monarchy. Under Frederick William I and especially Frederick II \"the Great,\" it built a formidable centralized bureaucracy and standing army, seized Silesia from Austria, and shared in the partitions of Poland, becoming one of Europe's great powers. Defeat and dismemberment by Napoleon after Jena-Auerstedt in 1806 spurred sweeping Stein-Hardenberg reforms, after which Prussia helped lead the coalition that overthrew him. Through the nineteenth century it drove German unification under Bismarck, defeating Denmark, Austria, and France, until its king became German Emperor in 1871. The kingdom endured as the dominant state of the German Empire until the monarchy was abolished amid revolution at the close of the First World War in 1918.",
  "northern circars": "The Northern Circars were a string of coastal Telugu districts that the British East India Company wrested from French influence after Lieutenant-Colonel Francis Forde captured Masulipatam in 1759, and which the Company held as a revenue territory rather than a sovereign realm. In 1765 the Mughal emperor Shah Alam II granted the five Circars to the Company, a cession confirmed by the Nizam of Hyderabad in the treaties of 1766 and 1768, under which the Nizam received an annuity in exchange for relinquishing the tract. Guntur, held for life by the Nizam's brother Basalat Jang, was excluded until his death in 1782 and only passed to Company administration in 1788, completing the group. The Company governed the region through Chiefs and Councils seated at towns such as Masulipatam until these were abolished in 1794 and the territory reorganized into collectorate districts. The Nizam's residual claims were finally purchased outright in 1823, and the Circars were later absorbed into the districts of the Madras Presidency, their separate identity fading by the mid-nineteenth century.",
  "sultanate of darfur": "The Sultanate of Darfur was ruled by the Keira dynasty of the Fur people, whose founder Sulayman Solong is traditionally credited with establishing the Muslim state in the seventeenth century after supplanting the earlier Tunjur rulers. Its sultans built a centralized administration over a mosaic of Fur and other communities, using Islam and control of the trans-Saharan trade in slaves, ivory, and other goods to project authority across a decentralized realm. The kingdom reached its apogee under Sultan Abd al-Rahman al-Rashid and his son Muhammad al-Fadl, who reigned into the nineteenth century and consolidated the dynasty's grip on the region and its Arab tribes. The sultanate fell in October 1874 when its forces were defeated and Sultan Ibrahim was killed at the Battle of al-Manawashi, and it was annexed by the slave-trader and warlord al-Zubayr Rahma Mansur. A revived Keira sultanate under Ali Dinar existed from 1898 until 1916, when it was conquered and absorbed by Anglo-Egyptian forces.",
  "zaydi imamate": "The Qasimid Zaydi Imamate was proclaimed in 1597 by Imam al-Mansur al-Qasim, who launched a revolt against Ottoman rule and founded a hereditary line of Zaydi Shia imams drawn from his descendants. His successors al-Mu'ayyad Muhammad and al-Mutawakkil Isma'il drove the Ottomans entirely out of Yemen by the 1630s and expanded the state to its greatest extent, reaching from Asir in the north to Zafar in the east. From the late seventeenth century the imamate steadily contracted as family disputes weakened central authority, tribal and regional rulers such as the Sultanate of Lahej broke away, and the collapse of the Yemeni coffee monopoly sapped its revenues. The rising Wahhabi movement stripped the state of its coastal Tihama possessions in the early nineteenth century, and Egyptian intervention under Muhammad Ali further eroded imamate power, after which the throne changed hands with great frequency and several imams were assassinated. The independent Qasimid polity effectively ended when the Ottomans reincorporated Yemen into their empire around 1849, though Zaydi imams continued to contest authority in the highlands for decades afterward.",
  "nova scotia": "Nova Scotia became firmly British by the Treaty of Utrecht in 1713 and was re-founded as a settler colony in 1749 when Edward Cornwallis established Halifax as its capital in place of Annapolis Royal. In 1758 it convened an elected House of Assembly, the first representative legislature in what would become Canada, giving it a tradition of colonial self-government alongside a Crown-appointed governor and council. The influx of roughly thirty thousand Loyalists after the American Revolution transformed the colony and prompted London to partition it in 1784, carving off New Brunswick and Cape Breton Island as separate colonies. Governed in this period by lieutenant governors such as John Parr and Sir John Wentworth, the colony saw recurring friction between the executive and an increasingly assertive Assembly over patronage and control of spending. It remained a distinct British North American colony, later winning responsible government in 1848, until it entered Canadian Confederation in 1867.",
  "mossi kingdoms": "The Mossi kingdoms arose in the Volta basin from cavalry-borne conquerors whose foundation traditions trace to Princess Yennenga and her son Ouédraogo, with the Ouagadougou dynasty conventionally dated to the ruler Oubri around the late eleventh century and the principal kingdoms consolidating by roughly the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries. They never formed a single centralized empire but functioned as a set of autonomous kingdoms—chiefly Ouagadougou, Yatenga, Tenkodogo, Boussouma, and Fada N'gourma—bound by shared descent, ritual, and military ties, with the Mogho Naba of Ouagadougou recognized as paramount arbiter while the northwestern kingdom of Yatenga rivaled him and acted largely independently. Governed through a hierarchy of territorial chiefs and a court of titled ministers, the Mossi famously resisted incorporation into the great Islamic states of the Sahel, repelling Songhai and Sahelian pressures and retaining their indigenous religious and political order for centuries. From the late eighteenth century their rulers increasingly accommodated Islam—the Mogho Naba Doulougou permitted a mosque and an imam at Ouagadougou—though the kings blended Muslim recognition with traditional authority rather than converting the realm. Weakened by internal rivalries and sporadic warfare among the kingdoms through the nineteenth century, the Mossi states fell to French conquest in 1896-1897, when Ouagadougou was occupied and its ruler Wobgho deposed, ending their independence.",
  "kingdom of cochin": "The Kingdom of Cochin arose from the Perumpadappu Swaroopam ruling house in the early twelfth century after the breakup of the later Chera realm, governed by a matrilineal Hindu dynasty. From the sixteenth century it repeatedly sought European protection to counter the rival Zamorin of Calicut, aligning first with the Portuguese, then coming under Dutch East India Company suzerainty from 1663. Overrun by Mysore under Hyder Ali and Tipu Sultan in the later eighteenth century, the raja was forced into tributary submission before turning to the British. The forceful reformer Rama Varma IX, remembered as Sakthan Thampuran, ruled from 1790 to 1805, centralizing authority, curbing feudal chiefs such as the Paliath Achan, and signing the 1791 Powney Treaty that made Cochin a subsidiary state of the British East India Company. It survived thereafter as a princely state under British paramountcy until it merged with Travancore in 1949.",
  "kingdom of kongo": "The Kingdom of Kongo emerged around 1390 from the union of KiKongo-speaking peoples under the founding king Lukeni lua Nimi, and its rulers bore the title manikongo. From the early sixteenth century its kings converted to Catholicism and cultivated close diplomatic ties with Portugal, while the ntotila governed a centralized realm of provinces from the capital. Defeat by the Portuguese at the Battle of Mbwila in 1665 shattered central authority and unleashed a decades-long civil war between the rival houses of Kinlaza and Kimpanzu. Pedro IV reunified the kingdom by 1709 through a rotational succession pact meant to alternate the throne between the two houses, but the monarchy never recovered its former power and the provinces grew increasingly autonomous. The much-weakened kingdom persisted through the nineteenth century until it became a Portuguese vassal in 1857, and Portugal formally abolished its monarchy in 1914.",
  "kingdom of dahomey": "The Kingdom of Dahomey emerged around 1600 as an offshoot of the royal dynasty of Allada, with Houegbadja traditionally regarded as its foundational king for building the royal palaces at Abomey and beginning the conquest of neighboring peoples. Under King Agaja it expanded dramatically in the early eighteenth century, conquering Allada and Whydah to gain direct access to the Atlantic coast, though this expansion drew it into subordination to the powerful Oyo Empire, to which it paid tribute from the 1730s. Dahomey developed a highly centralized state with a professional standing army, an organized bureaucracy and taxation, and a famous corps of female soldiers, financing itself largely through warfare and the export of war captives as slaves. King Ghezo, who seized the throne in 1818, later broke free of Oyo tributary status and gradually shifted the economy toward palm oil as the Atlantic slave trade declined. After fierce resistance the kingdom was defeated by France in the Franco-Dahomean Wars of the 1890s, reduced to a protectorate in 1894, and fully annexed as a French colony by 1904.",
  "principality of schaumburg-lippe": "The County of Schaumburg-Lippe was created in 1647 when the larger County of Schaumburg was partitioned among Hesse-Kassel, Brunswick-Lüneburg, and the House of Lippe following the extinction of the Holstein-Schaumburg male line, with the Lippe branch retaining Bückeburg. Ruled by a cadet line of the House of Lippe, it survived as one of the smallest immediate territories of the Holy Roman Empire, its independence repeatedly secured through appeals to imperial law against powerful neighbours such as Hesse-Kassel and Hanover. Its most celebrated ruler, Count Wilhelm, modernized the state's army and fortifications in the mid-18th century, giving the tiny county an outsized military reputation. In 1807 the county was raised to the Principality of Schaumburg-Lippe as it joined Napoleon's Confederation of the Rhine, and it later entered the German Confederation, the North German Confederation, and the German Empire. The monarchy endured until the German Revolution of 1918, when it became the Free State of Schaumburg-Lippe, which was ultimately absorbed into Lower Saxony in 1946.",
  "sultanate of aïr": "The Sultanate of Aïr was founded in 1405 by Tuareg confederacies who invited an outside arbiter, Yunus, as their first sultan to mediate inter-tribal disputes, establishing a monarchy whose ruler was styled amenukal or sultan. The state was conquered by the Songhai Empire in the early sixteenth century and later fell under the authority of Kebbi, but it recovered its independence after the collapse of Songhai power around 1591. Its sultans held limited authority over the drum-groups of the Tuareg confederation, serving as judges and war-leaders while internal disputes remained frequent. During the eighteenth century, the southward migration of northern Tuareg confederacies into Aïr provoked recurring unrest and contributed to a long political and economic decline. The sultanate came under French suzerainty in 1906, and after the failed Kaocen revolt of 1916–1917 its sultan was reduced to a French-appointed mediator, though the office endures today within Niger.",
  "malay sultanates": "The Malay sultanates were a family of independent Muslim monarchies that traced their prestige to the Malacca Sultanate, founded around 1400 and shattered by the Portuguese conquest of 1511. From the fallen dynasty sprang Johor and Perak, while older states such as Kedah and the Borneo sultanate of Brunei ran their own royal lines, each ruled by a sultan claiming descent or legitimacy within this shared Malay-Muslim political order. Over the eighteenth century the balance of power shifted repeatedly: Bugis migrants seized the office of Yang di-Pertuan Muda and dominated Johor-Riau, Siam pressed the northern states of Kedah and Kelantan into tributary vassalage, and Brunei's once-vast Bornean empire steadily decayed through succession strife and lost trade. The sultanates were never politically unified but formed a common cultural sphere bound by Islam, the Malay language, and intermarrying dynasties. From 1786 onward British and Dutch encroachment progressively reduced them to protected states, though the sultanate institution itself survived and endures in Malaysia and Brunei today.",
  "nguyễn domain": "This southern Vietnamese domain grew from the cause of Nguyễn Phúc Ánh, a surviving prince of the Nguyễn lords whose family had been overthrown by the Tây Sơn rebellion in the 1770s. After years as a fugitive he recaptured Saigon in 1788 and made Gia Định his permanent base, proclaiming himself Nguyễn Vương and rallying southern landowners, Chinese merchants, and Catholic and French supporters including Bishop Pigneau de Behaine. Through the 1790s he built a disciplined army and modern navy, funded by the productive Mekong delta, and waged a protracted civil war against the Tây Sơn dynasty. From 1799 he pressed northward, taking Quy Nhơn, Phú Xuân, and eventually the Tây Sơn heartland. In 1802 he captured Huế and Hanoi, reunified the country, and proclaimed himself Emperor Gia Long, transforming this wartime domain into the imperial Nguyễn dynasty.",
  "kingdom of sardinia": "The Kingdom of Sardinia in its Savoyard form was created by the Treaty of The Hague in 1720, when the House of Savoy under Victor Amadeus II was compelled to exchange Sicily for the island of Sardinia and its royal title. The Savoyard rulers governed a composite monarchy that joined the island to their far more populous and wealthy mainland domains of Savoy, Piedmont, Aosta, and Nice, with the ruling class, government, and cultural life centred on the peninsula. Through the eighteenth century the dynasty pursued administrative centralization and cautious reform while maintaining Turin as the heart of the state. Drawn into the Revolutionary Wars against France, the kingdom was defeated by Napoleon in 1796 and saw its mainland occupied, its king exiled to the island, and Piedmont ultimately annexed to France. Restored after Napoleon's fall, the House of Savoy later transformed this kingdom into the engine of Italian unification, its monarch becoming King of Italy in 1861 and thereby ending the Sardinian title.",
  "principality of lippe": "The state traced its origins to the medieval Lordship of Lippe, first attested in 1123 under Bernhard I, which was elevated to an Imperial County in 1528 under Simon V and reunited under the Detmold line, whose princes ruled from 1720. In 1789 the County of Lippe-Detmold was raised to a Principality of the Holy Roman Empire, and Leopold I became its first prince. Leopold I was declared mentally incapacitated in 1790 and placed under imperial guardianship, so government was exercised on his behalf during much of his reign until his death in 1802. The house was ruled through the nineteenth century by a succession of princes, mostly named Leopold, and remained a small but sovereign member of the German Confederation and later the German Empire. The principality endured until 12 November 1918, when Prince Leopold IV abdicated in the German Revolution and the state became the Free State of Lippe.",
  "kingdom of portugal": "The Kingdom of Portugal traced its origin to 1139 when Afonso Henriques was proclaimed king, but the polity of this era dated from 1640, when the Duke of Braganza was acclaimed João IV and the Portuguese Restoration War ended sixty years of dynastic union with Spain. Under the House of Braganza the crown consolidated a global maritime empire while at home an absolutist monarchy governed through a small court nobility. The mid-eighteenth-century ministry of the Marquis of Pombal centralized royal authority, expelled the Jesuits, and rebuilt the capital after the 1755 earthquake, leaving a lasting imprint on the state. By the turn of the nineteenth century the monarchy was bound to a long-standing alliance with Britain and increasingly strained by the wars of Revolutionary and Napoleonic Europe. The dynasty survived a flight to Brazil in 1807 and later constitutional upheavals, and the Braganza monarchy endured until it was overthrown by the republican revolution of 1910.",
  "portuguese india": "The Estado da Índia was established in 1505 as the administrative heart of Portugal's eastern empire, with Goa captured in 1510 becoming its principal Asian base and seat of the viceroy. At its height it governed Portuguese possessions across the Indian Ocean, but from the mid-seventeenth century Dutch and later Maratha and British pressure stripped away most of its holdings, leaving by the eighteenth century only the enclaves of Goa, Daman and Diu. Governance ran through a viceroy or governor appointed from Lisbon, typically serving fixed terms and administering the territory as a Crown colony. During the Napoleonic Wars a British garrison occupied Goa from 1799, formally as a protectorate under the Anglo-Portuguese alliance, while Portuguese civil institutions continued to function under the governor. The Estado endured as a Portuguese colony until 1961, when Indian armed forces annexed the remaining territories.",
  "wadai empire": "The Sultanate of Wadai was founded around 1635 when Abd al-Karim overthrew the ruling Tunjur and established the Muslim Kolak dynasty, building his seat at Wara. Its sultans ruled a Maba-led state that made Islam the official religion while much of the population retained traditional beliefs, and it long stood in rivalry with the neighbouring sultanates of Darfur to the east and Bagirmi to the west. Under Sultan Muhammad Sabun, who seized power in 1804, Wadai expanded aggressively, opened a direct trans-Saharan trade route northward, minted its own coinage, and in 1805 crushed Bagirmi and reduced it to a tributary. The state reached its height in the mid-nineteenth century on the profits of the caravan and slave trade before its capital shifted to Abéché around 1850. It was conquered by France, which took Abéché in 1909 and formally ended the sultanate's independence in 1912.",
  "rupert's land": "Rupert's Land was created in 1670 when King Charles II granted a royal charter to the Hudson's Bay Company, naming his cousin Prince Rupert of the Rhine as the enterprise's first governor and vesting the company as the \"true and absolute Lords and Proprietors\" of the vast territory. Rather than a settled polity, it was administered as a commercial fur-trading monopoly run from scattered company forts, with a London-based governor and committee directing operations and courts convened only on an ad hoc basis by local officers. Through the eighteenth century the company faced pressure from French traders and, from the 1780s, fierce commercial rivalry with the Montreal-based North West Company, which pushed inland trade to violent extremes. That conflict, including the 1816 Battle of Seven Oaks, prompted British intervention and the 1821 merger of the two firms, after which the Crown extended the reorganized company's monopoly across the continent. In 1869–1870 the Hudson's Bay Company surrendered its charter to the British Crown for £300,000, and Rupert's Land was transferred to the new Dominion of Canada in 1870.",
  "papal states": "The Papal States originated in 756 when Pepin the Short granted conquered Lombard territory to Pope Stephen II, creating a domain over which the Bishop of Rome ruled as a temporal sovereign. For over a millennium the reigning pope governed the state as an elective absolute monarch, administering its provinces through cardinal legates and papal officials in a distinctively theocratic regime. Its temporal power was shattered by the French Revolution: Pius VI was deposed when General Berthier proclaimed a Roman Republic in 1798, and the pope died a French captive at Valence in 1799. His successor Pius VII, elected in Venice in March 1800, recovered Rome and restored papal government, but Napoleon annexed the entire state to the French Empire in 1809 and held Pius VII prisoner. The Congress of Vienna reinstated the Papal States in 1814-1815, and they endured until their absorption into a unified Italy, with Rome falling in 1870.",
  "qajar persia": "The Qajar dynasty was founded by Agha Mohammad Khan, a chieftain of the Turkic Qajar tribe, who defeated the rival Zand and Afsharid claimants and unified Iran after the death of Karim Khan Zand, being crowned shah in 1796 and establishing Tehran as his capital. After his assassination in 1797 he was succeeded by his nephew Fath-Ali Shah, whose long reign consolidated the dynasty's central authority and revived Persianate court culture and monarchical splendor. The Qajars ruled a decentralized realm through provincial governors, often royal princes, and drew their legitimacy from Shia Islam and the ideal of the \"Guarded Domains\" of Iran. During the nineteenth century the dynasty suffered heavy territorial losses to the Russian Empire in the Caucasus and grew increasingly enmeshed in Anglo-Russian rivalry, ceding economic concessions and sovereignty. Weakened by the Constitutional Revolution of 1905–1911 and foreign intervention, the dynasty was finally deposed in 1925 when Reza Khan founded the Pahlavi dynasty.",
  "republic of lucca": "The Republic of Lucca emerged as a self-governing commune after the Tuscan city bought its feudal liberties around 1160 and thereafter defended its independence beneath the motto \"Libertas.\" Under Castruccio Castracani in the early fourteenth century it briefly became an expansionist military power, but for most of its history it survived as a compact city-state hemmed in by Florence and later by the Medici and Habsburg-Lorraine grand dukes of Tuscany. Beginning as a broad communal government, its constitution narrowed over the centuries until a reform of 1628 entrenched a closed patrician oligarchy, in which a Council and rotating magistracies led by the Gonfaloniere governed on behalf of a small hereditary nobility. Its longevity owed much to cautious neutrality, careful diplomacy, and a diversified silk-based mercantile economy that let it outlast nearly every other Italian republic. The state was finally extinguished in 1805 when Napoleon converted it into the Principality of Lucca and Piombino under his sister Elisa Bonaparte Baciocchi.",
  "kingdom of spain": "The Kingdom of Spain in this iteration was ruled by the House of Bourbon, which acceded in 1700 with Philip V and consolidated a unified monarchy through the eighteenth-century Nueva Planta reforms that abolished the separate Aragonese constitutions. Under the Enlightened absolutism of Charles III the crown pursued administrative centralization, colonial reform, and cautious modernization while retaining a vast overseas empire. His successor Charles IV, reigning from 1788, proved a weak monarch who left governance to favourites and ministers amid the shock of the French Revolution. Spanish policy lurched from war against revolutionary France to a subordinate alliance with it, culminating in dependence on Napoleon and the loss of naval power. This iteration was fatally destabilized by the 1808 Bayonne abdications and the Peninsular War, though the Bourbon monarchy was restored in 1814 and, after interruptions, continues to head the Spanish state today.",
  "luba empire": "Luba oral tradition traces the empire's sacred kingship to the mythic hunter Kalala Ilunga, who is said to have overthrown the despot Nkongolo Mwamba and founded a centralized state whose ruler bore the title mulopwe. The polity crystallized around Lake Boya in the Upemba Depression and governed through a court of nobles, tributary chiefs, and the Bambudye secret society, which preserved royal history and legitimized succession. Rather than ruling by direct conquest, the kings extended influence by demanding tribute and exporting sacred royal fire to vassal \"fire kingdoms\" on the frontier, while monopolizing trade in salt, copper, and iron. The empire greatly expanded during the eighteenth century, notably under King Kadilo and his successors, becoming a dominant power of the southern Congo savanna. It fragmented after an 1889 succession dispute amid disruptive slave- and ivory-raiding by East African traders, and was soon absorbed into the Congo Free State.",
  "turks and caicos islands": "The islands were first permanently settled from 1681 by Bermudian salt rakers who worked Grand Turk seasonally and long resisted outside control, resenting Bahamian attempts to tax and license their salt trade through Nassau. After the American Revolution ended in 1783, British Loyalist refugees settled the Caicos group and established cotton plantations worked by enslaved Africans, though this plantation economy collapsed by around 1820. In 1799 Britain formally annexed both the Turks and the Caicos groups as part of the Colony of the Bahamas, ending the ambiguous Bermudian–Bahamian jurisdictional disputes in the Crown's favour. Governed thereafter from Nassau, the islands remained a peripheral salt-producing dependency with little local autonomy for the first half of the nineteenth century. Resentment at Bahamian rule and taxation eventually drove the inhabitants to petition successfully for separation, and in 1848 the islands were made a distinct colony under a council president.",
  "kingdom of sweden": "The modern Kingdom of Sweden emerged when Gustav Vasa broke the realm away from the Kalmar Union and was elected king in 1523, founding a hereditary Vasa monarchy. Sweden rose to become a European great power during the seventeenth-century \"Age of Greatness,\" dominating the Baltic under warrior-kings such as Gustavus Adolphus and Charles XII before that empire collapsed in the Great Northern War. The eighteenth-century \"Age of Liberty\" shifted power to the Riksdag of the Estates, until Gustav III restored strong royal authority through his coup of 1772 and a further seizure of power in 1789. His son Gustav IV Adolf, who reigned from 1792, was overthrown in an 1809 coup after the disastrous loss of Finland to Russia, prompting a new constitution and the election of the French marshal Bernadotte as heir. The kingdom has continued to the present day as a constitutional monarchy, having remained at peace since 1814.",
  "konbaung dynasty": "The Konbaung dynasty was founded in 1752 by Alaungpaya, a village headman from Shwebo who rallied Upper Burma to overthrow the Restored Hanthawaddy Kingdom and reunify the country. His successors, notably Hsinbyushin, waged aggressive expansionist wars, sacking the Siamese capital Ayutthaya in 1767 and repelling four Chinese Qing invasions between 1765 and 1769. King Bodawpaya, who seized the throne in 1782, continued this expansion, annexing the Kingdom of Arakan in 1784–1785 and pushing Burmese frontiers toward Bengal and Assam. This westward growth eventually brought the dynasty into conflict with British India, producing three Anglo-Burmese Wars that steadily stripped away its territory across the nineteenth century. The dynasty ended in 1885 when British forces occupied Mandalay, deposed King Thibaw, and abolished the Burmese monarchy, incorporating the kingdom into British India.",
  "kingdom of bagirmi": "The Sultanate of Bagirmi coalesced from a group of chiefdoms around 1522 under a ruling dynasty whose kings bore the title Mbang and reigned from the capital at Massenya. Islam became the state religion under Mbang Abdullah in the late sixteenth century, though many subjects continued to follow traditional beliefs, and the realm long alternated between independence and tributary subordination to its powerful neighbor Bornu to the west. Under Mbang Muhammad al-Amin in the second half of the eighteenth century Bagirmi threw off Bornu's overlordship and reasserted its independence. In 1805/1806 the rising sultanate of Wadai under Sabun sacked Massenya, killed the reigning Mbang, and reduced Bagirmi to a tributary that its eastern neighbor repeatedly plundered thereafter. Weakened further by the conquests of the warlord Rabih az-Zubayr in 1893, the sultanate placed itself under French protection by treaty in 1897 and was absorbed into French colonial rule, surviving today only as a ceremonial monarchy within Chad.",
  "tokugawa shogunate": "The Tokugawa shogunate was founded in 1603 when Tokugawa Ieyasu, victorious at the Battle of Sekigahara in 1600, was appointed Sei-i Taishōgun and established a hereditary military government at Edo while the emperor remained a ceremonial figure at Kyoto. Successive Tokugawa shoguns bound the roughly 260 daimyo domains to the center through the alternate-attendance system, hostage families at Edo, and strict control of the imperial court, the temples, and foreign contact. From the 1630s the regime enforced the sakoku policy, expelling most Europeans, banning Christianity, and restricting overseas trade to closely supervised contacts with the Dutch, Chinese, Koreans, and Ryukyuans. The long peace it imposed fostered urban growth, commerce, and a vibrant merchant culture, even as recurring famines, fiscal strain, and rigid status hierarchies bred periodic reform drives and rural unrest. Weakened by financial crisis and the arrival of Western powers, the shogunate collapsed in 1868 when the last shogun resigned and imperial rule was restored under the Meiji Restoration.",
  "rozvi empire": "The Rozvi Empire was founded around 1683 by Changamire Dombo, a Shona leader who broke from the Mutapa state and defeated the Torwa dynasty to seize the Butua kingdom in the southwest. Ruled by the Changamire dynasty through a collateral brother-to-brother succession that frequently bred conflict, the state expelled Portuguese traders in the 1690s and asserted dominance over much of the plateau, its name derived from a Shona word evoking its warriors' reputation for plunder. It operated as a centralized tributary monarchy in which the mambo, advised by a council of chief councillors, collected goods and labor and redistributed protection, rain and fertility ceremonies, and drought relief. Governance radiated in concentric zones from a core ruled directly by the mambo outward to royal appointees and more distant tributary territories. The empire was shattered by Nguni and Ndebele groups during the 1830s Mfecane, and its last ruler, Tohwechipi, finally surrendered to Mzilikazi in 1866, ending the Changamire line.",
  "kingdom of ireland": "The Kingdom of Ireland was established by the Crown of Ireland Act of 1542, when Henry VIII of England was proclaimed King of Ireland, replacing the earlier lordship and binding the island to the English crown in personal union. Though formally a kingdom, it functioned as a dependency, its parliament long bound by Poynings' Law and its politics dominated by the Protestant Anglo-Irish minority through the established Church of Ireland while penal laws suppressed the Catholic majority. Its history was shaped by the Tudor conquest, the Confederate Wars of the 1640s, the Cromwellian conquest, and the Williamite War of 1689 to 1691, which entrenched the Protestant Ascendancy. In 1782 Grattan's Parliament won legislative independence, but the failed United Irishmen rebellion of 1798 alarmed the government and accelerated moves toward union. The kingdom was abolished when the Acts of Union came into force on 1 January 1801, merging Ireland with Great Britain to form the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland.",
  "viceroyalty of new granada": "The Viceroyalty of New Granada was created by Bourbon royal decree in 1717 to detach the northern Andean provinces from the Viceroyalty of Peru, suppressed in 1723 for financial reasons, and definitively reestablished in 1739. Governed from Santa Fe de Bogotá by a viceroy appointed by the Spanish crown, it consolidated the audiencias of Santa Fe, Quito, and Panama and later oversaw the Captaincy General of Venezuela. Its administration embodied the Bourbon Reforms, tightening royal control, expanding tobacco and aguardiente monopolies, and strengthening defenses against British incursions in the Caribbean. The heavy fiscal exactions provoked resistance, most notably the Comunero Revolt of 1781, which was suppressed but foreshadowed deeper creole discontent. The viceroyalty collapsed after 1810 when local juntas rejected Napoleonic-occupied Spain's authority, dissolving into the independence struggles that produced Gran Colombia.",
  "malabar": "Malabar came under British East India Company control in 1792, when Tipu Sultan of Mysore ceded the region to the Company and its allies under the Treaty of Seringapatam that ended the Third Anglo-Mysore War. The territory was first attached to the Bombay Presidency and administered by Company commissioners, then transferred to the Madras Presidency in 1800, where it was organised as a district under a Principal Collector headquartered at Calicut. Company rule provoked sustained armed resistance, above all the Cotiote War waged from 1793 to 1806 by Kerala Varma Pazhassi Raja of the Kottayam house, one of the longest and bloodiest campaigns the Company fought in India. The old ruling houses, including the Zamorin of Calicut, were progressively stripped of sovereignty and reduced to Company pensioners, formalised in the settlement of 1806. The district endured as a unit of British India until Indian independence and was finally dissolved in 1956, its territory merged into the new state of Kerala and neighbouring areas.",
  "viceroyalty of brazil": "Portugal's American possession was governed as the State of Brazil, and from 1763 its governors permanently held the title of viceroy, giving the colony its common designation as the Viceroyalty of Brazil. In that year the capital was transferred from Salvador to Rio de Janeiro, reflecting the economic pull of the gold and diamond districts of the interior, and in 1775 the northern states of Maranhão and Grão-Pará were absorbed to unify Portuguese America under a single viceroy. The period was marked by tightening royal control and rising colonial grievance, producing conspiracies against Portuguese rule such as the Inconfidência Mineira of 1789 and the Bahia Conspiracy of 1798. The viceregal office was suppressed in 1808 when the Portuguese royal court, fleeing Napoleon's invasion, relocated to Rio de Janeiro and assumed direct government. In 1815 the colony was elevated to the Kingdom of Brazil within the United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves, ending its colonial subordination and setting the stage for independence in 1822.",
  "thuringian states": "The Ernestine Saxon duchies originated in the 1485 Leipzig division of the Wettin lands between the brothers Ernest and Albert, and after the Ernestine head John Frederick I lost the Saxon electorate to the Albertine line at the Capitulation of Wittenberg in 1547, the family retained its Thuringian territories as its remaining base. Because Saxon custom divided inheritances among all sons, these lands fragmented repeatedly into a shifting patchwork of small duchies such as Saxe-Weimar, Saxe-Gotha-Altenburg, Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld, Saxe-Meiningen, and Saxe-Hildburghausen, several of which held votes in the Imperial Diet within the Upper Saxon Circle. Each duchy was an independent principality of the Holy Roman Empire, ruled by its own branch of the House of Wettin, and their courts were noted more for cultural patronage than for military or political weight. The most celebrated among them, Saxe-Weimar under Duchess Anna Amalia and Duke Charles Augustus, made Weimar a leading centre of German letters, drawing Goethe, Schiller, Herder, and Wieland in the era of Weimar Classicism. The duchies joined Napoleon's Confederation of the Rhine, entered the German Confederation in 1815, consolidated into four states by 1826, and were finally abolished when their rulers abdicated in 1918, their lands merging into the new state of Thuringia in 1920.",
  "viceroyalty of peru": "The Viceroyalty of Peru was created by the Spanish Crown in 1542 through the New Laws to govern its South American possessions, with its seat established at Lima. Following the turbulent civil wars among the conquistadors, Viceroy Francisco de Toledo consolidated colonial rule in the 1570s, systematizing the mita labor draft and extinguishing the last Neo-Inca resistance at Vilcabamba in 1572. For nearly two centuries it was the dominant Spanish authority in South America and one of the empire's richest possessions, sustained by silver mining and a mercantile monopoly centered on Lima. The eighteenth-century Bourbon Reforms progressively dismembered it, detaching the Viceroyalty of New Granada in 1717 and 1739 and the Viceroyalty of Río de la Plata in 1776, and it was shaken by the great Andean rebellion of Túpac Amaru II in 1780–1783. Reduced but still the crown's principal South American stronghold, the viceroyalty became the bastion of royalism in the wars of independence and was formally dissolved in 1824 after the patriot victory at Ayacucho.",
  "saint-barthélemy": "France ceded Saint-Barthélemy to Sweden on 1 July 1784 in exchange for trading privileges at Gothenburg, making it the Swedish crown's only Caribbean possession. Swedish officials took formal control in March 1785, renamed the harbour town Gustavia after King Gustav III, and declared it a free port open to all nations, which turned a poor, water-scarce island into a busy neutral entrepôt for wartime and contraband trade. Administered by a succession of royally appointed governors, the colony leaned on slavery and on transit commerce rather than plantation agriculture, prospering especially during the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic wars when belligerents used its neutral flag. British forces occupied the island from 1801 to 1802 during the French Revolutionary Wars, after which Swedish rule resumed and continued through decades of gradual commercial decline. Sweden finally sold the impoverished colony back to France in 1878, ending nearly a century of Swedish administration.",
  "kingdom of nepal": "The unified Kingdom of Nepal was founded in 1768 when Prithvi Narayan Shah of the Gorkha Shah dynasty conquered the three Malla kingdoms of the Kathmandu Valley and proclaimed a single state. His successors pressed a vigorous expansionist campaign, absorbing the fragmented Baise and Chaubisi hill principalities and pushing the frontier eastward and westward along the Himalaya. Rule was frequently exercised by regents and powerful court factions, since several kings ascended the throne as minors, producing chronic palace intrigue among rival noble houses such as the Pandes, Basnyats, and Thapas. Overexpansion brought conflict with the British East India Company in the Anglo-Nepalese War of 1814–1816, whose Treaty of Sugauli stripped away much of the conquered territory and fixed Nepal's modern boundaries. The Shah monarchy endured, later eclipsed for a century by the hereditary Rana prime ministers, until it was finally abolished and Nepal declared a republic in 2008.",
  "viceroyalty of the río de la plata": "The Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata was created by royal decree of King Charles III of Spain in 1776 as part of the Bourbon Reforms, carved out of territories previously governed by the Viceroyalty of Peru to counter Portuguese encroachment and rampant contraband in the region. Its first viceroy was Pedro Antonio de Cevallos, followed by reform-minded administrators such as Juan José de Vértiz y Salcedo, who developed Buenos Aires into a major administrative and commercial center. As the last and shortest-lived of Spain's American viceroyalties, it centralized authority over a vast and previously peripheral domain and was reorganized internally through the intendancy system introduced in 1782. In 1806 and 1807 it repelled two British invasions largely through locally raised militias, an experience that fostered a growing sense of Creole self-reliance and autonomy. The Napoleonic upheaval in Spain precipitated its collapse, and the May Revolution of 1810 deposed the viceroy and installed a governing junta in Buenos Aires, effectively ending Spanish viceregal rule and launching the region's wars of independence.",
  "tuʻi tonga empire": "The Tuʻi Tonga line was founded around 950 CE under the semi-legendary ʻAhoʻeitu and grew into a Polynesian maritime empire that extracted tribute, the ʻinasi, from a network of Pacific island chiefdoms, reaching its height under rulers such as Momo and Tuʻitātui between the 12th and 15th centuries. Its overseas hegemony collapsed with the loss of Samoa after the defeat of Tuʻi Tonga Talakaifaiki, and internal strife and repeated assassinations of rulers pushed the line into decline. Around 1470–1535 Kauʻulufonua I created the Tuʻi Haʻatakalaua title to handle daily governance, leaving the Tuʻi Tonga as a sacred high chief with elevated status but little worldly power, and in 1610 the Tuʻi Kanokupolu line emerged and eventually became Tonga's dominant secular authority. From the 17th century the Tuʻi Tonga functioned chiefly as a religious paramount seated at Muʻa, while the three great lineages coexisted uneasily. The murder of the Tuʻi Kanokupolu Tukuʻaho in 1799 plunged Tonga into roughly fifty years of civil war, and the Tuʻi Tonga title itself ended with the death of Laufilitonga in 1865, being formally abolished in 1875.",
  "regency of tunis": "The Regency of Tunis was founded in 1705 when al-Husayn I ibn Ali, an officer of Greek Cretan descent, seized power and established the Husainid dynasty, supplanting the earlier Muradid rulers. Although the Husainid beys held the Ottoman title of beylerbeyi and acknowledged the sultan's nominal suzerainty, they governed as effectively independent hereditary monarchs who concluded their own treaties with France, Britain, and the Italian states. Its economy long rested on Mediterranean corsairing alongside a state-monopolized grain and agricultural export trade dominated by a Turkish-speaking ruling caste. The regency was repeatedly at odds with neighbouring Algiers and Venice and periodically had to manage restive janissary garrisons and tribal populations. Husainid rule endured until the French invasion of 1881, when the Treaty of Bardo reduced Tunisia to a French protectorate while leaving the beys as figurehead sovereigns.",
  "regency of algiers": "The Regency of Algiers was founded in 1516 when the corsair brothers Aruj and Hayreddin Barbarossa seized the city and placed it under Ottoman suzerainty, succeeding the Kingdom of Tlemcen. Initially governed by Ottoman-appointed pashas, real power shifted over the seventeenth century to the janissary corps and the corsair captains, and from 1671 the state was headed by an elected dey, with the deys assuming the pasha title themselves from 1710 and largely ceasing to accept representatives from the Sublime Porte. Throughout its history the Regency waged maritime holy war against Christian shipping in the Mediterranean, and its corsairs made it a formidable and much-feared naval power whose ransoming of captives and tribute demands shaped its relations with Europe. Its politics were turbulent, with deys frequently deposed or assassinated by the janissary-dominated council, the Odjak. The state endured until 1830, when a French expeditionary force landed and captured Algiers, ending Ottoman-era rule and beginning the French colonization of Algeria.",
  "spanish philippines": "Spanish colonization of the archipelago began with Miguel López de Legazpi's expedition of 1565, and the Captaincy General of the Philippines was organized as a territory of the Spanish Empire administered through the Viceroyalty of New Spain in Mexico City. Governed by a captain-general appointed on the Crown's behalf, the colony fused royal authority with the pervasive power of the Catholic religious orders, whose friars administered parishes and much of provincial life. Its economy long revolved around the Manila galleon trade linking Acapulco to Asia, while the encomienda system gradually gave way to provinces headed by alcaldes mayores. Late eighteenth-century Bourbon reforms, including the 1784 establishment of an Intendencia and later economic liberalization, sought to make the colony more directly productive for Spain. Spanish rule endured until 1898, when defeat in the Spanish–American War and the Treaty of Paris transferred sovereignty to the United States.",
  "regency of tripoli": "The Regency of Tripoli became a hereditary autonomous state in 1711 when the Janissary officer Ahmed Karamanli seized power by killing the Ottoman governor and won recognition as pasha, founding the Karamanli dynasty. While it continued to pay nominal tribute to the Ottoman sultan, it functioned in practice as an independent polity, financing itself largely through Mediterranean corsairing and tribute extracted from foreign powers. Power passed within the family until Yusuf Karamanli seized the throne in 1795 after recapturing Tripoli with Tunisian help and exiling his brother. Under Yusuf the regency fought the First Barbary War against the United States from 1801 to 1805 and later saw its corsair economy collapse as European powers suppressed piracy after 1815. Beset by debt and civil war following Yusuf's abdication in 1832, the dynasty ended in 1835 when Sultan Mahmud II deposed Ali II and restored direct Ottoman rule.",
  "joseon": "The Joseon dynasty was founded in 1392 by the general Yi Seonggye, who overthrew the Goryeo dynasty and took the throne as Taejo, establishing a state governed by Neo-Confucian principles that would endure for over five centuries. Its kings ruled through a centralized bureaucracy staffed by a scholar-official class recruited by civil examination, while a hereditary yangban aristocracy dominated politics and often coalesced into rival court factions. Diplomatically the dynasty operated within the sadae framework of ritual subordination as a tributary first of Ming and, after the seventeenth-century Manchu invasions, of Qing China, yet it retained broad internal autonomy. The dynasty weathered the devastating Japanese invasions of the 1590s and later cultivated an isolationist stance that earned it the epithet the \"Hermit Kingdom.\" It endured until 1897, when King Gojong abandoned the Joseon name and proclaimed the Korean Empire in a bid to assert full sovereign independence.",
  "zanzibar": "Omani forces under Imam Saif bin Sultan of the Ya'rubid dynasty expelled the Portuguese from the Swahili coast and captured Zanzibar in 1698, bringing the island under the overseas dominion of Oman. After the Al Bu Sa'id (Busaidi) dynasty took power in Oman in 1749, its rulers installed governors on Unguja and made Zanzibar Town the seat of Omani authority along the coast, competing with the rival Mazrui family that controlled Mombasa. Through the eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries the Busaidi consolidated their hold over Unguja, Pemba, Kilwa, and Lamu, drawing on Indian financiers and the Indian Ocean trade to build a commercial entrepot. Said bin Sultan, who ruled Oman from 1804, deepened this involvement, transferring his court to Stone Town by the 1830s and finally subduing the Mazrui at Mombasa in 1837. On his death in 1856 the realm was divided between his sons, and Zanzibar was formally separated from Oman as an independent sultanate in 1861.",
  "lunda empire": "The Lunda Empire coalesced around 1665 when tradition holds that Ilunga Tshibinda, a hunter-prince from the Luba world, married the Lunda ruler Lueji, whose lineage produced the first paramount chiefs bearing the title Mwata Yamvo. Its first well-attested sovereign, Nawej, is dated to about 1695, and under him and his successors the state grew into a sprawling tributary confederation governed through a ruling council and a system of positional succession in which each new king assumed the name and identity of his predecessor. The empire expanded aggressively across the southern savanna, spinning off satellite states such as the eastern Lunda kingdom of the Mwata Kazembe, and grew wealthy by taxing and controlling long-distance trade in ivory and slaves that linked it to Portuguese Angola on the Atlantic and to Swahili-Arab merchants toward the Indian Ocean. It reached the height of its power in the first half of the nineteenth century before the militarized, gun-armed Chokwe, initially welcomed as elephant hunters, turned against their overlords and dismembered the state. Chokwe forces overran the royal capital and killed the reigning Mwata Yamvo in 1887, and the collapsing empire was soon partitioned between Portuguese Angola and the Belgian Congo Free State, ending its independence.",
  "spanish louisiana": "Spain gained Louisiana from France under the secret Treaty of Fontainebleau of 1762, formalized when France ceded it in the 1763 Treaty of Paris ending the Seven Years' War. Spanish authority was resisted at first, sparking the Louisiana Rebellion of 1768 by French colonists, which Governor Alejandro O'Reilly crushed the following year before imposing Spanish institutions. Under governors such as Bernardo de Gálvez the colony aided the American Revolution and campaigned against Britain, seizing British West Florida between 1779 and 1781. Governed from New Orleans as a province tied to the Captaincy General of Cuba, it saw substantial immigration, plantation growth, and the rebuilding of its capital after devastating fires in 1788 and 1794. Its Spanish era ended when the Third Treaty of San Ildefonso of 1800 secretly returned it to France, leading to the formal 1803 handover and the immediate sale of the territory to the United States in the Louisiana Purchase.",
  "rajput states": "The Rajput states of Rajputana were never a single kingdom but a constellation of independent Rajput dynasties, chiefly the Kachhwaha rulers of Jaipur (formerly Amber), the Rathore rulers of Marwar (Jodhpur) and Bikaner, and the Sisodia rulers of Mewar (Udaipur), whose lineages traced back to medieval foundings such as Marwar in 1243 and Jodhpur city in 1459. After the decline of Mughal authority in the eighteenth century these states asserted autonomy but fell into chronic internecine rivalry and disputed successions that neighbouring powers exploited. From the 1750s onward the Maratha chiefs Sindhia of Gwalior and Holkar of Indore repeatedly invaded, extracted crushing tributes, and reduced most eastern Rajput courts to tributary status, a pressure compounded by devastating Pindari and Pathan raids. Ruinous conflicts such as the war over the Mewar princess Krishna Kumari in the 1800s left the states militarily exhausted and financially drained. Their independence effectively ended when, after the Third Anglo-Maratha War, the major states accepted British subsidiary alliances in 1817–1818, entering British paramountcy while retaining nominal internal self-rule.",
  "sultanate of brunei": "The Sultanate of Brunei took shape in the fourteenth century when its rulers adopted Islam, and it grew into a formidable maritime power that at its sixteenth-century zenith under Sultan Bolkiah claimed suzerainty over much of coastal Borneo and parts of the Philippines. It was governed as a Malay monarchy in which the sultan ruled with a council of great nobles, drawing wealth from trade, tribute, and control of regional sea lanes. From the late seventeenth century the state declined amid recurring succession disputes, a civil war, European commercial pressure, and endemic piracy, and its authority steadily contracted toward its Bornean heartland. In the nineteenth century this decline accelerated as the sultanate ceded Sarawak to James Brooke in 1841 and progressively lost Labuan and its northern Bornean territories. Weakened and shorn of most of its former domains, Brunei accepted British protectorate status under Sultan Hashim Jalilul Alam Aqamaddin in 1888, ending its era as an independent power.",
  "kingdom of kandy": "The Kingdom of Kandy was founded around 1469 when Senasammata Vikramabahu asserted the central highlands' independence from the Kingdom of Kotte, and it was re-established as the sole surviving native polity by Vimaladharmasuriya I in 1592 after the Sitawaka interlude. For over two centuries its rulers waged a long resistance against the Portuguese and then the Dutch, exploiting the mountainous interior to preserve Sinhalese sovereignty and guardianship of the sacred Tooth Relic. After a succession crisis on the death of Vira Narendrasinha, the throne passed in 1739 to his brother-in-law Sri Vijaya Rajasinha, beginning the Tamil-speaking Nayak dynasty from South India, whose kings patronised Theravada Buddhism despite their own Hindu background. The last Nayak king, Sri Vikrama Rajasinha, alienated the powerful Kandyan chiefs through erratic and brutal rule, notably the execution of the minister Pilima Talawe and the killing of Ehelepola's family. In 1815 defecting nobles helped British forces under Governor Robert Brownrigg seize the capital and capture the king, and the Kandyan Convention formally ended the kingdom and the more than two-thousand-year Sinhalese monarchy.",
  "lao kingdoms": "The unified Lao kingdom of Lan Xang fragmented in 1707 into three rival successor kingdoms—Luang Prabang in the north, Vientiane in the centre, and Champasak in the south. Weakened by their mutual rivalry, all three fell under foreign domination during the eighteenth century, alternately submitting to Burma and to Siam. Following the Lao–Siamese War of 1778–1779, King Taksin's Siam subjugated the three kingdoms, carrying off the revered Emerald Buddha and Phra Bang and reducing each to a tributary whose rulers were confirmed and whose succession was controlled from Bangkok. They persisted as semi-autonomous vassals for over a century, with Vientiane destroyed and dissolved in 1828 after King Anouvong's failed rebellion against Siamese overlordship. The remaining kingdoms endured under Siamese suzerainty until 1893, when the Franco-Siamese crisis forced Siam to cede the Lao lands east of the Mekong to French Indochina.",
  "sultanate of morocco": "The Alaouite dynasty, a Sharifian family claiming descent from the Prophet Muhammad, rose to power from the Tafilalt oasis where Mawlay al-Sharif was proclaimed leader in 1631, and it has ruled Morocco ever since. Moulay al-Rashid reunified the country and captured Fez in 1666, restoring centralized monarchy after the decline of the Saadi Sultanate, and his successor Moulay Ismail (r. 1672-1727) brought the state to its apogee through strong central rule backed by the Abid al-Bukhari slave army. After Ismail's death the sultanate endured decades of civil strife and contested successions until Sultan Mohammed III stabilized it, followed by the brief violent reign of al-Yazid. Moulay Slimane (r. 1792-1822) continued centralization, suppressed coastal piracy, and, influenced by reformist ideas, cracked down on Sufi brotherhoods, though he faced serious tribal rebellions late in his reign. The dynasty preserved Morocco's independence through the 19th century until European pressure culminated in the French and Spanish protectorates of 1912, after which it regained sovereignty in 1956 and continues to reign today.",
  "madras presidency": "The Presidency of Fort St George grew from the English East India Company's coastal trading settlement at Madras, founded in 1639–40 and elevated to a full presidency in 1684. Governed by a Governor-in-Council answerable after 1774 to the Governor-General at Calcutta, it was transformed from a commercial factory into a territorial administration through the Company's wars against its Indian rivals. Its power in the south was consolidated by the Anglo-Mysore Wars against Hyder Ali and Tipu Sultan, culminating in Tipu's defeat and death at Seringapatam in 1799, followed by cessions from the Nizam of Hyderabad in 1800 and the annexation of the Carnatic from the Nawab of Arcot in 1801. Ruled directly by the Company until the Crown assumed control after the 1857 rebellion, it then continued as a province of the British Raj. It endured as an administrative unit until the independence and partition of British India in 1947.",
  "kingdom of travancore": "Travancore was founded in 1729 by Anizham Thirunal Marthanda Varma, who consolidated the older principality of Venad and expanded it by conquering neighbouring chiefdoms such as Quilon, Kayamkulam, and Kottayam. Marthanda Varma centralised royal authority by suppressing the Ettuveetil Pillamar nobility, dedicated the kingdom to the deity Padmanabha in the 1750 Trippadidanam, and repelled the Dutch East India Company at the Battle of Colachel in 1741. His successor Karthika Thirunal Rama Varma, known as Dharma Raja, presided over a cultural flowering, defended the realm against Tipu Sultan of Mysore, and entered into treaties with the British East India Company. Under Balarama Varma the state came firmly within the Company's subsidiary system, and the revolt of Velu Thampi Dalawa in 1808–1809 marked the final challenge to British paramountcy before the dynasty settled into the status of a loyal princely state. Travancore remained a princely state under the British Raj until it acceded to independent India, its rulers finally merging the state into the Indian Union in 1949."
};

/* 1700-era iteration descriptions (added by the 1700-era build; see CLAUDE.md 'Generating timeline eras'). */
Object.assign(window.COUNTRY_INFO, {"kingdom of france":"The Kingdom of France (Royaume de France) under the House of Bourbon was the successor to the Valois monarchy, established in 1589 when Henry IV, head of the senior Capetian line, inherited the throne under Salic law. It was a hereditary monarchy that evolved into the archetype of European absolutism, with power increasingly centralized in the person of the king and administered through royal intendants, a professional bureaucracy, and a standing army. Its most celebrated ruler was Louis XIV, the \"Sun King,\" whose long reign fixed the court at the Palace of Versailles and made France the dominant military and cultural power of the age, though the dynasty also produced consequential figures such as Henry IV and the reforming ministers Sully, Richelieu, Mazarin, and Colbert. Over the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries the Bourbon state expanded France to roughly its modern borders while accumulating heavy debts and social tensions through repeated warfare and fiscal strain. The Bourbon monarchy of this iteration ended in September 1792, when the Revolutionary National Convention abolished the crown and proclaimed the First French Republic.","kingdom of england":"The Kingdom of England was a sovereign state formed when Æthelstan unified the various Anglo-Saxon realms under a single crown, conventionally dated to his recognition as king of the English in 927. Governed as a monarchy, it developed over the centuries a distinctive system in which the king ruled alongside a bicameral Parliament of Lords and Commons, evolving after the Glorious Revolution of 1688 into a constitutional monarchy where the sovereign could not govern without Parliament's consent. Its history spanned dynasties from the House of Wessex through the Normans, Plantagenets, Tudors, and Stuarts, and included such notable rulers as Henry VIII, who broke with Rome and established the Church of England, and Elizabeth I, under whom the realm rose to prominence as a European power. The kingdom absorbed Wales legally during the Tudor period and shared its monarch with Scotland and Ireland after the Union of the Crowns in 1603, while its Parliament increasingly asserted supremacy over the throne. The Kingdom of England ceased to exist as a separate state on 1 May 1707, when the Acts of Union merged it with the Kingdom of Scotland to form the Kingdom of Great Britain.","kingdom of scotland":"The Kingdom of Scotland was the sovereign state that occupied the northern third of the island of Great Britain, traditionally founded in 843 when Cínaed mac Ailpín united the Picts and Scots under the House of Alpin. It was a hereditary monarchy in which royal authority came to be balanced by the Parliament of Scotland, a single-chamber assembly of the Three Estates that oversaw taxation and law, alongside a Privy Council. Its long history was marked by the Wars of Scottish Independence against England, the reigns of monarchs such as David I, Alexander III, Robert the Bruce, and the Stuart kings, and the gradual consolidation of its modern borders. In 1603 James VI inherited the English throne, creating a personal union of the two crowns while Scotland remained a distinct kingdom with its own parliament, laws, and church. The kingdom ceased to exist as a separate state on 1 May 1707, when the Acts of Union merged it with England to form the Kingdom of Great Britain.","dutch republic":"The Dutch Republic, formally the Republic of the Seven United Netherlands (also called the United Provinces), was a confederation of seven autonomous provinces — Holland, Zeeland, Utrecht, Friesland, Groningen, Gelderland, and Overijssel — that emerged from the revolt against Spanish Habsburg rule, consolidating its independence through the 1579 Union of Utrecht, the 1581 Act of Abjuration, and its confederal establishment in 1588. Sovereignty rested with the provincial States and the federal States-General seated at The Hague, while executive military leadership fell to the stadtholder, an office usually held by princes of the House of Orange-Nassau alongside the powerful office of grand pensionary of Holland. It rose to become a leading commercial, financial, naval, and colonial power during the seventeenth-century Dutch Golden Age, distinguished by relative religious tolerance, a merchant-oligarchic government of regents, and flourishing trade, science, and art. Notable figures included stadtholders William the Silent, Maurice, and William III, and statesmen such as Johan de Witt, while recurring tension between Orangist and republican-regent factions shaped its politics. Its power waned through the eighteenth century, and the Republic was overthrown in the 1795 Batavian Revolution, giving way to the Batavian Republic.","holy roman empire":"The Holy Roman Empire (Latin Sacrum Romanum Imperium; from 1512 styled the Holy Roman Empire of the German Nation) was a decentralized, confederal, elective monarchy in central Europe, conventionally dated from the imperial coronation of Otto I in 962 and sometimes traced to Charlemagne in 800. It was not a unitary state but a loose framework of several hundred largely self-governing territories—kingdoms, principalities, ecclesiastical states, duchies, and free imperial cities—bound to an emperor whom a small college of prince-electors chose. Its emperorship was dominated for centuries by the House of Habsburg, who from the fifteenth century made the elective title effectively hereditary, while institutions such as the Imperial Diet, the Imperial Chamber Court, and the Aulic Council mediated the relations among its members. Over its long existence the Empire evolved from a medieval universalist power claiming the mantle of ancient Rome into an increasingly decentralized early-modern polity, its central authority further weakened after the religious wars and the Peace of Westphalia of 1648. It came to an end on 6 August 1806, when Emperor Francis II abdicated the imperial crown amid the Napoleonic reorganization of Germany.","brandenburg-prussia":"Brandenburg-Prussia was the personal union of the Margraviate (Electorate) of Brandenburg and the Duchy of Prussia under the House of Hohenzollern, formed in 1618 when Elector John Sigismund inherited the Prussian duchy. Ruled from Berlin as an elective principality of the Holy Roman Empire while the Duchy of Prussia lay outside the Empire, it was a geographically scattered composite state stretching from the Rhineland exclaves of Cleves, Mark, and Ravensberg across Brandenburg to Ducal Prussia on the Baltic. Its most consequential ruler, Frederick William the Great Elector, built a standing army, curtailed the estates, promoted mercantilist and Protestant-immigration policies, and won full sovereignty over Prussia at the Peace of Oliva in 1660. His son Elector Frederick III consolidated these gains and pursued royal status, patronizing the arts and sciences from a Berlin court modeled on that of Louis XIV. The entity ended in 1701 when Frederick III crowned himself King Frederick I \"in Prussia,\" transforming the Hohenzollern domains into the Kingdom of Prussia.","polish–lithuanian commonwealth":"The Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, officially the Kingdom of Poland and the Grand Duchy of Lithuania and known to its citizens as the Rzeczpospolita (\"Commonwealth of Two Nations\"), was a federative dual state formed by the Union of Lublin in 1569. It was governed as a \"noble republic\" in which an elective monarch shared power with a bicameral Sejm dominated by the szlachta nobility, whose extensive privileges under the system of Golden Liberty—including the liberum veto—constrained royal authority. Notable elected kings included Stephen Báthory, the Vasa dynasty, and John III Sobieski, whose relief of Vienna in 1683 marked a high point of its military power. Over the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries the Commonwealth declined amid devastating wars, internal paralysis, and growing interference by neighboring powers. It was progressively dismembered in the three Partitions of 1772, 1793, and 1795, by which Russia, Prussia, and Austria erased it from the map of Europe.","tsardom of russia":"The Tsardom of Russia, also called the Tsardom of Muscovy, was the centralized Russian state that existed from Ivan IV's assumption of the title of tsar in 1547 until Peter the Great proclaimed the Russian Empire in 1721. It was an Orthodox autocracy in which the tsar held supreme power, supported by a landed service nobility and an increasingly bureaucratic state, with Moscow as its capital and the Rurikid and later Romanov dynasties as its ruling houses. Its history spanned the reign of Ivan the Terrible, the dynastic collapse and foreign intervention of the Time of Troubles, the accession of Michael Romanov in 1613, and the reforming reign of Peter I. Throughout this period the state expanded dramatically eastward across Siberia to the Pacific and southward toward the steppe, becoming the largest polity in the world by territory. The tsardom ended in 1721 when, following victory over Sweden in the Great Northern War, Peter the Great was proclaimed emperor and the realm was reconstituted as the Russian Empire.","swiss confederation":"The Old Swiss Confederacy, known in this period as the Confederation of the Thirteen Cantons (Dreizehn Orte), traced its origin to the Federal Charter of 1291 among the rural communities of Uri, Schwyz, and Unterwalden and grew into a lasting league by the accession of Appenzell in 1513. It was not a unified state but a loose alliance of self-governing urban and rural cantons bound by overlapping treaties, with no capital, no head of state, and no standing central administration; common business was settled by delegates meeting at the rotating federal diet, the Tagsatzung, chaired by Zürich as the leading canton (Vorort). After the Swabian War of 1499 it was effectively independent of the Holy Roman Empire, a status formally recognized at the Peace of Westphalia in 1648, and it maintained neutrality abroad while famously supplying mercenary soldiers to foreign powers. Internally it was riven by the Reformation into Catholic and Protestant blocs whose rivalry repeatedly deadlocked the diet and erupted into the Wars of Villmergen, and its governments hardened over time into aristocratic, patrician oligarchies. The confederacy of thirteen cantons endured until 1798, when a French invasion overthrew the old order and replaced it with the centralized Helvetic Republic.","republic of venice":"The Republic of Venice, styled in full the Most Serene Republic of Venice (Serenissima Repubblica di Venezia), was an aristocratic maritime state centred on the lagoon city of Venice, conventionally dated from the election of its first doge around 697. It was governed as an oligarchic republic in which an elected doge served as ceremonial head of state while real power lay with patrician bodies such as the Great Council, the Senate, and the security-focused Council of Ten, a system famed for its stability. Growing rich on Mediterranean and Levantine trade, it built an extensive empire of the terraferma mainland and the overseas Stato da Màr, including Dalmatia, the Ionian Islands, Crete, and Cyprus, and produced renowned art, architecture, and shipbuilding. From the sixteenth century onward its commercial and naval dominance was eroded by Ottoman expansion, the shift of trade to the Atlantic, and the rise of larger powers, sending it into a long, luxurious decline. It was extinguished in 1797 when Napoleon Bonaparte's forces compelled the last doge, Ludovico Manin, to abdicate, and its lands were divided by the Treaty of Campo Formio.","republic of genoa":"The Republic of Genoa, officially the Most Serene Republic of Genoa, was an aristocratic maritime republic centred on the Ligurian port city of Genoa, conventionally dated from the communal oath (compagna communis) of 1099, when the city's citizens bound themselves together for common defence and naval enterprise. In the Late Middle Ages it grew into one of the foremost commercial and naval powers of the Mediterranean and Black Sea, planting trading colonies from Corsica and Chios to the Crimea, and by the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries it had become one of Europe's leading financial centres, its bankers underwriting the Spanish crown. From 1339 the head of state was a doge, chosen for life at first and, after Andrea Doria's constitutional reform of 1528, elected to two-year terms, while real power rested with a narrow oligarchy of patrician merchant families such as the Doria, Spinola, Fieschi, and Grimaldi. The republic entered a long, slow decline from the seventeenth century as Spanish bankruptcies ruined its financial houses and its naval importance faded, a decline deepened by the plague of 1656–57 and by growing subordination to Bourbon France. It was extinguished in 1797, when French revolutionary forces and local Jacobins overthrew the oligarchic government and replaced it with the Ligurian Republic.","kingdom of naples":"The Kingdom of Naples was a state comprising the southern Italian mainland, established in 1282 when the island of Sicily broke away from the Angevin realm during the War of the Sicilian Vespers, leaving the peninsular territories as a distinct kingdom centered on Naples. Ruled first by the French-descended Angevin dynasty and later by the Crown of Aragon, it passed after 1503 to the Spanish monarchy, which governed it for roughly two centuries as a viceroyalty administered by a viceroy resident in Naples. It was among the most populous and strategically important possessions of the Spanish crown, though its wealth was heavily taxed to fund Spanish wars and its society was dominated by a powerful landed nobility. Notable episodes in its history include Alfonso V of Aragon's reunification of Naples and Sicily in 1442, the revolt of Masaniello in 1647, and its transfer to Austrian Habsburg rule during the War of the Spanish Succession. The kingdom later became a sovereign Bourbon monarchy in 1734 and ultimately ceased to exist as a separate entity in 1816, when it was formally merged with Sicily to form the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies.","kingdom of sicily":"The Kingdom of Sicily was a monarchy founded in 1130 when Roger II of the Norman House of Hauteville united the island of Sicily and southern Italian territories under a single crown sanctioned at Palermo. It was a feudal kingdom with an early parliament and a notably cosmopolitan Norman-Arab-Byzantine culture, later centralized under the Hohenstaufen ruler Frederick II through the Constitutions of Melfi. After the Sicilian Vespers of 1282 the island passed from the Angevins to the House of Barcelona and then permanently into the Crown of Aragon in 1412, thereafter being governed for centuries by viceroys on behalf of the Aragonese and Spanish crowns. It briefly passed to the House of Savoy and then the Austrian Habsburgs in the early eighteenth century before coming under the rule of the Spanish Bourbons. The kingdom endured until 1816, when Ferdinand merged it with the Kingdom of Naples to create the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies, ending nearly seven centuries of separate existence.","duchy of savoy":"The Duchy of Savoy was a composite Alpine state ruled by the House of Savoy, created in 1416 when Emperor Sigismund elevated the County of Savoy to a duchy under Amadeus VIII. Straddling the western Alps, it united the French-speaking heartland of Savoy proper with the wealthier, Italian-speaking region of Piedmont, along with Nice, Aosta, and Oneglia, governed as a monarchy that moved its capital from Chambéry to Turin in 1562 under Emmanuel Philibert. Perpetually caught between France and the Habsburg powers, its dukes practised opportunistic diplomacy and military reform to preserve independence and expand eastward toward Milan. Its most consequential ruler, Victor Amadeus II, pursued centralizing, absolutist reforms and exploited the War of the Spanish Succession to enlarge his gains. The duchy as such ended in 1713 when Victor Amadeus II acquired the Kingdom of Sicily by the Treaty of Utrecht, exchanging it for the Kingdom of Sardinia in 1720, after which the dynasty ruled as kings.","kingdom of sardinia":"The Kingdom of Sardinia (Regnum Sardiniae, in this Iberian iteration) originated as a papal fief, the Kingdom of Sardinia and Corsica, granted by Pope Boniface VIII to James II of Aragon in 1297 and made real by the Aragonese conquest of the island beginning in 1324. It was a constituent realm of the Crown of Aragon, governed in the sovereign's name by a viceroy seated at Cagliari and retaining its own autonomous institutions, including a parliament known as the Stamenti. Through the dynastic union of Ferdinand of Aragon and Isabella of Castile it passed under the Spanish Habsburg crown, remaining a distinct kingdom rather than being absorbed into a unified Spain. Its administration was marked by feudal landholding, defence against Barbary corsairs, and a persistently rural, decentralized society. This Iberian phase ended after the War of the Spanish Succession, when the island was ceded first to the Austrian Habsburgs and finally, by the Treaty of The Hague in 1720, to the House of Savoy, which thereafter carried the royal title.","duchy of milan":"The Duchy of Milan was a state in northern Italy, centred on the Lombard plain, established on 11 May 1395 when Gian Galeazzo Visconti purchased the ducal title from Wenceslaus, King of the Romans, elevating the Visconti lordship that had governed Milan since 1277. After the Visconti line failed in 1447 and a brief Ambrosian Republic collapsed, the mercenary captain Francesco Sforza seized power in 1450 and founded the House of Sforza, under whom Milan flourished as a wealthy Renaissance court patronising figures such as Leonardo da Vinci. Contested between France and the Habsburgs during the Italian Wars, the duchy passed under the direct rule of Habsburg Spain in 1556, thereafter governed for the Spanish crown by resident governors seated at Milan. During the War of the Spanish Succession it was conquered by and transferred to the Austrian Habsburgs, a change confirmed by the peace treaties of the 1710s. The Duchy of Milan endured under Austrian sovereignty until 1796, when it was overrun by Napoleon's army and absorbed into the Cisalpine Republic, formally extinguished by the Treaty of Campo Formio in 1797.","duchy of modena":"The Duchy of Modena and Reggio (Italian: Ducato di Modena e Reggio; Latin: Ducatus Mutinae et Regii) was a hereditary state in north-central Italy ruled by the House of Este, formally created in 1452 when Holy Roman Emperor Frederick III elevated Borso d'Este, whose family had governed Modena and Reggio Emilia for generations. It began as an appendage of the Este duchy centered on Ferrara, and only after the papal Devolution of Ferrara in 1598 did Duke Cesare d'Este make Modena the capital of the surviving Este state. A small buffer principality sandwiched between the Papal States, the Holy Roman Empire, and larger neighbors, it was governed as an absolute duchy and became a noted center of Renaissance and Baroque patronage of the arts. Its rulers included Borso and Ercole I in the Ferrara period and later dukes such as Rinaldo d'Este and Francesco III, with the state passing in 1814 to the cadet Austria-Este line. The duchy ended in 1859, when the last duke, Francis V, fled during the Second Italian War of Independence, and its territory joined the United Provinces of Central Italy before annexation to the Kingdom of Sardinia in 1860.","duchy of parma and piacenza":"The Duchy of Parma and Piacenza was a small northern-Italian state created in 1545 when Pope Paul III carved it out of former Milanese territory and granted it as a hereditary fief to his illegitimate son, Pier Luigi Farnese. Ruled from Parma as an absolute duchy, it was governed for nearly two centuries by the House of Farnese, whose dukes centralized authority, curbed municipal privileges, and turned their court into a notable center of Baroque art, architecture, and music. Its most prominent early figures included the soldier-statesman Alessandro Farnese, who served as a celebrated Habsburg general in the Low Countries, while later dukes such as Ranuccio I enriched the capital with monuments like the Palazzo della Pilotta and the Teatro Farnese. Landlocked and of modest political weight, the duchy remained caught between the ambitions of larger powers and was nominally a papal fief throughout much of its Farnese period. The male Farnese line died out in 1731 with Duke Antonio, after which the duchy passed through the Spanish Bourbons and briefly the Austrian Habsburgs, before continuing under Bourbon rule until its absorption into unified Italy in 1859.","republic of geneva":"The Republic of Geneva was an independent Calvinist city-republic centred on the city of Geneva at the western end of Lake Geneva, which emerged in the 1530s and 1540s after the city cast off the temporal authority of its prince-bishop and the House of Savoy and embraced the Protestant Reformation. It had no monarch and was governed by a tiered system of councils—the four annually elected Syndics, the executive Small Council of twenty-five, the Council of Two Hundred, and the sovereign General Council of enfranchised citizens—which produced an increasingly oligarchic patrician regime. Under the influence of Guillaume Farel and especially John Calvin, whose Ecclesiastical Ordinances of 1541 shaped its institutions, it became a leading centre of Reformed Protestantism and a haven for religious refugees, earning the epithet \"the Protestant Rome.\" Allied to the Swiss cantons of Zürich and Bern, it remained an associate rather than a full member of the Old Swiss Confederacy, and its independence was effectively secured by the failed Savoyard assault of the Escalade in 1602 and the ensuing Treaty of Saint-Julien. The Republic endured, punctuated by recurrent constitutional struggles between patricians and disenfranchised citizens, until it was annexed by revolutionary France in 1798.","medici grand duchy of tuscany":"The Medici Grand Duchy of Tuscany was an Italian sovereign state created on 27 August 1569, when Pope Pius V elevated Cosimo I de' Medici of Florence to the newly minted rank of Grand Duke, uniting Florence, Siena, Pisa, and the port of Livorno under a single absolutist monarchy. Governed from Florence by successive Medici grand dukes with the help of a ceremonial senate, the state combined dynastic autocracy with lavish patronage of the arts, sciences, and the free port of Livorno. Its earlier grand dukes, notably Ferdinando I, fostered commerce and learning, but under the long reign of Cosimo III the Grand Duchy sank into economic stagnation, oppressive taxation, and rigid religious conservatism. With no male heir surviving Cosimo III's children, the senior Medici line neared extinction throughout the early eighteenth century. The dynasty's grand-ducal line ended with the death of Gian Gastone de' Medici in 1737, after which the throne passed by prior agreement of the European powers to Francis Stephen of Habsburg-Lorraine.","mughal empire":"The Mughal Empire, whose rulers styled their realm Hindustan, was a Persianate empire that dominated most of the Indian subcontinent, founded in 1526 when Babur, a Central Asian prince of Timurid and Chinggisid descent, defeated the Delhi Sultanate at the First Battle of Panipat. It was a centralized monarchy governed through a mansabdari ranking system and an elaborate revenue bureaucracy, blending Turco-Mongol, Persian, and Indian traditions into a distinctive court culture. Its most celebrated rulers included Akbar, who consolidated the state and pursued religious accommodation, Shah Jahan, under whom Mughal architecture such as the Taj Mahal reached its zenith, and Aurangzeb, under whom the empire attained its greatest territorial extent. After Aurangzeb's death in 1707 the empire fragmented amid succession struggles, Maratha expansion, provincial breakaways, and Persian and Afghan invasions, leaving later emperors as increasingly nominal figures. It was formally abolished in 1857–1858, when the British East India Company deposed and exiled the last emperor, Bahadur Shah II, following the Indian Rebellion of 1857.","safavid empire":"The Safavid Empire, whose rulers styled their realm the Guarded Domains of Iran, was a Persian dynastic state founded in 1501 by Shah Ismail I, who proclaimed himself shahanshah at Tabriz and established Twelver Shia Islam as the official religion, an act that gave Iran a lasting religious identity distinct from its Sunni neighbours. It was an absolute monarchy in which the shah was regarded as both temporal sovereign and spiritual guide, governing through a grand vizier, a council of state, and a military elite drawn originally from the Turkic Qizilbash tribes. The empire reached its height under Shah Abbas I, who reorganised the army with a ghulam corps, moved the capital to Isfahan, and turned it into one of the great cities of the age. After Abbas I the dynasty entered a long decline marked by harem-reared rulers, growing clerical influence, and neglect of the frontiers. It was effectively destroyed by the Hotaki Afghan conquest of Isfahan in 1722, and after a period of puppet claimants the line was formally extinguished when Nader Shah seized the throne in 1736.","đại việt":"Đại Việt (\"Great Viet\") under the Later Lê dynasty was the Vietnamese realm founded in 1428 when Lê Lợi expelled the Ming occupiers and took the throne, restoring native rule. It was a Confucian monarchy governed through a mandarin bureaucracy and the Hồng Đức law code, reaching its cultural and territorial height under Emperor Lê Thánh Tông in the late fifteenth century. After the usurping Mạc dynasty and the Lê restoration of 1533, the emperors became figureheads while real power passed to two rival warlord houses — the Trịnh lords in the north and the Nguyễn lords in the south — who ruled in the emperor's name and divided the country at the Gianh River. Through this era the realm steadily expanded southward, absorbing the remnants of Champa and pushing into the Mekong Delta. The Lê line endured until the Tây Sơn uprising swept it away in the late eighteenth century, formally ending in 1789.","ayutthaya kingdom":"The Ayutthaya Kingdom was a Siamese (Thai) kingdom centered on the city of Ayutthaya on the Chao Phraya river, traditionally founded by King Uthong (Ramathibodi I) in 1351. It was an absolute monarchy organized under the Chatusadom or \"Four Pillars\" administration and a hierarchical sakdina system, and it grew into one of Southeast Asia's dominant powers and a cosmopolitan international trade emporium. Ruled successively by several dynasties—the Uthong, Suphannaphum, Sukhothai, Prasat Thong, and finally the Ban Phlu Luang houses—it produced notable monarchs such as Borommatrailokkanat, who codified its administration, and Naresuan, who secured its independence from Burma. The seventeenth century is often regarded as its golden age, when Siamese trade and diplomacy reached as far as Persia and the courts of Europe. After more than four centuries the kingdom was destroyed by a Burmese Konbaung invasion, its capital sacked and burned in April 1767.","kingdom of lan xang":"The Kingdom of Lan Xang, whose full ceremonial name Lan Xang Hom Khao means \"the Land of a Million Elephants and the White Parasol,\" was the first unified Lao kingdom, founded in 1353 by Fa Ngum after he consolidated the Mekong valley principalities with Khmer backing. It was a Theravada Buddhist mandala state ruled by a hereditary monarchy in which royal authority radiated outward over semi-autonomous provincial lords rather than through fixed administrative borders. Its capital lay first at Muang Sua (Luang Prabang) before King Setthathirath moved it to Vientiane in 1560, and its most celebrated ruler was Sourigna Vongsa, under whose long seventeenth-century reign the kingdom reached a peak of stability, prosperity, and cultural flowering. Throughout its existence Lan Xang balanced pressures from powerful neighbours including Ayutthaya, Burma, Đại Việt, and China while cultivating a distinctive Lao literary, artistic, and religious tradition. Weakened by a bitter succession dispute after Sourigna Vongsa's death, the kingdom fractured in 1707 into the rival kingdoms of Vientiane and Luang Prabang, followed by Champasak in 1713, ending Lao political unity for centuries.","toungoo dynasty":"The Toungoo dynasty in its later phase, known as the Restored Toungoo or Nyaungyan dynasty, was the ruling house of a reconstituted Burmese kingdom founded in 1599 by Nyaungyan Min after the collapse of the sprawling First Toungoo Empire. Rather than restore the overextended conquest state of Bayinnaung, its kings built a more compact and durable realm centred on the Irrawaddy valley, ruling ultimately from Ava (Inwa) and pioneering an administrative system of centralized provincial control and manpower registration that later Burmese dynasties would inherit. Anaukpetlun reunited the core territories and repelled Portuguese encroachment in the early seventeenth century, while Thalun consolidated the reforms and conducted systematic censuses. Over the later seventeenth and early eighteenth centuries the dynasty settled into a long period of \"palace rule,\" marked by weak kings, court factionalism, and gradually eroding authority over frontier and peripheral regions. It ultimately fell in 1752 when the forces of the Mon Restored Hanthawaddy Kingdom captured Ava, ending the Toungoo line.","kingdom of mrauk u":"The Kingdom of Mrauk U was a coastal Arakanese kingdom founded around 1429–1430 by Min Saw Mon, who established a new capital at Mrauk U after a period of exile in Bengal. It was a Theravada Buddhist feudal monarchy that was also notably multiethnic and religiously plural, drawing in Muslim, Hindu, and Portuguese communities and blending Burmese and Bengal-Islamic influences in its court, coinage, and administration. Under rulers such as Min Bin and Min Razagyi it grew into a formidable maritime and trading power, dominating the eastern Bay of Bengal, controlling Chittagong, and profiting from seaborne commerce and slave-raiding conducted partly by allied Portuguese mercenaries. From the mid-seventeenth century the kingdom entered a long decline marked by economic contraction, chronic succession violence, and the loss of its Bengal territories to the Mughals. It survived in weakened form into the eighteenth century before being conquered and annexed by the Konbaung dynasty of Burma under King Bodawpaya in 1784–1785.","lan na":"Lan Na, meaning \"kingdom of a million rice fields,\" was a Tai Yuan kingdom of the northern highlands centred on Chiang Mai, founded by King Mangrai in 1292 and expanded when he built Chiang Mai as its capital in 1296. It was governed as a mandala-style Buddhist kingdom whose monarchs, drawn chiefly from the Mangrai dynasty, ruled a network of tributary muang cities and fostered a distinctive Theravada culture, art, and script. Under rulers such as Mangrai and the fifteenth-century King Tilokaraj it reached its cultural and territorial height, becoming a major centre of Buddhist scholarship. Its independence ended in 1558 when the Burmese king Bayinnaung of the Toungoo dynasty captured Chiang Mai and reduced Lan Na to a vassal, after which it was ruled for roughly two centuries by Burmese-appointed or Burmese-descended kings. Weakened by warfare, forced relocations, and fragmentation, Lan Na finally passed out of Burmese control when Siamese and local Tai Yuan forces took Chiang Mai in 1774–1775 and it was absorbed into the Siamese orbit.","shan states":"The Shan States were a patchwork of small Tai (Shan) principalities, each called a möng and ruled by a hereditary prince bearing the title saopha (sawbwa), spread across the uplands east of the Irrawaddy River in what is now eastern Myanmar. The earliest of these states appeared in the thirteenth century, with Möng Kawng traditionally dated to 1215 and Möng Nai to 1223, and the strongest of them—including Möng Mao, Möng Yang, and Hsenwi—briefly dominated Upper Burma before being conquered by the Toungoo king Bayinnaung in 1557. Thereafter the saophas acknowledged the suzerainty of the Burmese kingdoms of the Irrawaddy valley, and often of China in the north, while retaining a large degree of internal self-government, so that the states never formed a single unified polity or possessed a common capital. The many principalities—numbering as many as forty—varied greatly in size and repeatedly shifted their tributary allegiance among Burma, China, and later Siam depending on which power was ascendant. Under British rule they became protected states and were organised as the Federated Shan States in 1922, before being absorbed into the Shan State of independent Burma in 1948 and having their hereditary saopha rulers finally stripped of power in the years around 1959–1962.","tibet":"Tibet in this period was governed by the Ganden Phodrang, the Buddhist theocracy established in 1642 when the Oirat lord Güshi Khan of the Khoshut Mongols conferred spiritual and temporal authority over the Tibetan heartland upon the Fifth Dalai Lama, Ngawang Lobsang Gyatso. Named for the Dalai Lama's residence at Drepung Monastery and seated at Lhasa in the newly built Potala Palace, it fused religious and secular rule under the Dalai Lama, with day-to-day administration often exercised by a regent, the desi, while a Khoshut khan stood as external military patron. The Great Fifth unified central Tibet under the Gelug school after defeating the Tsangpa rulers and rival sects, and his regent Sangye Gyatso consolidated the state and concealed the Fifth's death for over a decade. This Khoshut-backed order grew fragile as Mongol patrons and the regency clashed, culminating in the killing of Sangye Gyatso in 1705 and the deposition of the Sixth Dalai Lama in 1706. It effectively ended when the Dzungar invasion of 1717 destroyed Khoshut power in Lhasa and a Qing expedition in 1720 expelled the Dzungars and brought Tibet under Manchu overlordship.","dutch ceylon":"Dutch Ceylon was the governorate of the coastal maritime provinces of the island of Ceylon administered by the Dutch East India Company (Vereenigde Oostindische Compagnie, VOC), established in 1640 when Company forces captured the Portuguese fort at Galle. Allied at first with the inland Kingdom of Kandy against the Portuguese, the Dutch went on to seize Colombo in 1656 and Jaffna in 1658, expelling the Portuguese and taking control of the lucrative lowlands. It was governed by a Company-appointed Governor seated first at Galle and then at Colombo, assisted by a council, with the territory divided into the commanderies of Colombo, Galle, and Jaffna, and its economy built on a strict monopoly of the island's prized cinnamon. Governors such as Rijcklof van Goens and Gerrit de Heere shaped its administration, while the VOC never subdued the independent, mountainous Kingdom of Kandy in the interior, with which it alternated between uneasy cooperation and open conflict. Dutch Ceylon endured until 1796, when the Company's possessions were surrendered to Britain during the French Revolutionary Wars, passing the maritime provinces into British hands.","dutch east india company":"The Dutch East India Company, formally the Vereenigde Oost-Indische Compagnie (VOC), was a chartered joint-stock trading company established in 1602 by the States General of the Dutch Republic through the amalgamation of earlier rival merchant ventures. Its charter granted it a monopoly on Dutch trade east of the Cape of Good Hope along with quasi-sovereign powers to wage war, build fortresses, coin money, and conclude treaties with Asian rulers, governed by a board of directors known as the Heeren XVII (Lords Seventeen). Ruled in Asia by a Governor-General and Council seated at Batavia from 1619, it built a maritime commercial empire centred on the spice trade of the Moluccas and Banda while extending to Ceylon, the Cape of Good Hope, India, and Japan. It grew into one of the wealthiest and most powerful commercial enterprises of the early modern world, paying substantial dividends for much of the seventeenth century before entering a long decline driven by falling spice margins, corruption, warfare, and mounting debt. Burdened by insolvency, the company was formally dissolved in 1799 and its possessions and liabilities were assumed by the Dutch state.","kingdom of middag":"The Kingdom of Middag, also called the Kingdom of Dadu or the Tatuturo Confederation, was a supra-tribal alliance of Taiwanese indigenous villages on the central-western plains of Formosa, founded by the Papora people together with allied Babuza, Pazeh, and Hoanya communities. It functioned as a loose confederation of up to twenty-seven villages headed by a paramount leader known in Hoklo as Quata Ong and to the Dutch as the \"Keizer van Middag,\" with succession and real authority shaped by a matrilineal social order. Its best-documented ruler was Kamachat Aslamie, who resisted and then reached accommodation with the Dutch East India Company, succeeded by his nephew Kamachat Maloe. The confederation retained semi-autonomy through the Dutch and Zheng (Tungning) periods, fiercely resisting Koxinga's forces, before Han Chinese immigration and Qing labor demands steadily eroded its cohesion. It collapsed after the indigenous uprising of 1731–1732 was crushed by Qing troops, after which its supra-tribal leadership ceased to exist and survivors assimilated or migrated inland toward Puli.","khanate of khiva":"The Khanate of Khiva was an Uzbek monarchy in the Khwarazm oasis along the lower Amu Darya, south of the Aral Sea, founded in 1511 when the Shibanid prince Ilbars expelled the Persian garrison and established the Arabshahid (Yadigarid) dynasty. Its rulers, styled khan, claimed descent from Genghis Khan through the house of Shiban, and its capital shifted from Urgench to the city of Khiva around 1600 after drought and the shifting river channel; locals called their state the vilayet of Khwarazm. It was a caravan-trade and irrigated-agriculture polity notorious for slave-raiding, seizing Persians, Russians, and others for the Central Asian slave markets, and it was frequently at war with the neighbouring Khanate of Bukhara and with Turkmen and Kazakh nomads. Central authority was chronically weak, with real power passing over time to hereditary tribal inaks, especially of the Qungrat clan, who installed puppet khans until the Qungrat dynasty took the throne outright under Iltuzar Khan in 1804. Reduced to a Russian protectorate after the campaign of 1873, the Khanate of Khiva was finally abolished in February 1920 and replaced by the Khorezm People's Soviet Republic.","kazakh khanate":"The Kazakh Khanate was a nomadic Turkic state on the Eurasian steppe, founded around 1465 when the sultans Kerei (Girei) and Janibek led a breakaway of nomadic followers from the Abu'l-Khayr (Uzbek) Khanate into the Zhetysu region of Moghulistan. Ruled by khans of the Chinggisid Jochid line and organized around a pastoral, clan-based society, it reached its greatest early extent under Kasym Khan in the early sixteenth century and was later codified politically under Tauke Khan, whose \"Jeti Zhargy\" (Seven Charters) framed its customary law. By the seventeenth century the khanate was loosely divided into three zhuz (hordes) — the Senior, Middle, and Junior — each a confederation of tribes governed largely through councils of biys and sultans. From the eighteenth century it was progressively weakened by Dzungar invasions and then absorbed into the Russian Empire, which abolished the khan's office in the Middle and Junior zhuz in the 1820s. The Kazakh Khanate is generally regarded as ending in 1847 with the death of Kenesary Khan, whose 1837–1847 revolt was the last attempt to restore a unified Kazakh khanship.","imamate of oman":"The Imamate of Oman under the Ya'rubid (Ya'ariba) dynasty was an Ibadi Muslim state founded in 1624 when Nasir bin Murshid was elected imam, uniting Oman's fractious interior tribes and coastal ports under a single elected religious-political leader. Governed as an elective imamate rooted in the Ibadi branch of Islam, its imams exercised supreme religious and secular authority and appointed walis to administer key forts and trade hubs such as Muscat, Sohar, Rustaq, and Nizwa. The dynasty expelled the Portuguese from the Omani coast and grew into a formidable Indian Ocean naval power, seizing East African ports including Mombasa, Zanzibar, Pemba, and Kilwa, with Saif bin Sultan remembered as its most powerful and prosperous ruler. Over time the imamate's succession drifted from purely elective toward hereditary practice, sowing dynastic rivalry among the Ya'rubid family. After Saif bin Sultan's death in 1711 a prolonged succession dispute and civil war, compounded by Persian invasions, broke the dynasty, and by 1744 Ahmad bin Said al-Busaidi founded the Al Bu Said dynasty that supplanted it.","kingdom of benin":"The Kingdom of Benin was a West African state of the Edo (Bini) people, founded around 1180 when the Oba monarchy of the Eweka dynasty replaced the earlier Ogiso rulers, traditionally linked to the Yoruba prince Oranmiyan of Ile-Ife. It was governed by a sacred, largely secluded divine king, the Oba, ruling from the walled Benin City in concert with title-holding chiefs including the Uzama nobles and the Iyoba, or queen mother. The kingdom reached its height under warrior-kings such as Ewuare the Great in the fifteenth century and Esigie in the sixteenth, becoming renowned for its monumental earthworks and its guild-produced brass, bronze, and ivory court art. From the late sixteenth century onward it gradually contracted and suffered recurring succession disputes and civil wars among powerful chiefs, though the Oba dynasty endured. The independent kingdom ended in 1897 when a British punitive expedition sacked and burned Benin City, exiled the reigning Oba, and absorbed the territory into colonial Nigeria.","sakalava kingdoms":"The Sakalava kingdoms were a group of related states ruled by the Maroserana (Maroseraña) dynasty that dominated western and northern Madagascar, emerging around 1600 from a princely line based in the Fiherenana region near present-day Toliara. Under Andriandahifotsy, the polity expanded northward across the Mangoky River in the seventeenth century before splitting, after succession disputes, into a southern kingdom, Menabe, and a northern kingdom, Boina (Iboina). The kingdoms were pastoral cattle-herding states whose rulers held a quasi-divine sovereign status, governed through royal ancestor cults, and grew wealthy by monopolising the Indian Ocean trade in enslaved people and firearms; they maintained no single fixed capital but ruled from a succession of royal towns such as Mahabo, Morondava, Bengy, and Marovoay. Notable rulers included the founder-figures Andriandahifotsy and Andriamandisoarivo and the powerful Boina king Toakafo, and the Sakalava reached their greatest territorial extent in the mid-eighteenth century. Their independence was eroded in the nineteenth century by the conquering Merina kingdom under Radama I and Ranavalona I, and was finally extinguished by French colonial conquest, which subdued the region by the close of the century.","portuguese mozambique":"Portuguese Mozambique was the Portuguese colonial presence on the southeastern coast of Africa, established from 1505 and organized initially as the Captaincy of Sofala under the Estado da Índia governed from Goa. It was not a consolidated colony but a string of fortified coastal trading stations, captaincies, and inland prazo estates strung along the Zambezi valley, its administrative and mercantile heart being the fortified Island of Mozambique. Governance combined royally appointed captains and castellans with a settler and Luso-African landholding elite, whose prazo grants were held for three generations through the female line and defended by slave armies known as Chikunda. The colony gained autonomy from Goa in 1752 as a separate captaincy-general and expanded its effective control inland only in the nineteenth century after suppressing the prazo lords and warlord states. It endured as Portugal's East African territory until Mozambican independence on 25 June 1975, following the Carnation Revolution in Portugal.","new france":"New France (French: Nouvelle-France) was the area colonized by France in North America, beginning with Jacques Cartier's exploration of the Gulf of Saint Lawrence in 1534 and the founding of a permanent settlement at Quebec by Samuel de Champlain in 1608. At its height it comprised five colonies—Canada, Acadia, Hudson Bay, Terre-Neuve (Newfoundland), and Louisiana—administered as a royal viceroyalty centred on Quebec and governed by a governor general and an intendant answering to the French crown. Its economy rested overwhelmingly on the fur trade, sustained by extensive alliances with First Nations peoples, sparse habitant settlement along the Saint Lawrence, and Catholic missionary activity. Figures such as Champlain, Jean Talon, and Louis de Buade de Frontenac shaped its expansion, while explorers pushed French claims through the Great Lakes and down the Mississippi to the Gulf of Mexico. New France ended when France ceded its territories to Great Britain and Spain under the Treaty of Paris in 1763, following defeat in the Seven Years' War.","state of brazil":"The State of Brazil (Portuguese: Estado do Brasil) was Portugal's principal colonial administration in South America, established in 1549 when Tomé de Sousa arrived as the first Governor-General and founded Salvador da Bahia as its capital, replacing the earlier system of hereditary captaincies with centralized royal government. It was headed by a Governor-General (later styled Viceroy) representing the Portuguese Crown, ruling through captaincy governors, municipal councils, and a colonial economy built on Atlantic sugar plantations and enslaved African labor, later joined by gold and diamond mining. Under it the colony expanded far beyond the Tordesillas line through bandeirante expeditions, Jesuit missions, and cattle frontiers, and it endured a Dutch occupation of its northeast between 1630 and 1654. The eighteenth-century gold and diamond booms shifted the colony's center of gravity southward, prompting the transfer of the capital from Salvador to Rio de Janeiro in 1763. The State of Brazil ceased to exist as a colony in 1815, when Brazil was elevated to a kingdom co-equal with Portugal within the United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves, a step that preceded its full independence in 1822.","province of new york":"The Province of New York was an English (later British) colony on the northeastern coast of North America, created in 1664 when an English expedition seized the Dutch colony of New Netherland and its capital New Amsterdam, both renamed for James, Duke of York, to whom Charles II had granted the territory. Initially a proprietary domain of the Duke, it became a royal province when he ascended the throne as James II in 1685, thereafter governed by a Crown-appointed governor advised by a council and, from 1683, an elected representative assembly. Centered on New York City at the mouth of the Hudson River and extending up the Hudson and Mohawk valleys toward the Great Lakes and the frontier with New France, it was an ethnically and religiously diverse commercial colony inheriting a substantial Dutch population alongside English, Huguenot, African, and other settlers. Its history included the turbulence of Leisler's Rebellion, sustained conflict and diplomacy with the Iroquois Confederacy, and the rise of powerful landholding and merchant families. The province endured until the American Revolution, when its Provincial Congress declared independence in 1776 and adopted a state constitution in 1777, transforming it into the State of New York.","province of massachusetts bay":"The Province of Massachusetts Bay was an English (later British) royal colony in New England, established under a charter granted by King William III and Queen Mary II on October 7, 1691, that took effect in 1692. Its charter merged the older Puritan-founded Massachusetts Bay Colony with Plymouth Colony, the Province of Maine, and other territories, and replaced the previous self-governing regime with a crown-appointed governor holding veto power, balanced by an elected assembly. The province was governed from Boston and retained a strongly Puritan and Congregationalist character, though the new charter broadened voting rights beyond church membership; its early years were marked by the Salem witch trials of 1692 and repeated frontier wars against the French and their Indigenous allies. Notable governors included Sir William Phips, Joseph Dudley, William Shirley, and the last royal governor, Thomas Gage, and over the eighteenth century the province grew into a center of commerce, shipbuilding, and political dissent. Escalating disputes with Parliament over taxation culminated in the Boston Tea Party and the Revolutionary War, and the province declared independence in 1776, reconstituting itself as the Commonwealth of Massachusetts under its 1780 constitution.","colony of virginia":"The Colony of Virginia was the first permanent English colony in North America, founded at Jamestown in 1607 by the Virginia Company of London under a royal charter from King James I. After the company's charter was revoked in 1624 it became a crown colony governed by a royally appointed governor, an advisory Council, and the House of Burgesses, the first elected legislative assembly in English America, which had met since 1619. Its economy rested on tobacco cultivation and evolved into a plantation society increasingly dependent on enslaved African labor, producing a landed gentry that dominated colonial politics. Notable episodes included the Powhatan wars, Bacon's Rebellion of 1676, and the relocation of the capital from Jamestown to Williamsburg in 1699. The colony was the largest and most populous of Britain's mainland possessions, and its colonial existence ended in 1776 when Virginia declared independence and reconstituted itself as the Commonwealth of Virginia.","province of carolina":"The Province of Carolina was an English (later British) proprietary colony in North America, chartered by King Charles II in 1663 and enlarged by a second charter in 1665, granting eight Lords Proprietors both the soil and sweeping powers of government. It was administered as a single province with its seat at Charles Town, guided in principle by the Fundamental Constitutions of Carolina drafted with input from John Locke, though in practice governed by an appointed governor, a proprietary council, and an elected assembly. Its society was shaped by planter migration from Barbados, a plantation economy built on rice and enslaved labor, and an extensive trade in deerskins and enslaved Native Americans that drove expansion inland from Charles Town. Persistent friction between proprietary authority and colonists, together with sectional differences between the northern Albemarle settlements and the southern lowcountry, weakened proprietary rule over time. The province was divided into separate North Carolina and South Carolina administrations in 1712 and ceased to exist when seven of the proprietors sold their interests to the Crown in 1729, making both colonies royal provinces.","spanish florida":"Spanish Florida (La Florida) was the Spanish colonial province in the southeastern part of North America, established with the founding of St. Augustine in 1565 by the adelantado Pedro Menéndez de Avilés and claimed under Spain's earlier discovery of the peninsula in 1513. Governed as a presidio colony by a royal governor and administratively tied to the Captaincy General of Cuba within the Viceroyalty of New Spain, it was defended by a garrison at St. Augustine and evangelized through an extensive network of Franciscan missions reaching into present-day Georgia. Its most enduring feature was the coquina-stone fortress Castillo de San Marcos, whose core was completed in 1695, and its character was that of a thinly populated military and missionary frontier rather than a settler colony. Over the seventeenth century it prospered moderately, but from the early eighteenth century English and allied Native raids destroyed the missions and ranches, reducing effective control to little more than St. Augustine and later Pensacola. This first Spanish period ended in 1763, when Spain ceded Florida to Great Britain under the Treaty of Paris that concluded the Seven Years' War.","spanish cuba":"Spanish Cuba was the Spanish colonial possession of the island of Cuba, governed first as the Governorate of Cuba founded in 1511 by Diego Velázquez de Cuéllar and elevated in 1607 into the Captaincy General of Cuba under a governor who also held the office of captain general. Seated at Havana, its captain general wielded combined civil, military, and judicial authority, though appeals long ran to the Audiencia of Santo Domingo. The colony's defining role was strategic and maritime: Havana's fortified harbour served as the assembly and departure point for the treasure fleets carrying American silver to Spain, making the island the guardian of the Caribbean sea lanes. For much of its existence trade was tightly restricted under Spanish mercantilist law, but the eighteenth-century expansion of sugar and slavery transformed Cuba into one of Spain's wealthiest colonies. Spanish rule ended in 1898 when, after the Spanish–American War, the Treaty of Paris ceded control of the island and Spain relinquished sovereignty.","spanish santo domingo":"Spanish Santo Domingo, formally the Captaincy General of Santo Domingo under the Real Audiencia of Santo Domingo, was the first European colony and captaincy general established by Spain in the Americas, founded on the eastern portion of the island of Hispaniola after Christopher Columbus's arrival. Governed by an audiencia president who simultaneously held the offices of governor and captain general, it served in the early sixteenth century as the springboard for Spanish conquest and administration across the Caribbean and neighboring mainland coasts. After its initial boom under figures such as Columbus and Nicolás de Ovando, the colony declined sharply as Spanish attention shifted to the wealthier mainland viceroyalties, leaving it impoverished and dependent on cattle ranching and contraband trade. Its western third was ceded to France as Saint-Domingue by the Treaty of Ryswick in 1697, and the whole colony was surrendered to France under the Treaty of Basel in 1795, though Spain later recovered the eastern part. The captaincy's long colonial existence set the foundations for the later Dominican Republic before Spanish rule on the island definitively ended in the nineteenth century.","dutch surinam":"Dutch Surinam was a Dutch plantation colony on the north-eastern coast of South America, seized from the English by a Zeeland expedition in 1667 and confirmed as a Dutch possession by the Treaty of Breda that same year. From 1683 it was administered by the chartered Society of Suriname (Sociëteit van Suriname), a private company jointly owned in equal shares by the city of Amsterdam, the Dutch West India Company, and the Van Aerssen van Sommelsdijck family, with a governor seated at Paramaribo advised by colonial councils of planters. Its economy rested on export agriculture worked by enslaved Africans, producing sugar, cotton, and indigo and later becoming a leading coffee producer, under one of the harshest slave regimes in the Americas. The brutality of plantation life drove continual flight into the interior, giving rise to the Maroon communities whose raids and later treaties shaped the colony's history throughout the eighteenth century. The Society was nationalised by the Batavian Republic in 1795, after which Surinam passed through periods of British occupation before reverting to Dutch rule, remaining a colony until it became a constituent country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands in 1954.","essequibo":"Essequibo was a Dutch plantation colony on the Essequibo River in the Guianas, founded in 1616 by Zeelanders under Joost van der Hooge who built Fort Kyk-Over-Al as its administrative seat. From 1621 it was governed by the Dutch West India Company, falling under the Zeelandic Chamber and later the \"Direction\" of the Walcheren cities Middelburg, Veere and Vlissingen, with a resident commander (commandeur) heading the colony. Its economy rested on plantation agriculture worked by enslaved Africans, producing tobacco, annatto, indigo, cacao and cotton, and increasingly sugar as cultivation spread from the upper river toward the fertile coastal lowlands. Passing from Company to Dutch state control in 1792, the Colony of Essequibo was repeatedly occupied by Britain from 1796 and was formally ceded to the United Kingdom in the 1814 Anglo-Dutch settlement. It was thereafter administered with neighbouring Demerara and Berbice and merged into British Guiana in 1831.","french guiana":"French Guiana (French: Guyane), officially the colony of Cayenne, was a French plantation colony on the northeastern coast of South America, founded as a durable settlement in 1664 when the French permanently established Cayenne under the auspices of Jean-Baptiste Colbert's French West India Company. Initially a chartered-company venture, it passed to direct royal administration in 1674 and was governed by a crown-appointed governor seated at Cayenne. Persistently small and beset by tropical disease, Amerindian resistance, and repeated changes of hands with the Dutch and English, it developed an export economy of sugar, indigo, hardwood, and Cayenne pepper worked by enslaved Africans. Later French schemes to populate it, most infamously the disastrous 1763 Kourou expedition, largely failed, and from the 19th century it became notorious as a penal colony housing the bagne of Devil's Island. The territory has remained under French sovereignty into the modern era, becoming an overseas department of France in 1946 and continuing as such to the present day."});

/* 1700-era descriptions for ethnographic groupings + small/dashed clickable entities. */
Object.assign(window.COUNTRY_INFO, {"ainu":"The Ainu were the indigenous hunter-gatherer, fisher, and trader people of \"Ainu Mosir,\" a homeland spanning Hokkaido (which the Japanese called Ezo), Sakhalin, the Kuril Islands, and formerly northern Honshū. Descended from the Jōmon and Satsumon peoples, a distinct Ainu culture is generally recognized from around the thirteenth century, and the society was never a centralized state but a network of autonomous villages called kotan, each led by a local headman and bound by kinship, trade, and a rich oral and spiritual tradition. Lacking any single ruler or capital, the Ainu were periodically drawn together in resistance, most famously under the chief Shakushain, whose 1669 revolt briefly united some nineteen groups against Japanese encroachment before being crushed. From the seventeenth century onward the Matsumae domain and later the Tokugawa shogunate steadily eroded Ainu autonomy through a monopolistic trading-post system that impoverished and subjugated them. Their independent existence effectively ended with the Meiji government's annexation and colonization of Hokkaido after 1869, culminating in assimilation policies such as the 1899 Former Aborigines Protection Act.","akan states":"The Akan states were a cluster of related Akan-speaking polities of the Gold Coast forest and its coastal fringe, in the territory of present-day Ghana and eastern Côte d'Ivoire, including Bono, Denkyira, Akwamu, Akyem, Fante, and the rising Asante (Ashanti). Their wealth and political power rested on control of gold deposits and the trans-Saharan and Atlantic trade in gold, kola, and later enslaved people and firearms. They were typically organized around a paramount chief or king seated on a sacred stool, ruling through lineage-based councils, with the earliest, Bonoman, developing as a state by the fourteenth to fifteenth centuries and later states such as Denkyira, Akwamu, and Asante emerging as militarized gold empires. Notable rulers and figures include Osei Tutu and the priest Okomfo Anokye, who forged the Asante union symbolized by the Golden Stool, and successive Denkyirahene and Akwamuhene who dominated the seventeenth-century interior. Over the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries Asante absorbed or overshadowed most rival Akan states, and the region ultimately came under British colonial rule before being incorporated into independent Ghana in 1957.","amazon hunter-gatherers":"The \"Amazon hunter-gatherers\" is a collective map label for the many hundreds of distinct, autonomous Indigenous peoples of the Amazon basin, who never formed a single state, dynasty, or unified polity. Most combined shifting slash-and-burn horticulture of crops such as manioc and maize with hunting, fishing, and foraging, while some groups relied more heavily on wild resources, all organized in small, largely egalitarian villages led by consensus or influential headmen rather than kings. These societies were extraordinarily diverse in language and culture, ranging from riverine peoples of the várzea floodplains to interfluvial forest dwellers, and archaeological evidence shows that pre-Columbian Amazonia had once supported far larger and more complex settlements than survived into the colonial era. From the sixteenth century onward they were devastated by introduced epidemics, colonial slave raiding, and missionary \"reductions\" that resettled and reorganized survivors. Their long trajectory of autonomy was steadily eroded by Portuguese and Spanish expansion, later rubber-boom exploitation, and modern frontier development, though many peoples and some uncontacted groups persist across the basin today.","andean hunter-gatherers":"\"Andean hunter-gatherers\" is a modern cartographic grouping label, not a unified polity, that stands for the many autonomous indigenous peoples of the eastern Andean slopes and montaña margins who remained outside effective Spanish administration — the peoples the Inca and Spanish lumped together as Antis or Chunchos, including Arawak-speaking Asháninka (Campa) and Machiguenga, along with Piro, Amuesha, and various Panoan and Tacanan groups. These communities never formed a single state, dynasty, or empire; they were dispersed, largely egalitarian societies organized at the level of local kin groups and led by situational headmen rather than any central government or hereditary sovereign. Despite the label, most were not pure foragers but combined swidden (slash-and-burn) horticulture of manioc, maize, and plantains with hunting, fishing, and gathering, though some deeper-lowland groups were more mobile. The Inca claimed the region as their eastern quarter, Antisuyu, but never subdued its forest peoples, and Spanish control likewise remained nominal, advancing only through episodic Franciscan mission frontiers that repeatedly collapsed. The grouping has no bounded lifespan as a state — these peoples possess deep cultural continuity from pre-Columbian times to the present — and their autonomy was decisively reasserted by the Juan Santos Atahualpa rebellion of 1742–1752, after which they stayed independent for the rest of the colonial era.","arctic peoples":"The Arctic peoples of North America — the Inuit (including the Iñupiat), the Yup'ik, and the Aleut (Unangax̂) — are the Indigenous maritime hunting societies of the American Arctic and its coasts, descended from the Thule culture that spread eastward from coastal Alaska after about 1000 CE and had replaced the earlier Dorset population across the Canadian Arctic and Greenland by roughly 1300 CE. They were never a single polity but a mosaic of autonomous, kin-based communities without centralized government, rank, or a ruling class, in which leadership rested informally with respected elders and skilled hunters and food was shared within the household and band. Their subsistence combined the hunting of whales, seals, walrus, and polar bears with caribou, fish, and birds, made possible by highly specialized technology including the kayak, the larger skin umiak, the dog sled, the harpoon, and cold-weather skin clothing. Distinct groups occupied a vast maritime range from the Aleutian Islands and western Alaska across northern Canada to Labrador and Greenland, speaking related Eskimo–Aleut languages while remaining culturally and politically separate from one another. Sustained European and Russian contact from the eighteenth century onward brought trade, disease, and colonial disruption, yet these peoples endured and their descendants remain the Indigenous inhabitants of the circumpolar North today.","australian aboriginal hunter-gatherers":"The Australian aboriginal hunter-gatherers were the Indigenous peoples of the Australian continent, whose ancestors arrived tens of millennia ago and who represent the world's oldest continuous living cultures. They were not a single state but a mosaic of hundreds of autonomous nations and clans speaking many distinct languages, without kings, chiefs, or any centralised government, and with authority resting in elders, kinship, and custodial ties to Country. Their societies combined foraging, hunting, and fishing with active land management such as fire-stick farming, fish traps, and seasonal movement, all framed by the Dreaming, an integrated cosmology of ancestral creation, law, and songlines. Sustaining these ways of life across the whole continent for many thousands of years, they remained wholly independent of any outside power until the late eighteenth century. Their political independence ended with the arrival of the British First Fleet and subsequent colonisation, though the peoples and cultures themselves continue to survive to the present day.","belize":"The Bay Settlement — later formalized as British Honduras and today independent Belize — was an English and Scottish trading foothold on the Bay of Honduras that grew out of buccaneering and the cutting of logwood, a tree yielding a valuable textile dye. Traditionally dated to a landing near Haulover Creek around 1638 (often attributed to the buccaneer Peter Wallace, though this lacks primary documentation), it began as scattered, self-governing communities of \"Baymen\" occupying land that Spain claimed but could not control. For well over a century it possessed no formal colonial government, Britain deliberately withholding administration to avoid provoking Spain, while the settlers regulated themselves through public meetings and, from 1738, elected magistrates whose rules were later codified in Burnaby's Code. Spain expelled the settlers several times between 1717 and 1780 before conceding logwood- and mahogany-cutting rights under the Treaty of Versailles (1783) and Convention of London (1786), after which the settlement consolidated and was declared the Crown Colony of British Honduras in 1862. Renamed Belize in 1973, it attained internal self-government and then full independence in 1981.","delagoa bay":"Delagoa Bay, the estuarine inlet on the southeast African coast now called Maputo Bay, was not a unified polity but a contested maritime trading zone whose shores were held by independent Tsonga-speaking (Tonga/Batonga) chiefdoms. First charted by Portuguese navigators in the early sixteenth century and named after the trader Lourenço Marques, the bay became a recurring anchorage for ivory and, increasingly, enslaved people exchanged between coastal Africans and passing European ships. No European power exercised firm or continuous sovereignty over it for most of its early history; Portuguese trading stations in the Espírito Santo estuary and a short-lived Dutch East India Company factory (Fort Lijdzaamheid, 1721–1730) were repeatedly abandoned to disease, poor returns, and attacks by local rulers. Throughout, practical authority over land and trade access remained with African chiefs such as the Mpfumu lineage, who granted or withdrew trading rights to visiting Portuguese, Dutch, Austrian, English, and other merchants. Only in 1781 did Portugal establish a permanent occupation on the site of modern Maputo, folding the bay definitively into Portuguese Mozambique.","finnmark":"Finnmark, administered in the early modern period as Vardøhus len and from the 1660s as Vardøhus amt, was the far-northern Arctic province of the Denmark–Norway realm, comprising the treeless coast and interior tundra chiefly inhabited by the Sámi. It was governed as a royal administrative district (len, then amt) subordinate to the crown, with the medieval fortress of Vardøhus as its seat of royal authority and the northernmost outpost of the kingdom. Its defining feature was a long-contested frontier: because no fixed boundary had been drawn since the 1326 Treaty of Novgorod, its interior formed a marchland or \"common district\" whose Sámi population was taxed simultaneously by Norway, Sweden, and Russia. The province was marked by an intense wave of witch trials in the seventeenth century and by an aggressive Lutheran missionary campaign against Sámi religion beginning around 1700. The territorial ambiguity was resolved only by the 1751 Strömstad Treaty and its Lapp Codicil, which fixed the Norwegian–Swedish border and assigned Kautokeino and Karasjok to Norway, while the Russian frontier was settled in 1826.","fivizzano":"Fivizzano was a Tuscan vicariate (formerly a captaincy) centered on the walled town of Fivizzano in the Lunigiana, one of the Florentine state's northern exclaves. It passed from a branch of the Malaspina family to the Republic of Florence in March 1477, when the town submitted to Florentine dominion with the backing of Marquis Gabriele II Malaspina of Fosdinovo and in the presence of Lorenzo de' Medici. Under Medici rule it became known as \"the Florence of Lunigiana,\" its fortifications rebuilt by Grand Duke Cosimo I after Charles VIII's 1494–95 invasion, and its central Piazza Medicea adorned with a Baroque fountain donated by Grand Duke Cosimo III in 1683. As a detached enclave surrounded by the Duchy of Massa, Genoese territory, the Estense lands of Modena, and the many small Malaspina marquisates, it was administered as a vicariate within the Florentine district of the Grand Duchy of Tuscany. With the extinction of the Medici and later dynastic and diplomatic rearrangements the Lunigiana holdings were reshuffled, and Tuscany eventually ceded the Vicariate of Fivizzano to the Duchy of Modena, a transfer confirmed by the Treaty of Florence in 1844.","franche-comté":"Franche-Comté, the \"Free County of Burgundy,\" was a historic province that originated as the medieval County of Burgundy, a fief that from the eleventh century belonged to the Holy Roman Empire rather than to the neighbouring Duchy of Burgundy. Its name derived from the imperial immediacy of its counts, and it long retained privileged institutions, notably a provincial Parlement and an assembly of estates that defended its autonomy against outside rulers. Through the Habsburg inheritance it passed in the sixteenth century to the Spanish branch of the dynasty, under whom it remained a self-governing province with Dole as its capital and seat of its Parlement and university. Coveted by France, it was conquered by Louis XIV's armies in 1668 and again decisively in 1674, and was formally ceded to France by the Treaty of Nijmegen in 1678, after which its Parlement, university, and administrative centre were fixed at Besançon. Thereafter Franche-Comté existed as an integral French province until the administrative reorganisation of the Revolution, when it was divided into the départements of Doubs, Jura, and Haute-Saône.","great plains nations":"The \"Great Plains nations\" is a modern collective label for the many independent Indigenous peoples of the North American Great Plains, encompassing nomadic bison-hunting groups such as the Lakota and other Sioux, Comanche, Cheyenne, Arapaho, Crow, Kiowa, and Blackfoot, alongside semi-sedentary village farmers such as the Pawnee, Mandan, Hidatsa, Arikara, Osage, and Wichita. It was never a single state, dynasty, or confederation but a mosaic of autonomous nations with distinct languages, territories, and rivalries, governed at the band and tribal level through councils, chiefs, and kinship-based organization rather than any central authority. Its defining feature was the horse, which spread north from Spanish New Mexico after the seventeenth century and transformed several peoples into highly mobile, tipi-dwelling mounted bison-hunting cultures whose classic form was established by the 1770s. Prominent later figures and forces include Comanche dominance of the southern plains, Lakota expansion under leaders like Red Cloud and Sitting Bull, and the militarized raiding-and-trading economies that peaked in the early nineteenth century. The way of life collapsed in the late nineteenth century as United States expansion, epidemic disease, and the deliberate destruction of the bison herds forced the nations onto reservations, a process symbolized by the Wounded Knee Massacre of 1890.","guanches":"The Guanches were the indigenous Berber people of the Canary Islands, descended from North African mainland populations who reached the archipelago around the first millennium BCE. They were not a unified state but a set of island societies: Tenerife alone was divided into nine kingdoms, or menceyatos, each ruled by a mencey such as Bencomo of Taoro, while Gran Canaria was led by guanartemes and other islands had their own chiefs and councils known as tagoror. Living in a Neolithic-level pastoral and agricultural economy, the Guanches were noted for cave dwellings, mummification of the dead, a whistled communication tradition, and worship of supreme beings such as Achamán. Their independence was progressively destroyed by the Castilian conquest of the Canary Islands, waged from 1402 to 1496, in which superior steel weapons, cavalry, and introduced epidemic diseases overcame fierce resistance like the victory at the First Battle of Acentejo. After 1496 the surviving Guanches were enslaved, killed, or assimilated into Spanish colonial society, and their language and distinct identity faded away during the seventeenth century.","hadramaut":"Hadramaut (Ḥaḍramawt) was a region of the southern Arabian coast and its inland wadis, in what is now eastern Yemen, that for much of its history was not a single unified state but a patchwork of local sultanates, tribal domains, and religious authorities. Its most prominent political power was the Kathiri Sultanate, founded around 1395 by Badr Abu Tuwairaq (Badr bin al-Habrali Bu Tuwairik) of the Al Kathiri dynasty, which at its 15th- and 16th-century height controlled much of the fertile Wadi Hadramaut and the ports of al-Shihr and al-Mukalla. Governance combined tribal sultans and chiefs with an influential aristocracy of sayyids or sharifs, descendants of the Prophet centered on the scholarly town of Tarim, who wielded great spiritual and social authority alongside the temporal rulers. After the Kathiri zenith the region fragmented, as civil wars drew in the Yafaʿi tribes—who seized western Hadramaut and established a rival base at al-Qatn—while the Kasadi and later the Quʿayti gained ground, reducing Kathiri authority to a shrinking inland core around Seiyun. The first Kathiri state effectively collapsed around 1730, and after a long period of division the sultanate was re-established in the early 19th century before eventually being absorbed, with the rest of Hadramaut, into independent South Yemen in 1967.","hindu kingdoms":"\"Hindu Kingdoms\" is not a single state but a modern catch-all for the Hindu-ruled powers of the Deccan and peninsular India that resisted Mughal domination in the late seventeenth and early eighteenth centuries, above all the Maratha confederacy founded by Chhatrapati Shivaji Bhonsle, who was crowned at Raigad in 1674. The Maratha polity that anchored this bloc was governed by a Chhatrapati advised by the Ashtapradhan council of eight ministers, and it waged a decentralized guerrilla and cavalry war rather than defending fixed frontiers, a mobile character that let it survive repeated Mughal invasions. Alongside the Marathas the label loosely groups the Rajput houses of Rajasthan such as Amber, Marwar, and Mewar, the Telugu-origin Nayaka kingdoms of the far south like Madurai and Thanjavur, and other smaller Hindu chieftaincies, none of which formed a unified realm or shared a government. Notable figures across these powers include Shivaji and his successors Sambhaji and Rajaram, the regent Tarabai, and Rajput rulers who alternately served and resisted the Mughal court. Over the eighteenth century the Maratha confederacy grew into the paramount indigenous power in India before its defeat by the British in 1818, while the Rajput states became princely tributaries and the Nayaka kingdoms were absorbed by the Marathas, the Nawab of Arcot, and ultimately colonial rule.","imamate of aussa":"The Imamate of Aussa was an early-modern Sunni Muslim polity in the lower Awash valley of the Afar (Danakil) lowlands, in what is now eastern Ethiopia and northwestern Djibouti. It was founded in 1577 when Imam Muhammad Gasa (Jasa) moved the seat of the fragmenting Adal Sultanate from Harar to the oasis of Aussa, which was less exposed to Oromo raids, making the imamate the effective successor to Adal's Islamic leadership. Ruled by a line of imams who combined religious and political authority, it governed a harsh desert realm whose economy rested on salt extraction, caravan trade, and nomadic pastoralism. Throughout its existence it was weakened by Oromo incursions and by internal strife between Harla, Arab, and Afar factions, and it gradually decayed from a regional power into a localized one. It was progressively displaced by the Afar Mudaito clan and formally gave way in 1734 when Kadafo founded the Mudaito dynasty and the Sultanate of Aussa.","lombardy":"The Duchy of Milan was an Italian state on the Lombard plain, formally created in 1395 when Gian Galeazzo Visconti purchased the ducal title from Wenceslaus, King of the Romans, elevating the Visconti lordship that had ruled Milan since the thirteenth century. After the Visconti male line failed and a brief Golden Ambrosian Republic collapsed, the mercenary captain Francesco Sforza seized the city in 1450 and founded the House of Sforza, under whom Milan flourished as a wealthy Renaissance center known for silk, arms, and the patronage of figures such as Leonardo da Vinci. From the death of the last Sforza duke, Francesco II, in 1535 the duchy passed under Habsburg control and from the mid-sixteenth century was ruled by the kings of Spain through appointed governors rather than a resident duke, becoming a strategic and prosperous possession of the Spanish crown in northern Italy. During the War of the Spanish Succession the duchy was occupied by Austrian forces and transferred to the Austrian Habsburgs, a change confirmed by the treaties of Utrecht, Rastatt, and Baden between 1713 and 1714. The Duchy of Milan endured under Austrian rule until it was overrun by Napoleon and absorbed into the Cisalpine Republic in 1796–1797.","luxembourg":"The Duchy of Luxembourg (also Luxemburg) was a fief of the Holy Roman Empire created in 1354 when Emperor Charles IV elevated the County of Luxembourg to ducal rank for his brother Wenceslaus, uniting it with the lands of Arlon, Durbuy, La Roche, Thionville, Bitburg, and Marville. After the extinction of the direct line it passed in 1443 to Philip the Good of Burgundy, and through the Burgundian inheritance came under the House of Habsburg, held first by the Spanish and later the Austrian branch as one of the constituent provinces of the Habsburg (Southern) Netherlands. Governed from Brussels on behalf of a distant sovereign, it was above all a strategic borderland dominated by the great Fortress of Luxembourg, contested repeatedly between France and the Habsburgs and famously refortified by Vauban during a French occupation. Its history was one of subjection to successive foreign dynasties rather than self-rule, its territory and fortress prized for their position between France, the German lands, and the Low Countries. The duchy ceased to exist when the Southern Netherlands were annexed by the French First Republic on 1 October 1795, its lands reorganized into the Département des Forêts.","mahra":"The Mahra Sultanate, later styled the Mahra Sultanate of Qishn and Socotra, was a tribal Muslim sultanate of the Mahri people that controlled the Arabian Sea coast east of Hadhramaut together with the island of Socotra. It traced its origins to 1432, when the Ba Dujana family seized the port of Shihr from Rasulid control and founded the first organized state in Mahri lands, after which power passed to the Zwedi and Afrari families of Qishn and Socotra following the loss of Shihr in 1495. Governed as a hereditary monarchy under sultans of the Banu Afrar (Al-Afrar, or Al-Mahri) dynasty, it was a loosely centralized polity resting on tribal allegiance and control of coastal ports and the Socotra archipelago. Its rulers maintained substantial autonomy through the Portuguese seizure of Socotra in 1507–1511, Ottoman expansion, and later British protection under a treaty accepted in 1886. The sultanate endured for over five centuries until 1967, when it was abolished and absorbed into the newly independent People's Republic of South Yemen.","mali":"The map label \"Mali\" here marks the former heartland of the Mali Empire (Manden) along the upper Niger River, which by around 1700 had fragmented into a patchwork of Bamana (Bambara) chiefdoms and Mandinka successor states rather than a single polity. The medieval Mali Empire, founded by Sundiata Keita in the mid-13th century and ruled by the Keita dynasty of mansas, had declined steadily after its 14th-century golden age and effectively disintegrated when Bamana forces sacked its capital Niani around 1670. In its place the Keita rulers retreated to become provincial chiefs at Kangaba, while ambitious Bamana warlords carved out small kingdoms across the region. The most significant of these successors was the early Segou kingdom, first established by the mercenary warlord Kaladian Coulibaly around 1640, though it collapsed after his death about 1660 and would only be refounded as a centralized Bamana Empire under Biton Coulibaly in 1712. The label thus denotes a transitional, decentralized frontier of rival Mandinka and Bamana polities that succeeded the Mali Empire and preceded the great 18th-century Bambara states of Segou and Kaarta.","maori":"The Māori are the Indigenous Polynesian people of Aotearoa (New Zealand), descended from East Polynesian voyagers who settled the islands from around the late thirteenth century. Rather than a single unified state, Māori society was organised as a decentralised network of iwi (tribes) and hapū (sub-tribes) bound by whakapapa (genealogy), each led by rangatira (chiefs) whose authority rested on descent, mana (prestige), and demonstrated leadership. Over the following centuries the distinctive \"Classic\" Māori culture developed, marked by fortified pā, elaborate carving and pounamu (greenstone) working, a warrior ethos, and frequent inter-tribal warfare over land, resources, and mana. Māori remained wholly self-governing through the era of first European contact—Abel Tasman's brief violent encounter in 1642 and James Cook's arrival in 1769—after which trade, muskets, disease, and settler colonisation reshaped their world. Māori tribal identity and self-determination were profoundly disrupted by the 1840 Treaty of Waitangi and subsequent land loss, yet the Māori as a people endure to the present as tangata whenua of New Zealand.","nogai horde":"The Nogai Horde was a confederation of Turkic-Mongol nomadic tribes of the Pontic–Caspian steppe, ruled by a dynasty of beys descended from the Manghit commander Edigu that grew out of the fragmenting Golden Horde. It coalesced as an independent power in the 1440s under Edigu's descendants and was governed not by a khan but by a bey supported by a nur-al-din and lesser lords, with authority resting on personal prestige over semi-autonomous nomadic uluses. Centered originally in the steppe between the Volga, Ural, and Emba rivers with a winter seat at Saraychik on the Yaik, it reached its height in the early sixteenth century before splitting in 1557 into a Greater Nogai Horde in the east and a Lesser Nogai Horde toward the Kuban and North Caucasus. From the early seventeenth century it disintegrated under the westward advance of the Kalmyks and the growing power of Muscovy, its scattered groups falling under the nominal suzerainty of the Crimean Khanate and the Ottomans. What remained of the Nogais was progressively subjugated as the Russian Empire pushed south, the confederation's independent existence ending with the Russian annexation of Crimea and the crushing of the Kuban Nogai uprising in the 1780s.","northeastern woodlands nations":"The \"Northeastern Woodlands nations\" is a modern grouping term for the Indigenous peoples of the northeastern woodlands of North America, divided principally between Iroquoian-speaking nations, such as the Haudenosaunee (Iroquois) Confederacy and the Huron-Wendat, and Algonquian-speaking nations, such as the Abenaki, Mi'kmaq, Wampanoag, and Lenape. These were not a single state but many autonomous nations and confederacies of farmer-hunters who cultivated the \"Three Sisters\" of maize, beans, and squash while hunting, fishing, and gathering, and who governed themselves through councils of chiefs, clan systems, and, in the Haudenosaunee case, the Great Law of Peace centered on a Grand Council of fifty sachems at Onondaga. The most powerful was the Haudenosaunee Confederacy of the Mohawk, Oneida, Onondaga, Cayuga, and Seneca, formed before European contact and later joined by the Tuscarora, whose expansionist Beaver Wars shattered the Huron Confederacy in 1649 and reshaped the region. From the seventeenth century onward these nations were drawn into the fur trade and the rivalry of French and English colonies, suffering catastrophic epidemics and warfare that greatly reduced their numbers. Over the following centuries most were dispossessed of their lands through colonial and later United States and Canadian policy, though many nations, including the Haudenosaunee and the Wabanaki peoples, survive as distinct communities today.","oromo":"The Oromo (historically also called the Galla in external sources, a term now regarded as pejorative) were a large Cushitic-speaking people of the Ethiopian highlands and Horn of Africa who never formed a single unified state, but were organized instead through the egalitarian Gadaa system, an age-grade order that rotated political, military, judicial, and ritual authority among generational classes on fixed eight-year cycles. Their fundamental unit was the clan, gathered above into moieties and confederations—most broadly the Borana and Barentu (Barento)—rather than under any hereditary monarch or capital. From an original homeland in the south, around Lake Turkana and the southern Ethiopian lowlands, they undertook the great Oromo expansion of the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, moving northward and outward in the wake of the Ethiopian–Adal war and settling much of southern, central, and eastern Ethiopia. As they dispersed, different Oromo groups adapted their economy, religion, and institutions to local conditions, some remaining pastoralists, others taking up agriculture and later forming the monarchical Gibe kingdoms, and still others being absorbed into the Christian Ethiopian state as a powerful Christianized nobility. Rather than \"ending,\" the Gadaa-governed decentralized order gradually gave way from the eighteenth century onward to local kingdoms, incorporation into the Ethiopian Empire, and Islamic and Christian conversion, while the Oromo endured as the largest ethnic community of the region.</desc>\n<parameter name=\"year1700\">In 1700, the Oromo remained a decentralized people with no single ruler or capital, their affairs still governed by the Gadaa age-grade system and organized around competing clans and confederations across the Ethiopian highlands and neighboring lowlands. The main phase of the great migrations had largely subsided, and Oromo groups such as the Mecha, Tulama, and Barentu were settling and consolidating control over the lands they had occupied during the previous century and a half. In the Ethiopian Empire, Emperor Iyasu I \"the Great\" (reigned 1682–1706) both campaigned against hostile Oromo groups and recruited and settled others, encouraging their conversion to Christianity and elevating a Christianized Oromo elite into high military and provincial office. It was during his reign that individual Oromo first found regular service at the imperial court, marking the growing integration of powerful Oromo individuals into the nobility, a trend that would culminate in the later dominance of the Yejju Oromo. Meanwhile, in the southwest the settled Oromo of the Gibe region were beginning the long transition from Gadaa republics toward the hereditary monarchies—Jimma, Limmu-Ennarea, Gera, Gomma, and Gumma—that would fully crystallize only in the following century.","pampas cultures":"The \"Pampas cultures\" is a collective label for the mobile hunter-gatherer peoples of the Argentine Pampas south and west of the Río de la Plata, principally the Querandí (one of the Het peoples), the Puelche, and related bands, rather than a single unified state or dynasty. They were never a centralized polity: society was organized into small autonomous bands led by kinship heads, subsisting by hunting guanaco, rhea, and deer with the bola and by fishing and gathering, and moving seasonally across the grasslands. From the sixteenth century they violently resisted Spanish settlement, repelling early expeditions on the Río de la Plata, and over the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries they were transformed by the adoption of the horse and by \"Araucanization,\" the eastward cultural and linguistic expansion of the Mapuche, which spread Mapudungun, mounted nomadism, and raiding and trading economies across the plains. Under these pressures the older Querandí and Het identities were progressively absorbed into a broader mounted population generically called \"Pampas\" or \"Pampas Indians.\" This independent indigenous society persisted until the Argentine state's Conquest of the Desert in the 1870s–1880s, which shattered the mounted Pampas peoples through military campaigns and dispossession.","papous":"\"Papous\" (French for \"Papuans\") is not a single polity but the collective name given by European cartographers to the indigenous, predominantly Papuan-speaking peoples of New Guinea and its neighbouring islands, who were never unified under one state. These peoples lived in hundreds of small, autonomous village communities practising intensive horticulture of taro, yams, sago and later sweet potato, herding pigs, and speaking many hundreds of mutually unintelligible languages across the highland valleys, coastal lowlands and offshore islands. Political authority was highly localised and typically vested in \"big-men\" who earned influence through wealth redistribution, feasting and the mediation of disputes rather than through inherited monarchy, and communities were linked by trade networks and ceremonial exchange yet remained militarily independent, with endemic inter-clan warfare. Over the long term these societies were transformed from within by the adoption of the New World sweet potato and from without by the gradual encroachment of outside traders and, from the mid-nineteenth century, Dutch, German and British colonial powers. The label persisted only as an ethnographic and geographic description; it ended not as a state but through the partition of New Guinea among European empires, whose colonies eventually became modern Papua New Guinea and Indonesian Western New Guinea.","patagonian shellfish and marine mammal hunters":"The \"Patagonian shellfish and marine mammal hunters\" is a modern grouping label for the autonomous Indigenous foraging peoples of southernmost South America — chiefly the Tehuelche (Aónikenk) of the mainland steppe, the Selk'nam (Ona) and Haush (Manek'enk) of the Isla Grande de Tierra del Fuego, and the canoe-faring Yámana (Yaghan) and Kawésqar (Alacaluf) of the southern channels. They were never a unified state or polity but a mosaic of small, kin-based bands with no central authority, each holding recognized territories and led informally by band elders or headmen rather than by any sovereign. Their character was defined by subsistence: the Tehuelche and Selk'nam were terrestrial hunters of guanaco and rhea using bow and bola, while the Yámana and Kawésqar were maritime nomads who paddled bark canoes, dove for shellfish, and hunted sea lions and beached whales. Having occupied the region for thousands of years, these peoples remained effectively unconquered through more than three centuries after Magellan's 1520 encounter, sustaining their way of life until systematic European settlement began. Their societies collapsed rapidly in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries under the Patagonian sheep-farming boom, gold rush, introduced diseases, and outright killing, culminating in the Selk'nam genocide and the near-extinction of these cultures.","polynesians":"The Polynesians are an Austronesian ethnolinguistic family of peoples spread across the \"Polynesian Triangle\" of the central and eastern Pacific, descended from Lapita voyagers who settled western Polynesia — Tonga, Samoa, and Fiji's margins — in the first millennium BCE and then expanded eastward to reach Hawaii, the Society Islands (Tahiti), the Marquesas, the Cook Islands, Rapa Nui (Easter Island), and finally New Zealand by the medieval centuries. They never formed a single unified state but organized themselves into numerous independent chiefdoms and tribal confederations, typically ranked hereditary societies led by sacred chiefs (ariʻi, ariki, or aliʻi) who claimed descent from gods and wielded both political and religious authority. The largest political structure to approach an \"empire\" was the maritime Tuʻi Tonga, centered on Tongatapu, which drew tribute across parts of western Polynesia at its height before the sacred kingship devolved much of its temporal power to junior lines. Renowned as master navigators using double-hulled voyaging canoes and star, swell, and bird lore, Polynesian peoples developed distinctive traditions such as the moai statues of Rapa Nui, the marae temple complexes of the Society Islands, and elaborate genealogical and oral cultures. From the late eighteenth century onward these societies were transformed and often devastated by European contact, introduced diseases, missionization, and colonization, though Polynesian peoples, languages, and identities endure across independent nations and territories to the present.","pontremoli":"Pontremoli is a fortified town in the Lunigiana of the northern Apennines, first chartered as a free commune under Emperor Frederick II in 1226 at the strategic meeting of the Magra valley and the Cisa pass on the Via Francigena. Built to command a mountain crossroads, it was long torn between Guelph and Ghibelline factions, a rivalry that shaped its layout and its castle of Piagnaro above the town. Over the later Middle Ages and early modern period it passed through a long succession of overlords — the Malaspina, the Visconti and Sforza of Milan, the Fieschi and Campofregoso of Genoa, France, and finally Habsburg Spain, which governed it as an outlying dependency of the Duchy of Milan. Its wealth rested on its position controlling traffic between the Po plain and the Tyrrhenian coast, and in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries it acquired numerous Baroque palaces and churches. Sold by Spain and briefly held by Genoa, it was purchased into the Medici Grand Duchy of Tuscany in 1650, becoming an autonomous community in 1777 and formally a city in 1778.","republic of the seven zenden":"The Republic of the Seven Zenden, known in German as the Republik der Sieben Zenden and in French as the République des Sept-Dizains, was an early-modern federal republic in the upper Rhône valley that forms today's Swiss canton of Valais. It was a confederation of seven self-governing districts, or Zenden, of Central and Upper Valais—Goms, Brig, Visp, Raron, Leuk, Siders, and Sion—which together held the six banners of Lower Valais as subject lands. Its distinctive seven-star arms date from 1628, and by the constitutional settlement of 1634 the prince-bishop of Sion, though still nominally a prince of the Holy Roman Empire, was bound to submit to the decisions of the communal Diet led by a Landeshauptmann. As a formally Catholic state it was a sworn associate, or Zugewandter Ort, of the Old Swiss Confederacy, governing itself through assemblies of the tithings and parishes rather than through a single sovereign. It was abolished during the French invasion of 1798, when it merged with its former subject Lower Valais into the short-lived République du Valais and was absorbed into the Helvetic Republic.","savanna hunter-gatherers":"\"Savanna hunter-gatherers\" is not the name of a single polity but a generic cartographic label applied to the many Indigenous peoples of the North American interior — the prairies, plains, and savannas of the continent's midsection — who were never organized into one unified state. It encompasses both fully mobile bison-hunting bands and semi-sedentary village farmers, spanning dozens of distinct nations and several unrelated language families rather than a governed empire with a founding date. Politically these peoples were decentralized, organized into autonomous bands and tribes whose decisions were made collectively through councils and kin networks, without any overarching capital, monarch, or central authority. Well-known groups later associated with this region include the Lakota, Cheyenne, Arapaho, Comanche, Crow, and Blackfoot among the nomads, and the Mandan, Hidatsa, Pawnee, Arikara, and Wichita among the horticultural village-dwellers. As a \"polity\" it has no single founding or ending; the map label instead marks a broad cultural zone whose peoples endured, migrated, and transformed over millennia, most dramatically after the horse and Old World diseases reshaped Plains life from the seventeenth century onward.","shuar":"The Shuar are a Jivaroan (Chicham-speaking) people of the upper Amazon on the eastern slopes of the Andes, in the Zamora, Santiago, and upper Marañón drainages of what are now southeastern Ecuador and northern Peru. They never formed a centralized state, kingdom, or dynasty; their society was organized around autonomous, dispersed, polygynous households with no permanent chiefs or institutionalized political authority, temporary war leaders arising only for raids and feuds. The Shuar are renowned for a warrior culture bound up with blood feud and the ritual taking and shrinking of enemy heads (tsantsa), and for fiercely defending their territory, having repelled an Inca incursion under Huayna Capac around 1527. In 1599 allied Jivaroan groups destroyed the Spanish gold-mining towns of Logroño and Sevilla del Oro, after which the Shuar maintained effective independence from colonial rule for centuries with only limited and intermittent outside contact. Sustained missionary and state penetration came only in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, and the Shuar endure today as a distinct people who in the twentieth century pioneered formal Indigenous political organization in the region.","siberian peoples":"The \"Siberian peoples\" here denote the indigenous nations of far northeastern Siberia and Kamchatka — chiefly the Chukchi, Koryak, and Itelmen (Kamchadal) — who were not a single state but a mosaic of decentralized, stateless societies without any central government, ruler, or capital. Their economies rested on reindeer herding across the tundra and the hunting of sea mammals and fishing along the Pacific and Arctic coasts, with authority resting in kin groups, village elders, and local strongmen rather than in any unified polity. Anthropologists have described the Chukchi as \"tribes without rulers,\" and the Itelmen were organized around independent riverine villages that split and re-founded themselves as they grew. From the mid-seventeenth century these peoples came into contact and conflict with advancing Russian Cossacks, who built fortified ostrogs to extract yasak (fur tribute) and take hostages. Their independent status eroded through the eighteenth century as Russian military campaigns, disease, and colonization broke resistance, though the Chukchi in particular were never fully conquered by force and were eventually incorporated through trade and formal accommodation rather than defeat.","songhai":"The Songhai Empire was a West African state centered on the great bend of the Niger River, which grew from the earlier kingdom of Gao into the largest empire in African history under the Sonni and Askia dynasties. It was founded as an imperial power by Sunni Ali, who from 1464 conquered the trading cities of Timbuktu and Djenné and welded the middle Niger into a single realm governed from Gao. Under Askia Muhammad I it reached its height, adopting a more centralized Islamic administration, standing armies, and provincial governors, and it flourished on the trans-Saharan trade in gold, salt, and slaves. Timbuktu became a celebrated center of Islamic scholarship, its scribes, jurists, and libraries drawing students from across the Sudan. The empire was shattered in 1591 when a Saadi Moroccan expedition armed with firearms destroyed the Songhai army at the Battle of Tondibi, ending centralized Songhai rule and fragmenting its territory.","southeastern woodlands nations":"The \"Southeastern Woodlands nations\" is a modern collective label for the independent Indigenous peoples of the American Southeast — chiefly the Cherokee, Muscogee (Creek), Choctaw, Chickasaw, Catawba, and Natchez — who were never united under a single government but shared cultural traits and descended largely from the Mississippian mound-building chiefdoms of roughly 800–1500 CE. These were separate, self-governing nations organized around autonomous towns, matrilineal clans, and councils of headmen rather than a centralized state, with confederations such as the Creek forming loose alliances of talwas (towns). Their societies were heirs to the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex and platform-mound traditions, though most had abandoned mound-building by European contact, while the Natchez preserved a chiefly \"Great Sun\" theocracy into the eighteenth century. Over the colonial period these nations became deeply entangled in the deerskin and Indian slave trades with English Carolina, French Louisiana, and Spanish Florida, adopting firearms and playing the rival empires against one another. Devastated by epidemics, warfare, and later United States expansion, most were forcibly expelled westward under the Indian Removal Act of the 1830s, ending their sovereign presence in their southeastern homelands.","subarctic forest hunter-gatherers":"The \"Subarctic forest hunter-gatherers\" are not a single state but a broad ethnographic category for the mobile hunting-and-fishing peoples of the northern boreal forest and taiga, chiefly the Athabaskan-speaking Dene of the western Subarctic and the Algonquian-speaking Cree, Innu, and Ojibwe of the eastern Subarctic, alongside analogous Siberian taiga peoples. These societies were organized into small, autonomous, kin-based bands and family groups rather than any centralized polity, with non-hereditary leadership resting on hunting skill, experience, and the counsel of elders in broadly egalitarian communities. Their way of life revolved around seasonal mobility across vast territories, tracking caribou and moose and relying on fishing, trapping, and gathering, aided by snowshoes, toboggans, birchbark canoes, and dog sleds. From the seventeenth century onward, contact with European fur traders — especially the Hudson's Bay Company after 1670 — drew many bands into the commercial fur economy as trappers and middlemen, reshaping trade, mobility, and intergroup relations. These peoples were never conquered as a unit and their descendant nations persist today, though their independent hunter-gatherer world was progressively transformed by the fur trade, epidemic disease, and later colonial administration.","subarctic nations":"The \"Subarctic nations\" is a modern collective label for the Indigenous hunter-gatherer peoples of the North American boreal forest (taiga), spanning Athabaskan- or Dene-speaking groups in the west (such as the Chipewyan or Denesuline, Slavey, Gwich'in and Tlicho) and Algonquian-speaking Cree and Innu (Montagnais-Naskapi) in the east. They were not a single state but a mosaic of small, autonomous, kin-based bands and hunting lodges that formed, dissolved and reformed with the seasons, governed by consensus and temporary leaders rather than any central authority. Their societies were organized around mobile subsistence in a harsh subarctic environment, hunting caribou and moose, fishing, snaring waterfowl and gathering, with the caribou central to food, clothing, shelter and tools. From the late sixteenth and seventeenth centuries onward they were progressively drawn into the European fur trade, the Innu with the French on the St. Lawrence and Saguenay and the Cree with the English Hudson's Bay Company on the bay, some bands taking on lucrative middleman roles between coastal posts and interior trappers. These peoples were never conquered as a unit and endure to the present day as distinct First Nations and Innu communities, though the fur trade, disease and later colonial policies profoundly reshaped their traditional lifeways.","tasmanian hunter-gatherers":"The Tasmanian hunter-gatherers, known collectively as the Palawa or Aboriginal Tasmanians, were the Indigenous peoples of the island of lutruwita (Tasmania), descended from Aboriginal Australians who reached the region on foot across the Bassian Plain during the last glacial period at least thirty-five thousand years ago. They had no unified state, government, or ruler, but were organised into around nine loosely bounded \"nations\" comprising numerous clans, each made up of a few extended family units, with authority resting in kinship, elders, and custom rather than any central polity. Living as mobile hunter-gatherers, they moved seasonally between coast and interior, hunting land mammals such as wallaby and kangaroo, gathering shellfish and plant foods, and shaping the landscape through the deliberate use of fire. Cut off from mainland Australia when rising seas drowned Bass Strait some twelve thousand years earlier, they developed in near-total isolation for millennia, producing a material culture and toolkit distinct from that of the mainland. This way of life, unbroken for tens of thousands of years, was shattered after British colonisation began in 1803, when frontier violence, introduced disease, and forced removal during the so-called Black War brought the traditional societies to the brink of destruction, though Palawa descendants survive today.","western north american nations":"The \"Western North American nations\" is a modern cartographic grouping of the many autonomous Indigenous peoples of the Great Basin, Columbia Plateau, California, and the Southwest, including the Shoshone, Ute, Paiute, Nez Perce and other Plateau nations, the Pueblo peoples, and the Athabaskan-speaking Navajo (Diné) and Apache. It was never a single state, empire, or confederation but a mosaic of independent tribes, bands, villages, and language families organized at the level of the local community, ranging from mobile foraging bands to sedentary farming towns. Political authority was typically decentralized and consensual, exercised by village leaders, band headmen, and councils rather than by any overarching sovereign or capital. Its peoples were transformed over the sixteenth to nineteenth centuries by contact with New Spain, the spread of the horse after the 1680 Pueblo Revolt, epidemic disease, and expanding colonial and later United States frontiers. These nations were never dissolved as peoples; through the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries most were confined to reservations by Spanish, Mexican, and American expansion, and their descendant nations persist as federally and state-recognized tribes today.","wolof states":"The Wolof states were a cluster of kingdoms in the Senegambian region of West Africa that emerged from the fragmentation of the Jolof Empire, the great Wolof polity founded around the fourteenth century under Ndiadiane Ndiaye and headed by a paramount ruler titled the Buurba. After the Battle of Danki in 1549, in which Cayor under Amari Ngoone Sobel Fall broke free, the empire dissolved into independent successor kingdoms — Jolof, Cayor, Baol, and Waalo among the Wolof, together with the neighbouring Serer-ruled kingdoms of Sine and Saloum — each governed by its own monarch such as the damel of Cayor, the teigne of Baol, or the brak of Waalo. These states were aristocratic monarchies whose kings relied on a warrior slave-soldier class, the ceddo, and grew increasingly entangled in the Atlantic trade in enslaved people, gum arabic, and other goods through European posts on the coast. Powerful figures such as Lat Sukaabe Fall periodically united several of the kingdoms and asserted royal monopolies over commerce, while religious tensions between the secular nobility and Muslim marabouts recurred throughout their history. The states persisted as autonomous polities until the French conquest of Senegal in the nineteenth century absorbed them one by one, with Waalo falling in 1855 and Cayor extinguished in 1886."});

/* Trim Oromo general description to 5 sentences (year-specific content stays in the year paragraph). */
Object.assign(window.COUNTRY_INFO, {"oromo":"The Oromo (historically also called the Galla in external sources, a term now regarded as pejorative) were a large Cushitic-speaking people of the Ethiopian highlands and Horn of Africa who never formed a single unified state, but were organized instead through the egalitarian Gadaa system, an age-grade order that rotated political, military, judicial, and ritual authority among generational classes on fixed eight-year cycles. Their fundamental unit was the clan, gathered above into moieties and confederations—most broadly the Borana and Barentu (Barento)—rather than under any hereditary monarch or capital. From an original homeland in the south, around Lake Turkana and the southern Ethiopian lowlands, they undertook the great Oromo expansion of the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, moving northward and outward in the wake of the Ethiopian–Adal war and settling much of southern, central, and eastern Ethiopia. As they dispersed, different Oromo groups adapted their economy, religion, and institutions to local conditions, some remaining pastoralists, others taking up agriculture and later forming the monarchical Gibe kingdoms, and still others being absorbed into the Christian Ethiopian state as a powerful Christianized nobility. Rather than \"ending,\" the Gadaa-governed decentralized order gradually gave way from the eighteenth century onward to local kingdoms, incorporation into the Ethiopian Empire, and Islamic and Christian conversion, while the Oromo endured as the largest ethnic community of the region.</desc>\n<parameter name=\"year1700\">In 1700, the Oromo remained a decentralized people with no single ruler or capital, their affairs still governed by the Gadaa age-grade system and organized around competing clans and confederations across the Ethiopian highlands and neighboring lowlands."});

/* 1700 Spanish Netherlands (renamed from the mislabeled Luxembourg blob). */
Object.assign(window.COUNTRY_INFO, {"spanish netherlands":"The Spanish Netherlands were the provinces of the southern Low Countries held by the Spanish branch of the House of Habsburg. They emerged in 1556 when the Burgundian inheritance of Charles V was divided, and remained predominantly Catholic after the northern provinces seceded to form the Dutch Republic. The territory corresponded roughly to present-day Belgium and Luxembourg, governed from Brussels by a governor-general acting for the distant monarch. Its dense cluster of cloth-making and trading cities made it one of the wealthiest and most urbanized regions of Europe. The provinces passed to the Austrian Habsburgs in 1714, becoming the Austrian Netherlands."});


/* 1600-era info-box data (Atlas timeline) — added by the 1600 era build. */
Object.assign(window.COUNTRY_INFO, {"habsburg spain":"The Spanish Habsburg monarchy began in 1516 when Charles I inherited the crowns of Castile and Aragon, uniting them under a single ruler and, from 1556, forming a distinct Spanish branch of the dynasty under Philip II. It was a composite monarchy in which Castile, Aragon, and the empire's many realms retained their own laws and institutions under a shared sovereign, increasingly governed through royal favourites known as validos. The dynasty presided over a vast global empire and Spain's Golden Age of arts and letters, while championing the Catholic cause in Europe's confessional wars. Successive reigns saw mounting fiscal strain, repeated state bankruptcies, and the gradual erosion of Spanish military preponderance. The line ended in 1700 with the death of the childless Charles II, whose disputed inheritance triggered the War of the Spanish Succession.","kingdom of portugal":"The Philippine period of the Kingdom of Portugal began in 1580 when Philip II of Spain claimed the vacant Portuguese throne after the death of the childless King Henry, uniting the two Iberian crowns in a dynastic Iberian Union. Under the terms of the Cortes of Tomar of 1581, Portugal retained its own laws, currency, cortes, and administration, ruled on the king's behalf by a viceroy or governors resident in Lisbon. The three Habsburg kings, all named Philip in the Portuguese numbering, governed a still-vast overseas empire stretching from Brazil to India and the East Indies. Over the decades Portuguese resentment grew over Castilian influence, the neglect of Portuguese interests, and the entanglement of the empire in Spain's wars with the Dutch and English. The union ended in 1640 with the Restoration revolt that placed the Duke of Braganza on the throne as John IV, founding a new native dynasty.","duchy of prussia":"The Duchy of Prussia was created in 1525 when Albert of Hohenzollern, the last Grand Master of the Teutonic Knights, secularised the Order's Prussian state, converted to Lutheranism, and took it as a hereditary duchy held in fief from the King of Poland. It was the first Protestant state established on the basis of Lutheranism and was governed from Königsberg as a vassal principality within the Polish crown's sphere. Rule passed within the Hohenzollern family, and after the Ansbach ducal line neared extinction the fief was transferred to the Brandenburg branch of the dynasty, uniting Prussia and Brandenburg in personal union in 1618. Over the seventeenth century the dukes worked to loosen and finally throw off Polish suzerainty, achieving full sovereignty through the Treaty of Wehlau in 1657 and the Peace of Oliva in 1660. The duchy was elevated in 1701 when its ruler crowned himself King in Prussia, transforming the state into the Kingdom of Prussia.","crimean khanate":"The Crimean Khanate was founded around 1441 by Hacı I Giray, a descendant of Genghis Khan through the line of Jochi, as one of the successor states of the fragmenting Golden Horde. From 1475 it became a protectorate of the Ottoman Empire, and thereafter the Ottoman sultan held veto power over the choice of khan, though the ruling Giray dynasty retained substantial autonomy in steppe affairs. Governed from Bakhchisarai, the khanate combined a settled agricultural and urban core in Crimea with a nomadic and semi-nomadic population whose economy relied heavily on raiding and the slave trade in the surrounding steppes. Its light cavalry made it a major military power in Eastern Europe, repeatedly campaigning against Poland-Lithuania, Muscovy, and the Cossacks. The khanate declined in the eighteenth century, was rendered nominally independent by the 1774 Treaty of Küçük Kaynarca, and was annexed by the Russian Empire in 1783.","oman":"The Nabhani dynasty was a line of Omani rulers, drawn from the Banu Nabhan tribe, that dominated the interior of Oman from the mid-twelfth century after the decline of the early Ibadi imamate. Its kings, styled maliks, governed from interior strongholds and presided over a decentralized order in which tribal confederations and the Ibadi religious establishment retained great weight. Their authority waxed and waned, contested repeatedly by rival tribes and by revived claims to a properly elected Ibadi imam, and their hold never extended firmly to the whole coast. In its later phase Nabhani power was intermittent and fragmented, punctuated by civil strife and periods when elected imams displaced the dynasty. The line was eclipsed in 1624 when Nasir bin Murshid of the Yaruba was elected imam, inaugurating a new dynasty that would expel the Portuguese and unify the country.","gharra":"Gharra denotes a small, obscure entity on the southeastern coast of Arabia that appears as a distinct territory on some early-modern maps of the region. Its identity is poorly documented, and it is most plausibly associated with a minor coastal or highland tribal grouping between the Mahri lands and Dhofar rather than a well-organized state. It possessed no centralized dynasty, standing administration, or securely recorded line of rulers in the surviving record. Like its neighbours, any such community would have been organized along tribal and lineage lines, engaged in fishing, pastoralism, and coastal trade. Its boundaries and very existence as a discrete polity are uncertain and rest on cartographic rather than firm historical attestation.","central asian khanates":"This label, as drawn on the 1600 map, covers the vast steppe and taiga of western and central Siberia rather than the settled Central Asian oasis khanates of Bukhara and Khiva. The region had been loosely organized under the Khanate of Sibir, a Turco-Mongol successor state of the Golden Horde ruled by the Shaybanid line and centered on the Irtysh. That khanate was a decentralized realm of Siberian Tatar and indigenous Ugric and Samoyedic peoples, dependent on tribute, hunting, and the fur trade rather than dense agriculture. From 1581 the Cossack expedition of Yermak and the subsequent tsarist advance shattered its cohesion, planting a chain of forts across the taiga. The area passed piecemeal into the expanding Tsardom of Russia, ending independent Turkic rule over western Siberia.","vijayanagara empire":"The Vijayanagara Empire was a South Indian state founded in 1336 in the Deccan, traditionally attributed to the brothers Harihara I and Bukka Raya, and it grew into the dominant Hindu power of the peninsula. It was governed by a king styled Raya through a network of provincial governors and semi-autonomous military chiefs known as nayakas, who held land in return for maintaining troops. Ruled successively by the Sangama, Saluva, Tuluva, and finally the Aravidu dynasties, the empire reached its cultural and territorial zenith under Krishnadevaraya of the Tuluva line in the early sixteenth century. Its power was broken at the Battle of Talikota in 1565, when a coalition of Deccan sultanates defeated its forces and sacked the capital city of Vijayanagara, after which the Aravidu dynasty ruled a diminished realm from more southerly seats. The empire fragmented as its nayaka governors asserted independence, and it dissolved by the mid-seventeenth century, conventionally dated to around 1646.","ahmadnagar sultanate":"The Ahmadnagar Sultanate was a Deccan Muslim kingdom founded in 1490 by Malik Ahmad Nizam Shah I, who broke away from the disintegrating Bahmani Sultanate and established the Nizam Shahi dynasty. Ruled by a sultan and often dominated by powerful ministers and regents, it was one of the five Deccan sultanates that partitioned the former Bahmani realm. It took a leading part in the coalition of sultanates that destroyed the Vijayanagara army at Talikota in 1565, and its court was noted for factional rivalry between Deccani, foreign, and Habshi military elites. From the late sixteenth century the sultanate bore the brunt of Mughal expansion into the Deccan, and its survival came to depend on the resistance organized by the Habshi regent Malik Ambar. After decades of warfare the state was finally extinguished in 1636, when its remaining territory was partitioned between the Mughal Empire and the Sultanate of Bijapur.","bijapur sultanate":"The Sultanate of Bijapur was a Deccan Muslim kingdom founded in 1490 by Yusuf Adil Shah, who declared independence from the failing Bahmani Sultanate and established the Adil Shahi dynasty of Persianate origin. It was governed by a sultan and became one of the five successor sultanates of the Deccan, frequently shifting between Shia and Sunni state religion and drawing on Deccani, Persian, and Habshi elites. Bijapur joined the sultanate coalition that overthrew Vijayanagara at Talikota in 1565 and afterward expanded southward into former Vijayanagara lands. Under able rulers such as Ibrahim Adil Shah II the dynasty presided over a cosmopolitan court famous for its patronage of music, poetry, painting, and monumental architecture in its capital. Weakened by Maratha pressure and Mughal invasion in the seventeenth century, the sultanate was conquered and annexed by the Mughal emperor Aurangzeb in 1686.","golconda sultanate":"The Sultanate of Golconda was a Deccan kingdom founded in 1518 by Sultan Quli Qutb Shah, a governor of Turkoman origin who broke from the collapsing Bahmani Sultanate to establish the Persianate, Shia Qutb Shahi dynasty. It was ruled by a sultan from the great fortress of Golconda and later from the new city of Hyderabad, and it grew wealthy on the diamond mines and textile trade of the eastern Deccan. Golconda took part in the coalition of sultanates that defeated Vijayanagara at Talikota in 1565 and cultivated a syncretic court patronizing Persian, Dakhini Urdu, and Telugu literature. Its rulers, notably Muhammad Quli Qutb Shah, were celebrated as poets and builders, endowing Hyderabad with landmarks such as the Charminar. After ruling for well over a century and a half, the sultanate was besieged and conquered by the Mughal emperor Aurangzeb in 1687, ending the dynasty.","bidar sultanate":"The Bidar Sultanate was ruled by the Barid Shahi dynasty, founded by Qasim Barid I, a Bahmani courtier of Turkic or Georgian origin who accumulated power as the Bahmani Sultanate fragmented and whose successors ruled in their own right from the early sixteenth century. It was the smallest and most precarious of the five Deccan sultanates that emerged from the Bahmani collapse, governed as a Muslim sultanate from the fortified city of Bidar. Its rulers, styled Barid Shah, maintained a compact state through shifting alliances and rivalries with the neighbouring Deccan powers of Bijapur, Golconda, Ahmadnagar, and Berar. Perpetually overshadowed by its larger neighbours, the dynasty survived through diplomacy and the strength of its citadel rather than territorial expansion. It was extinguished when the sultanate was conquered and annexed by the Adil Shahi sultanate of Bijapur.","rajput states":"The Rajput states were a set of Hindu kingdoms in and around Rajputana in northwestern India, ruled by martial Rajput clans such as the Sisodias of Mewar, the Kachhwahas of Amber, and the Rathores of Marwar. Each was an independent hereditary monarchy governed by a raja or rana claiming Kshatriya warrior descent, and they were bound together by a shared aristocratic culture, intermarriage, and a strong ethos of honour and military service. Their relations were marked by frequent rivalry among themselves as well as by shifting resistance and accommodation toward the dominant imperial powers of northern India. From the later sixteenth century most Rajput houses were drawn into the Mughal Empire as allied vassals, providing many of its leading generals, while a few resisted subordination. The states persisted as princely realms into the modern era, eventually being integrated into independent India in the twentieth century.","bengal":"The Baro-Bhuyan were a loose confederacy of landholding chieftains, or zamindars, in the deltaic lowlands of eastern Bengal known as Bhati. Emerging as the Bengal Sultanate disintegrated in the sixteenth century, these largely autonomous lords banded together under a paramount leader to defend their riverine territories. The most prominent confederacy was led from Sonargaon by Isa Khan and afterward by his son Musa Khan, who commanded a formidable naval and land defence across the marshes and channels of the delta. Their power rested on control of the waterways, fortified strongholds, and the difficulty of campaigning in the flooded terrain. The confederacy was ultimately broken by the Mughal Empire, which absorbed the region into its provincial administration.","orissa":"The Khurda kingdom was the surviving Hindu successor of the Gajapati rulers of Orissa, established at Khurda after the older Gajapati capital region fell to outside powers. Its rajas claimed the ancient Gajapati title and the traditional role of first servant of the god Jagannath at Puri, giving the dynasty deep religious authority in the region. Governed as a Hindu monarchy, it retained custody of the great Jagannath temple and its ceremonial prerogatives even as its political independence narrowed. Founded by Ramachandra Deva in the late sixteenth century, it endured as a subordinate but symbolically important power. The line persisted as a temple-centred rajaship into the colonial period.","islamic and hindu states":"This label denotes a group of north-central Indian polities of mixed Muslim and Hindu rulership rather than any single sovereign state, and it does not correspond to one dynasty with a coherent history. In practice the north-central region it covers lay largely within the Mughal Empire by the end of the sixteenth century, interspersed with subordinate Hindu chiefs and zamindars. The area combined directly governed imperial provinces with a patchwork of tributary Rajput and other local rulers. Its Muslim and Hindu elites were bound into the imperial system through service, revenue obligations, and alliance. The designation is best understood as a broad ethnographic grouping rather than a discrete state with a founding, government, and end of its own.","ming dynasty":"The Ming dynasty was a Han Chinese imperial dynasty founded in 1368 by Zhu Yuanzhang, a former peasant and rebel leader who took the throne as the Hongwu Emperor after expelling the Mongol Yuan. Its government combined a centralized bureaucracy staffed through the Confucian civil-service examinations with an increasingly powerful palace eunuch establishment and, after the early reigns, emperors who often withdrew from active governance. The dynasty is remembered for the construction of much of the surviving Great Wall, the reconstruction of the Forbidden City after the capital moved to Beijing, and the maritime treasure voyages of Admiral Zheng He. Over its later course it faced fiscal strain, factional struggles at court, silver-driven commercialization, and mounting pressure on its northern frontiers. It collapsed in 1644 when the rebel Li Zicheng seized Beijing and the last emperor took his own life, after which the Manchu-led Qing entered China proper.","japan":"The Azuchi–Momoyama period was the closing phase of Japan's Warring States era, defined by the drive to reunify a country long fragmented among warring domains. It takes its name from the castles of Oda Nobunaga at Azuchi and Toyotomi Hideyoshi at Momoyama, the two hegemons who successively subdued rival warlords through force, alliance, and administrative reform. Nobunaga broke the power of entrenched Buddhist establishments and embraced firearms and European contact before being killed in 1582, after which Hideyoshi completed the reunification and rose from humble origins to supreme power. The era saw sweeping measures such as the sword hunt and cadastral land surveys, a flourishing of grand castle architecture and bold decorative arts, and ambitious but failed invasions of Korea. It gave way to the establishment of the Tokugawa shogunate in the early seventeenth century after Hideyoshi's death left a contested succession.","kingdom of tsang":"The Tsangpa were a dynasty of kings based in the Tsang region of west-central Tibet, seated at the fortress of Samdrubtse in Shigatse. Founded around 1565 by Karma Tseten, a former official who supplanted the earlier Rinpungpa lords, the house rose to become the dominant secular power over much of central Tibet. Its rulers were closely aligned with the Karma Kagyu school of Tibetan Buddhism and often stood in rivalry with the rising Gelug order and its Dalai Lamas. Through a succession of energetic kings the dynasty expanded its authority over southern, western, and northern Tibetan territories during the late sixteenth and early seventeenth centuries. It was overthrown in 1642 when Güshi Khan of the Khoshut Mongols, allied with the Fifth Dalai Lama, defeated and executed the last Tsangpa king, ushering in the Ganden Phodrang government.","kingdom of pegu":"The Kingdom of Pegu was a Mon-speaking realm of Lower Burma centred on the delta city of Bago (Pegu), founded in the late 13th century after the collapse of Pagan and consolidated by rulers such as Razadarit and the celebrated queen Shin Sawbu. It was governed as a Theravada Buddhist monarchy whose wealth rested on maritime trade through its Bay of Bengal ports and control of the rice-rich Irrawaddy delta. In 1539 it was conquered by the Burmese Toungoo dynasty, and under Tabinshwehti and Bayinnaung the city of Pegu became the opulent capital of a vast Southeast Asian empire that dazzled European visitors. That empire overextended through repeated wars, and after Bayinnaung's death its vassals rebelled and its authority disintegrated. Pegu was sacked and burned by a coalition of Arakanese, Toungoo, and Portuguese forces at the century's end, ending its role as an imperial seat.","aceh sultanate":"The Aceh Sultanate was an Islamic maritime state at the northern tip of Sumatra, conventionally dated from 1496 and unified in the following decades by its founding sultan Ali Mughayat Syah, who welded together the region's coastal principalities. It was ruled by a sultan and grew into one of the most powerful states of the Malay world, sustained by the pepper trade and by control of the Strait of Malacca's western approaches. Staunchly Muslim and often at war with the Portuguese at Malacca, it cultivated diplomatic and military ties with the Ottoman Empire and became a celebrated centre of Islamic scholarship. It reached its zenith in the early 17th century under Iskandar Muda before a long decline set in. After centuries as an independent power it was finally conquered by the Dutch following a protracted war, and its sultanate was abolished in the early 20th century.","johor sultanate":"The Johor Sultanate was a Malay state founded in 1528 by Sultan Alauddin Riayat Shah II, a son of the last sultan of Malacca, as the political successor to that fallen kingdom after its capture by the Portuguese. Ruled by the old Malaccan royal line and its Bendahara officials, it dominated the southern Malay Peninsula, the Riau-Lingga archipelago, and stretches of eastern Sumatra. For much of the 16th and 17th centuries it was locked in a three-cornered struggle with Portuguese Malacca and the Aceh Sultanate, repeatedly shifting its capital as rivals sacked its river ports. It later flourished as an entrepôt and by playing European powers against one another, before internal succession disputes and the murder of its last old-dynasty sultan brought in the Bendahara line. The realm eventually fragmented under British and Dutch pressure, its successor states emerging in the 19th century.","malay and bornean sultanates":"The Malay and Bornean sultanates were a constellation of independent Islamic maritime states scattered across Borneo and the surrounding archipelago, rather than a single unified polity. The greatest of them was Brunei, which in the 16th century claimed suzerainty over much of coastal Borneo and reached into the southern Philippines, alongside states such as Banjar in the southeast and various riverine principalities. Each was ruled by its own sultan and a nobility drawn from trading and warrior elites, deriving wealth from pepper, forest products, gold, and control of river-mouth trade. Islam, spread by merchants and missionaries, provided a shared religious and legal framework across these otherwise autonomous courts. Over the following centuries they were progressively eroded by European colonial expansion, with most eventually absorbed into the Dutch and British spheres in Borneo.","saadi sultanate":"The Saadi Sultanate was a Sharifian dynasty of Arab descent that rose in the Sous valley of southern Morocco in the early sixteenth century and claimed legitimacy through descent from the Prophet Muhammad. It supplanted the Wattasids to unify Morocco, blending tribal military power with a centralized administration funded by trans-Saharan gold, sugar production, and control of Atlantic trade. Its most celebrated ruler, Ahmad al-Mansur, presided over a golden age of monumental architecture, learning, and ambitious diplomacy with European and Ottoman powers, and famously projected Moroccan power across the Sahara. The dynasty defended Morocco's independence against both Ottoman expansion and Iberian crusading ambitions, notably at the Battle of the Three Kings. After al-Mansur's death the state fractured amid civil wars among his heirs and was eventually displaced by the Alaouite dynasty in the mid-seventeenth century.","pashalik of timbuktu":"The Pashalik of Timbuktu was a military regime established on the middle Niger after a Saadian Moroccan expedition crushed the Songhai Empire at the Battle of Tondibi in 1591. It was governed by the Arma, a corps descended from the Andalusian, Arab, and Berber musketeers of the invading army, who ruled the river cities of Timbuktu, Gao, and Djenné through a succession of pashas. Initially owing nominal allegiance to the sultan in Marrakesh, the pashalik rapidly became autonomous as Moroccan control loosened, and its politics were marked by chronic factional strife and frequent depositions. It sustained itself on the trans-Saharan trade and taxation of the Niger commerce but never recovered the territorial reach or scholarly prestige of Songhai. The regime declined into fragmentation and was ultimately extinguished when the Fulani conquered the region in the early nineteenth century.","adal sultanate":"The Adal Sultanate was a medieval Muslim state in the Horn of Africa, emerging in the early 15th century as a successor to the earlier Sultanate of Ifat and centered on the trading regions inland from the Gulf of Aden. It was governed by a sultan drawn largely from the Walashma dynasty, ruling a diverse population of Somali, Harari, Afar, and other Muslim communities engaged in long-distance caravan trade. Its most famous era came under Imam Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi, whose jihad of 1529–1543 overran much of Christian Ethiopia before his defeat with Portuguese help. The exhaustion of that war, combined with Oromo expansion, fatally weakened the state and drove the relocation of its capital from Harar to Aussa in 1577. Thereafter Adal fragmented into successor polities — chiefly the walled city-state of Harar and the Imamate of Aussa — and ceased to exist as a unified sultanate.","tunjur kingdom":"The Tunjur kingdom was a Sahelian state founded around the 15th–16th centuries by an Islamized dynasty of partly Nubian origin, ruling the region of Darfur and extending west into what became Wadai. Its Muslim rulers built the first stone and brick structures in the area, with early royal centers at Uri and later Ain Farah, and controlled the trans-Saharan trade routes crossing the region. The kingdom drew on and displaced earlier Daju political traditions while expanding through conquest and alliance across the eastern Sahel. Its power rested on control of long-distance commerce linking the central Sudan to Egypt and the Mediterranean. It was ultimately supplanted in the mid-17th century, giving way to the Fur Keira dynasty in Darfur and to the Maba-led sultanate in Wadai.","wadai":"Wadai denotes the region and later Islamic sultanate lying east of Lake Chad in the central Sahel, in the territory of present-day eastern Chad. Before the mid-17th century it formed part of the domains dominated by the Tunjur kingdom, whose Muslim rulers exercised overlordship from Darfur. An independent Islamic state emerged there only around 1635, when a Maba leader named Abd al-Karim overthrew the ruling Tunjur dynasty and established a sultanate centered at Wara. That later sultanate grew into a powerful trading and raiding state controlling the routes between the central Sudan and the Sahara, and it endured until the French conquest in the early 20th century. In 1600, however, no such unified Wadai state yet existed, the region being a Tunjur-dominated frontier of chiefdoms and small groups.","mutapa empire":"The Mutapa Empire was a Shona state on the northern Zimbabwean plateau, founded in the mid-fifteenth century by Nyatsimba Mutota, who migrated north from Great Zimbabwe in search of salt and pasture. Its ruler bore the title Mwenemutapa, meaning 'lord of the conquered lands,' and governed through a court of appointed officials and tributary chiefs whose loyalty was reinforced by ritual kingship and control of the gold and ivory trade. The state grew wealthy exporting gold and ivory down the Zambezi to Swahili and later Portuguese traders on the Indian Ocean coast. From the late sixteenth century onward it was increasingly drawn into dependence on the Portuguese, who intervened in its civil wars and extracted mining and trading concessions. Weakened by these entanglements and by rival Shona powers such as the Rozvi, the kingdom fragmented and finally collapsed in the eighteenth century.","lunda":"The Lunda (Ruund) were a Bantu-speaking people of the upper Kasai and Kalanyi river country in what is now the southern Democratic Republic of the Congo. Before the rise of a centralized state they lived in dispersed chiefdoms whose leaders drew authority from control of land, kinship networks, and local ritual. Lunda tradition holds that centralized sacred kingship was introduced when the Luba hunter-prince Chibinda Ilunga married the Ruund queen Lueji, grafting Luba court institutions onto the local polity. Out of this union grew the paramount title of Mwant Yav and, over the following decades, an expansive tributary empire centered on the capital of Musumba. The Lunda Empire went on to dominate a wide swath of Central Africa through trade and a flexible system of positional succession before declining in the nineteenth century.","swahili city-states":"The Swahili city-states were a chain of autonomous, cosmopolitan Muslim trading towns strung along the East African coast from present-day Somalia to Mozambique, including Kilwa, Mombasa, Malindi, Pate, Lamu, and Zanzibar. They emerged from the interaction of Bantu-speaking coastal communities with Indian Ocean commerce, developing a distinctive Swahili language, Islamic urban culture, and coral-stone architecture. Each town was governed independently, typically by a sultan or council of merchant elites, and they competed and traded with one another rather than forming a single unified state. Their prosperity rested on the export of gold, ivory, and enslaved people and the import of textiles, ceramics, and other goods from Arabia, Persia, India, and China. After 1498 the arrival of the Portuguese subordinated many of the towns, until Omani intervention expelled the Portuguese from the northern coast at the end of the seventeenth century.","madagascar":"This polygon represents the non-Merina remainder of Madagascar, a large island home to numerous Malagasy peoples descended from mixed Austronesian and Bantu-speaking settlers who arrived over the preceding centuries. Rather than a single state, it comprised a patchwork of kingdoms, chiefdoms, and clan confederations, most prominent among them the Sakalava of the western plains, alongside the Betsimisaraka and other eastern and southern peoples. Political authority typically rested on ancestral clan lineages, cattle wealth, and the ritual power of kings and their royal relics. Coastal groups engaged in trade with Arab, Swahili, and later European merchants in enslaved people, cattle, and goods, while the interior remained largely governed by local dynasties. Over the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries the Sakalava and Betsimisaraka would build the island's most powerful confederations before Merina expansion and French colonization reshaped the whole island."});
